36-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","7f832a88-280e-43d5-a515-01b65d5e428d_744015473","a3c70681-f2b9-494d-bb98-7de9c98f52da_736721641"],"documents":{"7f832a88-280e-43d5-a515-01b65d5e428d_744015473":{"id":"7f832a88-280e-43d5-a515-01b65d5e428d_744015473","text":"In the world\nNews of Moscow\nPolitics\nSociety\nAccidents\nScience and technology\nShow business\nArmy\nGames\n+ 24 \u00b0 C\nNamed the location of the left from Russia \u201cdigital nomads \u201d\nRussian IT specialists are massively moving to the countries of South America.\nThe reason for the departure was a military conflict.\nThis is reported by the Financial Times.\nPhoto by RIA NovostiRIA Novosti\nProfessor of Columbia University ICESI Vladimir Ruvinsky said that over the period from February to June 2022, hundreds of residents of Russia moved to the states of Central and South America.\nIt is noted that the Russians chose this macroregion for the reason that a visa is not required to visit many of its countries.\nIn addition, extending the standard 90-day residence permit is quite easy.\nMaxim Artushenko, manager of a startup in the field of e-commerce, said that the reason for moving is also the fact that some businessmen face problems doing business in Russia.\nThose who could not open their business in the Russian Federation or were forced to close it, are trying to enter new markets.\nHis words are confirmed by the manager of the investment company in Dubai.\nHe said that since the beginning of March 2022, he has received dozens of requests from businessmen from Russia who intend to move their companies to South America.\nHe believes that a Russian technological hub is gradually being formed in this region.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0019.json.gz:45128","uncompressed_offset":744015473,"url":"news.rambler.ru/community/48893856-nazvana-lokatsiya-uehavshih-iz-rossii-tsifrovyh-kochevnikov/","warc_date":"2022-06-26T12:22:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7f832a88-280e-43d5-a515-01b65d5e428d>","warc_url":"https://news.rambler.ru/community/48893856-nazvana-lokatsiya-uehavshih-iz-rossii-tsifrovyh-kochevnikov/"},"created":"2022-06-26T13:26:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"285c7275-5c5c-4c6d-924e-bdcf417d62b6_811230217":{"id":"285c7275-5c5c-4c6d-924e-bdcf417d62b6_811230217","text":"Top 10 cities in Vietnam are among the most popular among nomads! The top 10 cities are catching up with Tokyo\nInternational Center Lai Cheng-lin / General Report\nIn the wake of the pandemic, digital nomad has become the latest form of work, and many people who can \u201cwork remotely \u201d have begun to travel to other countries around the world, taking vacations and working with their computers.\nIn a survey of digital nomads, three cities in Vietnam are among the top 10 most visited places in the world for digital nomads: Da Nang, Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City.\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.\nAccording to Nomad List, the world \u2019 s largest database of remote workers, Da Nang, a coastal city in central Vietnam, ranks second behind Tokyo, Japan, with a 109% increase in the digital nomadic population in 2023; Hanoi ranks seventh with a 58% growth rate; and Ho Chi Minh City ranks ninth with a 55% growth rate.\nMost Vietnamese cities have excellent wireless access, low cost of living, and beautiful scenery, making them the latest darling of digital nomadic workers around the world.\nOf these three cities in Vietnam, Da Nang is considered the third largest city in Vietnam after Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City, with free Wi-Fi in the city center, fast internet speeds and beautiful coastline.\nAn important factor for digital nomads considering a temporary city is the living environment, as well as the cost of living to meet the convenient and comfortable working environment, while the cost of living in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City is quite low.\nThe average cost of living for a number of nomads in Hanoi is US $1,289 per month (about NT $38,000) and in Ho Chi Minh City US $1,157 per month (about NT $34,000).\nOther places on the list are Seoul, South Korea, in third place; Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in fourth place; Penang, Malaysia, in fifth place; Montevideo, Uruguay, in sixth place; Manila, Philippines, in eighth place; and Lubjana, Slovenia, in tenth place.\nTo compile the list, experts at Nomad List ranked the fastest-growing cities for remote workers by analyzing nearly 300,000 registrations in the database over the past two years.\nVietnam, with three cities on the list, does not offer a \u201cdigital nomad visa \u201d, but it offers global travelers from nearly 200 countries the ability to easily apply online for e-visas for up to 90 days, and in Southeast Asia only Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia offer special digital nomad visa programs for foreigners to work remotely if they meet certain requirements.\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0031.json.gz:26956","uncompressed_offset":811230217,"url":"www.nownews.com/news/6293782","warc_date":"2023-11-03T02:33:12.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:285c7275-5c5c-4c6d-924e-bdcf417d62b6>","warc_url":"https://www.nownews.com/news/6293782"},"created":"2023-11-03T03:50:46.000Z","lang":"eng"},"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":{"id":"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","text":"The Latest\nA Computer Goes the World: What do digital nomads bring to local communities when they go to work around the world?\nFrom Mexico to Iceland, how is the impact of digital nomad tourists traveling to destinations around the world?\nThe digital nomad life has boomed since COVID-19 and the fall of travel restrictions, but some on TikTok think the new type of traveler could be causing more harm than good.\nCredit: Daria Mamont, Unsplash\nCassie, a digital nomad from Australia, came to Bali to work for two months.\nShe wanted to experience the local community, but instead she stumbled upon the \u201cmini Australia \u201d of Canggu.\nCangu is a popular tourist attraction in Indonesia, favored by many digital nomads.\nKathy works as a virtual assistant around the world. In 2020, when she realized she could work anywhere, she thought of working as a virtual assistant on TikTok.\nWhen her lease ended last year, she gave up office work and commuting to work remotely from her favorite place, taking charge of virtual social media and email management.\nShe has seen firsthand the positive and negative impact that digital nomads can have on local communities.\nCanggu has become a popular destination for digital nomads escaping the traditional desk life.\nCredit: Cassie Gallegos, Unsplash\n\"A lot of westerners have bought [Kuragi's] restaurants and villas and they really drive up prices, which in some way pushes locals out of the market,\" she said.\nDigital nomads thrive in the era of telecommuting, often in freelance digital roles such as social media management or content creation, and even finance, where they revere the freedom to live and work overseas, free to choose their working hours and decide how to spend each day.\nThey are also being welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes offering cocktails and swimming pools, while co-op hotels offer high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities.\nCanggu is full of signs encouraging tourists to work remotely, and the economic benefits of tourism provide opportunities for the region.\nBut, as some have questioned on TikTok, is the digital nomadic movement a kind of neo-colonization?\nTourists come and go, but digital nomads can stay in one place for weeks, months or years, potentially exacerbating gentrification and the housing crisis.\nRecently, The New York Times reported that Mexico City has become a hub for digital nomads, but the surge has exacerbated the pressure on the already tight housing market, making it unaffordable for locals.\nHousing activists accused city leaders of allowing \u201cmodern colonization. \u201d\nThe rise of digital nomads\nCountries around the world are embracing the era of digital nomads, with 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offering specific visas for this new type of traveler.\nTo work remotely in Mexico, you need to prove that you have $43,000 in your savings account in the past 12 months; to Portugal, you need to have at least $4500 a month in income; to Indonesia, you need to have more than $200,000 in savings but can do \u201cinvestment and other activities. \u201d\nThe requirements mean many digital nomads use tourist visas to leave the country when their visas expire, just to re-enter.\nAccording to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting.\nOne enthusiast of the digital nomad industry predicts that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as the rise of high-speed internet and freelancing, as well as declining home ownership and marriage rates.\nAre digital nomads taking part in the new colonization?\nSome communities are opposed to the influx, and Mexico City residents say they see gentrification and housing drain problems triggered by foreigners seeking cheaper accommodation.\nAnthropologist Shaun Busuttil, a PhD candidate at the University of Melbourne who studies digital nomads, believes that digital nomads are undergoing some form of neo-colonization, but it \u2019 s not all black and white, or good and bad.\nIn an interview with Erik Muth of YouTube \u2019 s Rising Nomad channel, Basutil explained: \u201cHistorically, colonialism was when a group of people with more power or resources came into a place and effectively took over it and used the space for themselves. \u201d\n\u201cWhat are we doing as digital nomads? We go into these places, take over them, and enjoy their low cost of living. \u201d\nShops and businesses will eventually cater to the financial prowess of new visitors, Bousutier believes.\n\u201cSo the old-fashioned fruit and vegetable shop that has been in town or village for generations now has suddenly turned into a cafe to attract digital nomads.\nIs digital nomadism, then, a form of neocolonialism? \u201d he asked.\n\"Well, we're coming in and we're effectively taking over,\" he said.\n\"Look at Lisbon, or even Mexico City, or Barcelona, where locals are being replaced by foreign teleworkers and digital nomads,\" he said.\nHe told Moos that while it was usually those with fewer resources who were most affected by gentrification, those with more resources were able to take advantage of the economic opportunities offered by tourism.\nHow to avoid causing problems?\nKeith thinks deeply about the impact on the communities he visits and how it can have a positive impact.\n\"As a digital nomad, I feel like we should make sure we contribute to the local economy - eat at local restaurants, stay locally and pay a reasonable fee for that,\" said the statement.\nBoth Busutil and Casey believe tourists should pay the full price, not haggle.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s important to be aware of the impact you have on the local area, \u201d says Casey.\n\"That way you can walk into the local community, eat at the local restaurants, stay in the local area, and give back to the local community,\" said the statement.\nAt the moment, Casey likes the pace of life of digital nomads and has no plans for a pause.\n\u201cBeing able to finish work in the morning and then off work and take an adventure in the afternoon \u2013 I experienced paragliding in Laos and was great and went swimming to see the waterfall \u2013 I think when you can schedule your own time, you can experience more from life. \u201d\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 24 May 2023 11: 28am\nUpdated 5h ago 11: 48am\nBy Edwina Storie\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":77576442,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8","warc_date":"2023-05-24T06:15:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8"},"created":"2023-05-24T06:20:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"db019ab6-b296-4293-83c7-9abde9a9b8e0_856576344":{"id":"db019ab6-b296-4293-83c7-9abde9a9b8e0_856576344","text":"Work while playing! Taiwan ranked in the top 10 countries of the world 's digital nomads \"1 point\" was praised\n2024 / 07 / 05 09: 40\nAccording to William Russell, a human resources company, 10 countries are suitable for digital nomadic work, with Taiwan ranked third.\nKao Chia-ching / Authentication Editor\n[Financial Channel / Comprehensive Report] Job types have become more popular in recent years, and William Russell, a human resources company, points out that 10 countries are suitable for digital nomadic work, including Taiwan, which is also ranked third, and Taiwan \u2019 s \u201chealth care system \u201d is highly praised.\nSpain and Albania ranked first in the ranking of digital nomads, with a maximum five-year extension for digital nomads, according to the Daily Mail.\nHowever, in Spain, applicants for a digital nomad visa must have an undergraduate or postgraduate degree from a well-known university or business school, or have at least three years of work experience in the current field.\nMexico and El Salvador are tied for second place, with digital nomadic visas that can be extended for up to four years but require some proof of income to qualify.\nGermany, Malta, Taiwan and Cyprus are ranked third, and remote workers can obtain visas for up to three years.\nNorway and Portugal are ranked fourth, offering visas for up to two years.\nWilliam Cooper, marketing director at William Russell, said: \u201cThere are a lot of things to consider before moving to another country and officially becoming a digital nomad.\nFor example, in most countries or regions, it is necessary to have international health insurance to ensure that expenses such as doctor visits and hospitalization are covered while you live abroad.\n\"\"\nCountries such as Malta and Taiwan offer well-established health care systems for their residents, including expatriates and digital nomads, so they are unlikely to incur too much medical costs, Cooper said.\nI subscribe to the free finance Youtube channel.\nNo need to smoke, no need to grab, now use the APP to watch the news, guarantee the daily winning point I download the APP\nI've added friends, thank you.\nWelcome to Free Money.\nIt's a compliment. Good.\nIt has been praised, thank you.\nRelated News\nToday 's Hot News\nSee more!\nPlease join the free finance group.\nNetizens respond.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0017.json.gz:25442","uncompressed_offset":856576344,"url":"ec.ltn.com.tw/article/breakingnews/4726731","warc_date":"2024-07-05T06:05:43.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:db019ab6-b296-4293-83c7-9abde9a9b8e0>","warc_url":"https://ec.ltn.com.tw/article/breakingnews/4726731"},"created":"2024-07-05T07:04:03.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":{"id":"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","text":"  \u2022 Your one stop for college news and resources!\nFeatured, Features, Study Abroad\n\nA Guide for College Students Embracing the Digital Nomad Lifestyle\n\nA digital nomad is someone who works remotely and travels often. Their work doesn\u2019t require them to report to an office or adhere to a strict schedule. Instead, they can work anywhere in the world, doing the job they love.\n\nIt\u2019s no wonder this lifestyle is appealing more to college students. They can travel the world while studying and working abroad. That said, being a college student and a digital nomad is a challenge. It\u2019s not like a vacation where all you have to worry about is enjoying yourself.\n\nYou have to learn how to balance the fun of traveling with work and school commitments. The following tips will help you do just that.\n\nUnderstand What the Digital Nomad Lifestyle Will Be Like\n\nYou have to understand what the digital nomad lifestyle will be like if you want it to work out. You can assess whether this life is for you, and better prepare for it if you decide that it is.\n\nHere are some critical points to consider about the digital nomad lifestyle:\n\n  \u2022 A work-life balance is a must\n  \u2022 Traveling often can be exhausting\n  \u2022 You must ensure access to healthcare\n  \u2022 You need a plan for financial stability\n  \u2022 You\u2019ll have to adapt to new cultures and languages\n  \u2022 Knowing visa requirements and other legal requirements is essential\n  \u2022 You might experience homesickness, especially if you go international\n  \u2022 Balancing school with work and life in a new place is a big commitment\n\nDig into these factors and research all you\u2019ll have to do and give up to be a digital nomad. Then, you can make an informed decision about moving forward.\n\nMaster Time Management\n\nYou\u2019ll have to take your time management up a few notches if you want to be a digital nomad.\n\nIt\u2019s one thing to balance life and school. It\u2019s another to balance life, school, traveling, and potentially, work. You must learn how to divide your days so that you pay each of these things the attention they need. In addition, time management will ensure you don\u2019t burn out.\n\nStart with a routine to build some consistency into your days. Wake up at the same time regardless of your schedule and get ready for your days the same way.\n\nYou can establish priority tasks the night before, like your classes, if you\u2019re working, and when you\u2019ll study. Set aside time for breaks, meals, and leisure time as well. Building these activities into your schedule will ensure you actually do them.\n\nAttach times to each task and activity. For example, you have classes from 8 a.m. to 12 p.m. Next, you\u2019ll have lunch from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. After that, you have work from 1:30 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. Then, you\u2019ll study from 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., and the rest of the night is yours.\n\nManage your time wisely and you can achieve everything you set out for each day.\n\nLearn How to Stay Productive\n\nOne of the biggest challenges digital nomads run into is staying productive. All of the fun activities you can do when you travel to a new place can be distracting. It might be hard to stay motivated when you\u2019re homesick. Technical and logistical issues can impact your productivity as well.\n\nSo, learning how to maintain peak productivity while studying and working on the road is essential.\n\nAdhering to the routine we mentioned above will help keep you focused. Eliminate distractions while working by turning your phone on Do Not Disturb and muting social media apps. Create a designated workspace. You could also incentivize productivity by promising yourself a fun activity after you complete your work.\n\nSecure your tech setup as well to maintain optimal productivity. Make sure you have the basics, like a good laptop set up with the proper work and school software and noise-canceling headphones.\n\nAnother crucial tool to have is a mobile hotspot. A hotspot ensures you can connect to the internet wirelessly on your mobile devices from virtually anywhere. This will come in handy when you travel internationally or to places with spotty internet connections. No matter where you are, you can still access your studies and any work you\u2019re doing online.\n\nEquip yourself with the right tools and techniques to stay productive as a digital nomad.\n\nChoose Work That Aligns With Your Studies and Interests\n\nDigital nomads are known to take many different directions with their work. You have options and can easily make a living while studying and traveling abroad. The key is ensuring the work you do doesn\u2019t distract from your education and pull you away from who you are.\n\nYou\u2019ll have a much better experience as a digital nomad if you choose work that aligns with your studies and interests. Rather than taking the barista job at the local cafe, work with your school to see if there are any work-study opportunities where you\u2019re traveling.\n\nYou can also take the job search into your own hands. Search for job openings before you head to your destination through online job boards. Ask for referrals from fellow students.\n\nConsider fully remote positions as well. There are many work-from-home jobs available that can accommodate a college student\u2019s digital nomad lifestyle, such as being a tutor or a content writer for subjects related to your major.\n\nWhatever work you decide to do, make sure it doesn\u2019t take away from your studies and aligns with who you are and what you want to be.\n\nConclusion\n\nMany college students are attracted to the digital nomad lifestyle because it allows them to travel freely while studying and working where they want to. As enticing as this life is, being a digital nomad isn\u2019t void of challenges.\n\nMake sure you understand what you\u2019re getting into, master time management, learn to stay productive, and choose work that aligns with your studies and interests to give yourself a real chance at a successful digital nomad life.\n\nSEE ALSO: How to Choose the Right Student Housing in the U.S.\n\nPrevious ArticleNext Article","url":"https://www.collegenews.com/article/a-guide-for-college-students-embracing-the-digital-nomad-lifestyle/"},"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":{"id":"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748","text":"Drop everything and sail around the world\nIn recent years, the global media began to vigorously promote \"travel living\", translated from English - travel-life.\nIts supporters are called digital nomads, or digital nomads.\nThey are not attached to the place of residence and work and are ready to trade comfort, stability and career prospects for life in continuous motion.\nIn the US alone, this philosophy is shared by 22 million people, or one in 15 Americans, in the world \u2013 35 million, and by 2030, the number of digital nomads on the planet is projected to grow to one billion people.\nExperts believe that this is the way to form a \u201cseamless \u201d world with a\u201c connected person \u201d without roots.\nPhoto: Parliamentary GazetteParliamentary Newspaper\nDown with office stress\nVideo of the day\nThe first digital nomad was an American writer and programmer.\nIn 1983, he set off on a computerized bike and completed it on a yacht in 2021.\nThe revival of the ancient nomadic way of life in the 21st century has become possible thanks to the Internet and IT technologies, and the pandemic of the covid with a remote format of work has spurred it.\nBy 2030, the number of digital nomads could reach a billion people.\nWhat kind of people are these?\nThe first group is digital.\nProgrammers, project managers, graphic designers, journalists, writers, lawyers, translators, analysts, testers, copywriters, video editors, product managers.\nSix months in the Maldives, three months in Barbados or the United Arab Emirates, where the world \u2019 s fastest mobile Internet.\nThe second is adventurers and wanderers.\nThe third is mortgages, for which loan payments are more expensive than permanent tourism and being in cheap areas of the world.\nThe philosophy of digital nomads is to untie themselves from their place of birth and one job.\nChoose countries where the best climate, cheaper food, where there are no toxic offices, civil duties, but only the right to live in pleasure.\nDigital nomads consider themselves the chosen ones of fate, because, in their opinion, they make the free choice of a free person.\nLife in motion, they argue, is not bliss, but the norm.\nTheir favorite slogan is \u201cThe values of minimalism make us happy. \u201d\nNature, freedom, unprocessed food, physical activity...\nA lot is said about this on their profile sites.\nAnxiety and desire to change places\nHunting for a change of places is a problem of motives, and they are different, correspondent member, philosopher, chief researcher of the Institute of Sociology of the Russian Academy of Sciences Jean Toshchenko told the \u201cParliamentary newspaper \u201d.\nSomeone just has the opportunity to choose the best conditions of life and work.\nOthers have the pressure of economic circumstances.\nThis is facilitated by the growing class of precariat (people working in low-paid and unstable jobs without social guarantees - sick leave, vacation, with a reduced salary).\nThe transition from permanent to part-time, temporary, part-time employment makes it easier for such people to get out of place and go wherever they look.\nAnother category is those who, in principle, do not care about the content of the work, says the scientist.\nThey expect to find something to do everywhere.\nFrom here the ease of lifting.\nFinally, there are those who choose a way of life where civil obligations do not prevail over them.\nAn expert from the United States John Peters in a sensational article \u201cExile, Nomadism and the Diaspora \u201d called the opposition of nomad and state as the key idea of the movement.\nMany travelers begin with the term \u201cclimate emigration \u201d, but constant mobility erases the boundaries of cultural and national identity.\nAs a result, the concept of homeland is also being rethought, and this is already marginality, he concludes.\nA typical portrait of a digital nomad, according to the Nomad List survey, is a minimalist with a laptop, a backpack, a bachelor \u2019 s degree, a passport and a cup of coffee.\nLives in one place for an average of 70 days.\nAt the heart of the mentality is anti-materialism and contentment with small things.\nThe most attractive side of travel is cheapness, according to one of the profile sites.\nNomadism saves a lot of money because the costs of maintaining the property, maintaining the car, parking, winter clothes disappear.\nIt is fascinating and good for health.\nThe main cost item is renting a roof over your head and food.\nGeo-arbitrage helps to live better and cheaper \u2013 the use of price differences between countries.\nPeace in your pocket and nothing of your own\nSome researchers call traveling a new socio-economic model.\nIt echoes the program slogans of the \u201cgreat reset \u201d of the world proclaimed at the Davos Economic Forum.\nAccording to it, the preservation of the planet in the interests of future generations requires tightening the belts of the living, limiting economic growth and reducing consumption.\nThe projected image of the future assumes that a person will be available to the whole world, a lot of services, but at the same time he will not have anything of his own.\nGlobalizers argue that property and binding to a permanent place of residence burden and encroach on the personal freedoms of citizens.\nWhy buy a house when you can rent it?\nWhy a personal car when there is carsharing?\nWhy save money when you can have a basic guaranteed income?\nWhy spend money on heating an apartment, if you can go to the warm lands for the winter?\nWhen a person has no stake or yard, it is especially easy.\nModern nomads often call themselves citizens of the world.\nThe nomad is always online, and it is more convenient for him to communicate even with friends online, rather than offline.\nTherefore, some experts have given it the definition of \u201cconnected person \u201d.\nThe unwritten motto of digital nomads: movement is everything, goal is nothing.\nThere are 300 people in the world who have visited all 196 countries of the world (including unrecognized territories).\nAmong them are Australian Rach and Slovak Marty.\nThe women described the adventures of the 15-year-old circumnavigation in the blog \u201cVery Hungry Nomads \u201d.\nThey set out to inspire the women of the world to live without office stress, work on the beach, expand horizons and embrace new thinking.\nTravelers sold out all the property and lived with luggage from two backpacks of hand luggage.\nThe focus of their project was food.\nOdyssey cost 274 thousand dollars.\nHer conclusion: the most delicious food is in Ethiopia, Afghanistan and Uzbek farmers.\nThe number of nomadism activists in Russia is also increasing.\nFor example, ethnologist Mikhail Zarubin traveled to 193 countries for 10 years and wrote a book for children \u201cTales of Young Travelers \u201d.\nFour years more spent on the circumnavigation of his friend, the photographer.\n150 hotels annually - the norm for Lisa and Vitalik, whose journey lasts 12 years.\nMany other travel bloggers share their impressions on the website travcave.ru.\nTraffic infrastructure\nThe digital nomad relies on infrastructure.\nA digital nomad visa allows individuals who earn an income of at least $2,000 from a foreign jurisdiction to legally stay in the country longer than tourists.\nIts price in Brazil is 72 dollars, in Greece - 75, Costa Rica - 100, Argentina - from 120 to 240, in Bermuda - 260, in the Bahamas and in the UAE - a thousand dollars.\nValidity from 180 days to 10 years.\nIn countries where there is no such visa, nomads often live on tourist and even student, and the authorities turn a blind eye to this.\nThe elements of infrastructure are also coworking and coliving (common spaces where you can live and work with like-minded people).\nThe number of the first, according to forecasts, by 2025 will reach 26 thousand, and the second annually grows by a third.\nIn Russia, too, there is a coliving - \"Station Smena\".\nIt provides, according to the presentation, a unique opportunity to combine work and party.\nRemotely you can work from home, public libraries, cafes - if only there was an Internet and a laptop.\nThe wealthier ones move around in offices on wheels.\nHowever, the vans at home with a table, a lot of sockets, chargers and a background for conferences are like a luxury German crossover.\nThe system of hubs for nomads is characterized by a favorable climate, high-speed Internet, an easy visa regime and a low cost of living.\nThe most attractive locations are Chiang Mai (Thailand) and Bali (Indonesia), in Europe - Lisbon, Gran Canaria and the island of Madeira, in America - Medellin, Mexico City and Buenos Aires.\nIf the money runs out, nomads can spend the night in churches for free, in extreme cases - in a tent, especially since they do not tend to cold lands.\nSomeone on occasion earns remote trade, hand-made, bartenders, guides, DJs and VJs, nurses, teachers and what God will send.\nAs befits a philosopher, Jean Toshchenko is not surprised:\n\u201cThe world is entering an era of great migration of peoples, similar to the one that took place 15 centuries ago.\nThe process of global migration is driven by economic, political and climatic factors.\nAnd this general mobility affects all of humanity, making it dynamic. \u201d\nThe philosophy of individualism\nAnd if everyone wants to live on an eternal journey, who will remain in their native country and will improve it?\nIs there a balance between personal freedom and civic responsibility?\nIs not the sense of patriotism atrophied, for example, among the digital class, part of which has amicably rushed outside Russia?\nThe balance between freedom and responsibility was sought by Voltaire and Belinsky.\nThey are looking for it and will be looking for it at all times, \u201d the chairman of the Council for the Development of the Digital Economy evasively replied to the Parliamentary Newspaper.\nFirst Deputy Chairman of the Committee for Tourism and Tourism Development Nikolai Valuev did not hide skepticism from our publication:\n\u201cNo matter what you dream and want, people will always be tied by a bunch of circumstances to the place of residence.\nWork, habit, property, kinship and social ties, so these cosmopolitans will always be in the region of statistical error. \u201d\nComparing digital nomads, immigrants and relocants is incorrect, said the development director of VTsIOM Consulting.\nThe concept of \u201cdigital-nomadism \u201d develops a philosophy of individualism, he told\u201c Parlamentskaya Gazeta \u201d.\nIts values: freedom to choose life goals, ways and places of work, the desire for openness of information, intolerance of discrimination and the conditional \u201cseamless \u201d of the world.\nAt the same time, nomads, earning in their country, spend money in a foreign country.\nHow should this state be treated?\nWhy in the US with a population of 330 million people, Trump in his election program promises to introduce maternity capital for a new baby boom?\n\"Any government wants its citizens to work at home and develop the domestic economy,\" Yermolaev said. - The generation of the first baby boom is close to retirement age, which increases the burden on social infrastructure and reduces the number of able-bodied people.\nAnd the digital nomad community in the US is growing.\nAccording to MBO Partners, there are 16.9 million, and according to Nomand List, 22 million.\nIf the trend continues, the country \u2019 s economy will face a serious challenge in the coming years. \u201d\nIn Russia, according to Nomad List, digital nomads are still relatively few - 2.3 million.\nAnd yet they should be taken seriously, urges the dean of the Faculty of Economics.\nAs a rule, nomads do not seek to part with the country, they can continue to work for domestic companies, benefiting the state.\nAnd in order to preserve this human capital, to prevent its possible leakage, an income tax of 13 percent should be saved for this category, the economist believes.\nAccording to the current rules, tax non-residents - people who have been in Russia for less than 183 calendar days for twelve consecutive months - must pay income tax not 13 percent, but 30 percent, besides they are not entitled to tax deductions.\nAs the head of the State Duma Committee on Labor, Social Policy and Veterans Affairs Yaroslav Nilov told our publication, all the necessary regulation in the field of remote employment was developed and fixed in Chapter 49.1 of the Labor Code even during the coronavirus pandemic.\nThanks to this, many workers today work remotely, most of them within the country.\nAny changes to the law will also affect them, he explained.\nThis is usually used in a situation where there is an imbalance of interests of employers and employees.\n\u201cIf people continue to perform their duties in accordance with labor contracts, taxes and payments are deducted from their income, then why invent something? \u201d the deputy concluded.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:154842","uncompressed_offset":682732748,"url":"travel.rambler.ru/experience/50528843-brosit-vse-i-uplyt-v-krugosvetku/","warc_date":"2023-04-09T15:03:13.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891>","warc_url":"https://travel.rambler.ru/experience/50528843-brosit-vse-i-uplyt-v-krugosvetku/"},"created":"2023-04-09T15:55:57.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a3c70681-f2b9-494d-bb98-7de9c98f52da_736721641":{"id":"a3c70681-f2b9-494d-bb98-7de9c98f52da_736721641","text":"24 year old girl working in 20 countries in 5 years sharing 4 financial management tips for being a \u201cdigital nomad \u201d\nPersonal Value Added 21: 30 2023 / 06 / 10\nShare:\nShare:\nRemote work during the pandemic made home-based work or digital nomad popular, and Canadian schoolgirl Daniella Pashuk became a digital nomad five years ago.\nAt that time, the new crown had not yet broken out, and only at the age of 19, she entered an online university and began working full-time while traveling.\nThe term \u201cdigital nomads \u201d refers to people who travel freely while working remotely on the Internet.\nThey usually have the least material possessions. They work online using computers or smartphones in temporary homes, hotels, cafes, public libraries, shared offices or motorhomes. They often move between different countries and regions, and work as programmers, designers, writers, translators, etc.\n\u201cI can go where I want to go and do what I want in different countries.\nIt changed the trajectory of my life, \"she told CNBC.\nPashuk, 24, has traveled to more than 20 countries in five years and is a freelance writer whose monthly income fluctuates.\n\u201cMy monthly income ranges from $2,500 to $3,500 \u2026 Some months I travel as a family nanny, so I don \u2019 t have to pay any accommodation fees. \u201d\nIt also means that she has to plan her finances with extra care, although she can travel and work whenever she wants.\n\u201cYou have to accept a little bit of unpredictability \u2026 each month looks different because you \u2019 re often in different regions, in different currencies, with different spending, so forecasting is a challenge, \u201d she says.\nExtremes like \u201cspending 600 euros last month and 3,000 euros the next month, \u201d Pashuk recalls.\nTo be a digital nomad, she says, it \u2019 s important to keep your finances in good shape because you have to fund the lifestyle you really want.\nShe shared four financial tips for being a digital hobbyist with CNBC.\nDecide what kind of digital nomad you want to be\nPashuk says that what type of digital nomad you want to be will determine your situation.\nThe first type is people who change places frequently, going to a new place every one to two weeks.\nShe was in this state for almost two years at one time, but then stopped doing it because she found it was too stressful for her.\nThis can quickly become expensive, she said, as there is a big chance of problems with each move, such as high ticket prices, train cancellations and other extra costs.\nNow she \u2019 s a \u201cSlow Digital Nomad \u201d who stays in one place for at least a month or as long as her visa allows.\nPashuk says this helps the budget because the budget is fixed for months, and you stay in the same place and still spend the same things.\nIn addition, building an affordable \u201cbase camp \u201d can go a long way, providing some stability.\nCurrently, Pashuk has a \u201cheadquarters \u201d in Montenegro, but also works in different places:\u201c I still travel every month, but I have a place to come back. \u201d\nShe has to spend at least a certain amount each month, such as paying rent in Montenegro, but it has little impact on the total expenditure.\n2. Use the correct debit card\nWhen Pashuk started out as a digital nomad, having a stable and reliable cash flow was a huge challenge.\nHer Canadian bank account has been locked because she is constantly changing locations, which the bank thinks is a bit suspicious.\nSo she was forced to call the bank all the time.\nIn addition, when you use a Canadian card to withdraw money from a local ATM, the offshore transaction fee is also considerable.\n\u201cSometimes I lose $30 to $40 every time I withdraw cash, and if you have to withdraw it multiple times, you lose a lot of money. \u201d\nTwo years ago, she switched to a multi-currency debit card, which allowed her to top up and withdraw cash in the currency she wanted. Pashuk said she saved her freelance earnings into the card and took it to more than 20 countries without any problems.\n29-year-old nurse earns 1.5 million a year travelling the world: seizing the opportunity of high pay and working only nine months a year\n3.\nDo full research.\nShe said that as a digital traveller, in the process of moving to a workplace, it is really important to do adequate research.\nTo figure out the average local prices, determine if they fit your budget, and find the average prices for Airbnb apartments, food, and other essentials.\nBefore going somewhere, Pashuk always makes a small table of the items needed for life.\n\u201cYou never know what unknowns might creep up and steal your money. \u201d\nFor example, public transport can be prohibitively expensive in some countries. People often don \u2019 t think of this, Pashuk shares, because public transport is always cheap where you \u2019 re staying. \u201cBut I went to London and it cost a lot more than I thought, up to $20 a day. \u201d\nPay close attention to tax requirements\nPashuk also regularly keeps an eye on the latest tax requirements of different countries to ensure that a stay in one country is not long enough to be considered a tax resident.\n\"I just don't want to deal with it,\" she said. \"Canada's taxes are enough for me.\"\nIf you \u2019 re considering becoming a \u201cslow-moving digital traveller, \u201d Pashuk suggests studying digital traveller visas, as they typically offer tax relief \u2014 and some even complete exemption.\nThe more you travel, the more accurate you can predict how much you will spend, she says.\n\u201cWhere you can cut costs, you have to be a little smart.\nBeing financially proficient is definitely a good thing in the long run and can keep you moving forward. \u201d\n[Financial Freedom] My Blog Earns More Than 5 Million Dollars a Year Passive Income 33 Year-Old Young Mom: I Only Work 10 Hours a Week\n13 Simple Stupid Things for American Couples in Their 30s to Save Their First Pot of Gold\n= = = = =\n[ET Talk] Hang Seng Index or see 17,000 points? HSBC analysis Liu Shaowen looks ahead to the second half of the Hong Kong stock market trend analysis Support, resistance and value board\nDownload the Hong Kong Economic Times App for free now\nOpen hket app and read more\nColumn: Financial Gas Station\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook\nSubscribe to the Hong Kong Economic Times email newsletter\nReceive first-hand financial news Learn more about investment and financial knowledge Submit my consent to receive promotional messages from Hong Kong Economic Times Group. You may also check the privacy policy of this website Terms of Use","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0017.json.gz:11239","uncompressed_offset":736721641,"url":"wealth.hket.com/article/3544060/24%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F5%E5%B9%B4%E5%86%85%E5%9C%A820%E5%80%8B%E5%9C%8B%E5%AE%B6%E5%B7%A5%E4%BD%9C%E3%80%80%E5%88%86%E4%BA%AB%E5%81%9A%E3%80%8C%E6%95%B8%E5%AD%97%E9%81%8A%E6%B0%91%E3%80%8D%E7%9A%844%E5%80%8B%E7%90%86%E8%B2%A1%E6%8A%80%E5%B7%A7","warc_date":"2023-06-10T12:52:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a3c70681-f2b9-494d-bb98-7de9c98f52da>","warc_url":"https://wealth.hket.com/article/3544060/24%E6%AD%B2%E5%A5%B3%E7%94%9F5%E5%B9%B4%E5%86%85%E5%9C%A820%E5%80%8B%E5%9C%8B%E5%AE%B6%E5%B7%A5%E4%BD%9C%E3%80%80%E5%88%86%E4%BA%AB%E5%81%9A%E3%80%8C%E6%95%B8%E5%AD%97%E9%81%8A%E6%B0%91%E3%80%8D%E7%9A%844%E5%80%8B%E7%90%86%E8%B2%A1%E6%8A%80%E5%B7%A7"},"created":"2023-06-10T06:42:34.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1005","request_id":"1005","narrative_id":"1005"},"responses":[{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomadism refers to a lifestyle where individuals work remotely using technology, enabling them to travel and live without being tied to a specific location."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"This lifestyle has gained momentum due to advancements in IT technologies and the normalization of remote work during the COVID-19 pandemic."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Popular destinations for digital nomads include Bali, Lisbon, Chiang Mai, and Mexico City, which offer favorable climates, affordable living costs, and reliable internet connectivity."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"To support this growing trend, over 40 countries, including Spain, Portugal, and Thailand, have introduced digital nomad visas that allow longer stays and address tax and legal requirements."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"For example, Thailand offers a 10-year resident permit for remote workers meeting specific financial and professional criteria, while Japan\u2019s upcoming visa program will allow six-month stays for high-income earners."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often work in fields such as programming, graphic design, content creation, and Web3.0 industries, which are well-suited to remote work."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The lifestyle offers significant advantages, including flexibility, freedom, and the ability to balance work with unique experiences like exploring waterfalls or attending international seminars."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"However, challenges such as maintaining productivity across time zones, adapting to new cultures, and managing financial stability are common considerations for digital nomads."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Tools like mobile hotspots, remote desktop software, and platforms like Citizen Remote, which assist with visa applications and global health insurance, are essential for overcoming logistical hurdles."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Critics have raised concerns about the potential for gentrification and displacement in popular destinations, urging digital nomads to contribute positively to local economies."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, the digital nomad lifestyle is reshaping traditional work paradigms, offering a blend of professional productivity and personal exploration for those willing to embrace its complexities."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomadism refers to a lifestyle where individuals work remotely using technology, enabling them to travel and live without being tied to a specific location."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"This lifestyle has gained momentum due to advancements in IT technologies and the normalization of remote work during the COVID-19 pandemic."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Popular destinations for digital nomads include Bali, Lisbon, Chiang Mai, and Mexico City, which offer favorable climates, affordable living costs, and reliable internet connectivity."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"To support this growing trend, over 40 countries, including Spain, Portugal, and Thailand, have introduced digital nomad visas that allow longer stays and address tax and legal requirements."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"For example, Thailand offers a 10-year resident permit for remote workers meeting specific financial and professional criteria, while Japan\u2019s upcoming visa program will allow six-month stays for high-income earners."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often work in fields such as programming, graphic design, content creation, and Web3.0 industries, which are well-suited to remote work."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The lifestyle offers significant advantages, including flexibility, freedom, and the ability to balance work with unique experiences like exploring waterfalls or attending international seminars."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"However, challenges such as maintaining productivity across time zones, adapting to new cultures, and managing financial stability are common considerations for digital nomads."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Tools like mobile hotspots, remote desktop software, and platforms like Citizen Remote, which assist with visa applications and global health insurance, are essential for overcoming logistical hurdles."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Critics have raised concerns about the potential for gentrification and displacement in popular destinations, urging digital nomads to contribute positively to local economies."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, the digital nomad lifestyle is reshaping traditional work paradigms, offering a blend of professional productivity and personal exploration for those willing to embrace its complexities."}],"references":["b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748","ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041","255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899"],"documents":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":{"id":"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","text":"The Latest\nA Computer Goes the World: What do digital nomads bring to local communities when they go to work around the world?\nFrom Mexico to Iceland, how is the impact of digital nomad tourists traveling to destinations around the world?\nThe digital nomad life has boomed since COVID-19 and the fall of travel restrictions, but some on TikTok think the new type of traveler could be causing more harm than good.\nCredit: Daria Mamont, Unsplash\nCassie, a digital nomad from Australia, came to Bali to work for two months.\nShe wanted to experience the local community, but instead she stumbled upon the \u201cmini Australia \u201d of Canggu.\nCangu is a popular tourist attraction in Indonesia, favored by many digital nomads.\nKathy works as a virtual assistant around the world. In 2020, when she realized she could work anywhere, she thought of working as a virtual assistant on TikTok.\nWhen her lease ended last year, she gave up office work and commuting to work remotely from her favorite place, taking charge of virtual social media and email management.\nShe has seen firsthand the positive and negative impact that digital nomads can have on local communities.\nCanggu has become a popular destination for digital nomads escaping the traditional desk life.\nCredit: Cassie Gallegos, Unsplash\n\"A lot of westerners have bought [Kuragi's] restaurants and villas and they really drive up prices, which in some way pushes locals out of the market,\" she said.\nDigital nomads thrive in the era of telecommuting, often in freelance digital roles such as social media management or content creation, and even finance, where they revere the freedom to live and work overseas, free to choose their working hours and decide how to spend each day.\nThey are also being welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes offering cocktails and swimming pools, while co-op hotels offer high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities.\nCanggu is full of signs encouraging tourists to work remotely, and the economic benefits of tourism provide opportunities for the region.\nBut, as some have questioned on TikTok, is the digital nomadic movement a kind of neo-colonization?\nTourists come and go, but digital nomads can stay in one place for weeks, months or years, potentially exacerbating gentrification and the housing crisis.\nRecently, The New York Times reported that Mexico City has become a hub for digital nomads, but the surge has exacerbated the pressure on the already tight housing market, making it unaffordable for locals.\nHousing activists accused city leaders of allowing \u201cmodern colonization. \u201d\nThe rise of digital nomads\nCountries around the world are embracing the era of digital nomads, with 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offering specific visas for this new type of traveler.\nTo work remotely in Mexico, you need to prove that you have $43,000 in your savings account in the past 12 months; to Portugal, you need to have at least $4500 a month in income; to Indonesia, you need to have more than $200,000 in savings but can do \u201cinvestment and other activities. \u201d\nThe requirements mean many digital nomads use tourist visas to leave the country when their visas expire, just to re-enter.\nAccording to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting.\nOne enthusiast of the digital nomad industry predicts that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as the rise of high-speed internet and freelancing, as well as declining home ownership and marriage rates.\nAre digital nomads taking part in the new colonization?\nSome communities are opposed to the influx, and Mexico City residents say they see gentrification and housing drain problems triggered by foreigners seeking cheaper accommodation.\nAnthropologist Shaun Busuttil, a PhD candidate at the University of Melbourne who studies digital nomads, believes that digital nomads are undergoing some form of neo-colonization, but it \u2019 s not all black and white, or good and bad.\nIn an interview with Erik Muth of YouTube \u2019 s Rising Nomad channel, Basutil explained: \u201cHistorically, colonialism was when a group of people with more power or resources came into a place and effectively took over it and used the space for themselves. \u201d\n\u201cWhat are we doing as digital nomads? We go into these places, take over them, and enjoy their low cost of living. \u201d\nShops and businesses will eventually cater to the financial prowess of new visitors, Bousutier believes.\n\u201cSo the old-fashioned fruit and vegetable shop that has been in town or village for generations now has suddenly turned into a cafe to attract digital nomads.\nIs digital nomadism, then, a form of neocolonialism? \u201d he asked.\n\"Well, we're coming in and we're effectively taking over,\" he said.\n\"Look at Lisbon, or even Mexico City, or Barcelona, where locals are being replaced by foreign teleworkers and digital nomads,\" he said.\nHe told Moos that while it was usually those with fewer resources who were most affected by gentrification, those with more resources were able to take advantage of the economic opportunities offered by tourism.\nHow to avoid causing problems?\nKeith thinks deeply about the impact on the communities he visits and how it can have a positive impact.\n\"As a digital nomad, I feel like we should make sure we contribute to the local economy - eat at local restaurants, stay locally and pay a reasonable fee for that,\" said the statement.\nBoth Busutil and Casey believe tourists should pay the full price, not haggle.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s important to be aware of the impact you have on the local area, \u201d says Casey.\n\"That way you can walk into the local community, eat at the local restaurants, stay in the local area, and give back to the local community,\" said the statement.\nAt the moment, Casey likes the pace of life of digital nomads and has no plans for a pause.\n\u201cBeing able to finish work in the morning and then off work and take an adventure in the afternoon \u2013 I experienced paragliding in Laos and was great and went swimming to see the waterfall \u2013 I think when you can schedule your own time, you can experience more from life. \u201d\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 24 May 2023 11: 28am\nUpdated 5h ago 11: 48am\nBy Edwina Storie\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":77576442,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8","warc_date":"2023-05-24T06:15:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8"},"created":"2023-05-24T06:20:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":{"id":"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041","text":"Digital Nomad Visa Programs: An APAC Update\n\nK\nKlasko\n\nContributor\n\nKlasko Immigration Law Partners is dedicated to providing industry-leading employment-based, investment-based, and litigation immigration services to our clients. We help our clients achieve their goals by providing comprehensive immigration legal services. We have a reputation for creative solutions to difficult immigration problems through cutting-edge strategies. Our clients value our extreme responsiveness and our innovative, practical, and effective immigration strategies.\nDigital nomad visa programs have grown increasingly popular. Seen as a means of attracting top-tier, global talent and tax revenue, this trend is especially prevalent in the Asian Pacific region.\nUnited States Employment and HR\nTo print this article, all you need is to be registered or login on Mondaq.com.\n\nDigital nomad visa programs have grown increasingly popular. Seen as a means of attracting top-tier, global talent and tax revenue, this trend is especially prevalent in the Asian Pacific region. Indeed, Japan recently announced it joined the digital nomad visa party \u2013 its policy to be officially rolled out in early April 2024. Below, we discuss this new development and provide a summary of the current state of digital nomad programs in the APAC region.\n\nJapan's new digital nomad visa program: a sumo-sized development\n\nJapan's Ministry of Justice announced that Japan created a digital nomad visa. Situated as the 4th largest economy in the world, Japan began issuing digital nomad visas at the beginning of April 2024 to the citizens of 50 countries and territories.\n\nThe short-list of eligible countries includes at least the United States, Australia, and Singapore. The visas are valid for up to six months and available to those earning more than \u00a510 million (app. $68,300) per year. Nomads may work from anywhere in the country and bring their spouses and children with them. Their work must be tied to \"a sales contract or non-provision contract...with a public or private company in a foreign country\". Carrying private health insurance will be obligatory to participate in the program.\n\nBehind only China and Thailand, Japan is consistently ranked as one of the largest recipients of international visitors in APAC. In 2024 alone, it is forecasted that Japan will receive a total of 33.1 million visitors. With the aperture of this new program, coupled with sustained global interest in Japan's rich cultural heritage, the country is projected to receive thousands of digital nomads for years to come.\n\nThai-tanic-sized companies are welcomed in the Kingdom\n\nVisa options for digital nomads in Thailand remain limited. Whereas the B visa program allows visitors to enter the Kingdom for up to 90 days to engage in a short list of activities, the government has gone to greater lengths to attract international corporate investment.\n\nIndeed, under its \"Remote Workers for Well-Established Overseas Companies\" program, employees of publicly traded companies (or private companies with combined revenue of over $150 million in the last three years) will be able to apply for a 10-year long resident permit. The employee must (i) make an annual salary of at least $80,000.00 USD per year for two consecutive years or (ii) if holding a master's degree, make no less than $40,000 USD for the last two years. Alternatively, the individual may be self-employed provided they own productive intellectual property or have received Series A funding of no less than $1 million USD. Like Japan, visa applicants must carry personal health insurance.\n\nWith some of the lowest corporate tax rates in all of APAC, Thailand is situating itself as one of the region's premier hotbeds for foreign investment and, consequently, international talent.\n\nMalaysia welcomes entrepreneurs from backgrounds as diverse as their landscapes\n\nMaylasia arguably presents one of the most agile digital nomad visa programs in APAC. Offering temporary residence through the \"De Rantau Nomad\" program, employees of local or foreign employers, freelancers, and independent contractors are welcome. The nomad must be coming to work in an IT or digital space and earn at least $24,000 USD per year.\n\nPursuing a K-drama storyline in South Korea remains tricky\n\nEarly this year, South Korea made a splash on the global stage by launching its own version of a digital nomad visa: the \"Workcation\" visa. Whereas the visa program does offer a two-year period of validity, it is available only under a niche set of circumstances. For example, the minimum income threshold is KRW 85,000,000, or approximately $63,683.53. Digital nomads availing themselves must not only refrain from assuming gainful employment in South Korea, but must also refrain from earning money in South Korea associated with the South Korean economy (e.g., entering contracts with local businesses). In addition to having at least one year of work experience, nomads must also carry health insurance coverage valued at KRW 100 million, or about $75,000 USD. Given these restrictions, we anticipate S. Korea's digital nomad visa program to be leveraged only by the truest of K-POP fans.\n\nThe content of this article is intended to provide a general guide to the subject matter. Specialist advice should be sought about your specific circumstances.\n\nDigital Nomad Visa Programs: An APAC Update\n\nUnited States Employment and HR\n\nContributor\n\nKlasko Immigration Law Partners is dedicated to providing industry-leading employment-based, investment-based, and litigation immigration services to our clients. We help our clients achieve their goals by providing comprehensive immigration legal services. We have a reputation for creative solutions to difficult immigration problems through cutting-edge strategies. Our clients value our extreme responsiveness and our innovative, practical, and effective immigration strategies.\nSee More Popular Content From\n\nMondaq uses cookies on this website. By using our website you agree to our use of cookies as set out in our Privacy Policy.\n\nLearn More","url":"https://www.mondaq.com:443/unitedstates/employment-and-hr/1469128/digital-nomad-visa-programs-an-apac-update"},"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":{"id":"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","text":"Supplement\nWikiProject\nFEATURE\nChiangmai Coffee Shop Office Meeting on Bali Beach Digital Nomad Self-discipline for Freedom\nTravel + work, is it possible?\nRemote work has become a new normal in the workplace, so long as you have a laptop and a stable network, you can move the \u201coffice \u201d to any corner of the world.\nWhether it \u2019 s surfing season in the Philippines or winter in Chiang Mai, the \u201cdigital nomad \u201d lifestyle is no longer just an imagination.\nAfter 90 years, Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the epidemic to join the digital nomad, living and living in a different place, and returning to the rhythm of life. Kristie said, \u201cNomad \u2019 s gift to me is to help me clean up my life and start again. \u201d\nWhile the reporter was writing in the newspaper, Kristie, who had returned from Xinjiang for less than a month, flew to Chiang Mai, Thailand. Browse her sharing on social media platforms, she enjoyed the sunshine while leisurely working with her laptop in the open coffee shop, so that the reporter \u201cgrape \u201d\u201c bathed \u201d in the white light tube was very good. Kristie began her digital nomad career early last year. Bali, northern Thailand Chiang Mai, and then to Switzerland, a full year did not return to Hong Kong, \"began the journey about 1 month, I have decided to live such a life in the future.\"\nGet up at 8 and 9 a.m. every day, go to the beach, meditate, and work efficiently for 4 hours. After dusk, learn new things, read books, and live the creative life that many wage earners dream of.\nHe made $50,000 a month at the peak of his career.\nBefore the pasture, she worked in the advertising industry, and her body and mind were eroded by the pressure of work, and she suffered from chronic gastritis, \"(sometimes) pain so that she could not eat all day, and she would vomit after eating.\"\nFinally, the doctor said that even if the prescription of many drugs is useless, because my life pressure is too big, let her decide to change the environment, for their own life to a big clean.\nAt that time, she took the initiative to propose a 30% pay cut to her superiors, and switched from full-time employees to freelance workers.\nThere is no regular income, employee welfare, she confessed that \"initially very scared, suddenly lost the sense of security\", so she had saved six months of living reserve before leaving to prevent zero income during the period; and for themselves to open up a new source of income, operating from the media, doing small business.\nShe also became an oblique person, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations and marketing planning to maintain the nomadic living expenses, peak monthly income can reach 50,000 yuan, the off-season income is only more than 10,000 yuan, but stretched to make up for the short, life is still good.\nIn particular, she is mostly nomadic in Southeast Asia, where the consumption is low and the quality of life is good. Taking the island of Phangan in Thailand as an example, she lives in an independent holiday home, with a monthly expenditure of about 12,000 Hong Kong dollars, such as clothing, food, housing and travel.\nLow prices, good living, Indonesia, Thailand, a hot spot\nIn addition to freelancers like Kristie, there are also people engaged in online teaching, design, e-commerce, programming and other remote work, as well as enterprises due to industry characteristics, full-time employees can also work remotely, such as Kate working in the web3.0 industry. Web3.0 is a decentralized Internet based on blockchain technology, NFT, cryptocurrency, metaverse and other popular technology concepts in recent years. It is based on Web 3.0 technology.\nKate, 24, who worked as an occupational therapist for a year after graduating from college, found that she did not like working in fixed locations and hours, and wanted the freedom to travel while working as a digital nomad.\nShe is interested in cryptocurrency, so she turned to web3.0, engaged in marketing, operation of blockchain projects and other work, usually through online communication with colleagues.\n\"Web 3.0 is a more international company, with employees from all over the world, most of them do not have a physical office, and many times employees can only choose to work remotely.\"\nIt \u2019 s like living three or four different lives.\nEvery time she goes to different places to participate in seminars, and after completing her work, she will stay there for 1-2 weeks, traveling all over Japan, Thailand, Australia, Singapore, France, etc. Although she is a full-time employee, she has no fixed office hours, sometimes she does not need to turn on the computer all day, she can go sightseeing, sometimes she needs to meet and meet constantly. Bring a computer, wired headphones and plenty of mobile data.\nWhen I tried to watch animals in the Australian zoo, I suddenly had a meeting; I suddenly had to deal with work on the way to shopping in Korea, and the store has been closed for seven or eight years, which is completely different from the excellent nomadic life I imagined.\nKate, who often hangs \"work first\" and \"have self-discipline to have freedom\", admits that even the beauty of the current can not be completely relaxed and appreciated, \"I think you can not because your work location is not in a fixed place, and people feel unprofessional; it should make people believe that you can complete the work wherever you are, and there is quality, and no need for others to adapt, so as to maintain this way of life for a long.\"\nDigital nomads have bitterness and sweetness, but both say they can \u2019 t go back after they set foot on this road.\nRead this year Kristie published in the book fair, from the nomad, to find the heart of the sea \", she met on the road only two seasons of American couples, with children wandering the world of nomadic families, Lin Lin's total lifestyle has brought her a shock,\" I know in Hong Kong, many of them are a life to the end, but in the nomad meet them, I \u2019 ve lived three or four different lives, \u201d and there are fascinating stories in each life.\nEmbark on a nomadic journey to open Second Life, their book of life, and add a few unforgettable experiences.\n\u25cf\nText: Chang Shu-mei\nEditor: Liang Xiaoling\nArt: Hsieh Wai-ho\nFacebook @ Ming Pao Supplement\nCopyright \u00a9 2019 Mingpao. All Rights Reserved.\nRelated Words: Chiang Mai Visa Digital Nomad Visa Work from anywhere Digital Nomad\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:6809","uncompressed_offset":256892267,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919481762/%E6%B8%85%E9%82%81%E5%92%96%E5%95%A1%E5%BA%97%E8%BE%A6%E5%85%AC-%E5%B3%87%E9%87%8C%E6%B5%B7%E7%81%98%E6%97%81%E9%96%8B%E6%9C%83-%E6%95%B8%E7%A2%BC%E9%81%8A%E7%89%A7%E8%87%AA%E5%BE%8B%E6%8F%9B%E4%BE%86%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1","warc_date":"2023-12-19T03:26:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919481762/%E6%B8%85%E9%82%81%E5%92%96%E5%95%A1%E5%BA%97%E8%BE%A6%E5%85%AC-%E5%B3%87%E9%87%8C%E6%B5%B7%E7%81%98%E6%97%81%E9%96%8B%E6%9C%83-%E6%95%B8%E7%A2%BC%E9%81%8A%E7%89%A7%E8%87%AA%E5%BE%8B%E6%8F%9B%E4%BE%86%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1"},"created":"2023-12-19T03:41:58.000Z","lang":"eng"},"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":{"id":"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899","text":"SHARE\n\nWe may earn revenue from the products available on this page and participate in affiliate programs. Learn more \u203a\n\nIn an increasingly interconnected world, the allure of working abroad has never been stronger. The prospect of exploring new cultures, gaining international experience, and broadening one\u2019s professional horizons is undeniably enticing. However, beneath the surface of this exciting opportunity lies the complex challenge of setting up a shop in a foreign country. That\u2019s where Citizen Remote can help.\n\nRated 5/5 on the App Store, and featured in Digital Nomads Daily, Expedia, and Business Insider, Citizen Remote stands as the singular essential tool for navigating the lifestyle of remote work and is on sale now through Jan. 7. If becoming a digital nomad is part of your New Year\u2019s resolutions, this will be the best $39.97 you will spend.\n\nCitizen Remote streamlines the often complex process of working abroad by guiding individuals through every step of securing a visa. Their user-friendly web and mobile app is designed specifically for borderless remote citizens, and it offers a one-stop-shop for browsing a wide range of remote work visas available worldwide. With the app, users can easily navigate through visa applications, explore popular destinations, purchase E-sims for hassle-free communication, and build their journey all in one place.\n\nBeyond visa assistance, Citizen Remote addresses the practical aspects of relocation, offering a verified and secured inventory of rental properties for long-term accommodation. The platform ensures peace of mind during the adventure with adjustable and affordable global health insurance, allowing users to check coverage and eligibility requirements. Moreover, Citizen Remote fosters a travel-oriented community by connecting users with like-minded individuals through its social network feature. Whether you\u2019re seeking insights, finding your crowd, or exploring shared interests, the app, available for iOS and Android, provides a seamless platform for digital nomads to connect and enhance their working abroad experience.\n\nThe benefits of working abroad far outweigh the challenges for many adventurous professionals. Seeking guidance and help from Citizen Remote can help you navigate the paperwork maze and make the dream of working in a foreign land a reality.\n\nGet a lifetime subscription to Citizen Remote Premium for $39.97 (reg. $299) until 11:59 p.m. PST on Jan. 7, 2024, no coupon necessary.\u00a0\n\nWe may earn revenue from the StackSocial products available on this page and participate in affiliate programs.","url":"https://www.popsci.com/sponsored-content/citizen-remote-digital-nomad-deal/"},"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":{"id":"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431","text":"Supplement\nWikiProject\nFEATURE\nKnow more: \"Herdsmen\" may have to pay taxes in both places\n[Ming Pao News] Chen Lok Hsi, founder and chairman of China Master Global Group, said that the emerging lifestyle of digital nomads has many gray areas in tax. The group \u2019 s chief tax partner, Po-Chi Wong, said that the tax requirements and types of taxes are different in each place. It is also clear that there is no tax liability in the nomadic areas.\nShe suggested that it be possible to check whether there is a Comprehensive Avoidance of Double Taxation Agreement with Hong Kong. \"There are some indicators of the number of days (stay), such as how many days in a foreign country, it is not regarded as a local tax resident, but a Hong Kong tax resident, and it is necessary to pay tax to Hong Kong\".\nDigital Nomad Visa Can Work Legally\nIn response to this emerging lifestyle, more than 40 countries around the world, such as Spain and Portugal, have introduced \u201cdigital nomad visas \u201d to deal with tax and visa conditions. Tax exemption for a period of time to attract talent.\nKristie added that digital nomads who enter the country on a tourist visa can generally stay for a shorter period of time. After the visa expires, they may need a visa run, that is, after leaving the country, and the visa period is recalculated; while digital nomads usually provide a longer stay, some can stay for up to 5 years.\nHowever, she said that digital nomad visas generally require applicants to meet certain income requirements and provide proof of income, proof of employment, etc., which is not easy for freelancers like her to apply.\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:6812","uncompressed_offset":262065431,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919482823/%E7%9F%A5%E5%A4%9A%E5%95%B2-%E3%80%8C%E7%89%A7%E6%B0%91%E3%80%8D%E6%88%96%E9%A0%88%E5%85%A9%E5%9C%B0%E4%BA%A4%E7%A8%85","warc_date":"2023-12-19T03:26:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919482823/%E7%9F%A5%E5%A4%9A%E5%95%B2-%E3%80%8C%E7%89%A7%E6%B0%91%E3%80%8D%E6%88%96%E9%A0%88%E5%85%A9%E5%9C%B0%E4%BA%A4%E7%A8%85"},"created":"2023-12-19T03:41:39.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":{"id":"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","text":"  \u2022 Your one stop for college news and resources!\nFeatured, Features, Study Abroad\n\nA Guide for College Students Embracing the Digital Nomad Lifestyle\n\nA digital nomad is someone who works remotely and travels often. Their work doesn\u2019t require them to report to an office or adhere to a strict schedule. Instead, they can work anywhere in the world, doing the job they love.\n\nIt\u2019s no wonder this lifestyle is appealing more to college students. They can travel the world while studying and working abroad. That said, being a college student and a digital nomad is a challenge. It\u2019s not like a vacation where all you have to worry about is enjoying yourself.\n\nYou have to learn how to balance the fun of traveling with work and school commitments. The following tips will help you do just that.\n\nUnderstand What the Digital Nomad Lifestyle Will Be Like\n\nYou have to understand what the digital nomad lifestyle will be like if you want it to work out. You can assess whether this life is for you, and better prepare for it if you decide that it is.\n\nHere are some critical points to consider about the digital nomad lifestyle:\n\n  \u2022 A work-life balance is a must\n  \u2022 Traveling often can be exhausting\n  \u2022 You must ensure access to healthcare\n  \u2022 You need a plan for financial stability\n  \u2022 You\u2019ll have to adapt to new cultures and languages\n  \u2022 Knowing visa requirements and other legal requirements is essential\n  \u2022 You might experience homesickness, especially if you go international\n  \u2022 Balancing school with work and life in a new place is a big commitment\n\nDig into these factors and research all you\u2019ll have to do and give up to be a digital nomad. Then, you can make an informed decision about moving forward.\n\nMaster Time Management\n\nYou\u2019ll have to take your time management up a few notches if you want to be a digital nomad.\n\nIt\u2019s one thing to balance life and school. It\u2019s another to balance life, school, traveling, and potentially, work. You must learn how to divide your days so that you pay each of these things the attention they need. In addition, time management will ensure you don\u2019t burn out.\n\nStart with a routine to build some consistency into your days. Wake up at the same time regardless of your schedule and get ready for your days the same way.\n\nYou can establish priority tasks the night before, like your classes, if you\u2019re working, and when you\u2019ll study. Set aside time for breaks, meals, and leisure time as well. Building these activities into your schedule will ensure you actually do them.\n\nAttach times to each task and activity. For example, you have classes from 8 a.m. to 12 p.m. Next, you\u2019ll have lunch from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. After that, you have work from 1:30 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. Then, you\u2019ll study from 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., and the rest of the night is yours.\n\nManage your time wisely and you can achieve everything you set out for each day.\n\nLearn How to Stay Productive\n\nOne of the biggest challenges digital nomads run into is staying productive. All of the fun activities you can do when you travel to a new place can be distracting. It might be hard to stay motivated when you\u2019re homesick. Technical and logistical issues can impact your productivity as well.\n\nSo, learning how to maintain peak productivity while studying and working on the road is essential.\n\nAdhering to the routine we mentioned above will help keep you focused. Eliminate distractions while working by turning your phone on Do Not Disturb and muting social media apps. Create a designated workspace. You could also incentivize productivity by promising yourself a fun activity after you complete your work.\n\nSecure your tech setup as well to maintain optimal productivity. Make sure you have the basics, like a good laptop set up with the proper work and school software and noise-canceling headphones.\n\nAnother crucial tool to have is a mobile hotspot. A hotspot ensures you can connect to the internet wirelessly on your mobile devices from virtually anywhere. This will come in handy when you travel internationally or to places with spotty internet connections. No matter where you are, you can still access your studies and any work you\u2019re doing online.\n\nEquip yourself with the right tools and techniques to stay productive as a digital nomad.\n\nChoose Work That Aligns With Your Studies and Interests\n\nDigital nomads are known to take many different directions with their work. You have options and can easily make a living while studying and traveling abroad. The key is ensuring the work you do doesn\u2019t distract from your education and pull you away from who you are.\n\nYou\u2019ll have a much better experience as a digital nomad if you choose work that aligns with your studies and interests. Rather than taking the barista job at the local cafe, work with your school to see if there are any work-study opportunities where you\u2019re traveling.\n\nYou can also take the job search into your own hands. Search for job openings before you head to your destination through online job boards. Ask for referrals from fellow students.\n\nConsider fully remote positions as well. There are many work-from-home jobs available that can accommodate a college student\u2019s digital nomad lifestyle, such as being a tutor or a content writer for subjects related to your major.\n\nWhatever work you decide to do, make sure it doesn\u2019t take away from your studies and aligns with who you are and what you want to be.\n\nConclusion\n\nMany college students are attracted to the digital nomad lifestyle because it allows them to travel freely while studying and working where they want to. As enticing as this life is, being a digital nomad isn\u2019t void of challenges.\n\nMake sure you understand what you\u2019re getting into, master time management, learn to stay productive, and choose work that aligns with your studies and interests to give yourself a real chance at a successful digital nomad life.\n\nSEE ALSO: How to Choose the Right Student Housing in the U.S.\n\nPrevious ArticleNext Article","url":"https://www.collegenews.com/article/a-guide-for-college-students-embracing-the-digital-nomad-lifestyle/"},"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":{"id":"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748","text":"Drop everything and sail around the world\nIn recent years, the global media began to vigorously promote \"travel living\", translated from English - travel-life.\nIts supporters are called digital nomads, or digital nomads.\nThey are not attached to the place of residence and work and are ready to trade comfort, stability and career prospects for life in continuous motion.\nIn the US alone, this philosophy is shared by 22 million people, or one in 15 Americans, in the world \u2013 35 million, and by 2030, the number of digital nomads on the planet is projected to grow to one billion people.\nExperts believe that this is the way to form a \u201cseamless \u201d world with a\u201c connected person \u201d without roots.\nPhoto: Parliamentary GazetteParliamentary Newspaper\nDown with office stress\nVideo of the day\nThe first digital nomad was an American writer and programmer.\nIn 1983, he set off on a computerized bike and completed it on a yacht in 2021.\nThe revival of the ancient nomadic way of life in the 21st century has become possible thanks to the Internet and IT technologies, and the pandemic of the covid with a remote format of work has spurred it.\nBy 2030, the number of digital nomads could reach a billion people.\nWhat kind of people are these?\nThe first group is digital.\nProgrammers, project managers, graphic designers, journalists, writers, lawyers, translators, analysts, testers, copywriters, video editors, product managers.\nSix months in the Maldives, three months in Barbados or the United Arab Emirates, where the world \u2019 s fastest mobile Internet.\nThe second is adventurers and wanderers.\nThe third is mortgages, for which loan payments are more expensive than permanent tourism and being in cheap areas of the world.\nThe philosophy of digital nomads is to untie themselves from their place of birth and one job.\nChoose countries where the best climate, cheaper food, where there are no toxic offices, civil duties, but only the right to live in pleasure.\nDigital nomads consider themselves the chosen ones of fate, because, in their opinion, they make the free choice of a free person.\nLife in motion, they argue, is not bliss, but the norm.\nTheir favorite slogan is \u201cThe values of minimalism make us happy. \u201d\nNature, freedom, unprocessed food, physical activity...\nA lot is said about this on their profile sites.\nAnxiety and desire to change places\nHunting for a change of places is a problem of motives, and they are different, correspondent member, philosopher, chief researcher of the Institute of Sociology of the Russian Academy of Sciences Jean Toshchenko told the \u201cParliamentary newspaper \u201d.\nSomeone just has the opportunity to choose the best conditions of life and work.\nOthers have the pressure of economic circumstances.\nThis is facilitated by the growing class of precariat (people working in low-paid and unstable jobs without social guarantees - sick leave, vacation, with a reduced salary).\nThe transition from permanent to part-time, temporary, part-time employment makes it easier for such people to get out of place and go wherever they look.\nAnother category is those who, in principle, do not care about the content of the work, says the scientist.\nThey expect to find something to do everywhere.\nFrom here the ease of lifting.\nFinally, there are those who choose a way of life where civil obligations do not prevail over them.\nAn expert from the United States John Peters in a sensational article \u201cExile, Nomadism and the Diaspora \u201d called the opposition of nomad and state as the key idea of the movement.\nMany travelers begin with the term \u201cclimate emigration \u201d, but constant mobility erases the boundaries of cultural and national identity.\nAs a result, the concept of homeland is also being rethought, and this is already marginality, he concludes.\nA typical portrait of a digital nomad, according to the Nomad List survey, is a minimalist with a laptop, a backpack, a bachelor \u2019 s degree, a passport and a cup of coffee.\nLives in one place for an average of 70 days.\nAt the heart of the mentality is anti-materialism and contentment with small things.\nThe most attractive side of travel is cheapness, according to one of the profile sites.\nNomadism saves a lot of money because the costs of maintaining the property, maintaining the car, parking, winter clothes disappear.\nIt is fascinating and good for health.\nThe main cost item is renting a roof over your head and food.\nGeo-arbitrage helps to live better and cheaper \u2013 the use of price differences between countries.\nPeace in your pocket and nothing of your own\nSome researchers call traveling a new socio-economic model.\nIt echoes the program slogans of the \u201cgreat reset \u201d of the world proclaimed at the Davos Economic Forum.\nAccording to it, the preservation of the planet in the interests of future generations requires tightening the belts of the living, limiting economic growth and reducing consumption.\nThe projected image of the future assumes that a person will be available to the whole world, a lot of services, but at the same time he will not have anything of his own.\nGlobalizers argue that property and binding to a permanent place of residence burden and encroach on the personal freedoms of citizens.\nWhy buy a house when you can rent it?\nWhy a personal car when there is carsharing?\nWhy save money when you can have a basic guaranteed income?\nWhy spend money on heating an apartment, if you can go to the warm lands for the winter?\nWhen a person has no stake or yard, it is especially easy.\nModern nomads often call themselves citizens of the world.\nThe nomad is always online, and it is more convenient for him to communicate even with friends online, rather than offline.\nTherefore, some experts have given it the definition of \u201cconnected person \u201d.\nThe unwritten motto of digital nomads: movement is everything, goal is nothing.\nThere are 300 people in the world who have visited all 196 countries of the world (including unrecognized territories).\nAmong them are Australian Rach and Slovak Marty.\nThe women described the adventures of the 15-year-old circumnavigation in the blog \u201cVery Hungry Nomads \u201d.\nThey set out to inspire the women of the world to live without office stress, work on the beach, expand horizons and embrace new thinking.\nTravelers sold out all the property and lived with luggage from two backpacks of hand luggage.\nThe focus of their project was food.\nOdyssey cost 274 thousand dollars.\nHer conclusion: the most delicious food is in Ethiopia, Afghanistan and Uzbek farmers.\nThe number of nomadism activists in Russia is also increasing.\nFor example, ethnologist Mikhail Zarubin traveled to 193 countries for 10 years and wrote a book for children \u201cTales of Young Travelers \u201d.\nFour years more spent on the circumnavigation of his friend, the photographer.\n150 hotels annually - the norm for Lisa and Vitalik, whose journey lasts 12 years.\nMany other travel bloggers share their impressions on the website travcave.ru.\nTraffic infrastructure\nThe digital nomad relies on infrastructure.\nA digital nomad visa allows individuals who earn an income of at least $2,000 from a foreign jurisdiction to legally stay in the country longer than tourists.\nIts price in Brazil is 72 dollars, in Greece - 75, Costa Rica - 100, Argentina - from 120 to 240, in Bermuda - 260, in the Bahamas and in the UAE - a thousand dollars.\nValidity from 180 days to 10 years.\nIn countries where there is no such visa, nomads often live on tourist and even student, and the authorities turn a blind eye to this.\nThe elements of infrastructure are also coworking and coliving (common spaces where you can live and work with like-minded people).\nThe number of the first, according to forecasts, by 2025 will reach 26 thousand, and the second annually grows by a third.\nIn Russia, too, there is a coliving - \"Station Smena\".\nIt provides, according to the presentation, a unique opportunity to combine work and party.\nRemotely you can work from home, public libraries, cafes - if only there was an Internet and a laptop.\nThe wealthier ones move around in offices on wheels.\nHowever, the vans at home with a table, a lot of sockets, chargers and a background for conferences are like a luxury German crossover.\nThe system of hubs for nomads is characterized by a favorable climate, high-speed Internet, an easy visa regime and a low cost of living.\nThe most attractive locations are Chiang Mai (Thailand) and Bali (Indonesia), in Europe - Lisbon, Gran Canaria and the island of Madeira, in America - Medellin, Mexico City and Buenos Aires.\nIf the money runs out, nomads can spend the night in churches for free, in extreme cases - in a tent, especially since they do not tend to cold lands.\nSomeone on occasion earns remote trade, hand-made, bartenders, guides, DJs and VJs, nurses, teachers and what God will send.\nAs befits a philosopher, Jean Toshchenko is not surprised:\n\u201cThe world is entering an era of great migration of peoples, similar to the one that took place 15 centuries ago.\nThe process of global migration is driven by economic, political and climatic factors.\nAnd this general mobility affects all of humanity, making it dynamic. \u201d\nThe philosophy of individualism\nAnd if everyone wants to live on an eternal journey, who will remain in their native country and will improve it?\nIs there a balance between personal freedom and civic responsibility?\nIs not the sense of patriotism atrophied, for example, among the digital class, part of which has amicably rushed outside Russia?\nThe balance between freedom and responsibility was sought by Voltaire and Belinsky.\nThey are looking for it and will be looking for it at all times, \u201d the chairman of the Council for the Development of the Digital Economy evasively replied to the Parliamentary Newspaper.\nFirst Deputy Chairman of the Committee for Tourism and Tourism Development Nikolai Valuev did not hide skepticism from our publication:\n\u201cNo matter what you dream and want, people will always be tied by a bunch of circumstances to the place of residence.\nWork, habit, property, kinship and social ties, so these cosmopolitans will always be in the region of statistical error. \u201d\nComparing digital nomads, immigrants and relocants is incorrect, said the development director of VTsIOM Consulting.\nThe concept of \u201cdigital-nomadism \u201d develops a philosophy of individualism, he told\u201c Parlamentskaya Gazeta \u201d.\nIts values: freedom to choose life goals, ways and places of work, the desire for openness of information, intolerance of discrimination and the conditional \u201cseamless \u201d of the world.\nAt the same time, nomads, earning in their country, spend money in a foreign country.\nHow should this state be treated?\nWhy in the US with a population of 330 million people, Trump in his election program promises to introduce maternity capital for a new baby boom?\n\"Any government wants its citizens to work at home and develop the domestic economy,\" Yermolaev said. - The generation of the first baby boom is close to retirement age, which increases the burden on social infrastructure and reduces the number of able-bodied people.\nAnd the digital nomad community in the US is growing.\nAccording to MBO Partners, there are 16.9 million, and according to Nomand List, 22 million.\nIf the trend continues, the country \u2019 s economy will face a serious challenge in the coming years. \u201d\nIn Russia, according to Nomad List, digital nomads are still relatively few - 2.3 million.\nAnd yet they should be taken seriously, urges the dean of the Faculty of Economics.\nAs a rule, nomads do not seek to part with the country, they can continue to work for domestic companies, benefiting the state.\nAnd in order to preserve this human capital, to prevent its possible leakage, an income tax of 13 percent should be saved for this category, the economist believes.\nAccording to the current rules, tax non-residents - people who have been in Russia for less than 183 calendar days for twelve consecutive months - must pay income tax not 13 percent, but 30 percent, besides they are not entitled to tax deductions.\nAs the head of the State Duma Committee on Labor, Social Policy and Veterans Affairs Yaroslav Nilov told our publication, all the necessary regulation in the field of remote employment was developed and fixed in Chapter 49.1 of the Labor Code even during the coronavirus pandemic.\nThanks to this, many workers today work remotely, most of them within the country.\nAny changes to the law will also affect them, he explained.\nThis is usually used in a situation where there is an imbalance of interests of employers and employees.\n\u201cIf people continue to perform their duties in accordance with labor contracts, taxes and payments are deducted from their income, then why invent something? \u201d the deputy concluded.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:154842","uncompressed_offset":682732748,"url":"travel.rambler.ru/experience/50528843-brosit-vse-i-uplyt-v-krugosvetku/","warc_date":"2023-04-09T15:03:13.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891>","warc_url":"https://travel.rambler.ru/experience/50528843-brosit-vse-i-uplyt-v-krugosvetku/"},"created":"2023-04-09T15:55:57.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":{"id":"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649","text":"Skip to main content\n+ 1.408.886.7177 Free Trial\nRemote work\nStay Connected Anywhere: Remote Desktop for Digital Travellers\nby Verena Cooper\nUpdated\nSubscribe\nNews RSS feed\nShare\nAs the world rapidly adapts to the digital revolution, we are witnessing the rise of a new type of worker: digital nomads.\nDigital nomads are professionals who work remotely using technology, enabling them to travel and live a lifestyle unrelated to location.\nThis trend of nomadic working life is more than just a fad; it \u2019 s a sweeping shift in the way we look at work, and it \u2019 s made possible thanks in large part to advances in technologies such as remote storage and remote desktop software.\nRemote desktop storage has become an important tool for digital nomads.\nWith it, they can access their work computer or office network from anywhere in the world as long as they have an internet connection.\nThis ability to work remotely not only provides flexibility, but also allows digital nomads to maintain high levels of productivity wherever they are.\nSplashtop understands the complexity of this lifestyle and is committed to providing solutions to address the unique challenges faced by digital travelers, such as connectivity issues and secure access to remote resources.\nWe strive to improve the flexibility provided by this lifestyle, aiming to make the world a seamless workspace.\nWith the right remote desktop and remote storage tools, the world can indeed be your workplace.\nThat \u2019 s the power of technology today \u2013 it makes geography irrelevant, it \u2019 s changing the way we work, travel and live.\nWelcome to the digital nomadic world powered by Splashtop \u2019 s remote desktop solutions.\nDefining digital nomads and their challenges\nDigital nomadism is the practice of doing work by relying on digital technology, often for remote work from abroad.\nThis lifestyle offers enticing benefits such as flexibility, freedom and the charm of travel.\nHowever, this is not without challenges.\nThe key is connectivity issues due to different global internet stability and maintaining productivity in different time zones and environments.\nThe right tools, including reliable remote desktop software, can help address these challenges and make digital nomadic a rewarding and efficient way to work.\nRemote Desktop: Solutions for Digital Travellers\nRemote desktop software bridges the connection between your device and computer by using the Internet as a medium.\nThis process involves using two applications, even the \"client\" application on the portable device and the \"proxy\" application installed on the desktop.\nThis duo enables you to establish a remote desktop connection that effectively lets you control and interact with your desktop, regardless of time and place, as if you were immersive.\nBasically, you can control your primary computer, access files, use apps, and even perform complex tasks from a remote location, all as if you were sitting in front of your computer.\nDigital nomads can leverage remote desktop technology to dramatically increase their productivity.\nFor example, let \u2019 s say you \u2019 re a digital hobbyist who often uses specialized software installed on your home computer.\nWith remote desktop storage, you can use your laptop or even tablet to run this software from anywhere in the world without having to carry your home computer with you.\nAlternatively, you may be a software developer or graphic designer (and also a digital nomad!) and you may need access to a powerful home desktop for coding or testing.\nBy using remote desktop software, you can take advantage of the processing power of your home computer to run intensive applications smoothly while traveling from a portable laptop or even tablet.\nAs a digital hobbyist, you may be worried that the main computer in your home is going into sleep mode, which may interrupt your remote storage.\nThis can interfere with your workflow, especially if you are in a different time zone or location.\nHowever, with Splashtop, this concern is a thing of the past. Splashtop offers a \u201cWake Up Computer \u201d feature specifically designed to wake your remote computer from its sleep state.\nThis feature ensures that you can always connect to your computer, no matter where you are in the world, providing an uninterrupted, reliable remote storage experience.\nRemote desktop tools also provide secure access to your files without the need to sync or transfer them across devices, reducing the risk of data loss or theft.\nThis technology is also beneficial when digital nomads need to collaborate with team members in real time, as they can remotely access a colleague \u2019 s computer to get help or perform a task.\nOne of the major benefits that remote desktop storage brings to digital travelers is the ability to overcome the unpredictability of travel.\nWhether it \u2019 s an unforeseen situation that causes a hardware failure, or simply an inability to access a specific document, a remote desktop solution can provide the necessary buffers to keep your workflow running smoothly.\nOne such solution is Splashtop, which is designed to provide secure and reliable remote storage. With a user-friendly interface and strong connectivity, Splashtop supports a seamless remote work experience.\nIt is an effective tool for connecting to your main computer from any other device (laptop, tablet or even smartphone).\nIts cross-platform features allow you to work across operating systems without compatibility issues.\nAll of this doesn \u2019 t require a lot of technical setup. All you need is an internet connection.\nWith Splashtop or similar tools, the world truly becomes a workspace for digital hobbyists, making geography a consideration of the past.\nTips for Using Remote Desktop Storage Effectively\nChoosing the right remote desktop tool is critical to getting the benefits of this technology.\nWhen choosing a tool, consider factors such as ease of use, reliability, speed, and security features.\nCompatibility with different operating systems and devices is also an important factor, especially for digital nomads who may use various devices.\nEnsuring safe and smooth remote storage is just as important.\nFind tools that provide robust security measures such as two-factor authentication and data encryption.\nA reliable internet connection also plays a vital role in ensuring smooth access.\nIt is recommended to use backup connection options in case of network instability, such as portable Wi-Fi or mobile hotspots.\nWith Splashtop \u2019 s adaptive streaming technology, you can still experience high-performance remote storage even on less than perfect internet connections, ensuring a seamless digital nomadic experience.\nWith Splashtop Remote Desktop Software, you will be able to...\n\u2022 Work from home or anywhere in the world by accessing your work computer from any device without having to worry about transferring data to the cloud or investing in additional hardware or software licenses.\n\u2022 Experience real-time, high-definition viewing of a remote computer screen, delivering up to 4K streaming at 40 frames per second for a low-latency remote storage experience.\nControl your computer remotely from another computer, tablet, or mobile device as if you were sitting directly in front of it.\n\u2022 Direct access and modification of any document on a remote computer without cloud upload or email transfer.\n\u2022 Operate any software on a remote computer, from Adobe Creative Suite and video editing applications to CAD programs and much more.\nSecurity is a top priority at Splashtop, and we protect your and your company \u2019 s data with encrypted connections, multi-level password options, two-factor authentication, and other features.\nLearn more about Splashtop \u2019 s security and sign up for a free trial to experience it for yourself!\nConclusion \u2013 Remote Desktop for Digital Nomads\nEmbracing the digital nomadic lifestyle requires versatile tools to meet the unique challenges of remote work.\nRemote desktop storage is an indispensable tool that increases flexibility and ensures productivity no matter where you are.\nIt allows you to access and control your main computer from a remote location, use specific software, and securely access your files.\nTools like Splashtop provide a seamless remote work experience that digital hobbyists anywhere in the world can rely on.\nBy offering a combination of strong connectivity, cross-platform compatibility, security features, and high-performance streaming, Splashtop is the ideal companion for digital hobbyists, hybrid workers, and remote workers.\nReady to unleash your full potential as a digital nomad?\nLearn more about Splashtop \u2019 s remote desktop software and discover how it can revolutionize your remote work experience.\nSign up for a free trial now!\nVerena Cooper\nVerena is an International SEO Manager at Splashtop.\nFree Trial\nRelated Content\nCustomer focus\nThis Week \u2019 s Featured Comments\nIn-depth knowledge\nCompare\nScaling Alternatives to Remote IT Support\nIn-depth knowledge\nRemote Learning and Education\nDemo video: Using Chromebooks to remotely access Windows and Mac computers\nIn-depth knowledge\nRemote Learning and Education\nSolve online education challenges with remote access and document security software\nIn-depth knowledge\nView All Blogs\nWe'd love to hear from you.\nContact Us\nGet the latest Splashtop news and special offers\nSubscribe Now\n\u2022 Standard Specification\n\u2022 Privacy Policy\n\u2022 Terms of Use\nCopyright \u00a9 2023 Splashtop Inc.\nAll rights reserved.\n$Prices shown are in USD","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0018.json.gz:4164","uncompressed_offset":37536649,"url":"www.splashtop.com/tw/blog/remote-desktop-for-digital-nomads","warc_date":"2023-06-18T06:22:01.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd>","warc_url":"https://www.splashtop.com/tw/blog/remote-desktop-for-digital-nomads"},"created":"2023-06-18T06:25:46.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1006","request_id":"1006","narrative_id":"1006"},"responses":[{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads are individuals who prioritize continuous movement over stability and comfort, working remotely while traveling to various locations."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"This lifestyle has been enabled by advancements in internet technology and the normalization of remote work during the COVID-19 pandemic."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"By 2030, the global population of digital nomads is projected to reach one billion, reflecting the growing appeal of this lifestyle."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomadism involves leveraging digital technology to perform remote work, often from abroad, without being tied to a specific location."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"In 2019, 7.3 million Americans identified as digital nomads, marking an increase of 2.5 million from the previous year."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"The COVID-19 pandemic has further accelerated the adoption of remote work, contributing to the rise in digital nomadism."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Popular destinations for digital nomads include Chiang Mai, Bali, Lisbon, Gran Canaria, Madeira, Medellin, Mexico City, and Buenos Aires, which offer favorable climates, high-speed internet, and affordable living costs."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Southeast Asia, particularly Indonesia and Thailand, is a preferred region for digital nomads due to its low living costs and high quality of life."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"While digital nomadism can bring economic benefits to host locations, it has also been criticized for contributing to gentrification and housing pressures."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Anthropologist Shaun Busuttil highlights that digital nomads often take over spaces, enjoying low living costs but potentially displacing local residents."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"To mitigate negative impacts, digital nomads are encouraged to support local economies by patronizing local businesses and paying fair prices."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomad visas allow individuals earning income from foreign jurisdictions to legally stay in countries for extended periods, with costs ranging from $72 in Brazil to $1,000 in the UAE."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Japan's digital nomad visa program, launching in April 2024, permits remote work for up to six months for citizens of 50 countries, provided they meet income and health insurance requirements."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Thailand offers a 10-year resident permit for remote workers employed by large international companies or self-employed individuals who meet specific financial and professional criteria."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Malaysia's 'De Rantau Nomad' program welcomes remote workers in IT or digital fields earning at least $24,000 USD annually."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"South Korea's 'Workcation' visa provides a two-year validity but imposes strict conditions, including a minimum income threshold and restrictions on earning money tied to the South Korean economy."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"More than 40 countries, including Spain and Portugal, have introduced digital nomad visas to address tax and visa conditions for remote workers."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"Digital nomad visas often provide longer stays, with some allowing up to five years of residence."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"Eligibility for digital nomad visas typically requires proof of income, employment, and meeting minimum income thresholds."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Challenges for digital nomads include connectivity issues due to varying global internet stability and maintaining productivity across different time zones."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Key considerations for digital nomads include maintaining a work-life balance, managing financial stability, and adapting to new cultures and languages."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Understanding visa requirements and legal obligations is essential for digital nomads traveling internationally."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Access to reliable healthcare and managing homesickness are important aspects of the digital nomad lifestyle."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Time management is crucial for digital nomads to balance work, travel, and personal commitments effectively."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Establishing a daily routine and prioritizing tasks can help digital nomads maintain consistency and avoid burnout."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Creating a designated workspace and eliminating distractions are strategies to stay productive as a digital nomad."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Critics argue that digital nomadism can contribute to neo-colonialism by driving up local prices and displacing residents."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often face challenges such as balancing work and leisure, maintaining professionalism, and adapting to unpredictable schedules."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle offers enticing benefits such as flexibility, freedom, and the charm of travel."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The flexibility of this lifestyle allows individuals to balance work with unique experiences, such as paragliding or exploring waterfalls."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads report higher job satisfaction, with 91 percent citing flexibility as a primary benefit."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":100.0},"text":"A US study found that digital nomads are 45 percent more productive than their office-based counterparts."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Both Kristie and Kate agree that once they embraced the digital nomad lifestyle, they could not imagine returning to traditional work settings."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often work in professions such as programming, graphic design, journalism, writing, translation, video editing, and project management."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Freelance digital roles such as social media management, content creation, and finance are particularly suited to the nomadic lifestyle."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie transitioned from a full-time advertising job to freelance work, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations, and marketing planning to sustain her nomadic lifestyle."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate transitioned from being an occupational therapist to working in the Web3.0 industry, which allows her to work remotely while traveling internationally."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Web3.0 companies often operate without physical offices, enabling employees to work remotely from anywhere in the world."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate's work in blockchain marketing and operations involves online communication with colleagues and traveling to seminars in various countries."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Remote desktop software bridges the connection between a device and computer, using the internet as a medium."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads can leverage remote desktop technology to dramatically increase their productivity by accessing specialized software or powerful home desktops remotely."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Remote desktop tools provide secure access to files without the need to sync or transfer them across devices, reducing the risk of data loss or theft."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Backup connection options like portable Wi-Fi or mobile hotspots are recommended to ensure smooth access during network instability."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote is a tool designed to assist digital nomads with visa applications and relocation processes."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"The Citizen Remote app provides a one-stop-shop for browsing remote work visas available worldwide."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote offers features such as E-sim purchases for communication and a verified inventory of rental properties for long-term accommodation."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"The platform includes adjustable and affordable global health insurance options for digital nomads."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote fosters a travel-oriented community by connecting users with like-minded individuals through its social network feature."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the pandemic to embrace the digital nomad lifestyle, living in different places and rediscovering their rhythm of life."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie described the digital nomad lifestyle as a way to clean up her life and start anew."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie has traveled to Bali, northern Thailand, Chiang Mai, and Switzerland, living as a digital nomad for over a year without returning to Hong Kong."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie's daily routine includes meditation, efficient work for four hours, and creative activities like reading and learning new things."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie saved six months of living expenses before transitioning to freelance work to ensure financial security during the initial phase."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate emphasizes the importance of self-discipline and professionalism to maintain the digital nomad lifestyle long-term."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The rise of digital nomads is driven by factors such as high-speed internet, freelancing opportunities, declining home ownership, and lower marriage rates."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads are welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes and co-op hotels offering amenities like high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"The emerging lifestyle of digital nomads has many gray areas in tax regulations, with tax requirements differing by location."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"Research from MBO Partners suggests that digital nomads are increasingly populating campgrounds and public lands."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads are individuals who prioritize continuous movement over stability and comfort, working remotely while traveling to various locations."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"This lifestyle has been enabled by advancements in internet technology and the normalization of remote work during the COVID-19 pandemic."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"By 2030, the global population of digital nomads is projected to reach one billion, reflecting the growing appeal of this lifestyle."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomadism involves leveraging digital technology to perform remote work, often from abroad, without being tied to a specific location."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"In 2019, 7.3 million Americans identified as digital nomads, marking an increase of 2.5 million from the previous year."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"The COVID-19 pandemic has further accelerated the adoption of remote work, contributing to the rise in digital nomadism."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Popular destinations for digital nomads include Chiang Mai, Bali, Lisbon, Gran Canaria, Madeira, Medellin, Mexico City, and Buenos Aires, which offer favorable climates, high-speed internet, and affordable living costs."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Southeast Asia, particularly Indonesia and Thailand, is a preferred region for digital nomads due to its low living costs and high quality of life."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"While digital nomadism can bring economic benefits to host locations, it has also been criticized for contributing to gentrification and housing pressures."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Anthropologist Shaun Busuttil highlights that digital nomads often take over spaces, enjoying low living costs but potentially displacing local residents."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"To mitigate negative impacts, digital nomads are encouraged to support local economies by patronizing local businesses and paying fair prices."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomad visas allow individuals earning income from foreign jurisdictions to legally stay in countries for extended periods, with costs ranging from $72 in Brazil to $1,000 in the UAE."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Japan's digital nomad visa program, launching in April 2024, permits remote work for up to six months for citizens of 50 countries, provided they meet income and health insurance requirements."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Thailand offers a 10-year resident permit for remote workers employed by large international companies or self-employed individuals who meet specific financial and professional criteria."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"Malaysia's 'De Rantau Nomad' program welcomes remote workers in IT or digital fields earning at least $24,000 USD annually."},{"citations":{"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":100.0},"text":"South Korea's 'Workcation' visa provides a two-year validity but imposes strict conditions, including a minimum income threshold and restrictions on earning money tied to the South Korean economy."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"More than 40 countries, including Spain and Portugal, have introduced digital nomad visas to address tax and visa conditions for remote workers."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"Digital nomad visas often provide longer stays, with some allowing up to five years of residence."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"Eligibility for digital nomad visas typically requires proof of income, employment, and meeting minimum income thresholds."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Challenges for digital nomads include connectivity issues due to varying global internet stability and maintaining productivity across different time zones."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Key considerations for digital nomads include maintaining a work-life balance, managing financial stability, and adapting to new cultures and languages."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Understanding visa requirements and legal obligations is essential for digital nomads traveling internationally."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Access to reliable healthcare and managing homesickness are important aspects of the digital nomad lifestyle."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Time management is crucial for digital nomads to balance work, travel, and personal commitments effectively."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Establishing a daily routine and prioritizing tasks can help digital nomads maintain consistency and avoid burnout."},{"citations":{"4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390":100.0},"text":"Creating a designated workspace and eliminating distractions are strategies to stay productive as a digital nomad."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Critics argue that digital nomadism can contribute to neo-colonialism by driving up local prices and displacing residents."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often face challenges such as balancing work and leisure, maintaining professionalism, and adapting to unpredictable schedules."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"The digital nomad lifestyle offers enticing benefits such as flexibility, freedom, and the charm of travel."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The flexibility of this lifestyle allows individuals to balance work with unique experiences, such as paragliding or exploring waterfalls."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads report higher job satisfaction, with 91 percent citing flexibility as a primary benefit."},{"citations":{"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":100.0},"text":"A US study found that digital nomads are 45 percent more productive than their office-based counterparts."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Both Kristie and Kate agree that once they embraced the digital nomad lifestyle, they could not imagine returning to traditional work settings."},{"citations":{"72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads often work in professions such as programming, graphic design, journalism, writing, translation, video editing, and project management."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Freelance digital roles such as social media management, content creation, and finance are particularly suited to the nomadic lifestyle."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie transitioned from a full-time advertising job to freelance work, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations, and marketing planning to sustain her nomadic lifestyle."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate transitioned from being an occupational therapist to working in the Web3.0 industry, which allows her to work remotely while traveling internationally."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Web3.0 companies often operate without physical offices, enabling employees to work remotely from anywhere in the world."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate's work in blockchain marketing and operations involves online communication with colleagues and traveling to seminars in various countries."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Remote desktop software bridges the connection between a device and computer, using the internet as a medium."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads can leverage remote desktop technology to dramatically increase their productivity by accessing specialized software or powerful home desktops remotely."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Remote desktop tools provide secure access to files without the need to sync or transfer them across devices, reducing the risk of data loss or theft."},{"citations":{"b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649":100.0},"text":"Backup connection options like portable Wi-Fi or mobile hotspots are recommended to ensure smooth access during network instability."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote is a tool designed to assist digital nomads with visa applications and relocation processes."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"The Citizen Remote app provides a one-stop-shop for browsing remote work visas available worldwide."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote offers features such as E-sim purchases for communication and a verified inventory of rental properties for long-term accommodation."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"The platform includes adjustable and affordable global health insurance options for digital nomads."},{"citations":{"255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899":100.0},"text":"Citizen Remote fosters a travel-oriented community by connecting users with like-minded individuals through its social network feature."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the pandemic to embrace the digital nomad lifestyle, living in different places and rediscovering their rhythm of life."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie described the digital nomad lifestyle as a way to clean up her life and start anew."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie has traveled to Bali, northern Thailand, Chiang Mai, and Switzerland, living as a digital nomad for over a year without returning to Hong Kong."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie's daily routine includes meditation, efficient work for four hours, and creative activities like reading and learning new things."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kristie saved six months of living expenses before transitioning to freelance work to ensure financial security during the initial phase."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":100.0},"text":"Kate emphasizes the importance of self-discipline and professionalism to maintain the digital nomad lifestyle long-term."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"The rise of digital nomads is driven by factors such as high-speed internet, freelancing opportunities, declining home ownership, and lower marriage rates."},{"citations":{"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":100.0},"text":"Digital nomads are welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes and co-op hotels offering amenities like high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities."},{"citations":{"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431":100.0},"text":"The emerging lifestyle of digital nomads has many gray areas in tax regulations, with tax requirements differing by location."},{"citations":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":100.0},"text":"Research from MBO Partners suggests that digital nomads are increasingly populating campgrounds and public lands."}],"references":["b67cd69f-4c83-4193-99ab-2cc0767b6bfd_37536649","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_262065431","ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716","4acd88c5-7d2b-4157-a17b-8edb9d9769ad_4928390","72836102-23df-4f82-b338-56a356464891_682732748","ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041","255cffed-9128-4d3c-aeb9-60ac4940c381_592587899"],"documents":{"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716":{"id":"5324a4fc-50ff-4055-8112-dd9dcb7fc46a_802668716","text":"TRAVERSE CITY \u2014 Kyle Anderson seems to meander through his 40-foot blue school bus still in awe of what he\u2019s created. With a large, callused hand he gives his shaggy Irish wolfhound a pat on the head as she snoozes away on the couch.\n\nYes, the couch is inside the school bus \u2014 among many other things like a sink, stove, toilet, and a queen-sized bed. It\u2019s the culmination of work stretched nearly two years.\n\nAnderson was back in Traverse City, his hometown, just for a while before setting out on his next adventure. His bus has become somewhat of a spectacle in the area, he says. When it drives down Front Street the trees and mountains painted on its side stand taller than most cars.\n\nThe bus wears its name above its front and rear windows, \u201cMakwaden\u201d \u2014 aka \u201cThe Bear Den.\u201d It\u2019s the combination of English and Anderson\u2019s native language which is used by the bear clan of Grand Traverse band of Ottawa and Chippewa Indians.\n\nAnderson said he has had the idea to live in a bus since his school years.\n\n\u201cIt just made sense,\u201d he said. \u201cHaving a school bus being one of the safest vehicles on the road, transporting children, that why not build [a home] inside of that bus? These engines are made to be robust and travel long distances.\u201d\n\nHe bought the retired bus from Anchor Bay School District for $1,800 with the goal of renovating the whole thing for under $10,000.\n\nOf course, Anderson isn\u2019t the first to convert a school bus to a mobile home. He said much of his vision came from following other projects on social media, mainly Instagram.\n\nWhen a bus turns into a home, it\u2019s called a \u201cskoolie,\u201d and, according to Anderson, there are hundreds of skoolie enthusiasts occupying American roads.\n\nAnderson said his most memorable pilgrimage was to a Skoolie-Palooza in Arizona where more than 200 buses congregated in the dessert.\n\nOne of these meetups was held for the first time in the Upper Peninsula last month, organized by fellow nomad who lived on the road with her family for more than six years.\n\nAs the nomadic lifestyle becomes popular, the skoolie community grows. she said.\n\n\u201cWhen we first started out in the nomadic life we had to almost hide it because people didn\u2019t understand it,\u201d Walenski said. \u201cNow it has come into the spotlight thanks to the pandemic and the internet has absolutely opened up a world that you can\u2019t even imagine.\u201d\n\nResearch from MBO Partners, a Virginia-based consulting agency, suggests \u201cdigital nomads\u201d are increasingly populating campgrounds and public lands. A digital nomad is someone who can take their work anywhere, anytime \u2014 if they have an internet connection.\n\n7.3 million Americans described themselves as digital nomads in 2019, which is 2.5 million more people than the previous year, according to MBO Partners. That number is expected to hike as the COVID-19 pandemic normalizes remote work.\n\nAnderson is one such digital nomad. He\u2019s a tech entrepreneur and IT professional for his own consulting company called Makwa USA. After working in Los Angeles during his early 30s, he moved back to Michigan and began working closely with the Grand Traverse Band of Ottawa and Chippewa Indians \u2014 his father\u2019s tribe.\n\nHe sat on the Grand Traverse Band LLC board, the non-gaming side of the tribe, then worked to start Arrowhead Incubator, a Traverse City-based nonprofit.\n\nDuring this time, Anderson said minimalism became one of the most important aspects of his life, in addition to environmental protection.\n\n\u201cWe\u2019re driven in this time right now to buy, buy, buy, and consume, consume, consume,\u201d Anderson said. \u201cI think we need to take a step back and ask, \u2018what are we doing with this planet right now in our time? Are we making decisions right now for the next seven generations?\u2019\u201d\n\nIn the two years since Anderson first bought Makwaden in August 2019 and designed it to be a bachelor pad, he has taken on new responsibilities. He now takes care of a family, putting their safety and happiness at the forefront.\n\nThat does not mean giving up the bus life, he said. More people means another Makwaden.\n\n\u201cThe first bus was my proof of concept,\u201d Anderson said. \u201cIt was really just a bus to give me an idea of what I wanted to do for the next one before I dropped a lot of money into it. I\u2019m really excited to get it done and see where we go with this bus.\u201d\n\nAnderson has been documenting the Makwaden v2 build along with all his camping adventures on his Instagram page.\n\nHis travels and lifestyle, he said, has taught him things about himself and the world around him. While he understands the nomadic lifestyle isn\u2019t feasible for everyone, he hopes to inspire people to take a leap of faith.\n\n\u201cMost of us base our lives off the experiences that we gain,\u201d Anderson said. \u201cYou have to dare to cut that rope and be free.\u201d\n\nTrending Video\n\nRecommended for you","url":"https://www.record-eagle.com/news/enter-makwaden-traverse-city-man-renovates-school-buses-for-cross-country-adventures/article_5a778f80-f482-11eb-98bf-633a070144b9.html"},"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006":{"id":"ec9e942a-2b47-4552-9825-4e206606823c_696735006","text":"\nJapan's 'Digital Nomad Visa' Up For Grabs In March From Who Can Apply To Eligibility, Here's All You Need To Know\n\n\n(MENAFN- Live Mint) \"Japan is set to launch a digital nomad visa in March that will allow citizens of 49 countries to stay in the nation for up to six months serves as the best place to combine work and travel considering its metropolitan cities, diverse natural landscapes and world-renowned pop culture. In a move to boost the tourism industry and its economy and international competitiveness, the island country is increasingly opening up to foreigners read: 'With current service, visas can be issued in very short time to Indian citizens': German envoyFind out who can apply for Japan's digital nomad visaJapan's digital nomad visa will be available to citizens of 49 countries and territories. These eligible nations are those that have signed a tax treaty with the country or are visa-exempt when visiting Japan. The list of eligible nations includes all EU countries, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Moldova, Monaco, North Macedonia, Norway, Serbia, Switzerland, Turkey and the United Kingdom, reported Euronews. However, as of now, India is not on the list read: Visa, Mastercard to stop card-based B2B payments via third party fintech platforms: SourcesOne must work for an employer or corporation outside of the host nation or own a business that can be managed from anywhere in the world to be eligible for this visa. The visa mainly targets IT professionals as well as highly skilled professionals. This visa is expected to apply to YouTubers as well who make revenue from overseas advertisers read: US visa news: H-1B, L-1 and EB-5 visa fees hiked; to come into effect from 1 April. Check details hereThis East Asian country is threatened by its ageing population and hence faced with a high dependency ratio. According to Japan's labour ministry, over two million foreign nationals work in the country currently, which is the highest number ever recorded much does one need to earn to be eligible?To qualify for Japan's digital nomad visa, applicants must earn at least 10 million Japanese Yen (\u20ac62,672) annually and have private health insurance coverage, reported Euronews read: VFS Global expects visa processing time to ease this yearMoreover, family members including children and spouses will be allowed to accompany digital nomads during their stay in Japan but they also have to be covered by private medical insurance read: Schengen visa fee hike: Here's how costly your trip to Europe can getDigital nomads are 45 per cent more productive than their office-based counterparts, according to a US study. It was also found that these digital nomads are happier, with 91 per cent reporting job satisfaction and flexibility as the primary benefits countries including Portugal, Canada, and Germany, have introduced digital nomad visas and modified laws to promote working tourism. Dedicated remote working centres have emerged over the years that offer individuals the freedom to choose their workplace including beachside locations.\n\nMENAFN16022024007365015876ID1107862125\n\n\nLegal Disclaimer:\nMENAFN provides the information \u201cas is\u201d without warranty of any kind. We do not accept any responsibility or liability for the accuracy, content, images, videos, licenses, completeness, legality, or reliability of the information contained in this article. If you have any complaints or copyright issues related to this article, kindly contact the provider above.","url":"https://menafn.com/1107862125/Japans-Digital-Nomad-Visa-Up-For-Grabs-In-March-From-Who-Can-Apply-To-Eligibility-Heres-All-You-Need-To-Know"},"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442":{"id":"ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8_77576442","text":"The Latest\nA Computer Goes the World: What do digital nomads bring to local communities when they go to work around the world?\nFrom Mexico to Iceland, how is the impact of digital nomad tourists traveling to destinations around the world?\nThe digital nomad life has boomed since COVID-19 and the fall of travel restrictions, but some on TikTok think the new type of traveler could be causing more harm than good.\nCredit: Daria Mamont, Unsplash\nCassie, a digital nomad from Australia, came to Bali to work for two months.\nShe wanted to experience the local community, but instead she stumbled upon the \u201cmini Australia \u201d of Canggu.\nCangu is a popular tourist attraction in Indonesia, favored by many digital nomads.\nKathy works as a virtual assistant around the world. In 2020, when she realized she could work anywhere, she thought of working as a virtual assistant on TikTok.\nWhen her lease ended last year, she gave up office work and commuting to work remotely from her favorite place, taking charge of virtual social media and email management.\nShe has seen firsthand the positive and negative impact that digital nomads can have on local communities.\nCanggu has become a popular destination for digital nomads escaping the traditional desk life.\nCredit: Cassie Gallegos, Unsplash\n\"A lot of westerners have bought [Kuragi's] restaurants and villas and they really drive up prices, which in some way pushes locals out of the market,\" she said.\nDigital nomads thrive in the era of telecommuting, often in freelance digital roles such as social media management or content creation, and even finance, where they revere the freedom to live and work overseas, free to choose their working hours and decide how to spend each day.\nThey are also being welcomed by the tourism and hospitality industry, with co-working cafes offering cocktails and swimming pools, while co-op hotels offer high-speed Wi-Fi and group activities.\nCanggu is full of signs encouraging tourists to work remotely, and the economic benefits of tourism provide opportunities for the region.\nBut, as some have questioned on TikTok, is the digital nomadic movement a kind of neo-colonization?\nTourists come and go, but digital nomads can stay in one place for weeks, months or years, potentially exacerbating gentrification and the housing crisis.\nRecently, The New York Times reported that Mexico City has become a hub for digital nomads, but the surge has exacerbated the pressure on the already tight housing market, making it unaffordable for locals.\nHousing activists accused city leaders of allowing \u201cmodern colonization. \u201d\nThe rise of digital nomads\nCountries around the world are embracing the era of digital nomads, with 50 countries, including Dubai and Iceland, offering specific visas for this new type of traveler.\nTo work remotely in Mexico, you need to prove that you have $43,000 in your savings account in the past 12 months; to Portugal, you need to have at least $4500 a month in income; to Indonesia, you need to have more than $200,000 in savings but can do \u201cinvestment and other activities. \u201d\nThe requirements mean many digital nomads use tourist visas to leave the country when their visas expire, just to re-enter.\nAccording to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, between January and September last year, 3,000 foreigners entered Indonesia on B211A tourist visas for telecommuting.\nOne enthusiast of the digital nomad industry predicts that there will be 1 billion digital nomads by 2035, driven by factors such as the rise of high-speed internet and freelancing, as well as declining home ownership and marriage rates.\nAre digital nomads taking part in the new colonization?\nSome communities are opposed to the influx, and Mexico City residents say they see gentrification and housing drain problems triggered by foreigners seeking cheaper accommodation.\nAnthropologist Shaun Busuttil, a PhD candidate at the University of Melbourne who studies digital nomads, believes that digital nomads are undergoing some form of neo-colonization, but it \u2019 s not all black and white, or good and bad.\nIn an interview with Erik Muth of YouTube \u2019 s Rising Nomad channel, Basutil explained: \u201cHistorically, colonialism was when a group of people with more power or resources came into a place and effectively took over it and used the space for themselves. \u201d\n\u201cWhat are we doing as digital nomads? We go into these places, take over them, and enjoy their low cost of living. \u201d\nShops and businesses will eventually cater to the financial prowess of new visitors, Bousutier believes.\n\u201cSo the old-fashioned fruit and vegetable shop that has been in town or village for generations now has suddenly turned into a cafe to attract digital nomads.\nIs digital nomadism, then, a form of neocolonialism? \u201d he asked.\n\"Well, we're coming in and we're effectively taking over,\" he said.\n\"Look at Lisbon, or even Mexico City, or Barcelona, where locals are being replaced by foreign teleworkers and digital nomads,\" he said.\nHe told Moos that while it was usually those with fewer resources who were most affected by gentrification, those with more resources were able to take advantage of the economic opportunities offered by tourism.\nHow to avoid causing problems?\nKeith thinks deeply about the impact on the communities he visits and how it can have a positive impact.\n\"As a digital nomad, I feel like we should make sure we contribute to the local economy - eat at local restaurants, stay locally and pay a reasonable fee for that,\" said the statement.\nBoth Busutil and Casey believe tourists should pay the full price, not haggle.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s important to be aware of the impact you have on the local area, \u201d says Casey.\n\"That way you can walk into the local community, eat at the local restaurants, stay in the local area, and give back to the local community,\" said the statement.\nAt the moment, Casey likes the pace of life of digital nomads and has no plans for a pause.\n\u201cBeing able to finish work in the morning and then off work and take an adventure in the afternoon \u2013 I experienced paragliding in Laos and was great and went swimming to see the waterfall \u2013 I think when you can schedule your own time, you can experience more from life. \u201d\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 24 May 2023 11: 28am\nUpdated 5h ago 11: 48am\nBy Edwina Storie\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":77576442,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8","warc_date":"2023-05-24T06:15:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ea90bb4e-0607-4636-afd5-5e325bcbfef8>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/digital-nomads-like-cassie-are-setting-up-laptops-worldwide-but-are-they-always-welcome/n53ngrmh8"},"created":"2023-05-24T06:20:47.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041":{"id":"f9238697-72e5-45a4-88bd-8504c4016eba_427630041","text":"Digital Nomad Visa Programs: An APAC Update\n\nK\nKlasko\n\nContributor\n\nKlasko Immigration Law Partners is dedicated to providing industry-leading employment-based, investment-based, and litigation immigration services to our clients. We help our clients achieve their goals by providing comprehensive immigration legal services. We have a reputation for creative solutions to difficult immigration problems through cutting-edge strategies. Our clients value our extreme responsiveness and our innovative, practical, and effective immigration strategies.\nDigital nomad visa programs have grown increasingly popular. Seen as a means of attracting top-tier, global talent and tax revenue, this trend is especially prevalent in the Asian Pacific region.\nUnited States Employment and HR\nTo print this article, all you need is to be registered or login on Mondaq.com.\n\nDigital nomad visa programs have grown increasingly popular. Seen as a means of attracting top-tier, global talent and tax revenue, this trend is especially prevalent in the Asian Pacific region. Indeed, Japan recently announced it joined the digital nomad visa party \u2013 its policy to be officially rolled out in early April 2024. Below, we discuss this new development and provide a summary of the current state of digital nomad programs in the APAC region.\n\nJapan's new digital nomad visa program: a sumo-sized development\n\nJapan's Ministry of Justice announced that Japan created a digital nomad visa. Situated as the 4th largest economy in the world, Japan began issuing digital nomad visas at the beginning of April 2024 to the citizens of 50 countries and territories.\n\nThe short-list of eligible countries includes at least the United States, Australia, and Singapore. The visas are valid for up to six months and available to those earning more than \u00a510 million (app. $68,300) per year. Nomads may work from anywhere in the country and bring their spouses and children with them. Their work must be tied to \"a sales contract or non-provision contract...with a public or private company in a foreign country\". Carrying private health insurance will be obligatory to participate in the program.\n\nBehind only China and Thailand, Japan is consistently ranked as one of the largest recipients of international visitors in APAC. In 2024 alone, it is forecasted that Japan will receive a total of 33.1 million visitors. With the aperture of this new program, coupled with sustained global interest in Japan's rich cultural heritage, the country is projected to receive thousands of digital nomads for years to come.\n\nThai-tanic-sized companies are welcomed in the Kingdom\n\nVisa options for digital nomads in Thailand remain limited. Whereas the B visa program allows visitors to enter the Kingdom for up to 90 days to engage in a short list of activities, the government has gone to greater lengths to attract international corporate investment.\n\nIndeed, under its \"Remote Workers for Well-Established Overseas Companies\" program, employees of publicly traded companies (or private companies with combined revenue of over $150 million in the last three years) will be able to apply for a 10-year long resident permit. The employee must (i) make an annual salary of at least $80,000.00 USD per year for two consecutive years or (ii) if holding a master's degree, make no less than $40,000 USD for the last two years. Alternatively, the individual may be self-employed provided they own productive intellectual property or have received Series A funding of no less than $1 million USD. Like Japan, visa applicants must carry personal health insurance.\n\nWith some of the lowest corporate tax rates in all of APAC, Thailand is situating itself as one of the region's premier hotbeds for foreign investment and, consequently, international talent.\n\nMalaysia welcomes entrepreneurs from backgrounds as diverse as their landscapes\n\nMaylasia arguably presents one of the most agile digital nomad visa programs in APAC. Offering temporary residence through the \"De Rantau Nomad\" program, employees of local or foreign employers, freelancers, and independent contractors are welcome. The nomad must be coming to work in an IT or digital space and earn at least $24,000 USD per year.\n\nPursuing a K-drama storyline in South Korea remains tricky\n\nEarly this year, South Korea made a splash on the global stage by launching its own version of a digital nomad visa: the \"Workcation\" visa. Whereas the visa program does offer a two-year period of validity, it is available only under a niche set of circumstances. For example, the minimum income threshold is KRW 85,000,000, or approximately $63,683.53. Digital nomads availing themselves must not only refrain from assuming gainful employment in South Korea, but must also refrain from earning money in South Korea associated with the South Korean economy (e.g., entering contracts with local businesses). In addition to having at least one year of work experience, nomads must also carry health insurance coverage valued at KRW 100 million, or about $75,000 USD. Given these restrictions, we anticipate S. Korea's digital nomad visa program to be leveraged only by the truest of K-POP fans.\n\nThe content of this article is intended to provide a general guide to the subject matter. Specialist advice should be sought about your specific circumstances.\n\nDigital Nomad Visa Programs: An APAC Update\n\nUnited States Employment and HR\n\nContributor\n\nKlasko Immigration Law Partners is dedicated to providing industry-leading employment-based, investment-based, and litigation immigration services to our clients. We help our clients achieve their goals by providing comprehensive immigration legal services. We have a reputation for creative solutions to difficult immigration problems through cutting-edge strategies. Our clients value our extreme responsiveness and our innovative, practical, and effective immigration strategies.\nSee More Popular Content From\n\nMondaq uses cookies on this website. By using our website you agree to our use of cookies as set out in our Privacy Policy.\n\nLearn More","url":"https://www.mondaq.com:443/unitedstates/employment-and-hr/1469128/digital-nomad-visa-programs-an-apac-update"},"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267":{"id":"f2d39679-7714-4818-8520-3a94256d29a9_256892267","text":"Supplement\nWikiProject\nFEATURE\nChiangmai Coffee Shop Office Meeting on Bali Beach Digital Nomad Self-discipline for Freedom\nTravel + work, is it possible?\nRemote work has become a new normal in the workplace, so long as you have a laptop and a stable network, you can move the \u201coffice \u201d to any corner of the world.\nWhether it \u2019 s surfing season in the Philippines or winter in Chiang Mai, the \u201cdigital nomad \u201d lifestyle is no longer just an imagination.\nAfter 90 years, Kristie and Kate quit their jobs during the epidemic to join the digital nomad, living and living in a different place, and returning to the rhythm of life. Kristie said, \u201cNomad \u2019 s gift to me is to help me clean up my life and start again. \u201d\nWhile the reporter was writing in the newspaper, Kristie, who had returned from Xinjiang for less than a month, flew to Chiang Mai, Thailand. Browse her sharing on social media platforms, she enjoyed the sunshine while leisurely working with her laptop in the open coffee shop, so that the reporter \u201cgrape \u201d\u201c bathed \u201d in the white light tube was very good. Kristie began her digital nomad career early last year. Bali, northern Thailand Chiang Mai, and then to Switzerland, a full year did not return to Hong Kong, \"began the journey about 1 month, I have decided to live such a life in the future.\"\nGet up at 8 and 9 a.m. every day, go to the beach, meditate, and work efficiently for 4 hours. After dusk, learn new things, read books, and live the creative life that many wage earners dream of.\nHe made $50,000 a month at the peak of his career.\nBefore the pasture, she worked in the advertising industry, and her body and mind were eroded by the pressure of work, and she suffered from chronic gastritis, \"(sometimes) pain so that she could not eat all day, and she would vomit after eating.\"\nFinally, the doctor said that even if the prescription of many drugs is useless, because my life pressure is too big, let her decide to change the environment, for their own life to a big clean.\nAt that time, she took the initiative to propose a 30% pay cut to her superiors, and switched from full-time employees to freelance workers.\nThere is no regular income, employee welfare, she confessed that \"initially very scared, suddenly lost the sense of security\", so she had saved six months of living reserve before leaving to prevent zero income during the period; and for themselves to open up a new source of income, operating from the media, doing small business.\nShe also became an oblique person, relying on writing advertising copy, public relations and marketing planning to maintain the nomadic living expenses, peak monthly income can reach 50,000 yuan, the off-season income is only more than 10,000 yuan, but stretched to make up for the short, life is still good.\nIn particular, she is mostly nomadic in Southeast Asia, where the consumption is low and the quality of life is good. Taking the island of Phangan in Thailand as an example, she lives in an independent holiday home, with a monthly expenditure of about 12,000 Hong Kong dollars, such as clothing, food, housing and travel.\nLow prices, good living, Indonesia, Thailand, a hot spot\nIn addition to freelancers like Kristie, there are also people engaged in online teaching, design, e-commerce, programming and other remote work, as well as enterprises due to industry characteristics, full-time employees can also work remotely, such as Kate working in the web3.0 industry. Web3.0 is a decentralized Internet based on blockchain technology, NFT, cryptocurrency, metaverse and other popular technology concepts in recent years. It is based on Web 3.0 technology.\nKate, 24, who worked as an occupational therapist for a year after graduating from college, found that she did not like working in fixed locations and hours, and wanted the freedom to travel while working as a digital nomad.\nShe is interested in cryptocurrency, so she turned to web3.0, engaged in marketing, operation of blockchain projects and other work, usually through online communication with colleagues.\n\"Web 3.0 is a more international company, with employees from all over the world, most of them do not have a physical office, and many times employees can only choose to work remotely.\"\nIt \u2019 s like living three or four different lives.\nEvery time she goes to different places to participate in seminars, and after completing her work, she will stay there for 1-2 weeks, traveling all over Japan, Thailand, Australia, Singapore, France, etc. Although she is a full-time employee, she has no fixed office hours, sometimes she does not need to turn on the computer all day, she can go sightseeing, sometimes she needs to meet and meet constantly. Bring a computer, wired headphones and plenty of mobile data.\nWhen I tried to watch animals in the Australian zoo, I suddenly had a meeting; I suddenly had to deal with work on the way to shopping in Korea, and the store has been closed for seven or eight years, which is completely different from the excellent nomadic life I imagined.\nKate, who often hangs \"work first\" and \"have self-discipline to have freedom\", admits that even the beauty of the current can not be completely relaxed and appreciated, \"I think you can not because your work location is not in a fixed place, and people feel unprofessional; it should make people believe that you can complete the work wherever you are, and there is quality, and no need for others to adapt, so as to maintain this way of life for a long.\"\nDigital nomads have bitterness and sweetness, but both say they can \u2019 t go back after they set foot on this road.\nRead this year Kristie published in the book fair, from the nomad, to find the heart of the sea \", she met on the road only two seasons of American couples, with children wandering the world of nomadic families, Lin Lin's total lifestyle has brought her a shock,\" I know in Hong Kong, many of them are a life to the end, but in the nomad meet them, I \u2019 ve lived three or four different lives, \u201d and there are fascinating stories in each life.\nEmbark on a nomadic journey to open Second Life, their book of life, and add a few unforgettable experiences.\n\u25cf\nText: Chang Shu-mei\nEditor: Liang Xiaoling\nArt: Hsieh Wai-ho\nFacebook @ Ming Pao Supplement\nCopyright \u00a9 2019 Mingpao. All Rights Reserved.\nRelated Words: Chiang Mai Visa Digital Nomad Visa Work from anywhere Digital Nomad\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:6809","uncompressed_offset":256892267,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E5%89%AF%E5%88%8A/article/20231219/s00005/1702919481762/%E6%B8%85%E9%82%81%E5%92%96%E5%95%A1%E5%BA%97%E8%BE%A6%E5%85%AC-%E5%B3%87%E9%87%8C%E6%B5%B7%E7%81%98%E6%97%81%E9%96%8B%E6%9C%83-%E6%