"},{"citations":{"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":100.0},"text":"The J-10 fighter jet was developed by Chengdu Aircraft Company, with its first model, the J-10A, entering mass production in 2000."},{"citations":{"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":100.0},"text":"The J-10A features a single engine, single vertical tail, and dual delta wing configuration, which provides excellent high-altitude and high-speed performance."},{"citations":{"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":100.0},"text":"However, the J-10A faced export challenges due to poor reliability and bottlenecks in domestic engine development."},{"citations":{"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":100.0},"text":"The J-10B, an improved version of the J-10A, was successfully tested in December 2008 and featured a redesigned intake channel."},{"citations":{"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":100.0},"text":"The J-10C, introduced in 2017, includes further advancements such as an active phased array radar, enhancing its combat capabilities."},{"citations":{"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755":100.0},"text":"The J-10C offers multiple features and performance advantages over the F-16, particularly in terms of armament, flight, and overall performance."}],"references":["7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755","cd6f7c06-5e22-4103-9de2-9817a9a60efa_121885815","a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069","7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_1044319203"],"documents":{"cd6f7c06-5e22-4103-9de2-9817a9a60efa_121885815":{"id":"cd6f7c06-5e22-4103-9de2-9817a9a60efa_121885815","text":"Adsence Ads 300X250\nAdsense Ads 900\u00d7250\n\nPAF formally inducts Rafale rival China-made J-10C fighter jets\n\nWeb Desk BOL News\n\n11th Mar, 2022. 02:25 pm\nAdsense Ads 300 x 100\nAdsence Ads 300X250\n\nKAMRA: The Pakistan Air Force (PAF) formally inducted a modern Chinese-made J-10C multi-role combat aircraft also known as \u201cvigorous dragon\u201d during a ceremony held at Kamra Airbase on Friday.\n\nPrime Minister Imran Khan attended the induction ceremony of the single-engine fighter jet at the invitation of Chief of the Air Staff (CAS) Air Chief Marshal Zaheer Ahmad Babar, along with other federal ministers and the Chinese ambassador.\n\nDuring the ceremony, The Prime Minister has witnessed a thrilling flypast of various aircraft formations, including the newly inducted J10C, F-16s, JF-17s, and Mirages, which displayed a sophisticated array of avionics and weaponry.\n\nRead more:\u00a0PAF\u2019s acquisition of J10-C\n\nFollowing the flypast, the Prime Minister witnessed the landing of five J-10C aircraft, which have been inducted into the 15 Squadron.\n\nThe J-10C is larger and can be outfitted with a bigger active electronically scanned array (AESA) radar than the JF-17 Block 3 uses.\n\nThe aircraft can carry fourth-generation air-to-air missiles such as the short-range PL-10 and the beyond-visual-range PL-15.\n\nAccording to a foreign media report, China will deliver a total of 25 J-10C fighter jets to Pakistan, significantly increasing the country\u2019s military capability to defend airspace.\n\nRead more:\u00a0J-10C induction ceremony: Pakistan knows how to protect its boundaries, says Imran\n\nAfter being tested in Chengdu, the first batch of combat aircraft arrived in Pakistan a few days ago.\n\nImages of a Pakistan Air Force (PAF) J-10C fighter jet with the Pakistan Air Force (PAF) markings recently surfaced on social media and were widely circulated by media outlets.\n\nChinese analysts have praised the latest defence cooperation between China and Pakistan, saying that the move is significant for both countries because it strengthens the Pakistani military\u2019s combat capabilities, promotes China\u2019s aviation equipment, and serves regional security interests.\n\n\u201cThe J-10C will significantly improve the Pakistan Air Force\u2019s combat capabilities,\u201d Chinese analysts predicted.\n\n\u201cThe J-10C is a 4.5-generation medium-sized fighter jet that is more powerful than the China-Pakistan jointly developed lightweight fighter jet, the JF-17, which is currently in service with the Pakistan Air Force,\u201d Shi Hong, Executive Chief Editor of Shipborne Weapons, told the Global Times.\n\n\nDownload BOL News App for latest news","url":"https://www.bolnews.com/pakistan/2022/03/paf-formally-inducts-rafale-rival-china-made-j-10c-fighter-jets/"},"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755":{"id":"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_115461755","text":"Turkey replaces F-16 with Chinese fighter jet\nWednesday 08 March 2023 - 12: 09 GMT\nKagri Erhan, a member of the Security Council and Foreign Policy of the Turkish Presidency, announced that Ankara is expected to abandon its requests for American-made fourth-generation F-16C / D fighter jets due to the availability of a better alternative.\nWorld - Turkey\nThe Turkish official noted that the \u201c$20 billion cost package \u201d and the availability of more cost-effective options, notably the Chinese J-10C, could make such a rollout a reality.\n\"Now we have other options such as the Chinese plane that was sold to Pakistan, the Russian planes and also the Eurofighter,\" he said.\nAccording to Miltary Watch, Pakistan began receiving Chinese J-10C fighters in February 2022.\nThe Chinese fighter is of the same weight as its American counterpart, the F-16, but it is several decades newer with multiple features and performance advantages, especially in terms of armament, flight and flight performance.\nIt is a lightweight single-engine fighter with low operating cost and improved fifth-generation avionics.\nChinese aircraft also have similar capabilities and in most respects are superior to their American counterparts, in addition to requiring less maintenance needs and much faster delivery time.\nAlthough Turkey is the largest foreign operator of the US F-16, with about 250 in service, which means the new aircraft can be easily integrated with existing training and logistics systems and weapons, China has in the past modified its fighters to be able to operate US weapons at the request of foreign customers.\nOne of the main advantages of the Chinese fighter is its very low cost compared to its American counterpart, due to the fact that China manufactures large quantities of them, unlike the American.\nTurkey \u2019 s preference for lightweight fighters makes the Chinese single-engine aircraft an effective and pioneering option.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0007.json.gz:10313","uncompressed_offset":115461755,"url":"www.alalam.ir/news/6559603/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A8%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2023-03-08T12:32:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72>","warc_url":"https://www.alalam.ir/news/6559603/%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A8%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2023-03-08T12:37:13.000Z","lang":"eng"},"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_1044319203":{"id":"7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72_1044319203","text":"The American F-16...\nInformation on the Chinese J-10C fighter\n\u00a9 AFP 2023 / KARIM SAHIBChinese J-10 fighter\nFollow us via\nThe Chinese J-10 is touted as the best alternative to the US fourth-generation F-16, which has led some countries to consider acquiring it.\nChina has produced about 350 such aircraft since they entered service in 2005, according to Military Factory.\nThe aircraft has a single crew and is used by China and Pakistan and is designed for aerial combat missions with a variety of weapons.\nTurkey to replace F-16 with Chinese fighter jet\nPhotos & Videos\nWhat are the technical specifications of the J-10?\nLength: 15.5 meters.\nDistance between wings: 9.7 meters.\nHeight: 4.7 meters.\nWeight of empty aircraft: 9.7 tons.\nThe total weight of the aircraft is 18.5 tons.\nSpeed: 2,336 km / h.\nAltitude: 20,000 meters.\nRange: 1800 kilometers.\nWhat is the arming of the J-10?\nThe Chinese J-10 has six under-wing and five under-hull external suspension points that allow it to carry a large external payload of weapons, including air-to-air missiles, laser-guided bombs and other types of conventional bombs, as well as a 23 mm internal machine gun.\nThere are several versions of the aircraft, some with one seat and others with two seats for training tasks, including:\nThe J-10A is a single-seat multirole fighter.\nJ-10B: Marine version with twin-engine engines.\nJ-10C: An upgraded version of the B version with an electronic radar and infrared guidance system for missiles.\n\u00a9 AFP 2023 / WANG ZHAO Chinese J-10 fighter\nThe Chinese J-10 fighter.\nThe J-10C is an upgraded export version, which Turkey may acquire as a replacement for the U.S. F-16 fighter jets.\nEarlier, a Turkish presidential official said Ankara was expected to abandon the U.S. F-16 fighter jets due to the availability of a better alternative in the Chinese J-10 signal.\n\u00a9 SputnikWhat are the capabilities of the Chinese J-16 fighter?\nWhat are the capabilities of the Chinese J-16 fighter?\nNews Ticker\n0.\nTo participate in the discussion\nSign in or Register\nloader\nConversations\n\u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0430","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0007.json.gz:10508","uncompressed_offset":1044319203,"url":"sputnikarabic.ae/20230308/%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%88%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AC%D9%8A%D9%87-10%D8%B3%D9%8A-1074471956.html","warc_date":"2023-03-08T12:32:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7662ae65-98c5-4a3f-9b24-83a5f9fb7a72>","warc_url":"https://sputnikarabic.ae/20230308/%D8%A8%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%81-16-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%88%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AC%D9%8A%D9%87-10%D8%B3%D9%8A-1074471956.html"},"created":"2023-03-08T13:16:09.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069":{"id":"a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52_942464069","text":"Chinese Army J-10 Crossing the Strait Central Line Ministry of Defense: Strict Monitoring of Missiles\nReporters Lu Chiung-chang / reporting from Taipei\nThe Ministry of Defense said that since 0600 hours yesterday (8) to 0600 hours, six sorties (including one over the middle line of the strait) and three ships have been detected, and activities around the Taiwan Strait have continued.\nThe military uses mission aircraft, ships and shore missile systems to closely monitor and respond.\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.\nAccording to the plan released by the Ministry of Defense, the Chinese People's Liberation Army entered the airspace around the Taiwan Strait, and one of the PLA's J-10 fighters crossed the northern end of the Strait Central Line and immediately turned back.\nIn the 1980s, Israel Aerospace (IAI) developed the Lavi based on the F-16, but production was canceled due to opposition from the United States.\nSince then, Chengdu Aircraft Company has cooperated with Lion to develop new fighters. Although Israel and China ended cooperation after 1989, Chengdu Aircraft Company continued to develop and develop the J-10A in 1998, and completed the test flight of the J-10A, and completed mass production two years later.\nThe J-10A adopts a single engine, a single vertical tail, and a single wing pneumatic configuration in the dual delta wing, which is characterized by excellent high altitude and high speed performance, and the front delta wing can improve the maneuverability of medium and low altitude, which can effectively shorten the take-off and landing distance.\nJ-10 fighter after service with Su-27SK, Su-30MKK, J-11 and other fighters formed a high and low match. Although the price of the J-10A is only half that of the F-16, but due to poor reliability, the supporting domestic engine development into a bottleneck, resulting in poor export performance.\nAfter the production of the J-10A, Chengdu Aircraft Company started a performance improvement and improvement program in 2004, and the J-10B was successfully tested in December 2008. The J-10B abandoned the rectangular intake channel design and switched to a Rampless integrated intake channel similar to the FC-1, and continued to improve the launch of the J-10C. 2017 In June, the J-10C participated in the 90th anniversary parade of the People's Liberation Army, making its first public appearance, and the J-10C was replaced with an active phased array radar.\nThe Pakistan Air Force is the only foreign procurement unit of the J-10, ordering 36 J-10CE fighters, and J-10CE is the export model of the J-10C.\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0000.json.gz:25410","uncompressed_offset":942464069,"url":"www.nownews.com/news/6022738","warc_date":"2023-01-08T00:39:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a834da70-5664-4631-bba7-dba8ef82cd52>","warc_url":"https://www.nownews.com/news/6022738"},"created":"2023-01-08T02:23:05.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1009","request_id":"1009","narrative_id":"1009"},"responses":[{"citations":{"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364":100.0},"text":"Saharan dust storms, originating from North Africa, travel across the Atlantic Ocean and peak during late June to mid-August, impacting regions in the Americas, including South Texas and San Antonio."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"These storms carry a mix of sand, dust, and microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, which can lead to respiratory issues, allergies, and other health concerns, particularly for individuals with pre-existing conditions like asthma or COPD."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"In addition to health risks, Saharan dust can reduce visibility, disrupt transportation systems, and impair the performance of solar panels, posing challenges to urban infrastructure and daily life."},{"citations":{"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364":100.0},"text":"The dust also affects air quality, creating hazy skies and potentially causing breathing difficulties for sensitive populations, with conditions expected to worsen as dust levels increase throughout the week."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, Saharan dust provides environmental benefits, such as delivering nutrients like phosphorus to ecosystems, fertilizing ocean waters, and supporting biodiversity in regions like the Amazon rainforest and the Caribbean Sea."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"However, excessive dust deposition can harm ecosystems, including coral reefs, by blocking sunlight and reducing photosynthetic activity, which may lead to biodiversity loss."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"Climate change is influencing the frequency and intensity of these storms, as evidenced by events like the massive 2020 'Godzilla' dust storm, highlighting the need for proactive environmental strategies."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"To mitigate the impacts of Saharan dust storms, individuals with respiratory conditions should stay indoors, while broader measures such as afforestation and environmental sustainability projects can address long-term challenges."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"City planners should also consider reviewing environmental regulations and raising public awareness to prepare for the increasing frequency of dust storms."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364":100.0},"text":"Saharan dust storms, originating from North Africa, travel across the Atlantic Ocean and peak during late June to mid-August, impacting regions in the Americas, including South Texas and San Antonio."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"These storms carry a mix of sand, dust, and microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, which can lead to respiratory issues, allergies, and other health concerns, particularly for individuals with pre-existing conditions like asthma or COPD."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"In addition to health risks, Saharan dust can reduce visibility, disrupt transportation systems, and impair the performance of solar panels, posing challenges to urban infrastructure and daily life."},{"citations":{"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364":100.0},"text":"The dust also affects air quality, creating hazy skies and potentially causing breathing difficulties for sensitive populations, with conditions expected to worsen as dust levels increase throughout the week."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"Despite these challenges, Saharan dust provides environmental benefits, such as delivering nutrients like phosphorus to ecosystems, fertilizing ocean waters, and supporting biodiversity in regions like the Amazon rainforest and the Caribbean Sea."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"However, excessive dust deposition can harm ecosystems, including coral reefs, by blocking sunlight and reducing photosynthetic activity, which may lead to biodiversity loss."},{"citations":{"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":100.0},"text":"Climate change is influencing the frequency and intensity of these storms, as evidenced by events like the massive 2020 'Godzilla' dust storm, highlighting the need for proactive environmental strategies."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"To mitigate the impacts of Saharan dust storms, individuals with respiratory conditions should stay indoors, while broader measures such as afforestation and environmental sustainability projects can address long-term challenges."},{"citations":{"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":100.0},"text":"City planners should also consider reviewing environmental regulations and raising public awareness to prepare for the increasing frequency of dust storms."}],"references":["1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144","958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541","5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364"],"documents":{"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364":{"id":"5dc9163b-9ad8-4a82-8d61-269b3aa8f216_79048364","text":"Breaking News\nMore () \u00bb\n\nSan Antonians may want to stay indoors next week. Here's why.\n\nA noticeable change in the air will arrive to the Alamo City next week.\n\nSAN ANTONIO \u2014 San Antonio skies could look quite different next week but not in the way we're hoping for.\u00a0\n\nAs San Antonians eagerly wait for rain to break our triple-digit temperatures another common occurrence will pick-up next week known as Saharan dust.\u00a0\n\nThe dust is a combination of sand and dust traveling from North Africa across the Atlantic that peaking in late June through mid-August.\u00a0\n\nLight amounts of Saharan dust have arrived to the Alamo City this past week but will become more noticeable. Therefore, if you have asthma, COPD or any other type of respiratory illness you will want to stay indoors as much as possible during this time.\n\nTiming of Saharan dust:\n\nMonday - Little changes will be in the forecast as heavier amounts of dust remain over the gulf coast.\u00a0\n\nCredit: KENS 5 Weather\n\nTuesday\u00a0- A large moderate level of Saharan dust will move into South Texas and San Antonio by late afternoon. San Antonians may notice hazy skies and trouble breathing if you're more sensitive to dusty air. But the dust doesn't stop here.\u00a0\n\nCredit: KENS 5 Weather\n\nWednesday - By mid-week Saharan dust ramps up continuing to build and push farther north stretching to the Dallas area. The continuing flow of the dust is partly due to a high pressure bringing a southeasterly flow to help pump the dust toward South Texas.\u00a0\n\nCredit: KENS 5 Weather\n\nThursday\u00a0- As the week progresses dust levels continue to rise and could affect air quality levels. For those with any respiratory illnesses they should avoid outdoor activity including vigorous exercise. Also try to keep windows and doors closed. We will continue to monitor this development next week.\u00a0\n\nCredit: KENS 5 Weather\n\nAs dust increases across the area, San Antonians will notice more vibrant sunrises and sunsets. However, during the afternoons the sky appears a more milky white color.\u00a0\n\nBefore You Leave, Check This Out","url":"https://www.kens5.com/article/weather/saharan-dust-san-antonio-weather/273-dccf511f-64e1-422e-945c-9b99ff1a29ed"},"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144":{"id":"1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624_55169144","text":"Dust storms.\nsources and danger.\n|\nAt the beginning of this year's spring season, the incidence of dust storms increased significantly.\nTheir frequency varies from year to year, but generally increases in the transitional periods between seasons, especially spring and autumn, for many reasons, some natural and others of a human nature, that is, by man.\nDust storms are fast winds that transport dust and plankton, causing a lack of visibility at short distances.\nDespite the great controversy over the causes of dust or dust storms and the fact that the camel bears full responsibility for their occurrence, as stated in one of the videos circulated on social media, the reasons are not limited to the poor camel alone, even if it is one of the reasons!\nThe causes of dust storms are many, including: (1) Desertification as a result of drought resulting from low rainfall.\n(2) Desertification due to human activities associated with overgrazing as a result of increasing numbers of camels and sheep on pasture capacity.\n(3) Extensive agricultural activities, especially ploughing the land and leaving it exposed for long periods.\n(4) Soil movement as a result of development and military actions and absurd car tracks in deserts that led to the breaking and dismantling of the soil and the destruction of vegetation cover.\n(5) The reduction of the surface groundwater table, which led to the drying of the soil and thus the impact on the vegetation cover.\nGlobally, sub-Saharan Africa is the main contributor to Earth \u2019 s dust storms, which travel to the Americas via the Atlantic Ocean via tropical east winds.\nBut the Fertile Crescent has also become a source of dust, due to the halving of agricultural production as a result of climate change.\nIraq is one of the sources of dust storms as a result of the decline of the level of rivers, which led to the drought of the marshes and lakes in Iraq and Iran, and add to the list of sources open deserts of the Kingdom, which suffer environmental degradation as a result of human tampering of unfair grazing and wood and the like.\nDust storms are one of the factors responsible for increased allergic reactions, asthma attacks and chronic breathing problems, as well as blood vessels and heart disease.\nDust storms are also carriers of microorganisms, including bacteria, fungi, germs and viruses that cause certain diseases.\nBesides, dust storms have economic effects, they adversely affect agricultural production by transporting agricultural pests, reducing photosynthetic activity, destroying crops, as well as affecting infrastructure, by reducing visibility, disrupting energy and air and road transport systems, burying railways, as well as contributing to the deterioration of the performance of solar panels, as well as damaging residential property.\nThere is no doubt that dust storms and their increased frequency are a warning sign that requires a rapid response through a review of environmental regulations, the need to raise the environmental awareness of the population, the organization of grazing seasons based on the identification of the pastoral capacity of each region, as well as innovative solutions to mitigate desertification that benefit from tremendous technical progress.\nFinally, it follows from the above that the problem is not country-specific, but a regional problem that requires concerted efforts.\nThe Green Middle East initiative by Prince Mohammed bin Salman is designed to design innovative solutions to address climate change and promote environmental sustainability through a number of projects, including: planting 50 billion trees across the Middle East region and reclaiming 200 million hectares of degraded land through afforestation, which contributes to a 2.5 per cent reduction in global carbon emissions.\nPublish it.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0011.json.gz:26502","uncompressed_offset":55169144,"url":"www.aleqt.com/2022/04/17/article_2299001.html","warc_date":"2022-04-17T00:06:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:1fd604e6-30ba-4b91-b53c-ecb5241f2624>","warc_url":"https://www.aleqt.com/2022/04/17/article_2299001.html"},"created":"2022-04-17T00:13:58.000Z","lang":"eng"},"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541":{"id":"958ae1ee-19d5-41c4-8e42-0583f3ed6841_957102541","text":"03-27-2024\n\nSahara desert dust storms carry harmful bacteria and fungi around the globe\n\nWe often dismiss springtime allergies as reactions to local pollen. Yet, something else might cause our sniffles and sneezes: a massive dust storms that originate thousands of miles away in Africa\u2019s Sahara region.\n\nThese gargantuan dust plumes travel the globe every summer, carrying a cocktail of pollutants and potential pathogens across continents.\n\nDr. Shankar Chellam, a Texas A&M University professor is leading the charge to understand the biological hitchhikers within dust storms.\n\nHe and his team are working to determine what microbes, specifically bacteria and fungi, migrate with the dust and explore their potential impact on human health.\n\nHidden passengers in Sahara dust\n\n\u201cWe all get allergies and potentially other more severe health effects when we breathe in dust, and it\u2019s not fully known as to what causes those allergies,\u201d said Dr. Chellam.\n\n\u201cSome people may think it is just the sand or clay minerals in the dust. Others think it is the metals or organics in the dust, and then some think it\u2019s the bacteria and fungi.\u201d\n\nThe Saharan dust cloud carries vast amounts of sand particles that transport bacteria and fungi.\n\nDr. Chellam\u2019s research uniquely addresses how Saharan dust storms introduce these microbes into North America.\n\nWhat the dust storm from Sahara tells us\n\nDr. Chellam and his team analyzed samples from a Saharan dust event that reached Houston in 2018. They measured metals, bacteria, and fungi to investigate any connections.\n\nFascinatingly, their findings revealed strong links between the biodiversity of the microbes and specific elements, especially calcium.\n\nWhile these elements occur naturally in the Sahara, they also exist in our local environments. Pinpointing the exact origin of the dust and its cargo remains a challenge that scientists continue to tackle.\n\nOur air \u2013 Not as empty as we think\n\nPerhaps the most startling discovery is that even seemingly lifeless clouds of dust brim with biological activity.\n\n\u201cA key takeaway from this study is that a lot of biodiversity is not scientifically described. It doesn\u2019t have a name, it can\u2019t be cultured, and because it can\u2019t be cultured, it\u2019s difficult to study,\u201d explained Dr. Daniel Spalink, assistant professor at Texas A&M.\n\nThe team\u2019s high-tech DNA analysis allowed them to create an inventory of bacteria and fungi, even if the microbes themselves weren\u2019t active.\n\nSurprisingly, they found traces of several pathogens known to cause disease in humans, as listed by the World Health Organization (WHO).\n\n\u201cIt doesn\u2019t tell us if they are going to be able to infect us and make us sick,\u201d Spalink cautions, \u201cBut at least the DNA of several pathogenic bacteria and fungi were identified in the African dust.\u201d\n\nImpact of climate change on Sahara dust\n\nClimate change is altering weather patterns globally. This transformation affects dust storm behavior, leading to variations in their frequency and intensity.\n\nIn 2020, the United States experienced the most massive Saharan dust storm ever recorded, which experts named \u201cGodzilla.\u201d\n\nThis event highlighted the potential for increasing occurrences of such dust invasions. \u201cThe whole dynamics of the Saharan dust coming to Houston is primarily driven by atmospheric processes,\u201d said Dr. Sourav Das, a former student of Dr. Chellam.\n\nGlobal connection of Sahara dust\n\nSahara dust storm travels far beyond the borders of North America, affecting global environmental systems in profound ways.\n\nThis dust, originating from the vast Sahara Desert, embarks on transcontinental journeys that influence climate, ocean biology, and ecosystems far removed from its source.\n\nThe Saharan dust plays a critical role in climate regulation. As it travels across oceans and continents, it reflects sunlight back into space, cooling the Earth\u2019s surface.\n\nThis natural phenomenon acts as a counterbalance to the warming effects of greenhouse gases, showcasing how desert dust can influence global temperatures.\n\nHowever, the dust also carries microorganisms and nutrients, such as phosphorus, that fertilize remote ecosystems, from the Amazon rainforest to the Caribbean Sea, demonstrating nature\u2019s complex nutrient cycles.\n\nBenefits to oceans\n\nOcean biology benefits from the nutrient-rich dust as well. When Saharan dust settles on ocean waters, it delivers essential minerals that stimulate the growth of phytoplankton.\n\nThese microscopic plants form the foundation of the oceanic food chain, supporting a diverse array of marine life.\n\nThe influx of nutrients from the Sahara can thus boost marine productivity, affecting fish populations and the global fishing industry.\n\nDisadvantages\n\nThe impact of Saharan dust is not universally beneficial. In ecosystems unaccustomed to the influx of foreign particles and nutrients, the dust can disrupt local environments.\n\nFor example, excessive dust deposition can smother coral reefs, blocking sunlight and hindering photosynthesis. This can stress coral ecosystems, leading to bleaching events and loss of biodiversity.\n\nMoreover, the health implications of Saharan dust extend across continents. The dust carries not only nutrients but also pollutants and pathogens that can affect air quality and public health.\n\nCommunities in the path of these dust plumes may experience increased respiratory issues, allergies, and diseases, highlighting the need for global health monitoring and preparedness.\n\nStudy insights\n\nIt\u2019s crucial to gather data across multiple dust events, spanning many years, to get a clearer picture of these airborne microbial communities and how they might transform over time.\n\nWhile a lot remains unknown, research like this shines a spotlight on the hidden travelers swirling in the air we breathe \u2014 travelers who might be affecting our health in surprising ways.\n\nThe next time you catch a glimpse of a dust storm rolling in, remember the globe-trotting microbes it carries!\n\nThe findings of the study are published in Environmental Science & Technology.\n\n\u2014\u2013\n\nLike what you read? Subscribe to our newsletter for engaging articles, exclusive content, and the latest updates.\u00a0\n\nCheck us out on EarthSnap, a free app brought to you by Eric Ralls and Earth.com.\n\n\u2014\u2013\n\nNews coming your way\nThe biggest news about our planet delivered to you each day","url":"https://www.earth.com/news/sahara-desert-dust-storms-carry-harmful-bacteria-and-fungi-around-the-globe/"}}}
