d carbon emissions reduction."},{"citations":{"515c5776-a50e-4782-835a-77bfb011b38e_922454685":100.0},"text":"Aircraft manufacturers are focusing on next-generation designs that incorporate advanced materials, aerodynamic improvements, and more efficient engines to reduce carbon emissions and operating costs."},{"citations":{"515c5776-a50e-4782-835a-77bfb011b38e_922454685":100.0},"text":"The single-aisle aircraft market is projected to grow at a CAGR of 12.5%, reaching $222.20 billion by 2030, driven by the expansion of low-cost carriers and rising middle-class populations in emerging economies."},{"citations":{"65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e_72581204":100.0},"text":"Airbus and Boeing are expected to dominate the single-aisle jet market, with the A320neo and 737 Max 8 representing 50% of deliveries, while the dual-aisle market will be led by the B787 and A350 models."},{"citations":{"65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e_72581204":100.0},"text":"Freighter capacity is anticipated to grow by 3.3% over 2019 levels, with 3,500 freighters projected to be delivered over the next 20 years, driven by e-commerce growth and the conversion of airliners to freighters."},{"citations":{"9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96_466373894":100.0},"text":"The aviation industry is recovering from the impact of COVID-19, with air traffic rebounding significantly in regions like Latin America and Africa, despite lingering challenges."},{"citations":{"9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96_466373894":100.0},"text":"Overall, the aerospace market is poised for long-term growth, with manufacturers like Airbus and Boeing strategically positioned to capitalize on increasing demand for fuel-efficient and sustainable aircraft."}],"references":["65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e_72581204","515c5776-a50e-4782-835a-77bfb011b38e_922454685","9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96_466373894"],"documents":{"65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e_72581204":{"id":"65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e_72581204","text":"Cirium expects 45,000 more fuel-efficient aircraft to be delivered by 2040, worth $2.9 trillion\nCirium predicts that over the next 20 years, the world will spend $2.9 trillion on about 45,000 new aircraft.\n\u2022 New aircraft expected to be delivered will replace the ageing fleet to meet projected annual growth of 3.7% in air passenger traffic\nSingle-aisle jets are expected to account for 70% of passenger aircraft deliveries by 2040\n\u2022 China is expected to top the list with a 20% share in aircraft deliveries \u2013 the region \u2019 s air passenger growth is expected to exceed 6%\n\u2022 Around 80% of existing passenger aircraft will be retired between 2021 and 2040\nOver 3,500 freighter deliveries over the next 20 years \u2013 including new freighters and modified airliners\nDownload\nLoading media player...\nAn estimated 45,000 aircraft worth U.S. $2.9 trillion to be delivered by 2040.\nRevealed in Cirium's new Fleet Forecast.\nLONDON -- The newly released 2021 Cirium Fleet Forecast shows that around 45,000 new, more fuel-efficient aircraft will be purchased globally over the next 20 years, with an estimated $2.9 trillion in aircraft purchases.\nAccording to the Cirium Fleet Forecast released by Ascend by Cirium, a consulting firm of aviation analytics firm Cirium, global cumulative aircraft deliveries for the next 20 years will be 4% higher than predicted a year ago by 2040.\nThe report outlines the positive outlook for the aviation industry and its recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.\nThe COVID-19 pandemic has severely affected air travel, as well as aircraft deliveries.\nGlobal aircraft deliveries fell by 43% - or 600 aircraft - in 2020.\nAircraft deliveries recovered somewhat in 2021, but are still 25% below 2019 levels.\nAir travel is reopening as global vaccination programs become more widespread, leading to an increase of 300 aircraft deliveries in 2021 \u2014 a feat achieved when Boeing 787 was found to be problematic.\nRob Morris, Global Advisory Director, Ascend by Cirium, said: \u201cThe Cirium Fleet Forecast 2021 presents an optimistic long-term outlook for the aviation industry, which will return to a more traditional growth trajectory after 2024, although structurally different from before.\nAir passenger traffic is expected to grow at an annual rate of 3.7%, so the global passenger fleet will need to increase by almost 22,000 aircraft.\n\u201cIf the above projections are realized, the global passenger fleet will reach the size of about 47,200 aircraft by the end of 2040. \u201d\nThe projected delivery of new aircraft will not only meet the growing demand for air transport, but will also replace older aircraft that are less fuel efficient. \"\nChina leads in aircraft deliveries\nThe number of aircraft deliveries will vary depending on the region where the airline is located, and the Asian market is expected to be the growth engine.\nChina is expected to lead the world with more than 6% growth in air passenger traffic \u2013 also topping the list in aircraft deliveries, accounting for 20% of the world \u2019 s total.\nChina \u2019 s delivery figures are significantly ahead of all other Asia-Pacific countries, which together account for 22% of the total.\nNorth American carriers are expected to account for 20 percent, while European carriers will account for 17 percent.\nThe Middle East is estimated to account for 7% of the share, but because the region will deliver a large number of twin-aisle aircraft, it will account for 11% in terms of aircraft value.\nLatin America, which is similar to the Middle East, will also account for 7%.\nRussia and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) accounted for 4%, and Africa accounted for 3%.\nMost of the new deliveries will be single-aisle jets\nThe fleet forecast report shows that over the next 20 years, single-aisle jets will account for 70% of total aircraft deliveries and 55% of total delivery value.\nThe total value of newly delivered single-aisle jets is $1.6 trillion.\nThe mainstream model will still be the 150-seat aircraft, represented by the Airbus A320neo and Boeing 737 Max 8, which will account for 50% of deliveries.\nPopular models with more than 180 seats include the A321 neo and the B737 Max 10, which will have an increasing share each year and will account for 40% of deliveries over the next 20 years.\nAirbus and Boeing are expected to develop a new generation of single-aisle aircraft in the early to mid-2030s.\nThe $1.1 trillion dual-aisle aircraft market will be dominated by the B787 and A350 models, with 250-300-seat \u201cmedium \u201d aircraft accounting for about 65% of the total value delivered.\nThe large passenger aircraft market will be contested by the A350-1000 and the B777-9.\nAircraft deliveries in regional markets are expected to reach a scale of $150 billion.\nAbout a third of them will be turboprop aircraft, based on 70-seat models.\nStarting in 2030, a larger 90-seat model will enter the market.\nFuture new aircraft projects in the market include the MA700 from China and an expected new line of aircraft from Embraer.\nOlder models will be replaced by a new generation of aircraft.\nIt is predicted that about 80% of current passenger aircraft will be out of passenger service between 2021 and 2040.\nAs the airline industry begins to focus on driving down carbon emissions and focusing on sustainability, it will become increasingly important to replace these older, more fuel-efficient aircraft with new models.\nOverall, in addition to several relatively new aircraft that are being phased out earlier, around 19,000 aircraft in the global passenger fleet will be phased out by the end of 2020.\nAccording to analysis by Ascend by Cirium, the average economic life expectancy for single-aisle aircraft is 22 years and for twin-aisle aircraft is 20 years.\nThe number of freighters is growing: including new freighters and refitted freighters\nAs the global freight industry continues to perform strongly, freighter capacity (based on available tonnage kilometres) is expected to grow by 3.3% over 2019, with a projected supply of around 3,500 freighters over the next 20 years.\nOf this total, it is expected that 30 per cent will be new freighters and 70 per cent will be converted from passenger aircraft.\nAbout 1,050 new freighters are expected to be shipped, valued at $121 billion.\nMore online shopping during the epidemic period has promoted the development of e-commerce, and the growth of e-commerce has promoted the conversion of airliners to freighters.\nModification projects are focused on newer models such as the A321, B737-800, A330 and B777-300ER.\nThe Cirium Fleet Forecast is an independent outlook report on the global commercial passenger and cargo aircraft market, based on the industry \u2019 s premier combination of data and years of expertise.\nClick here to download the executive summary of the Cirium Fleet Forecast 2021.\nAbout Cirium\nCirium is a company that combines powerful data and analytics services to drive the world \u2019 s continued growth. With decades of industry experience, Cirium provides clients with expert insights to help companies, aircraft manufacturers, airports, airlines and financial institutions make informed business decisions that shape the future of the travel industry, improve business returns and improve customer experience. RELX PLC is the world \u2019 s leading provider of information and data analytics to professional and commercial customers across a wide range of industries.\nShares of parent company RELX PLC are traded on the London, Amsterdam and New York Stock Exchanges using the following ticker symbols: London: REL; Amsterdam: REN; New York: RELX.\nVisit cirium.com for more information or follow Cirium \u2019 s LinkedIn account and WeChat account, CiriumCN.\nDisclaimer: The original version of this announcement is the official authorized version. The translation is for convenience only. Please refer to the original version, the original version is the only version with legal effect.\nContacts\nFor media inquiries, please contact:\nCirium Media Team\nRachel Humphries / June Lee\nmedia @ Cirium.com\nThe PC Agency\nPaul Charles / Michael Johnson / Callum McGoldrick\nCirium @ pc.agency\nContacts\nFor media inquiries, please contact:\nCirium Media Team\nRachel Humphries / June Lee\nmedia @ Cirium.com\nThe PC Agency\nPaul Charles / Michael Johnson / Callum McGoldrick\nCirium @ pc.agency","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0037.json.gz:6260","uncompressed_offset":72581204,"url":"www.businesswire.com/news/home/20211215005496/zh-CN/?feedref=1-6SMMw3HgudSqfciOInFAT1albrG1Eq4mAeVP392109CPVbsZzkxB2zncMjZ7S5evRMp3sIgu8q3wq1OF24lT93qbEzrwa15HGbLqMObxahCRHqO6sXub3Hylc4qv6iOhC8fNUMDBuoZ8W8sD2diw%3D%3D","warc_date":"2021-12-20T12:41:14.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:65a6d821-4ded-4ba5-874a-2aa5ee48ba5e>","warc_url":"https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20211215005496/zh-CN/?feedref=1-6SMMw3HgudSqfciOInFAT1albrG1Eq4mAeVP392109CPVbsZzkxB2zncMjZ7S5evRMp3sIgu8q3wq1OF24lT93qbEzrwa15HGbLqMObxahCRHqO6sXub3Hylc4qv6iOhC8fNUMDBuoZ8W8sD2diw=="},"created":"2021-12-20T12:45:06.000Z","lang":"eng"},"515c5776-a50e-4782-835a-77bfb011b38e_922454685":{"id":"515c5776-a50e-4782-835a-77bfb011b38e_922454685","text":"Friday, 08 September 2023 05:25 GMT\n\nGlobal Single-Aisle Aircraft Market Is Projected To Reach The Value Of $222.20 Billion By 2030 X Herald\n\n\n(MENAFN- Ameliorate Digital Consultancy) According to the latest report by Virtue Market Research, in 2022, the Global Single-Aisle Aircraft Market was valued at USD 86.6 billion and is projected to reach a market size of USD 222.20 billion by 2030. Over the forecast period of 2023-2030, the market is projected to grow at a CAGR of 12.5%.\n\nRequest Sample Brochure @\n\nA prominent long-term driver for the Single-Aisle Aircraft market is the growing global demand for air travel. Even though the COVID-19 pandemic had a severe impact on the aviation industry, the long-term trend remains robust. The demand for single-aisle aircraft is fueled by several factors, including the expansion of low-cost carriers, increasing urbanization, and rising middle-class populations in emerging economies.\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic had an unprecedented impact on the aviation sector, leading to grounded fleets, reduced passenger demand, and financial strain on airlines. This setback prompted airlines to rethink their fleet strategies, with some deferring aircraft orders and retiring older aircraft to cut costs. Additionally, the pandemic accelerated the adoption of safety and hygiene measures in aircraft cabins, leading to increased investments in cabin air filtration and touchless technologies.\n\nA notable short-term driver for the Single-Aisle Aircraft market is the rebound in domestic and regional air travel. As countries reopen their borders and vaccination efforts progress, there is a growing preference for shorter flights, leading to increased demand for single-aisle aircraft. Airlines are reactivating grounded aircraft and placing orders for new, fuel-efficient models to meet this surge in regional travel.\n\nAn exciting opportunity in the Single-Aisle Aircraft market is the development of next-generation, fuel-efficient aircraft. With a growing emphasis on sustainability and reducing carbon emissions, aircraft manufacturers are investing in research and development to create more eco-friendly models. This includes the use of advanced materials, aerodynamic improvements, and more efficient engines. Airlines that invest in these next-gen aircraft can not only reduce their environmental footprint but also benefit from lower operating costs in the long run.\n\nOne of the prominent trends observed in the Single-Aisle Aircraft industry is the rise of digitalization and connectivity. In-flight Wi-Fi, entertainment systems, and integrated passenger services are becoming standard features in modern single-aisle aircraft. Airlines are leveraging these trends to enhance the passenger experience and gain a competitive edge. Additionally, digitalization plays a crucial role in aircraft maintenance and operations, helping airlines optimize their fleet performance and reduce downtime.\n\nCustomize The Report According to Your Needs @\n\nSegmentation Analysis:\n\nThe global Single-Aisle Aircraft Market segmentation includes:\n\nBy Type of Aircraft: Narrow-Body, Wide-Body, Regional Aircraft\n\nAmong these, the Narrow-Body aircraft category stands out as the largest segment. These aircraft are designed for short to medium-haul flights and are favored by airlines for their versatility and cost-efficiency. Narrow-Body aircraft are well-suited for both domestic and international routes, making them the preferred choice for many carriers.\n\nIn terms of growth, the Narrow-Body segment takes the lead yet again. The market for Narrow-Body aircraft is witnessing significant expansion due to the increasing demand for regional and domestic travel. Airlines are looking to replace older aircraft with more fuel-efficient and environmentally friendly Narrow-Body models, driving the growth of this segment.\n\nBy Engine Type: Turbofan, Turboprop\n\nAmong these categories, Turboprop engines are the largest segment. These engines are commonly found in regional aircraft that operate shorter routes and require a different set of performance characteristics compared to their Turbofan counterparts. Turboprop engines are known for their fuel efficiency and reliability, making them a preferred choice for regional carriers.\n\nHowever, when it comes to growth, Turbofan engines take the lead. The demand for Turbofan-powered Single-Aisle Aircraft is on the rise, driven by the need for higher efficiency, reduced emissions, and greater operational range. Airlines are increasingly opting for Turbofan engines in their narrow-body aircraft to meet the growing demand for longer-haul regional and international flights.\n\nPurchase Full Report @\n\nRegional Analysis:\n\nThe Single-Aisle Aircraft market spans across variregions, including North America, Europe, Asia-Pacific, South America, and the Middle East & Africa. Each of these regions has its unique characteristics and influences on the market.\n\nAsia-Pacific emerges as the largest region in this segment. This region encompasses numerfast-growing economies, a burgeoning middle class, and a robust travel and tourism industry. As a result, airlines in Asia-Pacific have been expanding their fleets to meet the increasing demand for air travel. With a foon domestic and regional routes, narrow-body aircraft have been particularly favored in this region, contributing to its leadership in the Single-Aisle Aircraft market.\n\nIn terms of growth, Europe takes the lead. Despite being a mature aviation market, Europe is experiencing a surge in demand for narrow-body aircraft, primarily due to the need for more fuel-efficient and environmentally friendly options. European airlines are increasingly looking to modernize their fleets with state-of-the-art single-aisle aircraft, thereby driving the growth of this segment in the region.\n\nThe Middle East & Africa region also shows promise in terms of growth, driven by the emergence of airlines in the Middle East as major global players. These airlines are expanding their networks and investing in modern, fuel-efficient narrow-body aircraft to meet the growing demand for long-haul travel.\n\nNorth America, with its well-established aviation industry, continues to be a significant market for single-aisle aircraft. While it may not be the fastest-growing region, North America remains a stable and vital market for these aircraft, catering to both domestic and international routes.\n\nSouth America, although a smaller market compared to the other regions, also contributes to the demand for single-aisle aircraft. Airlines in South America are focusing on modernizing their fleets to enhance operational efficiency and reduce emissions.\n\nLatest Industry Developments:\n\n  \u2022 One of the key strategies adopted by companies is a strong emphasis on fuel-efficient and environmentally friendly aircraft. With the aviation industry facing increasing pressure to reduce carbon emissions, manufacturers are investing in the development of next-generation single-aisle aircraft with improved fuel efficiency. This includes the use of advanced materials, aerodynamic design enhancements, and the incorporation of more fuel-efficient engines. Furthermore, there is a growing trend towards the electrification of aircraft systems, including electric taxiing systems and more electric aircraft architectures. These innovations aim to reduce the overall carbon footprint of single-aisle aircraft, aligning with global sustainability goals.\n  \u2022 To enhance their market share, aircraft manufacturers are expanding their global reach and customer base. They are targeting emerging markets with fast-growing air travel demand, such as Asia-Pacific and the Middle East. These regions represent significant opportunities for fleet expansion, especially with narrow-body aircraft designed for short- to medium-haul routes. Another trend is fleet modernization. Airlines, particularly in mature markets like North America and Europe, are retiring older aircraft and replacing them with state-of-the-art single-aisle aircraft. This trend is driven by the need to improve operational efficiency, reduce maintenance costs, and enhance passenger comfort. Manufacturers that offer the latest technology and fuel-efficient options have a competitive advantage in this regard.\n  \u2022 Connectivity and digital solutions are becoming increasingly important in the aviation industry. Airlines are seeking aircraft equipped with advanced connectivity options to enhance the passenger experience, provide in-flight entertainment, and enable seamless inteaccess. Manufacturers are responding by integrating cutting-edge connectivity solutions into their single-aisle aircraft offerings. Additionally, the use of data analytics and predictive maintenance has gained prominence. Airlines are leveraging data from their aircraft to optimize operations, reduce downtime, and lower maintenance costs. Aircraft manufacturers are incorporating these features into their products to meet the demand for data-driven solutions.\n\nAbout Us:\n\nVirtue Market Research stands at the forefront of strategic analysis, empowering businesses to navigate complex market landscapes with precision and confidence. Specializing in both syndicated and bespoke consulting services, we offer in-depth insights into the ever-evolving interplay between global demand and supply dynamics. Leveraging our expertise, businesses can identify emerging opportunities, discern critical trends, and make decisions that pave the way for future success.\n\nContact Us:\n\nVirtue Market Research\n\nKumar Plaza, #103, SRPF Rd, Ramtekadi, Pune, Maharashtra 411013, India\n\nE-mail:\n\nPhone: +1-917 436 1025\n\n\n\nMENAFN08092023004660010643ID1107033579\n\n\nLegal Disclaimer:\nMENAFN provides the information \u201cas is\u201d without warranty of any kind. We do not accept any responsibility or liability for the accuracy, content, images, videos, licenses, completeness, legality, or reliability of the information contained in this article. If you have any complaints or copyright issues related to this article, kindly contact the provider above.","url":"https://menafn.com/1107033579/Global-Single-Aisle-Aircraft-Market-Is-Projected-To-Reach-The-Value-Of-22220-Billion-By-2030-X-Herald"},"9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96_466373894":{"id":"9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96_466373894","text":"March 10, 2022\nAbu Dhabi UAE\nPrayer times\nFlying...\nTaking off from epidemic airports\nFlying...\nTaking off from epidemic airports\nMarch 6, 2022 16: 52\nHassouna Al Tayeb (Abu Dhabi)\nMajor industries typically take over the helm of the economy and create jobs in society.\nThe growth of the world economy in the past decade has been boosted by developments in various industries, in particular technology, science, health and manufacturing.\nAs the pace of spending and wealth increases around the world, existing industries grow and others disappear from the scene amid the rising development of human society.\nIt is the responsibility of large industries to provide essential products and services that improve the lives of billions of people around the world.\nThe aviation industry is among the industries most affected by the COVID-19 virus, with Boeing, for example, suffering losses of about $11.9 billion in 2020.\nThis industry includes a number of companies that are involved in the development and manufacture of aircraft for purposes including commercial, passenger, military, cargo, government, surveillance and refueling of other aircraft in the air.\nIt also includes sales by private companies of equipment used for space flights and missions.\nThe value of the global aviation sector declined to $359.3 billion in 2020, from $818.3 billion in 2019, as a result of the Coronavirus epidemic, with expectations of $471.8 billion this year.\nThe aviation industry encompasses almost all aspects of air travel and related activities.\nThis means that it includes the entire aviation sector, the aircraft industry, research companies, military aviation, and others.\nThe term aviation is usually used to describe mechanical air transport that is carried out through the use of aircraft.\nThe sector consists of two types of aircraft, regular and helicopter, as well as the new type of drones.\nThe aviation industry has two types of activity, the first related to passenger and cargo transport, while the second includes aircraft manufacturing, research operations, safety and military aviation, as well as companies specialized in the production, design and use of drones.\nThe importance of the aviation industry lies in connecting different continents, countries and cultures, as well as facilitating long-distance travel.\nIt also contributes significantly to the global economy, trade between countries and the creation of millions of jobs around the world.\nAmong the largest aircraft manufacturers are Boeing, Airbus and Lockheed Martin.\nThe European Airbus, which has industrial facilities in Germany, France and the Netherlands, is the largest in the world.\nThe Airbus A380 is also the largest aircraft in the world.\nAmerican Boeing, based in Chicago, comes in second place.\nIn addition to producing military aircraft, the company is also known for manufacturing spaceships.\nLockheed Martin is the world's largest manufacturer of warplanes, including the F-16, F-35 and others.\nAircraft manufacturers are planning to reduce the rate of production of large aircraft and focus on smaller ones, a trend that began just before the outbreak of the pandemic.\nThese companies are working to convince airlines to buy this type of aircraft because of its fuel efficiency of 15%.\nAmong the largest suppliers in the aviation industry are United Technologies, General Electric Aviation, Safran, Rolls-Royce Holdings, Honeywell Aerospace and others.\nThe activities of manufacturers vary from the design, construction, testing, sale, maintenance and production of spare parts, spaceships and others.\nThe value of aircraft production in 2015 was about $180.3 billion, of which 61 percent was for airlines, 14 percent for business and general aviation, 12 percent for military helicopters and about 3 percent for civilian helicopters.\nThe value of maintenance, repairs and refurbishment of the aircraft is estimated at $135.1 billion, bringing the total volume of production to $315.4 billion.\nBoosting demand activity is the growing affluence of the middle class in emerging markets.\nAir traffic is expected to rebound significantly in Latin America and Africa, although these regions are expected to suffer even more from the spread of COVID-19.\nWhile the proportion of aircraft grounded is usually estimated at 10%, it rose to 60% during the epidemic for 13,350 aircraft.\nAccording to data from Asnad Aviation Consultancy, 902 new aircraft were ordered from Boeing and Airbus this year, excluding cancelled orders and orders from non-profit customers, compared to 672 in 2020.\nIn this climate of awakening, airlines are planning to renew their fleets, driven by a rebound in summer travel, even in Europe, despite the slower pace of recovery from the epidemic than in the United States.\nAll rights reserved to Al Ittihad Newspaper 2022 \u00a9","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0007.json.gz:18562","uncompressed_offset":466373894,"url":"www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%8A/4268143/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-----%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%82%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%A1","warc_date":"2022-03-09T22:07:25.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9973d6d5-a9dc-411f-a89d-969510946c96>","warc_url":"https://www.alittihad.ae/news/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%8A/4268143/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-----%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%82%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B9-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%A1"},"created":"2022-03-09T22:36:02.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
