in access to construction careers and challenge ingrained biases."},{"citations":{"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743":100.0},"text":"In the United States, the share of women in construction has reached a record 14.1 percent, with initiatives like apprenticeships and training programs enabling more women to enter the field."},{"citations":{"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743":100.0},"text":"Women like Jenny Parker and Nicole Goulsby have demonstrated that attention to detail and relationship-building skills allow them to excel in construction roles, despite the need to prove themselves in male-dominated environments."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"These stories of success and resilience illustrate that women can thrive as crane operators and in other construction roles, paving the way for greater gender equality in the industry."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"The construction industry has long been perceived as a male-dominated field, with societal norms and gender stereotypes limiting women's access to technical roles and training opportunities."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Despite these barriers, women are increasingly breaking into construction, driven by passion and determination to challenge traditional expectations and succeed in male-dominated roles."},{"citations":{"08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15_17345750":100.0},"text":"Inspiring case studies, such as Noura Jamal Taha Mohamed, who became the first woman in Upper Egypt to obtain a heavy equipment driver\u2019s license, demonstrate how perseverance can overcome societal bullying and gender restrictions."},{"citations":{"08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15_17345750":100.0},"text":"Noura\u2019s journey included mastering loader operation to support her family and receiving training despite initial skepticism, showcasing her love for the profession and her ability to excel."},{"citations":{"fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff_953125432":100.0},"text":"Similarly, Li Rui, a tower crane operator in China, has achieved financial independence and professional growth, earning over 9,000 yuan monthly and investing in certifications to expand her skills."},{"citations":{"fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff_953125432":100.0},"text":"Li Rui\u2019s pride in contributing to the development of Xiongan New Area highlights the rewarding nature of construction work and the improved living conditions for workers in the industry."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Supportive measures, such as vocational training programs and mentorship opportunities, are helping women gain access to construction careers and challenge ingrained biases."},{"citations":{"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743":100.0},"text":"In the United States, the share of women in construction has reached a record 14.1 percent, with initiatives like apprenticeships and training programs enabling more women to enter the field."},{"citations":{"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743":100.0},"text":"Women like Jenny Parker and Nicole Goulsby have demonstrated that attention to detail and relationship-building skills allow them to excel in construction roles, despite the need to prove themselves in male-dominated environments."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"These stories of success and resilience illustrate that women can thrive as crane operators and in other construction roles, paving the way for greater gender equality in the industry."}],"references":["fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff_953125432","589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743","08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15_17345750","c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418"],"documents":{"08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15_17345750":{"id":"08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15_17345750","text":"General Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nGeneral Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nNoura learned to drive a loader and braved bullying to help her husband treat her two sons.\nA video.\nNoura put her two children with autism in front of her eyes and did not look at the difficulty and hardship of driving heavy equipment and decided to learn to drive \"Lauder\" to be the first woman in Upper Egypt to obtain a driver's license to improve her condition and help her husband to pay for the treatment of their two sons without considering the bullying she faced from the surrounding society in light of the customs and traditions that restrict women in Upper Egypt\nNoura Jamal Taha Mohamed, 36, daughter of Assiut, said that I am married and have three children, including two with autism, and since their birth, my husband and I visit doctors \u2019 clinics to treat them, and they are all in schools. I learned to drive a loader and challenge all the ridicule and bullying so that I can improve my income to help my husband to pay for my children \u2019 s treatment.\nNoura added: I learned from my friend about the announcement of the initiative of a decent life at the training center about training young people on crafts and applied to learn the craft of construction, but when I went to the training center I found the teaching of driving heavy equipment, so I decided to learn to drive the loader equipment and there were many challenges ahead of me.\nShe continued: When I asked the management of the training center to apply to learn to drive the loader, there was a great surprise from them, especially since it is an effort on any girl, but after presenting my request to the management of the training center, I found a welcome and support for me and joined the training on driving the loader and learn about all the basic tasks that follow during driving and check the stomach before operating it for the availability of safety means during driving.\nShe continued: I found great support from my husband, unlike the community that faced my desire to bully me, but this was an incentive for me to achieve my ambition, especially as I was putting my children in front of my eyes to find a source of income to help me with my husband in completing their treatment journey and not need anyone.\nAfter receiving my driver \u2019 s license, I will seek to find a real job opportunity within a company that values women \u2019 s work, especially as I seek to develop my life for the better.\nNoureddine Ahmed Mostafa Darwish, a heavy equipment trainer at the Assiut training center, said that the center provides training services for a number of equipment and trades, including training equipment on loaders, excavators and other heavy equipment, but for the first time in Assiut, a woman is applying to learn to drive a loader.\nNoureddine added that \u201cNoura \u201d was quick to respond during the training period due to her love for this profession and this helped greatly in passing the tests and showed proficiency in the speed of receiving information and going through the experience without fear or hesitation and I did not face any difficulties in training her only at the beginning because she is a woman undergoing a huge experience as a heavy stomach driving for the first time but she excelled after.\nWhen Noura applied for a heavy equipment driving course, we asked her to think and slow down on this matter, especially as she was the first woman to apply for such courses, but we found her determination to take this course, so we presented the matter to the head of the agency, who welcomed the order and asked us to support her.\nhttps: / / fb.watch / kLkP7r8 _ TB /? mibextid = NnVzG8","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0015.json.gz:51381","uncompressed_offset":17345750,"url":"www.elbalad.news/5782555","warc_date":"2023-05-26T09:15:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:08bf5561-f112-47d8-ae82-2041a9b4fc15>","warc_url":"https://www.elbalad.news/5782555"},"created":"2023-05-26T09:16:21.000Z","lang":"eng"},"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":{"id":"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418","text":"Women severely underrepresented in construction, but that\u2019s changing\n\nWhat you need to know:\n\n  \u2022 In nearly every construction site I encounter, the workforce is overwhelmingly male.\n  \u2022 The term \u2018foreman\u2019 is deeply ingrained in our collective lexicon, while phrases like \u2018forewoman\u2019 or the more inclusive \u2018foreperson\u2019 remain relatively uncommon.\n\nAcross the country, construction sites are a hive of activity, with the government\u2019s ambitious affordable housing project leading the charge. Whenever I pass through these bustling sites, I can\u2019t help but notice the workers clad in overalls, their faces dusted with cement powder as they push wheelbarrows brimming with mortar. Amidst this flurry of activity, one figure stands out \u2013 the foreman, barking instructions and overseeing the skilled artisans, or fundis, as they are commonly known.\n\nInterestingly, in nearly every construction site I encounter, the workforce is overwhelmingly male. Rarely do I spot a woman among the fundis, save for the occasional food vendor. Historically, the construction industry has been a predominantly male bastion, a fact reflected in the terminology we use \u2013 the term \u2018foreman\u2019 is deeply ingrained in our collective lexicon, while phrases like \u2018forewoman\u2019 or the more inclusive \u2018foreperson\u2019 remain relatively uncommon.\n\nWhile the underrepresentation of women in this field is a global issue, the challenges faced by women in this industry are particularly pronounced in Africa. This gender imbalance reflects a deeper, systemic issue within the construction sector. For too long, this industry has been perceived as a \u2018man\u2019s playground\u2019, with women often relegated to peripheral roles or excluded entirely. The reasons for this disparity are multifaceted, ranging from societal norms and gender stereotypes, to a lack of equal opportunities and support systems for women seeking careers in this field.\n\nLimited access to education and training opportunities, particularly in Stem fields, hinders women\u2019s preparedness for technical roles. Furthermore, societal expectations and domestic responsibilities frequently clash with the demanding nature of construction work, making it difficult for women to balance their professional and personal lives. This gender imbalance not only perpetuates inequality but also deprives the industry of the valuable contributions and perspectives that women can bring to the table. However, times are changing, and more women are breaking into the industry, driven by their passion, determination, and desire to contribute to community development. Despite obstacles such as teenage pregnancies, early marriages, and societal pressures, many carved out their place in this male-dominated field.\n\nTheir stories are a testament to the power of perseverance and an unwavering commitment to pursuing their dreams. From the high school dropout who found her calling on a construction site, to the young mother who juggled parenting responsibilities while mastering the art of bricklaying, these women have shattered stereotypes and proved that no challenge is too great when met with an indomitable spirit. Through their journeys, they have not only acquired valuable skills and experience but have also become beacons of inspiration for others.\n\nThis week, we celebrate these trailblazers, exploring their unique paths and the lessons they have learned along the way. Their stories offer a candid glimpse into the challenges and triumphs that have shaped their lives, from navigating male-dominated workplaces to balancing family responsibilities with demanding careers. As we strive to create a more inclusive and equitable society, it is imperative that we challenge the deeply ingrained biases and stereotypes that have traditionally kept women on the sidelines of the construction industry.\n\nThe government can play a pivotal role by implementing initiatives that support and empower women in this field, including investing in educational programmes, vocational training, mentorship opportunities, and inclusive policies that promote gender equality and non-discrimination. This way, we can empower a new generation of women to take their rightful place alongside their male counterparts, ushering in an era of diversity and excellence in this vital sector.\n\nEmpowering women in the construction industry can have far-reaching benefits, contributing to the overall advancement of gender equality and sustainable development in the country.","url":"https://nation.africa/kenya/news/gender/women-severely-underrepresented-in-construction-but-that-s-changing-4641542"},"fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff_953125432":{"id":"fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff_953125432","text":"People 's Daily Online > > Economy and Technology\nLet farmers live sesame blossoms high\nJanuary 14, 2022 06: 07 | Source: People's Daily - People's Daily\nSmall number\nFigure 1: Shuangfeng County in Hunan Province develops lantern manufacturing and processing industry, driving farmers to increase income.\nRecently, in the employment poverty alleviation workshop of Sangyuan community in Jinkai Street, employees are driving red lanterns.\nPhoto by Naijihui (People 's Vision)\nFigure 2: In the corn drying field of Sanzha Village, Sanzha Town, Ganzhou District, Zhangye City, Gansu Province, large-scale thresher carried out corn threshing operations.\nPhoto by Yang Yongwei (People 's Vision)\nSource: Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs\nCore reading\nJust past 2021, from the beginning to the end of the year, the majority of farmers worked hard and worked hard, in exchange for heavy harvests.\nThis year, absolute poverty has been eradicated, mountains and villages have changed dramatically, mountains and rivers have become a well-off society, and things have been good for the people and the years have been good.\nLooking back, the harvest is full; looking forward, the future can be expected.\nThis year, the 20th National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) will be held to ensure a stable and healthy economic environment and a peaceful social environment.\nThe new journey of the new mission, the development of \"three rural\" to open a new chapter, consolidate and expand the achievements of poverty alleviation, comprehensively promote rural revitalization, so that the majority of farmers' lives sesame flowers high, the field of hope is full of vitality.\nGrain farmer Qiu Jiebo\nHigh efficiency chain extension\nOur reporter is calm.\n\"As long as we find the right way, there is a great future for agriculture,\" said Qiu Jiebo, an 85-year-old in Qinyan Village, Henghe Town, Cixi City, Zhejiang Province.\nUniversity mechanical engineering graduate, he returned to the village in 2010, registered a family farm, planting wheat, rice and other food crops, and now has been dealing with crops for more than 10 years.\nGideon has a good policy.\nThe city will give 20,000 to 30,000 yuan a year to college students under the age of 35 who return to their hometown to start businesses.\nQiu Jiebo said that many young people have gone out to work, and the village still relies on machinery and technology to grow land.\nIn June 2020, Qiu Jiebo purchased the first unmanned rice transplanter in Cixi City, relying on Beidou positioning system and Internet of Things technology to \u201cintelligently upgrade \u201d the traditional rice transplanter. Qiu Jiebo lamented:\u201c The intelligent agricultural machine can plan the optimal route by itself, complete automatic rice transplanting, intelligent obstacle avoidance, turning and other operations, which is very convenient! \u201d\nIn Cixi, the late rice harvest begins in early November every year, which is also the busiest day of Qiu Jiebo - receive the study tour team during the day, take the students to experience cutting rice, beating rice, drying, and grasp the processing of rice at night, packaging finished rice.\n\"Last year, I planted more than 200 mu of rice, all of 'Jiahe 218' high-quality japonica rice, each mu yield of thousands of jin, half sold to the grain warehouse, about 1.5 yuan per jin. The rest of the processing sold to the market.\" Qiu Jiebo said of the grain industry is very proud.\nOver the years, he registered a trademark and took the brand route, \"our rice can sell 3.5 to 4 yuan per catty, and the husk is provided to the farmers as feed, 7 yuan per catty, and the gross profit can reach more than 100,000 yuan a year.\"\nFrom planting to hosting, to processing and sales, and rice paddies to study, Qiu Jiebo tasted the sweetness of elongating the food industry chain.\nThe town is a key food producing area in Cixi City.\nIn the past two years, the town has set up a professional cooperative association of Jinsui Agricultural Machinery Service Co., Ltd., and the young Qiu Jiebo was elected as the head of the association. Grain farmers integrate into the modern agricultural industry chain.\nQiu Jiebo said confidently: \"We will definitely expand the area of grain growing.\"\nA few days ago, the farm has signed a new transfer contract for 300 acres of land.\nNext, we must strengthen rice processing, carry out socialized services, and let more farmers meet a bumper harvest through mechanized grain growing. \"\nExpatriate worker Li Rui\nStable income in hand\nThis reporter is often Qin\nLi Rui started a new day of work at a construction site in Xiongan New District of the Second Bureau of China Construction and Construction: Wear gloves, fasten safety belts, and prevent falling ropes, and in less than five minutes, skilfully climbed from the ground to the 50-meter high cab.\nAs a tower crane female driver, this less than 5 square meters of the \"square grid\" is Li Rui's big stage - hook, lift, yard... a series of actions clean, steel, cement, scaffold pipe and other building materials are accurately placed in the designated position.\n\"Eye sharp, accurate, careful, eat craft rice, heart steady!\" Li Rui spirit, it is difficult to connect this double fiber slim hand with the huge tower crane boom.\nIn March 2021, Li Rui bid farewell to his hometown, Guizhou Bijie, and came to Xiongan New Area to work. \"Less than one year, she saved more than 70,000 yuan.\"\nThe job of a tower crane driver is not easy to do.\nLi Rui said: \"At the beginning of climbing up and down, the legs are soft, palms are sweating, and every day to complete the workload of 80 to 100 cranes, which requires excellent psychological quality and superb operation skills.\" And...\nA skill in hand, the monthly income \"rose high\", rose to more than 9,000 yuan.\nLi Rui told reporters that the construction site has now set up a \"special account\" mechanism for the payment of wages for migrant workers.\n\"The monthly salary hits the personal card on time, timely and convenient.\nI give money to my old relatives every month, and I feel full of achievement.\nThis is not, and to the child to buy a phone watch, direct video call, can be convenient! \"\nIn addition to income, Li Rui also praised the living conditions of the construction site. \u201cIn winter, you can take a hot bath at any time. \u201d She said that the construction site is getting better and better for migrant workers, and every dormitory is equipped with air conditioning, 24-hour hot water, and the food is delicious and the price is not expensive.\nNow the construction industry for technical jobs more and more demand, speaking of their career planning, Li Rui out a \"learning investment plan\": she every month from the salary to take part in the purchase of learning materials and apply for professional certificates, \"art more than pressure, I plan to test an excavator certificate.\"\nIn the past year, the construction of Xiong'an New Area has been changing with each passing day, and buildings have been constantly refreshing the \"height\".\nLi Rui is not only a \"beautiful dancer\" in the sky, but also a witness to the growth of the Xiongan New Area. \"Look, this is the building I took from the height, beautiful...\" From digging the foundation to building the tall building, from the mud and water to planting, a photo in the mobile phone is the common growth log of Li Rui and this new city.\n\"My New Year 's wish is to bring my children to the construction site and tell him about the happiness of growing up with the city.\" Li Rui' s words are full of pride.\nZhang Kang, Head of the Village Revitalization Team\nRaise the lives of the poor to a higher level\nOur reporter Wang Hao, Li Xiaoqing\nThe green mountains are stacked, a ridge of tea trees like a green belt coiled.\nZhang Kang took a deep breath, refreshing air accompanied by the fragrance of tea into the heart and spleen, \"good ecology will certainly grow a good product.\"\nIn May 2021, Zhang Kang, who works at the statistical bureau of the Enshi Family Miao Autonomous Prefecture in Hubei Province, \u201cmoved \u201d his office to the deep mountains and became the leader of the village revitalization team of Dongzhou Village in Hefeng County.\nAfter taking over the baton, he took lessons from the former team leader, and then held a forum without stopping and looking for villagers to do their homework.\nZhang Kang, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, made the remarks at a meeting with visiting\nOpening the account book of the village: In 2018, the whole village was lifted out of poverty, and cement roads and running water were opened; in 2020, the per capita net income of farmers was more than 12,000 yuan...\nThe industry \u2019 s \u201cstrength \u201d is growing.\nIn the past, the villagers almost planted tea at home, but these years the market changes fast, the villagers can not keep up. \"As long as we find the advantages, improve the industrial competitiveness, tea will be able to sell a good price.\" Zhang Kang calculated that the village is clean and beautiful, this is the biggest advantage, take the road of green development, and can not be wrong.\nHow to promote the new technology? Will the villagers accept it? There are many challenges ahead.\nZhang Kang and the team members held a mobilization meeting in the village, looking for large growers to demonstrate, and helping the villagers to pick up the fine accounts. \"We docked with the tea factory, and the quality is good, which is higher than the market price.\" A trip to work, everyone's bottom is enough.\n\"With the organic fertilizer, the output has increased, the quality of tea is better, and each mu can earn 500 yuan more,\" tea farmer She Kunming said.\nA family of tea farmers signed a commitment to green production, and a number of tea gardens were upgraded to ecological tea gardens.\nAt the end of the year, the price of fresh tea per catty was 50 yuan higher, and the tea industry is expected to drive farmers to increase their income by 3.5 million yuan a year.\nWith good mountains and good water, the development potential of the village is not small.\nIt is the new exploration of the village task force to make a workshop in the field and a tea garden into a park.\nZhang Kang opened a plan, 22 project construction points are densely marked, \"When the forest fruit picking park, education and research base and other infrastructure is built, the planting and sales links can be opened,\" the \"season harvest\" becomes \"season harvest\", Zhang Kang said.\nIn October 2021, some villagers encountered a water problem. \u201cThe water tap at home does not water. \u201d Zhang Kang and village cadres investigated the problem, opened up water sources, and laid water pipes, and 17 villagers quickly drank tap water.\n\"Good management of water, in order to long-term benefit.\" The village team organized the villagers to set up a drinking water association, 19 pools, 25 water cellars have a special person responsible, many beneficiary farmers, party members representatives actively participate in the daily patrol.\nThe premise of rural revitalization is to consolidate the achievements of poverty alleviation. \"We do everything in the village well, ensure that the help is kept in the file, and lead the villagers to stride toward the goal of prosperous industry, rural beauty, and rich farmers.\" Zhang Kangdao made his New Year's wish.\nLayout: Cai Huawei\nPeople 's Daily (January 14, 2022, 18 pages)\n(Editor: Yang Guangyu, Yue Hongbin)\nShare it so more people can see it.\nBack to top","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0001.json.gz:9220","uncompressed_offset":953125432,"url":"finance.people.com.cn/n1/2022/0114/c1004-32330981.html","warc_date":"2022-01-13T22:36:49.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fa814205-0346-442b-87c5-93059583ffff>","warc_url":"http://finance.people.com.cn/n1/2022/0114/c1004-32330981.html"},"created":"2022-01-13T23:32:25.000Z","lang":"eng"},"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743":{"id":"589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9_935642743","text":"Daytime Plus\nSend Save Print PDF\nWomen break into construction sector to fill labour shortages\nBloomberg: The number of construction workers in the United States exceeded 1 million in May last year, for the first time since data collection began in 1964, and the share of women among workers in the sector reached its highest level at 14.1 percent last month.\nAbout a third of construction workers in the United States are Hispanic, according to BLS.\nCerato herself got to know the industry at an early age through her Mexican immigrant father, saying, \u201cI used to go out to work with him, and I never saw anyone like me, so it never occurred to me that it could be a viable career path. \u201d\nThe presence of another Latina as a mentor made a big difference, she said, adding: \u201cThat \u2019 s why our representation is important. \u201d\nOne of the women is Andy Dirkschneider, who negotiates millions of dollars in loans to buy land for her family \u2019 s homebuilder, but sometimes vendors call her \u201cpetite \u201d and ask to speak to the man in charge.\nDirkschneider, 32, who heads Brookline Homes in Charlotte, said: \u201cI tell them I \u2019 m the man in charge.\nA young blonde girl doing this job confuses everyone.\nIt \u2019 s frustrating, but it can \u2019 t be allowed to. \u201d\nDirkschneider and thousands of women like her are breaking through the walls of the professions.\nIt is not brittle, it is concrete.\nThe field of construction has always been a world for men, from handicrafts such as construction and carpentry to the offices of developers and executive companies.\nThe accelerating wave of retirement of the 1960s and 1970s generation has exacerbated the industry \u2019 s chronic labor shortage.\nConstruction jobs totaled 440,000 in April, the highest in Bureau of Labor Statistics records that began in 2001.\nAryan Higuish, a senior researcher and fellow at the Women \u2019 s Policy Research Institute, said there is room for growth, because the construction sector \u2019 s historical dependence on men now risks constraining its growth.\nThe institute estimates that about a third of women in the industry work in deals, and their share across sectors such as painting and carpentry is still as small as a tenth, though Higuish believes it will continue to grow.\nThis is partly because of the need for labor and because states and local administrations want to see more diversity in companies when they are awarded contracts.\nPatrice Haley, of the diversity leadership team at construction giant DPR, said: \u201cIn this industry, we can \u2019 t dismiss people on the basis of gender.\n\u201cA lot of veterans are retiring, and we can \u2019 t leave any of the doors closed. \u201d\nOne of the temptations for women in the industry, Haley said, was to see what they were building right in front of their eyes, and she had started working in the industry in a manual job that required wearing a helmet and toe boots.\nShe said, \"I can say I worked on this and built that.\"\nThere \u2019 s also the temptation to pay better than many other jobs that don \u2019 t require a college degree: In 2021, the average salary of an electrician was $59,000 and $98,500 for a construction manager, according to U.S. Department of Labor data.\nTaqiya Wallace, 35, works for a large energy company in tracking construction project documents.\nBut she dreams of getting a license as a general contractor to start working on her own.\nIn June, I began studying building skills in a 16-week curriculum organized by Goodwill Industries in South Piedmont, Charlotte, where I learned to read blueprints and handle equipment.\nIf all goes according to plan, she will finish training with four industry certifications.\nAlthough Goodwill does not target women, its organizers say a group of 15 people who completed training last year were all women, about half of whom went on to work in industry jobs.\nWallace, who was the first to receive a college degree in her family, sees getting a contractor \u2019 s license and hanging a sign for her company as a way to build the wealth she can bequeath to her family.\nShe said, \u201cI want to be able to tell them this is our legacy. \u201d\nHarassment and discrimination\nDespite these encouraging trends, the sector still has a long way to go.\nAbout a quarter of respondents to a survey of 2,635 workers conducted by the Women \u2019 s Policy Research Institute last year said they had experienced sexual harassment or repeated harassment on the basis of sex.\nHalf of those surveyed said that their lack of equal treatment by men was frequent or persistent.\nJenny Parker stood at a construction site in High Point, North Carolina, on a very hot day in July, grabbing a paper cup with an iced drink as she looked at her sawdust, paint and sweat stained shirt and said, \"I love this.\nIt took me 10 years to get here. \u201d\nParker, who spent nine years in the Marine Corps, was upset by the managerial jobs she worked so she could pay her bills while raising her daughter, so she started working hard in real estate.\nShe signed up for training in building skills so she could repair the rental housing she owned.\nAt High Point, Parker received hands-on training in building house structures, performing stone work, and installing roofs.\nShe said she was able to work in partnership with the men on the team, but there were tensions at times, adding: \u201cTo be female in a male environment you have to prove yourself and work twice as hard, \u201d noting that some men do not accept instructions from a woman.\nShe said, \u201cIt \u2019 s a mindset that men should overcome. \u201d\nNicole Goulsby, owner of Red Ladder Residential, a construction company in Raleigh, North Carolina, recalls that when she started running worksites, some men ignored her when she addressed them.\nShe said her experience of bias faded when she distributed her signed paychecks, and she now notes that there are more women on the crews she contracts, whether they ride boards or paint.\nGolsby explained that women build relationships easily and are more attentive to details, making them suitable for her field of work.\nNicknamed \u201cBecky Nicky, \u201d Golsby said,\u201c I see things that no one else sees, and that \u2019 s why I do my job well. \u201d\nThe construction industry is also attracting more minority women.\nAn analysis by the Women \u2019 s Policy Research Institute found that the number of female construction apprentices between 2016 and 2019 nearly doubled, while Latinas recorded the largest increase of any race.\nIf we look at Ferridiana Cerato who graduated from college in 2020 with a double major in history and Spanish without being able to find any job that would enable her to benefit from her education well, she decided to try construction management.\nCerato took courses and received some certificates, including a certificate in welding.\nShe is now a project engineer in Indianapolis.\nThe job requires toughness, the 24-year-old says, with a lot of conversational \u201cthat doesn \u2019 t conform to HR rules \u201d and dealing with cynicism at times.\nCerato is one of three women in a team of nine managers and the only Latina among them.\nAdd a new comment\nThe comment received from the participant or reader is an expression of his own opinion and does not reflect the opinion of the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Nahar\nView comments","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0025.json.gz:9599","uncompressed_offset":935642743,"url":"www.annaharkw.com/annahar/Article.aspx?id=941636","warc_date":"2022-08-24T03:53:07.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:589ca671-5a89-4831-abc9-9f0a59aeb2b9>","warc_url":"https://www.annaharkw.com/annahar/Article.aspx?id=941636"},"created":"2022-08-24T05:00:57.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
