14-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Nevertheless, many women have successfully entered the construction industry through perseverance, overcoming obstacles such as teenage pregnancies, early marriages, and societal pressures."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Government initiatives, including educational programs, vocational training, mentorship opportunities, and inclusive policies, play a crucial role in supporting and empowering women in the construction industry."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"For example, Ferrexpo has implemented a diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) strategy since 2020, resulting in a 60% increase in women in leadership positions over three years."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"In 2022, Ferrexpo further demonstrated its commitment to gender equality by signing the Women\u2019s Empowerment Principles to promote career opportunities for women."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"The company also offers male parental leave programs to support women\u2019s career growth, ensuring family income stability during transitions."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Embedding inclusion efforts at all organizational levels ensures that gender parity becomes the norm rather than the exception."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Training programs that include mentorship, skill-building workshops, and leadership development opportunities are instrumental in helping women succeed in technical fields."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Leadership support and well-researched DEI policies significantly boost confidence in fair treatment, aiding in the recruitment and retention of dedicated workers."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Employers in Ukraine are actively attracting women to atypical positions and supporting their retraining to adapt to new roles."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Meest Group, for instance, has formed entire women\u2019s teams in roles such as warehouse employees, sorting center staff, and operational department heads."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"The company has also adjusted operational processes and introduced technology to create more comfortable working conditions for women."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Women at Meest Group have demonstrated effective work characterized by consistency, adaptability, and openness to new knowledge."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Meest Group plans to attract women to courier positions and is making adjustments to accommodate the physical demands of these roles."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Similarly, ATB employs over 56,000 Ukrainians, with 67% being women, and has adapted to include women in roles traditionally considered male, such as security guards."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"ATB also provides free training for employees, enabling women to gain new skills and advance in their careers, including in male-dominated roles like loader drivers."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"At Ferrexpo, women have advanced in operating heavy machinery, such as dump trucks and mining equipment, through targeted training and mentorship programs."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Ferrexpo has successfully addressed gender biases, increasing trust in female leaders and motivating employees to pursue professional development."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"The shipping industry has also made progress in recruiting and retaining women, particularly at junior and trainee levels, though fewer women occupy senior roles."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"When women constitute 30% of decision-making forums, they are no longer treated as 'exceptional,' fostering more inclusive environments and reducing backlash to DEI efforts."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"It is important to recognize that women in the workforce are diverse in their needs, with workplace requirements varying based on factors such as age, nationality, ethnicity, and gender identity."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Technical positions, such as fleet and port management, show slower progress in gender inclusion compared to fields like HR and marketing, underscoring the need for targeted initiatives in technical roles."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Peer support systems are pivotal in fostering an inclusive workplace, but disparities based on factors like nationality and culture must be addressed to ensure all employees feel valued."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Regular feedback mechanisms and updated policies can help maintain employee morale and engagement, particularly during challenging industry conditions."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Embedding fair practices and equality is a key differentiator for success in a global and competitive workforce."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Farkhana Safargaleeva, a seasoned crane operator, embarked on her career immediately after finishing school and has accumulated over 15 years of experience in the field."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"After taking a break, Safargaleeva returned to crane operation and has been working passionately for the past five years, demonstrating her enduring commitment to the profession."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Her family has been a source of unwavering support, encouraging her interest and success in this traditionally male-dominated role."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Similarly, Natalia Danilova, a compressor operator at Unity LLP, has spent 16 years in the construction industry, describing it as her dream job."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Danilova emphasizes the importance of maintaining good health to sustain her career and expresses her desire to continue working until retirement."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Women like Safargaleeva and Danilova exemplify how calmness and attentiveness\u2014qualities often associated with women\u2014can contribute to excelling in crane operation."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Modern women are increasingly breaking stereotypes by thriving in professions traditionally dominated by men, such as crane operation."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"At Unity LLP, women make up a significant portion of the workforce, with 25 out of 152 employees being women, and their professional skills are widely recognized."},{"citations":{"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":100.0},"text":"Chief Engineer Andrei Nekrasov acknowledges the exceptional professionalism of women at Unity LLP, noting their ability to faithfully perform their duties and mentor younger colleagues."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"The construction industry has long been perceived as a male-dominated sector, with women historically relegated to peripheral roles or excluded entirely."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Societal norms, gender stereotypes, and unequal opportunities have significantly contributed to the underrepresentation of women in construction roles."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"However, this trend is beginning to shift as more women break into the field, challenging traditional gender barriers."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Women in construction have overcome numerous challenges and stereotypes, proving their capabilities and inspiring others to pursue careers in male-dominated industries."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Empowering women in construction not only promotes gender equality but also contributes to sustainable development, benefiting both the industry and society at large."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Despite these advancements, women in construction still face challenges such as limited access to education and training opportunities, particularly in STEM fields."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Societal expectations and domestic responsibilities often conflict with the demanding nature of construction work, making it difficult for women to balance professional and personal lives."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Nevertheless, many women have successfully entered the construction industry through perseverance, overcoming obstacles such as teenage pregnancies, early marriages, and societal pressures."},{"citations":{"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":100.0},"text":"Government initiatives, including educational programs, vocational training, mentorship opportunities, and inclusive policies, play a crucial role in supporting and empowering women in the construction industry."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"For example, Ferrexpo has implemented a diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) strategy since 2020, resulting in a 60% increase in women in leadership positions over three years."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"In 2022, Ferrexpo further demonstrated its commitment to gender equality by signing the Women\u2019s Empowerment Principles to promote career opportunities for women."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"The company also offers male parental leave programs to support women\u2019s career growth, ensuring family income stability during transitions."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Embedding inclusion efforts at all organizational levels ensures that gender parity becomes the norm rather than the exception."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Training programs that include mentorship, skill-building workshops, and leadership development opportunities are instrumental in helping women succeed in technical fields."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Leadership support and well-researched DEI policies significantly boost confidence in fair treatment, aiding in the recruitment and retention of dedicated workers."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Employers in Ukraine are actively attracting women to atypical positions and supporting their retraining to adapt to new roles."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Meest Group, for instance, has formed entire women\u2019s teams in roles such as warehouse employees, sorting center staff, and operational department heads."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"The company has also adjusted operational processes and introduced technology to create more comfortable working conditions for women."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Women at Meest Group have demonstrated effective work characterized by consistency, adaptability, and openness to new knowledge."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Meest Group plans to attract women to courier positions and is making adjustments to accommodate the physical demands of these roles."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Similarly, ATB employs over 56,000 Ukrainians, with 67% being women, and has adapted to include women in roles traditionally considered male, such as security guards."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"ATB also provides free training for employees, enabling women to gain new skills and advance in their careers, including in male-dominated roles like loader drivers."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"At Ferrexpo, women have advanced in operating heavy machinery, such as dump trucks and mining equipment, through targeted training and mentorship programs."},{"citations":{"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":100.0},"text":"Ferrexpo has successfully addressed gender biases, increasing trust in female leaders and motivating employees to pursue professional development."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"The shipping industry has also made progress in recruiting and retaining women, particularly at junior and trainee levels, though fewer women occupy senior roles."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"When women constitute 30% of decision-making forums, they are no longer treated as 'exceptional,' fostering more inclusive environments and reducing backlash to DEI efforts."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"It is important to recognize that women in the workforce are diverse in their needs, with workplace requirements varying based on factors such as age, nationality, ethnicity, and gender identity."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Technical positions, such as fleet and port management, show slower progress in gender inclusion compared to fields like HR and marketing, underscoring the need for targeted initiatives in technical roles."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Peer support systems are pivotal in fostering an inclusive workplace, but disparities based on factors like nationality and culture must be addressed to ensure all employees feel valued."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Regular feedback mechanisms and updated policies can help maintain employee morale and engagement, particularly during challenging industry conditions."},{"citations":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":100.0},"text":"Embedding fair practices and equality is a key differentiator for success in a global and competitive workforce."}],"references":["59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573","485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500","65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178","c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418"],"documents":{"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573":{"id":"59271291-9f4e-455a-b133-f91be9278e03_342512573","text":"Seatrade Maritime is part of the Informa Markets Division of Informa PLC\n\nThis site is operated by a business or businesses owned by Informa PLC and all copyright resides with them. Informa PLC's registered office is 5 Howick Place, London SW1P 1WG. Registered in England and Wales. Number 8860726.\n\n5 key takeaways for DEI in maritime\n\nPhoto: Diversity Study Group\nHeidi Heseltine founder of Diversity Study Group\nEffective diversity, equality, and inclusion (DEI) initiatives are built on clear insight, agreed upon outcomes, and targeted approaches \u2014 intentionally working to avoid the inevitable pitfalls of a \u2018one-size-fits-all\u2019 approach.\n\nDrawing on data-led insights from members of the Diversity Study Group (DSG), Founder Heidi Heseltine offers 5 key insights on getting the basics right in maritime.\n\n1. Building inclusion throughout an organisation\u2019s levels\n\nWe know that shipping has made vital progress in recruiting and retaining women in certain sectors over the last few years, with significant effort put in into achieving a more gender balanced workforce. For instance, we\u2019ve seen improvements in closing the gap in more junior/trainee levels and in management positions \u2014 though these numbers drop off at head of department and director roles, indicating fewer women in executive and senior roles.\n\nWhile the knee-jerk reaction to this would be to specifically target greater inclusion only at specific tiers of management \u2014 which is often effective and can look great on corporate ESG registers \u2014 organisations should look to embed and maintain inclusion efforts at all levels, so that gender-parity is reflected throughout the business whether lower level or higher. After all, we know from well-established research that when women make up 30% in any given decision-making forum they stop being treated as \u2018exceptional\u2019 and additional women are not seen as particularly remarkable or threatening. This can be particularly key for creating welcoming spaces and proactively preventing backlash to DEI efforts, where possible. If the goal is embedding sustainable and resilient DEI practices, then our focus must be on ensuring that having women in all spaces in reasonable numbers is not the exception, but the rule.\n\n2. Avoiding seeing women in maritime as a monolith\n\nWomen are diverse in their requirements of a workplace and its culture, and should not be lumped into a single group defined by our presumptions. When considering what DEI approaches work best at sea or even on shore, we need to account for the fact that our global workforces are culturally diverse and have different levels of awareness when it comes to gender, age, nationality, ethnicity, sexual orientation, disability, neurodiversity and gender identity, amongst others. Societal norms, local legislation, and what is understood as \u2018diverse\u2019 can vary based on lived experience as well as the demographics of those involved. Understanding what is important to the women in individual workplaces and how we as an industry can support them will help us develop appropriate action plans for the short and long term.\n\n3. Creating support systems to enable gender parity in technical positions\n\nTechnical positions, fleet and port management are slower to evidence change and inclusion when compared to progress seen in more traditionally female-led fields like maritime finance, Human Resources (HR), and Communications and Marketing. Organisations keen to address this disparity might benefit from creating training programs that include mentorship initiatives, skill-building workshops, and leadership development opportunities tailored to women in technical fields. This can foster confidence for the employee and their co-worker, help establish relationships for them to draw on in the workplace, and ensure they have the sector-specific knowledge and tools that they need to succeed.\n\n4. Fostering relationships and embedding peer support\n\nFollowing on from the previous point, peer support often plays a pivotal role in fostering an inclusive workplace but this doesn\u2019t mean that disparities may not persist among different groups of people. Working with DSG, I\u2019ve seen factors such as nationality, culture, ethnicity, and location all help or hinder DEI efforts. This is why it is crucial to closely monitor changes in perceptions, especially during challenging industry conditions, to prevent any employee from feeling undervalued or unsupported since this can impact engagement, efficiency and productivity. It\u2019s important that organisations proactively work to recognise and address any issues in morale, which then helps maintain employee wellbeing and ensures a continued level of performance and investment in the organisation\u2019s goals. Regular feedback mechanisms and evolving and updated policies can help support better company culture.\n\n5. The support of leadership in successful DEI practices\n\nData from our members at DSG indicates that simply having knowledge of an organisation's commitment to equality, with good intentions evolving to well-researched and considered action and policy, significantly boosts confidence in fair treatment. This is often irrespective of group affiliations benefiting from such policies \u2014 everyone benefits from the process.\n\nThis confidence in a company\u2019s commitments not only supports recruitment and retention \u2014 as establishing a sense of belonging and fairness often attracts dedicated workers and keeps them \u2014 but often helps elevate the public and private profiles of the organisation and its leaders.\n\nThe future of our workforce is global; to remain competitive within and outside of our industry, embedding fair practices and equality is likely to be a key differentiator for success.\n\n\u00a0","url":"https://www.seatrade-maritime.com/opinions-analysis/5-key-takeaways-dei-maritime"},"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500":{"id":"485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa_207874500","text":"Women in Male Occupations\n8 March\n23: 08 4 March 2022\nFarkhana Safargaleeva immediately after school, together with her friend, decided to enter the crane operator.\nRomance or inner call - what pulled the fragile girl to manage the crane, build houses and make panels, she does not know.\nShe said she liked the job from the start.\nFarkhana Safargaleeva, crane operator of \u201cUnity \u201d LLP:\n\u2014 We graduated from the GPTU, in the direction of us were sent here to the precast.\nShe worked here for 15 years, decree, perestroika, then went to other construction works.\nI already as 5 years returned to this concrete concrete, my heart was sick for my crane, I love, I love this crane very much, I love working on the crane.\nBut, I did not even expect that I was before retirement, I am already 59 years old, I will return here.\nHow many houses were erected in the region with the help of skillful actions and many years of experience of crane operator Farkhana Safargaleeva, it is simply impossible to count.\nSuch qualities as calmness and attentiveness help in the work.\nHer burning eyes are seen not only in the profession, but also at home.\nA husband, a daughter and a small grandson will all gather at the festive table on March 8.\nFarkhana Safargaleyeva \u2019 s relatives support her interest and success.\nAnastasia Kuznetsova, correspondent:\n\u2014 A woman is calm and brisk, vulnerable and warlike, tender and strong.\nModern women break stereotypes, showing the world how they can create and create.\nIn the \u201cmale \u201d professions, among other things.\n\"Unity\" LLP produces reinforced concrete products.\nThe company employs 152 people, including 25 women.\nChief engineer Andrei Nekrasov says that they skillfully show their skills.\nAndrey Nekrasov, Chief Engineer of Unity LLP:\n\u2014 Our company employs a large number of women who are excellent professionals and faithfully perform their work.\nIt passed, one might say, Crimea and Rome here.\nShe is an excellent professional, she transfers her skills to young professionals.\nAnother representative of the fair sex in LLP \"Unity\" - Natalia Danilova.\nShe's a compressor operator.\nWorking in the construction industry is her dream.\nAnd it came true.\nAll my life I have dreamed of working in the construction industry.\n16 she devoted to ensuring the continuous operation of the enterprise.\nNatalia Danilova, operator of the compressor unit of \u201cUnity \u201d LLP:\nI have been working here since 2006 for 16 years.\nI like my job here.\nWe supply cement so that our production does not stand, pour slabs, pour panels.\nThe most important thing is health, so that the world will be around 03.54 and to finish until my retirement \u2013 that \u2019 s my wish.\nOn the eve of the holiday on March 8, according to tradition, all the men of the enterprise will set a table and give gifts to women who give their strength to such a difficult, but so beloved for them work.\nAnastasia Kuznetsova\nRead also\n\"Miss Pampushka 2022\".\nConvicted prisoners beauty contest held at EU institution 164 / 6\nOn the eve of March 8, the Council of Mothers congratulated the deputy akim of the region Gani Nygymetov\nWomen of different professions were congratulated on March 8","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0006.json.gz:172978","uncompressed_offset":207874500,"url":"mtrk.kz/ru/2022/03/04/ZHenshhiny-v-muzhskikh-professiyakh/","warc_date":"2022-03-04T21:28:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:485cdc95-bbf9-4578-9b0d-47d964d3e7aa>","warc_url":"https://mtrk.kz/ru/2022/03/04/ZHenshhiny-v-muzhskikh-professiyakh/"},"created":"2022-03-04T21:39:09.000Z","lang":"eng"},"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418":{"id":"c40b5c1c-6e7a-45f6-a314-adcf276acb8c_663217418","text":"Women severely underrepresented in construction, but that\u2019s changing\n\nWhat you need to know:\n\n  \u2022 In nearly every construction site I encounter, the workforce is overwhelmingly male.\n  \u2022 The term \u2018foreman\u2019 is deeply ingrained in our collective lexicon, while phrases like \u2018forewoman\u2019 or the more inclusive \u2018foreperson\u2019 remain relatively uncommon.\n\nAcross the country, construction sites are a hive of activity, with the government\u2019s ambitious affordable housing project leading the charge. Whenever I pass through these bustling sites, I can\u2019t help but notice the workers clad in overalls, their faces dusted with cement powder as they push wheelbarrows brimming with mortar. Amidst this flurry of activity, one figure stands out \u2013 the foreman, barking instructions and overseeing the skilled artisans, or fundis, as they are commonly known.\n\nInterestingly, in nearly every construction site I encounter, the workforce is overwhelmingly male. Rarely do I spot a woman among the fundis, save for the occasional food vendor. Historically, the construction industry has been a predominantly male bastion, a fact reflected in the terminology we use \u2013 the term \u2018foreman\u2019 is deeply ingrained in our collective lexicon, while phrases like \u2018forewoman\u2019 or the more inclusive \u2018foreperson\u2019 remain relatively uncommon.\n\nWhile the underrepresentation of women in this field is a global issue, the challenges faced by women in this industry are particularly pronounced in Africa. This gender imbalance reflects a deeper, systemic issue within the construction sector. For too long, this industry has been perceived as a \u2018man\u2019s playground\u2019, with women often relegated to peripheral roles or excluded entirely. The reasons for this disparity are multifaceted, ranging from societal norms and gender stereotypes, to a lack of equal opportunities and support systems for women seeking careers in this field.\n\nLimited access to education and training opportunities, particularly in Stem fields, hinders women\u2019s preparedness for technical roles. Furthermore, societal expectations and domestic responsibilities frequently clash with the demanding nature of construction work, making it difficult for women to balance their professional and personal lives. This gender imbalance not only perpetuates inequality but also deprives the industry of the valuable contributions and perspectives that women can bring to the table. However, times are changing, and more women are breaking into the industry, driven by their passion, determination, and desire to contribute to community development. Despite obstacles such as teenage pregnancies, early marriages, and societal pressures, many carved out their place in this male-dominated field.\n\nTheir stories are a testament to the power of perseverance and an unwavering commitment to pursuing their dreams. From the high school dropout who found her calling on a construction site, to the young mother who juggled parenting responsibilities while mastering the art of bricklaying, these women have shattered stereotypes and proved that no challenge is too great when met with an indomitable spirit. Through their journeys, they have not only acquired valuable skills and experience but have also become beacons of inspiration for others.\n\nThis week, we celebrate these trailblazers, exploring their unique paths and the lessons they have learned along the way. Their stories offer a candid glimpse into the challenges and triumphs that have shaped their lives, from navigating male-dominated workplaces to balancing family responsibilities with demanding careers. As we strive to create a more inclusive and equitable society, it is imperative that we challenge the deeply ingrained biases and stereotypes that have traditionally kept women on the sidelines of the construction industry.\n\nThe government can play a pivotal role by implementing initiatives that support and empower women in this field, including investing in educational programmes, vocational training, mentorship opportunities, and inclusive policies that promote gender equality and non-discrimination. This way, we can empower a new generation of women to take their rightful place alongside their male counterparts, ushering in an era of diversity and excellence in this vital sector.\n\nEmpowering women in the construction industry can have far-reaching benefits, contributing to the overall advancement of gender equality and sustainable development in the country.","url":"https://nation.africa/kenya/news/gender/women-severely-underrepresented-in-construction-but-that-s-changing-4641542"},"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178":{"id":"65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161_540514178","text":"ua en ru\n(not) women's professions.\nHow the war has changed the labor market, and Ukrainian women are increasingly mastering \u201cmale \u201d professions\nThe war has replaced the labor market, and Ukrainian women are increasingly mastering \u201cmale \u201d professions (Getty Images)\nAuthor: Spetsproekt\nSince the beginning of the full-scale war in many areas of the Ukrainian labor market there is a shortage of personnel.\nIn particular, there is a shortage of specialists in professions that are usually considered \u201cmale \u201d.\nHowever, employers are ready to attract women to atypical positions, and Ukrainian women more actively respond to such vacancies and undergo retraining.\nMeest, ATB and Ferrexpo tell about the professions in which women replace men during the war - in a special project for RBC-Ukraine.\nMeest Group: whole women \u2019 s teams occupying \u201cmale \u201d positions\nIn the international postal and logistics group of companies Meest, historically, women are an integral part of the team: they work with finance, personnel, marketing, are regional directors and partners.\nAt the same time, due to the specifics of the work - sorting, transportation, logistics - the linear staff of the company, which is two-thirds of the staff, previously consisted mainly of men.\nAfter the start of Russia \u2019 s full-scale invasion of Ukraine, this began to change.\nAccording to the company, since February 2022, part of Meest has joined the Defense Forces: today, the state is protected by more than 130 employees of the company.\nMany were forced to change their place of residence within the country or even go abroad.\n\u201cWe clearly saw a change in trend around the summer of 2022.\nAt that time, we were able to solve the most critical issues with the help of employees, adaptation of operational work, etc.\nAnd they restored the recruitment of people to positions that, for one reason or another, were vacant.\nWe noticed that it is women who respond most actively, including roles that were previously considered purely male, \u201d the company added.\nSince then, companies have begun to attract women, and over the following months this trend has only intensified.\nAs of now, Meest has formed entire women \u2019 s teams, occupying \u201cmale \u201d positions.\nIn total, these are three categories of personnel: employees of warehouses, sorting centers, as well as heads of operational departments.\n\u201cIf earlier our warehouse teams were more than 80% men, now some units are 70% women.\nThe distribution of the staff of warehouse centers has also changed significantly - in some areas it is already 50% to 50%, sometimes even with the advantage of female staff.\nTo do this, the company has changed some operational processes, as well as introduced technology so that women were comfortable working in new conditions, \u201d Meest said.\nAt first, the involvement of women in the composition, logistics were treated with caution: the work is extremely difficult both physically and morally.\nWithin a few months, all doubts were gone.\nWomen \u2019 s teams and women show extremely effective work.\nThe company distinguishes their consistency and structure, as well as elasticity and adaptability.\nIn general, they are always open to new knowledge and opportunities - and they are strongly supported in this.\nThe changes also affected the management of the operating departments \u2013 now the company has many women in these positions, more than in previous years.\nAnd it is important that in many cases, the leaders grow from the inner team.\nFor example, during the war, a woman became the head of a branch in one of the regional centers, who had previously worked as an operator at this location - and now performs her own functions without complaint.\n\u201cOur plans are to attract women to the posts of couriers.\nThis area also has its own challenges, because we deliver packages up to 30 kg inclusive.\nTherefore, here the company needs to adjust to allow women to work with less weight - and work in this direction is already underway, \"the company said.\nIn the near future, Meest is convinced that the most active will be two categories of search engines \u2013 women, as well as veterans and veterans.\nThey need changes in recruiting and operating processes, so the company is actively working on this: they introduce new technologies and procedures for both women and veterans of both sexes, and for the latter they began to attract psychologists for the purpose of moral support.\n\u201cIn the end, we see that our people are ready to work and give results under any circumstances.\nThe main thing is to create comfortable and transparent conditions for them, \u201d the company concluded.\nATB: the company of strong women\nAs of today, more than 56 thousand Ukrainians are employed at ATB enterprises, 67% of which are representatives of the fair sex.\nHistorically, work in grocery retail is considered female, although it requires maximum involvement and dedication.\nAs the experience of the company has shown, for a Ukrainian woman there is no night impossible.\nLeading programmer of the company Kristina Mishchenko at one time made an ascent to the mountain with a height of 6,500 m, set the Ukrainian flag and the ATB flag on the top.\nAs of today, more than 4.5 thousand ATB employees have joined the ranks of the APU, the Defense Ministry and the National Guard.\nIf you count only male staff, then about 30% of men are mobilized.\nIn view of this, women have already adapted, for example, to work as security guards.\nOn average, almost every store in the network has such an employee.\nThe number of women involved in what was previously thought to be purely male positions depends on the circumstances, but in some cases it reaches 50%.\nThe personnel policy of the company is aimed at the development of human resources.\nIf a woman seeks to become a specialist of an extra-class, to take the coveted position, then a priori cannot be any conventions.\nIn particular, we are talking about the so-called division into traditionally \"female\" or \"male\" positions.\nHowever, it is important to understand that not all women can do men \u2019 s work.\nThe complete absence of gender stereotypes in the company proves that more than two thirds of the staff are women.\nAmong colleagues and business partners, ATB is even called a company of strong women.\n\u201cThrough dedicated work, the company has withstood the powerful blow of a full-scale invasion, acquired the title of\u201c network of indestructibility \u201d and became an outpost of food security of the whole country, \u201d the company says.\nIn the ATB, there were many examples of how women work effectively and quickly climb the career ladder in professions that can be considered \u201cmale \u201d, for example, leading key regions, dealing with safety, security, etc.\nAlso, the company is proud of its training centers in Dnipro, Kiev, Lviv and Odessa.\nAnnually more than 4 thousand employees undergo free training and improve their skills there.\nThere are no gender restrictions or stereotypes.\n\u201cWomen and men gain new skills, master the desired professions, become specialists of the highest level and quickly rise to career levels in the team of the leader of domestic retail.\nAs for the \"male\" professions, our women master the specialty of \"loader driver\".\nIt is possible to \u201cwork \u201d such physically difficult activities, but such a replacement will be incredibly valuable and very slow.\nTherefore, the solution of this issue was taken into their hands by our guardians, \u201d the ATB stated.\nFerrexpo: support for women 's leadership and decrees for men\nFerrexpo is one of the trendsetters of large Ukrainian business, demonstrating an integrated approach to issues of inclusiveness and gender equality.\nIn 2022, the company signed the Women \u2019 s Empowerment Principles to promote gender equality.\nTherefore, one of the group's priorities is diversity at the managerial level and the promotion of career opportunities for women.\nSince 2020, Ferrexpo has been implementing a comprehensive DE & I strategy, implementing the principles of inclusiveness and gender equality.\nThanks to her, over the past three years, the number of women in leadership positions in Grade 10 + (management staff) has increased by 60%.\nThe share of women in leadership positions in 2022 was 21%, the goal is to reach the figure of 25% by 2030.\n\u201cThe introduction of ideas of gender equality has increased the stability of staff, readiness for innovation and the ability to respond quickly to the challenges of the time.\nThis decision allowed us to strengthen relations with foreign partners, because they are pleased to cooperate with companies where the same level of trust in managers and managers, \u201d the company said.\nAccording to her, within enterprises, this has allowed to change the views of male skeptics and successfully overcome prejudices against female leaders.\nThe employees of the enterprises felt their value for the production process, which motivated them to further develop their professional qualities.\nElena Nikolaevchuk-Neroda, who has been working as a driver of motor vehicles in her career at Yeristovsky GOK since 2018, dreamed of driving a car since childhood.\nThis dream she was able to realize in Ferrexpo.\nAt one time, Elena was offered a job as a BelAZ driver, and she agreed, although she did not have previous experience driving such a car.\nThe nuances of work during the internship were taught by experienced mentors.\nFor 5 years of work, Elena worked in a career on a car, after obtaining a driving license of category C, she began to drive MAZ and KrAZ dump trucks.\nThen switched to more powerful Bell and Caterpillar with a carrying capacity of 40 and 90 tons, already has a certificate that allows you to control the 220-ton.\nIn the future, Elena plans to master other mining equipment - a bulldozer and an excavator.\nIn addition, the company has a male decree program that allows women to continue their career growth.\nIf in the family of Ferrexpo employees a woman wants to leave maternity leave earlier in order to continue to grow professionally, a man can take care of the child until he reaches the age of three.\nAt the same time, the company takes care that the family income does not become less: if a man has a large salary, but goes on maternity leave and the family because of this decreases the total income, Ferrexpo compensates for this amount.\n\u201cThe hardest thing about the decree is not being able to work, I missed my job very much.\nI am grateful to the man who supported my desire to return to the workplace in a year.\nThis is our second daughter, so I am sure that my husband will cope, and I can safely perform everyday duties, \u201d admits Olga Romantsova, a specialist in the production department of the foundry and mechanical workshop.\nThe practice of \u201cmale \u201d decrees is gaining momentum, because the company understands the importance of development for both men and women.\nIn general, the company will emphasize that the Ferrexpo workforce is a community where everyone has access to equal opportunities - mastering new professions, improving skills, career growth and development of the company, regardless of gender.\nIn addition, the company received the opportunity to replenish the team with professional personnel (both men and women), especially with regard to vacancies that became critical in the conditions of martial law.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0014.json.gz:32735","uncompressed_offset":540514178,"url":"www.rbc.ua/ukr/news/ne-zhinochi-profesiyi-k-viyna-zminila-rinok-1716467637.html","warc_date":"2024-05-27T08:51:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:65fbc85d-e429-4d5a-9efc-ced8faf79161>","warc_url":"https://www.rbc.ua/ukr/news/ne-zhinochi-profesiyi-k-viyna-zminila-rinok-1716467637.html"},"created":"2024-05-27T09:33:58.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1029","request_id":"1029","narrative_id":"1029"},"responses":[{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"Science fiction has undergone significant evolution since its early days, transitioning from the speculative works of pioneers like H.G. Wells to a genre that embraces diverse voices and perspectives."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"In the early 20th century, science fiction was often dominated by male authors and focused on themes of technological advancement and exploration, reflecting societal interests in industrial progress and scientific discovery."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"However, the genre has expanded over time to include narratives that explore social, cultural, and environmental issues, influenced by changing global dynamics and technological developments."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking recent trends in science fiction is the rise of Chinese female writers, who are reshaping the genre with unique perspectives and themes centered on women's experiences."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"Regina Kanyu Wang, a prominent figure in this movement and a two-time Hugo Award nominee, has highlighted the growing presence of women in Chinese science fiction, which was virtually nonexistent before the 1990s."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"This surge in female authorship has led to the publication of four anthologies exclusively featuring works by female and non-binary Chinese authors, marking a significant breakthrough in representation."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"The Internet has played a pivotal role in fostering diverse voices in science fiction, serving as a platform that removes traditional barriers imposed by industry and societal stereotypes."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"As the audience for science fiction has grown more diverse, the genre is no longer perceived as being exclusively 'written and read by boys,' according to leading Chinese science fiction writer Chen Qiufan."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"This evolution reflects a broader shift in science fiction, where contemporary authors from underrepresented demographics, including women and people of color, are making significant contributions to the genre's richness and complexity."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"Science fiction has undergone significant evolution since its early days, transitioning from the speculative works of pioneers like H.G. Wells to a genre that embraces diverse voices and perspectives."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"In the early 20th century, science fiction was often dominated by male authors and focused on themes of technological advancement and exploration, reflecting societal interests in industrial progress and scientific discovery."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"However, the genre has expanded over time to include narratives that explore social, cultural, and environmental issues, influenced by changing global dynamics and technological developments."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking recent trends in science fiction is the rise of Chinese female writers, who are reshaping the genre with unique perspectives and themes centered on women's experiences."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"Regina Kanyu Wang, a prominent figure in this movement and a two-time Hugo Award nominee, has highlighted the growing presence of women in Chinese science fiction, which was virtually nonexistent before the 1990s."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"This surge in female authorship has led to the publication of four anthologies exclusively featuring works by female and non-binary Chinese authors, marking a significant breakthrough in representation."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"The Internet has played a pivotal role in fostering diverse voices in science fiction, serving as a platform that removes traditional barriers imposed by industry and societal stereotypes."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"As the audience for science fiction has grown more diverse, the genre is no longer perceived as being exclusively 'written and read by boys,' according to leading Chinese science fiction writer Chen Qiufan."},{"citations":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":100.0},"text":"This evolution reflects a broader shift in science fiction, where contemporary authors from underrepresented demographics, including women and people of color, are making significant contributions to the genre's richness and complexity."}],"references":["40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979"],"documents":{"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979":{"id":"40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f_387896979","text":"Science Fiction: Chinese Female Writers | Culture | DW | 21.10.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nCultural warp and weft\nScience fiction: the rise of Chinese women writers\nWhile the space for feminist expression in China has shrunk further over the past decade, there \u2019 s good news from this week \u2019 s World Science Fiction Conference in Chengdu: Chinese female writers are thriving in the science fiction world, making them one of the most striking trends in the genre.\nThe rise of Chinese female writers in science fiction has become one of the most striking trends in the genre, according to participants at this week's World Science Fiction Conference in Chengdu.\nThe World Science Fiction Conference, the world \u2019 s oldest and most influential science fiction event, was held in China for the first time this year and attracted a large number of local fans, both male and female.\nChina remains a relatively socially conservative country, and under President Xi Jinping, the space for feminist expression has narrowed further over the past decade.\nBut author and editor Regina Kanyu Wang, who was nominated for two prestigious Hugo Awards at the World Science Fiction Conference this year, said the number of women writers in science fiction has soared in recent years.\nShe said more and more women are now realizing that \"it's not just nerdy, nerdy science-fiction novels like Liu Cixin [author of the three-body series] that can be published, or can be considered science fiction.\" Liu Cixin is great, and we all like him.\nBut there's a lot more to it than Liu Cixin's style. \"\nThe good news, says Wang, is that once women start to become writers, they don \u2019 t feel they \u2019 re being treated unequally.\nThe market and readers need a new perspective, she said.\nThe 81st World Science Fiction Conference will be held in Chengdu from October 18 to 22.\n\"Now, many Chinese female science fiction writers focus on issues that women face that men may not feel,\" Zhou Danxue, a literary scholar at XJCC Liverpool University, told AFP. \"These writers can reflect unique female experiences in their own way.\"\nWang said that in the past two years, four anthologies of Chinese fantasy novels written only by female or non-binary authors have been published, which is a major breakthrough.\nThere wasn \u2019 t even an all-female science fiction writer \u2019 s portfolio before that.\nBefore the 1990s, there were very few female science fiction writers.\nAn article in the collection \"The Way Spring Comes\", which Wang Kanyu participated in compiling, pointed out that the Internet is a training base for women and queer talents.\nAuthor Ni Xueting explained that the widespread use of the Internet \u201cnot only brought a new sense of community to people, but also \u2026 removed many barriers to writing based on industry and social stereotypes, especially for non-male writers. \u201d\nChen Qiufan, one of China \u2019 s leading science fiction writers, told AFP that the genre had traditionally not received special attention and was seen as \u201cwritten and read by boys. \u201d\nHe said there was now a \"wider and more diverse audience\", estimating that his readers were split equally between men and women.\nChinese women writers begin to make their mark in science fiction\nMonet, a 21-year-old woman who visited the science fiction convention on Friday, said she sometimes felt isolated among her own fan base.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s hard to share my interests with people who don \u2019 t understand me.\nThey ask, \"Why does a girl like science fiction?\"\nShe is optimistic about these changes in attitude, pointing out that there are a lot of interested primary and secondary school students at the conference site.\n\u201cI think interest in Chinese science fiction has to be nurtured from an early age, \u201d she says.\u201c We didn \u2019 t have that opportunity when we were young \u2026 I really envy them, to be honest. \u201d\n(AFP)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0030.json.gz:29419","uncompressed_offset":387896979,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E7%A7%91%E5%B9%BB%E5%B0%8F%E8%AF%B4%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%A5%B3%E6%80%A7%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%A3%8E%E7%94%9F%E6%B0%B4%E8%B5%B7/a-67173649","warc_date":"2023-10-21T19:06:29.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:40905120-1cf6-49fc-a73d-e415e5ce057f>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E7%A7%91%E5%B9%BB%E5%B0%8F%E8%AF%B4%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%A5%B3%E6%80%A7%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%A3%8E%E7%94%9F%E6%B0%B4%E8%B5%B7/a-67173649"},"created":"2023-10-21T19:35:37.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
