t in sub-Saharan Africa on the World Bank\u2019s Ease of Doing Business Index."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":100.0},"text":"India has become the fifth-largest investor in Africa, with 18 of its 25 newly established embassies located on the continent, reflecting its growing economic engagement."},{"citations":{"fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696":100.0},"text":"The China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo has facilitated partnerships, with 120 projects worth $10.3 billion signed during its third edition, emphasizing innovation and cooperation."},{"citations":{"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555":100.0},"text":"African businesses in banking and telecoms have demonstrated global competitiveness through technology-led innovation, further enhancing the region's investment appeal."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782":100.0},"text":"Foreign direct investment (FDI) in Africa experienced a decline of 16% in 2020, dropping to $40 billion from $47 billion in 2019, but rebounded to $45 billion in 2022, signaling a recovery to pre-pandemic levels."},{"citations":{"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782":100.0},"text":"Africa's demographic and economic potential is immense, with its population projected to reach 2.53 billion by 2050 and combined consumer and business spending estimated at $16.12 trillion."},{"citations":{"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782":100.0},"text":"The African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA) is creating a single market of 1.3 billion people with a combined GDP of $3.4 trillion, enhancing the region's attractiveness for foreign investors."},{"citations":{"fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696":100.0},"text":"China remains a dominant player in Africa, with trade volume reaching a record $282 billion in 2022 and direct investments exceeding $10 billion over the past two decades."},{"citations":{"678c8e7d-86cc-4e60-89d2-ea52b69bed0e_44218457":100.0},"text":"The UAE has focused on sectors like renewable energy, agriculture, and logistics, aiming to achieve sustainable development in Africa through projects such as green hydrogen and agricultural technology."},{"citations":{"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555":100.0},"text":"Major global companies, including Google, Toyota, and Samsung, have established operations in Africa, with Google committing $1 billion to support digital transformation on the continent."},{"citations":{"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555":100.0},"text":"West Africa, particularly Ghana, is emerging as a tech hub, while Mauritius is recognized for its favorable business environment, ranking highest in sub-Saharan Africa on the World Bank\u2019s Ease of Doing Business Index."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":100.0},"text":"India has become the fifth-largest investor in Africa, with 18 of its 25 newly established embassies located on the continent, reflecting its growing economic engagement."},{"citations":{"fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696":100.0},"text":"The China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo has facilitated partnerships, with 120 projects worth $10.3 billion signed during its third edition, emphasizing innovation and cooperation."},{"citations":{"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555":100.0},"text":"African businesses in banking and telecoms have demonstrated global competitiveness through technology-led innovation, further enhancing the region's investment appeal."}],"references":["100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555","678c8e7d-86cc-4e60-89d2-ea52b69bed0e_44218457","df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696","a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782"],"documents":{"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555":{"id":"100ec187-499c-4e90-9c2e-c8bcbc89b665_79045555","text":"Optimists talk about Africa as the next economic frontier\n\nBy 54m ago\n\nShare this article:\n\nBY DELIA DE VILLIERS\n\nFor years Africa has been shrouded in controversy when it comes to its future potential. The optimists talk about Africa as the next economic frontier, while the sceptics point to a low growth rate, poverty and conflict as key challenges standing in the way of notable development.\n\nYet, the continent has grown its economy by around 5 percent a year over the past decade, is as urbanised as China and has as many cities as Europe with a population of more than one million, according to Future Agenda.\n\nThe World Bank reports that sub-Saharan Africa is \u201chome to more than 1 billion people, half of whom will be under 25 years old by 2050\u201d, suggesting that the workforce of the future is based here. They go on to say that Africa is a \u201cdiverse continent offering human and natural resources that have the potential to yield inclusive growth and eradicate poverty\u201d.\n\nWhile potential is not a measure of performance, what is productive is to consider the motivations of businesses opting either to enter the African market or expand operations on the continent. And that\u2019s notwithstanding the challenges, or as Shaw Mabuto, partner at private equity firm Spear Capital, puts it: \u201cWhile there are undoubtedly risks in Africa, they are well known and understood. Investors can mitigate for them.\u201d\n\nSpear Capital is particularly excited about the opportunities in the ESG (environmental, social, governance) space in Africa. \u201cThere are many businesses that have been able to thrive in spite of the prevailing environment and lack of government support. With the right backing, companies across the continent can grow successfully while at the same time making the world a better place and providing returns to their investors,\u201d Mabuto says.\n\nGoogle\u2019s recent announcement of plans to invest $1 billion (R15.6bn) to support digital transformation in Africa is another very positive indicator of the potential of the continent. The investment, which was announced in October 2021, will be used to enable affordable internet access and building helpful products, for investments in entrepreneurship and technology, as well as to empower businesses as they continue or embark on their digital transformation.\n\nThis positive sentiment about Africa\u2019s potential is echoed by a number of businesses who have chosen to expand their operations on the continent.\n\nPicking your next market is key\n\nWhen SweepSouth decided to scale their business across the African continent in 2020, they chose Kenya as the first territory to launch their on-demand home services model outside of South Africa\u2019s borders. Three months ago they started operations in Nigeria, and plans are now afoot to expand further into Africa.\n\n\u201cThere are so many factors that go into choosing a new market, so we decided to look at countries where people experience the same sort of home-care needs South Africans required when SweepSouth was started,\u201d says Aisha Pandor, SweepSouth chief executive.\n\nKenya and Nigeria were obvious choices, representing big-market regions with a high growth opportunity, ever-increasing internet penetration and digital literacy, and the potential for positive impact on employment, education and economic growth via smart, scalable technology solutions.\n\n\u201cKenya appealed to us because it felt like an in-between in terms of culture, market segment and dynamics, and also smartphone and internet penetration when compared with West Africa. And Nigeria is a really exciting new venture that we hope will serve as a base for further expansion into the West African region,\u201d says Pandor.\n\nWest Africa, too, is increasingly recognised as an area of economic and growth interest for businesses looking to get a foothold on the continent.\n\nIntegrated PR and marketing agency Irvine Partners recently opened an office in Ghana in response to an increasing number of their global clients needing support there. The agency already has wholly owned offices in South Africa, Kenya and Nigeria, and has realised the potential of this West African country.\n\n\u201cMost of our clients\u2019 interest in the region stems from Ghana\u2019s position as a tech hub within sub-Saharan Africa and its growing financial services industry, but we\u2019re also seeing many other industries looking to invest in and expand into the country. Strategically, it makes a lot of sense for us to have a presence in the country and we\u2019re optimistic about its potential,\u201d says managing director Hayley van der Woude.\n\nBeyond the obvious\n\nImportantly, the interest in Africa extends beyond the traditionally popular economic areas such as Lagos, Nairobi and Accra, with Mauritius serving as a prime example of potential beyond the obvious. It is currently the top-ranked economy in sub-Saharan Africa, according to the World Bank\u2019s Ease of Doing Index and is recognised for offering a sound political and economic environment that strongly encourages investment thanks to a sophisticated banking system, a favourable tax regime and low inflation.\n\nThese are among the main reasons.\n\nThe Business Exchange (TBE), a South African-launched serviced office offering, not only expanded operations to Mauritius but also designed an investment opportunity for others with their sectional title shared office investment that offers a safe and affordable way to get into this bustling market.\n\n\u201cMauritius, in our view, is fast becoming one of the hottest investment hubs on the continent. Major international brands, including Samsung, Broll, Expedia and NBA (North America\u2019s National Basketball Association), are based at our serviced office space there, which speaks to the interest in the location and offers an indication of its dynamism as a business destination,\u201d says David Seinker, the founder and chief executive of TBE.\n\nEmbracing innovation\n\nLastly, but certainly very significantly, when it comes to businesses where customer-centricity is key, such as banking and telecoms, African players compete more effectively than their international counterparts, according to a finding in the Boston Consulting Group\u2019s digital maturity index.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s also hardly surprising that these are two sectors where Africa has led the world when it comes to technology-led innovation,\u201d says Ngadi Job Goshi, the general manager at Liferay Africa. \u201cUltimately, while Africa may be less digitally mature than other markets, there can be no doubt that businesses on the continent are unafraid to embrace technology and innovation. And, in the customer-centric ways in which they\u2019ve done so, despite facing adversity and strong headwinds, there are lessons for the rest of the world in the tenacity and ingenuity birthed and nurtured in the African soil.\u201d\n\nDelia de Villiers is the senior account manager, Irvine Partners.\n\nBUSINESS REPORT\n\nShare this article:","url":"https://www.iol.co.za/business-report/economy/optimists-talk-about-africa-as-the-next-economic-frontier-d1a55d86-524b-41b9-979d-a95365955350"},"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":{"id":"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","text":"Japan, Korea and India experience to expand Africa, Taiwan and Africa entrepreneurs association\nThe \u201cTaiwan-Africa Entrepreneurs Association \u201d, commissioned by the International Trade Bureau of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, attracted more than 130 enterprises interested in exploring the African market. The exhibition and consultation desk at the representative office showed that our company's desire to expand the African market is very hot.\nThe theme of the event was \u201cThe Key to Success for Foreign Investors (Japan, Korea and India) in Expanding Africa \u201d. The event was addressed by Wang Ximeng, Secretary General of the Foreign Trade Association, Liu William, Deputy Director of the Bureau of International Trade of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, Msibi, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Swaziland, and Chen Shu-fang, President of the Association of Taiwan Commerce. In addition, Hung Sheng Packaging General Manager Tang Jung-hung, Yi Ho Industrial General Manager Fu Yang-li, and Nam Wei Industrial Strategy Director Yang Wei-han analyze the development opportunities in Africa from their practical experience in the packaging, building materials, and textile industries.\nWang Ximeng, secretary general of the Foreign Trade Association, pointed out that in addition to the competition between Europe, America and China over the layout of the African continent, Japan, South Korea, India and other countries in Asia are committed to increasing investment and economic cooperation in Africa.\nThere are more than 1.3 million people of Indian descent in Africa, such as in East Africa, where more than 60% of the economic lifeline is controlled by Indians.\nIn addition, 18 of India's 25 newly established embassies and consulates are located in Africa, and India has become the fifth largest investor in Africa, while Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba have already planted flags in Africa; South Korea's Hyundai, Samsung, LG and other large enterprises have also been stationed in Africa.\nThrough this event, we hope to help our business people to learn from foreign companies such as Japan, Korea and India, as well as African market leaders, and shorten the path to enter the African market.\nLiu, deputy director of the International Trade Bureau, said that in recent years, the global economy has continued to be volatile due to changes in the international situation such as Sino-US trade frictions, global inflation, and the Russian-Ukrainian war, but Africa has shown great resilience during this period.\nIn addition, foreign direct investment in Africa reached US $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered. In 2022, the total import and export value of Africa reached a new high in recent years, with imports reaching US $694.5 billion, up 14%, and exports reaching US $661.4 billion, up 19%. It is hoped that through the activities of the association, upstream and downstream companies in various industries can learn from each other and share their experiences, and work together to promote Taiwan-Africa economic and trade relations.\nThe event will be held in conjunction with AGOA, a major textile manufacturer in South China, and the representative offices of African embassies in Taiwan, Africa-related associations, and import and export banks providing trade and financial services. For more information, please visit africa.taiwantrade.com for more information.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0024.json.gz:5975","uncompressed_offset":494470718,"url":"ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html","warc_date":"2023-08-17T03:05:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e>","warc_url":"https://ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html"},"created":"2023-08-17T03:43:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"678c8e7d-86cc-4e60-89d2-ea52b69bed0e_44218457":{"id":"678c8e7d-86cc-4e60-89d2-ea52b69bed0e_44218457","text":"00: 00\nExpo 2020 Dubai Today\nUAE seeks to boost investment flow with African countries at Expo 2020\nHis Excellency Dr. Thani bin Ahmed Al Zeyoudi, Minister of State for Foreign Trade, held a series of meetings with ministers, officials and businessmen from African countries to discuss ways to stimulate trade and investment flows between the UAE and the continent.\nDuring the meetings, Dr. Al Zeyoudi reviewed the economic opportunities and potential of the UAE-Africa partnership in sectors such as renewable energy, agriculture, minerals and logistics.\nDuring the meetings, Dr. Al Zeyoudi briefed the ministers on the developments in the UAE \u2019 s economic environment during the past phase, including the 50 projects, new economic legislations and qualitative initiatives launched by the UAE to shift to a new economic model based on knowledge and characterized by flexibility, competitiveness and sustainability.\nIn his meeting with Dr. Chilichi Kabuibwe, Secretary General of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), Al-Zeyoudi pointed to opportunities to increase the current volume of trade exchange between the UAE and the 21 African member countries of COMESA through greater cooperation in areas such as logistics and advanced technology.\nIn his meeting with H.E. Ntabazi Harriet, Minister of State for Trade of the Republic of Uganda, Thani Al Zeyoudi focused on investment opportunities in agriculture, minerals and retail sectors, and discussed the possibility of investing in irrigation systems and agricultural technology that can enhance the production of key crops such as coffee, cocoa, tea, cotton and flowers.\nIn a related context, the renewable energy sector, specifically green hydrogen, was the main focus of the discussions that took place during her meeting with Her Excellency Naha Bint Hamdi Ould Meknes, Minister of Trade, Industry, Handicrafts and Tourism of Mauritania, and Her Excellency Lucia Ibombo, Minister of Manufacturing and Trade of Namibia. for production.\nH.E. Al Zeyoudi also held constructive talks with H.E. Sikai Nzinza, Minister of Industry and Trade of Zimbabwe; H.E. Carlos Alberto Fortis Mesquita, Minister of Industry and Trade of Mozambique; H.E. Maween Diggs, Minister of Trade and Industry of Liberia; H.E. Thabiso Paul, Minister of Trade and Industry of Lesotho; H.E. Edward Henga Sande, Minister of Trade and Industry of Sierra Leone; H.E. Ndir Nigel Hahel Mead Hassan, Minister of Finance, Economic Planning and Trade of Seychelles, David Osiani, Secretary General of the Ministry of Industrialization, Trade and Enterprise Development of Kenya, and Admaso Tadesse, President of the Trade and Development Bank of Kenya.\nH.E. Dr. Thani Al Zeyoudi stressed that Africa is one of the most attractive markets in the world for foreign direct investment, as it enjoys huge investment opportunities in vital and strategic sectors for the UAE such as renewable energy, agriculture and logistics.\nHe added: \u201cThe UAE seeks to strengthen economic, trade and investment cooperation with the African continent, especially as there are common visions between the two sides to achieve sustainable development through future-oriented projects such as green hydrogen, renewable energy and the deployment of agricultural technology solutions, which was highlighted during joint meetings with ministers and senior officials. \u201d\nAl Zeyoudi said: \u201cThe UAE continues to implement its ambitious plans to establish itself as a key global gateway for regional and global trade and investment flows. The UAE also provides opportunities for African exporters to access new markets, thanks to its advanced infrastructure linking the country through ports and airports to more than 400 cities around the world, as well as the legislative and regulatory environment that stimulates business and investments. \u201d\nAl-Zeyoudi expressed his aspiration to continue meetings and discussions with ministers and senior officials from African countries to bring trade and investment relations between the UAE and African countries to new heights of growth and prosperity.\nHis Excellency Thani Al Zeyoudi \u2019 s series of meetings with ministers and senior officials from Africa are part of the UAE \u2019 s efforts to expand trade relations with the world, as part of the UAE \u2019 s ambitious strategy for the next 50 years to build a more dynamic and competitive knowledge-based economy.\nTalks have been announced in recent weeks to reach a comprehensive economic partnership agreement between the UAE and Indonesia and India, and a joint statement of intent between the UAE and South Korea on a comprehensive economic partnership agreement between the two countries was announced on Sunday.\nPrint Email","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:23530","uncompressed_offset":44218457,"url":"www.albayan.ae/expo/news/2021-10-19-1.4275391","warc_date":"2021-10-19T11:51:14.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:678c8e7d-86cc-4e60-89d2-ea52b69bed0e>","warc_url":"https://www.albayan.ae/expo/news/2021-10-19-1.4275391"},"created":"2021-10-19T11:53:43.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782":{"id":"a948934f-cc3e-4b6b-ba17-7748e34ef2c6_397268782","text":"Global investors waiting to pour in money in Africa to firewall China\n\nBy IANS | Published: August 2, 2021 02:09 PM2021-08-02T14:09:05+5:302021-08-02T14:25:34+5:30\n\nNew Delhi, Aug 2: After a tepid inflow of foreign direct investments (FDI) into Africa in 2020 amid the ...\n\nNext\n\nNew Delhi, Aug 2: After a tepid inflow of foreign direct investments (FDI) into Africa in 2020 amid the Covid-19, investors are once again warming up to the continent. According to the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), FDI flows into Africa declined by 16 per cent in 2020 to $40 billion, from $47 billion in 2019.\n\nChina, the primary investor in the continent, has also slowed down its investments into the continent leaving an opportunity for other investors.\n\nWhile the UNCTAD projected FDI inflow into Africa to grow this year, it said that the slow vaccine roll-out programme is a cause for concern. According to UNCTAD, FDI to the continent is projected to grow by only 5 per cent in 2021. But analysts said Africa as an investment destination has led to \"an unprecedented curiosity\" among other countries, which are now aggressively looking to mute China's dominance in the continent.\n\n\"Africa is critical in the new geopolitical and geo-economic contours. The continent, with its vast natural resources, offers a ready growth platform,\" an analyst told India Narrative.\n\nAccording to a study published by Brookings Institution last week, Africa is home to 17 per cent of the world population. However, by 2050, it will have 26 per cent of the global population 2.53 billion people. \"If Africa is not successfully integrated into the global economy, there could be a major threat to global prosperity and stability,\" the study said, adding that by 2050, the continent will be home to an estimated $16.12 trillion of combined consumer and business spending.\n\nThe African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA) \u2013 the mega trade could give a push to intra-continental investment.\n\nTouted as one of the biggest trade deals in the world, the AfCTA aims to create a single market comprising 1.3 billion people with a combined GDP of about $3.4 trillion.\n\nMeanwhile, the US may have woken up late in recognising the potential of Africa but is making all attempts to make up for the lost time.\n\nThe Group of Seven or G7 has already decided to support US President Joe Biden's proposal of carving out a mega infrastructure plan under the \"Build Back Better World\" (B3W) initiative, expected to bring in transparency and sustainability. Besides, the initiative will be carried out only in consultation with local communities.\n\nThe G7 in its meeting in June also announced that it will increase its support to the Indo Pacific and Africa. \"We resolve to collaborate with partners around the world, including in the Indo-Pacific and Africa, to actively promote these shared values for the good of all,\" said the statement.\n\nIndia too has pressed the pedal on investments in the region. Sources said that the still-born Asia Africa Growth Corridor\u2014the mega infrastructure project that was launched in 2017 to connect Asia and Africa must be revived.\n\nCarnegie Endowment for International Peace noted that Chinese financiers committed $153 billion to African public sector borrowers between 2000 and 2019. \"After rapid growth in the 2000s, annual lending commitments to Africa peaked in 2013, the year the BRI was launched. By 2019, though, new Chinese loan commitments amounted to only $7 billion to the continent, down 30 percent from $9.9 billion in 2018,\" it said.\n\nDisclaimer: This post has been auto-published from an agency feed without any modifications to the text and has not been reviewed by an editor\n\nOpen in app","url":"https://english.lokmat.com/international/global-investors-waiting-to-pour-in-money-in-africa-to-firewall-china/"},"fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696":{"id":"fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a_813234696","text":"People 's Daily Online > > Economy and Technology\nChina-Africa economic and trade cooperation giant ship set sail again\nOur reporter Zhao Jiawei, our correspondent Jia Ke\nJuly 3, 2023 08: 57 | Source: Guangming Daily\nSmall number\nOriginal title: Promoting China-Africa economic and trade cooperation giant ship set sail again\nOn July 2, the third China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo (hereinafter referred to as the \"China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo\") officially came to an end. Over the past four days, 53 African countries, 12 international organizations, 30 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities, more than 1,700 enterprises, business associations and financial institutions from China and Africa have participated in the exhibition.\nA total of 120 projects have been signed by the parties, with a total value of 10.3 billion US dollars, demonstrating the strong vitality and resilience of China-Africa economic and trade cooperation.\nConvergence of development efforts\nOn June 30, at the high-end seminar on China-Africa economic and trade cooperation, the Institute of International Trade and Economic Cooperation of the Ministry of Commerce released the \"Report on China-Africa Economic and Trade Relations 2023\".\nAccording to the report, China has maintained its position as Africa's largest trading partner for 14 consecutive years. In 2022, China-Africa trade volume further increased to 282 billion US dollars, a record high.\nChina's direct investment in Africa has exceeded 10 billion US dollars in the past 20 years.\nIn particular, infrastructure cooperation between China and Africa has greatly promoted poverty reduction in our country, \"said Dr. Alkabe Okabe, a former special adviser to the Ethiopian prime minister.\n\u201cChinese investors have a lot of courage and perseverance.\nWe have a very difficult project conditions, foreign enterprises can not avoid, but Chinese enterprises are willing to come to invest and develop, and successfully completed the project. \u201d Niger Minister of Commerce Ahada Akachi shared the story of Chinese investment in the local area in the keynote speech.\nIn order to expand the breadth and depth of China-Africa cooperation, the Changsha initiative of \"innovation and exploration of in-depth cooperation\" in China-Africa economic and trade was also released during the expo, which advocated building consensus on development, strengthening pragmatic economic and trade cooperation, and sharing friendly partnership.\nChina in the Non-Corporate Social Responsibility Alliance issued the \"China in Non-Corporate Social Responsibility Joint Action Initiative\", calling on China to actively carry out its mission and responsibilities in non-enterprises, strive to integrate into African development, and draw a blueprint for sustainable development of Africa with the African people and the international parties.\n\"What China has done is not to teach people to fish, but to teach people to fish.\" Malawi is one of the guest countries of this exposition. Malawi President Chakvila said that the China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo, as an important platform for in-depth cooperation between China and Africa, will deepen the links between people, industry and industry, and between countries.\nExpanding the circle of young friends in Central Africa\n\u201cIs it possible to build a platform to bring together the Chinese people in Africa? \u201d\nWith such an idea, we established a foreign home platform and opened the road of entrepreneurship. \"On June 30, at the China-Africa Youth Innovation and Entrepreneurship Forum, Lei Ting, founder of Hunan Foreign Home Information Technology Co., Ltd., described his entrepreneurial feelings.\nAt the forum, young people from China and Africa gathered to tell entrepreneurial stories and share innovative experiences.\nAfter countless thoughts, Wang Shuangyin, a Chinese boy, created the drama \u201cHujiambo, Africa \u201d to show the support of the Chinese people in life, and won the most characteristic award of the\u201c Belt and Road \u201d literary and creative competition. In order to solve the transportation problem of medical supplies in sub-Saharan Africa, Zambian youth Krivet Meba created a digital platform to send basic medical supplies \u2026\nThere are many stories of China-Africa youth entrepreneurship like this, and the \u201cChina-Africa Youth Innovation and Entrepreneurship Story Collection \u201d released at the forum will record their stories into a book and compose a chapter, so that the story of China-Africa youth moving forward side by side and innovation and entrepreneurship will be known by more people.\n\u201cThe China-Africa Economic and Trade Expo is a good platform for exchanges, and the Youth Innovation and Entrepreneurship Forum is a bridge for exchanges between China-Africa youth. \u201d Mendu, founder of the China-Africa Youth Federation, said that in the future, the youth federation will play its advantages to promote more exchanges between China-Africa youth and let more African youth leaders know about China.\nAchieving development outcomes for all\nOn June 29, the China-Africa Economic and Trade Fair held the first China-Africa Women's Forum, attended by more than 80 foreign guests from 23 African countries.\nThe forum adopted the \"China-Africa Women's Forum Joint Initiative\" on the spot, calling for closer cooperation along the fundamental direction of building a community with a shared future for China and Africa.\n\u201cEmpowered by mycelium technology, women become an important part of productivity.\nThe progress of each rural woman will lead to the improvement and progress of the family and ultimately promote the progress of the rural areas, \"said Lin Dongmei, deputy director of the National Fungus Engineering Technology Research Center, who is a participant and witness of friendly exchanges and mutually beneficial cooperation between China and Africa.\nThrough the implementation of the Chinese government's foreign aid project and the China-United Nations Peace and Development Fund fungus project, the National Fungus Center has pioneered the model of \"10 square meters mushroom farm\" in South Africa, where all women can participate and benefit.\n\"After they earn money from studying mushrooms, they can send their children to school, open a grocery store in the village, and buy a car to hire people to transport them, changing the fate of themselves and their families.\"\n\u201cToday \u2019 s forum is a rare opportunity for us to exchange experiences and bring new hope to the poverty reduction plans of thousands of African people living in misery, \u201d said Joana Thomas, general secretary of the Women \u2019 s Liberation Movement of Angola (MPLA).\n(Edited by: Yang Xi, Lu Qian)\nPublic Number \uff1a People 's Network Finance\nShare it so more people can see it.\nBack to top","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0019.json.gz:25523","uncompressed_offset":813234696,"url":"finance.people.com.cn/n1/2023/0703/c1004-40026386.html","warc_date":"2023-07-04T06:46:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fe0a09f8-0d9d-405b-a939-27fdd4642f3a>","warc_url":"http://finance.people.com.cn/n1/2023/0703/c1004-40026386.html"},"created":"2023-07-04T07:36:47.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
