100.0},"text":"Morocco has become a global leader in solar energy, with renewable sources contributing nearly two-fifths of the country's electricity."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Benban Solar Park in Aswan, Egypt, is one of the largest solar photovoltaic parks in the world, with a capacity of 1,800 megawatts and a valuation of $4 billion."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"Spanning 37 square kilometers, the Benban Solar Park includes 41 solar power plants and over 7 million photovoltaic panels."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park in the UAE is set to become the largest solar park globally, with a planned capacity of 5,000 megawatts."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"The Al Dhafra Solar PV Plant in Abu Dhabi, UAE, is being developed as the world\u2019s largest solar power plant, with a capacity of 2 gigawatts."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"Oman\u2019s Renewable Energy Plan, part of its Vision 2040, aims to secure 16% of electricity from renewables by 2025 and 30% by 2030."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The UAE has launched the 'Net Zero by 2050 Initiative,' with an investment of $163 billion to ensure that 50% of its electricity comes from renewable and nuclear sources by 2050."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"Saudi Arabia aims to increase the share of renewable energy in its energy mix from 0.3% to 50% by 2030 as part of its energy transition strategy."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"Bahrain has committed to achieving net zero carbon emissions by 2050, while Kuwait has announced plans to reduce its carbon footprint."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The UAE was the first Gulf country to adopt a net zero domestic consumption policy and ratify the Paris Agreement."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"Green hydrogen is emerging as a key focus in the Middle East, with Gulf countries targeting export revenues of $200 billion by 2050."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"Oman is positioning itself as a leading exporter of renewable hydrogen, aiming to ship to demand centers in Europe and Asia."},{"citations":{"7ec19ba5-524f-4f3d-b2cf-df9cea4378e7_857676748":100.0},"text":"The UAE has announced an investment of AED 200 billion ($54.5 billion) in renewable energy as part of its National Hydrogen Strategy."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Gulf of Suez Wind Power Project in Egypt is expected to power over one million households and reduce annual CO2 emissions by 2.4 million tons."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"Saudi Arabia's Neom project includes The Line, a car-free, carbon-free city powered entirely by renewable energy."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The GCC countries are leveraging their capital, abundant sunlight, and vast empty spaces to diversify energy sources and promote a low-carbon economic future."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Benban Solar Park in Egypt was developed under the Renewable Energy Feed-in Tariff (FiT) program, introduced in 2014 to encourage private investment in renewable energy."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"Jordan has implemented policies since 2012 to promote solar energy, including financial incentives for investors and reduced electricity bills for consumers."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"The UAE's Green Economy Initiative and Saudi Arabia's Green Initiative are key policies aimed at building diversified, sustainable economies."},{"citations":{"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117":100.0},"text":"The MENA Solar Conference 2023, held in Dubai, focused on advancing solar energy technologies, including photovoltaics and hybrid tandem solar cells."},{"citations":{"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117":100.0},"text":"The Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park was showcased at the WETEX and Dubai Solar Show 2023 as a flagship renewable energy project."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"The Middle East, traditionally known for its oil wealth, is undergoing a significant energy transition, with several countries investing heavily in renewable energy to align with global environmental goals."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"The Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) projects that five countries\u2014Egypt, Morocco, Oman, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE\u2014will contribute 72% of the region's renewable energy growth by 2027."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"In 2022, the Middle East added 3.2 gigawatts of renewable energy capacity, marking a 12.8% increase compared to the previous year, according to the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA)."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"Arab countries are expected to invest $1 trillion in renewable energy projects by 2040, as estimated by the Arab Renewable Energy Authority (AREA)."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"Electricity generated from renewable sources in the Middle East is projected to increase six-fold over the next decade, with solar photovoltaic energy playing a central role."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"Oman is emerging as a leader in renewable energy expansion, with its capacity projected to grow three-fold over the next five years."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"The region is expected to see a 62-gigawatt increase in renewable energy capacity by 2028, with solar photovoltaic systems accounting for over 85% of this growth."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"Morocco has become a global leader in solar energy, with renewable sources contributing nearly two-fifths of the country's electricity."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Benban Solar Park in Aswan, Egypt, is one of the largest solar photovoltaic parks in the world, with a capacity of 1,800 megawatts and a valuation of $4 billion."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"Spanning 37 square kilometers, the Benban Solar Park includes 41 solar power plants and over 7 million photovoltaic panels."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park in the UAE is set to become the largest solar park globally, with a planned capacity of 5,000 megawatts."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"The Al Dhafra Solar PV Plant in Abu Dhabi, UAE, is being developed as the world\u2019s largest solar power plant, with a capacity of 2 gigawatts."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"Oman\u2019s Renewable Energy Plan, part of its Vision 2040, aims to secure 16% of electricity from renewables by 2025 and 30% by 2030."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The UAE has launched the 'Net Zero by 2050 Initiative,' with an investment of $163 billion to ensure that 50% of its electricity comes from renewable and nuclear sources by 2050."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"Saudi Arabia aims to increase the share of renewable energy in its energy mix from 0.3% to 50% by 2030 as part of its energy transition strategy."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"Bahrain has committed to achieving net zero carbon emissions by 2050, while Kuwait has announced plans to reduce its carbon footprint."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The UAE was the first Gulf country to adopt a net zero domestic consumption policy and ratify the Paris Agreement."},{"citations":{"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":100.0},"text":"Green hydrogen is emerging as a key focus in the Middle East, with Gulf countries targeting export revenues of $200 billion by 2050."},{"citations":{"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":100.0},"text":"Oman is positioning itself as a leading exporter of renewable hydrogen, aiming to ship to demand centers in Europe and Asia."},{"citations":{"7ec19ba5-524f-4f3d-b2cf-df9cea4378e7_857676748":100.0},"text":"The UAE has announced an investment of AED 200 billion ($54.5 billion) in renewable energy as part of its National Hydrogen Strategy."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Gulf of Suez Wind Power Project in Egypt is expected to power over one million households and reduce annual CO2 emissions by 2.4 million tons."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"Saudi Arabia's Neom project includes The Line, a car-free, carbon-free city powered entirely by renewable energy."},{"citations":{"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":100.0},"text":"The GCC countries are leveraging their capital, abundant sunlight, and vast empty spaces to diversify energy sources and promote a low-carbon economic future."},{"citations":{"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":100.0},"text":"The Benban Solar Park in Egypt was developed under the Renewable Energy Feed-in Tariff (FiT) program, introduced in 2014 to encourage private investment in renewable energy."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"Jordan has implemented policies since 2012 to promote solar energy, including financial incentives for investors and reduced electricity bills for consumers."},{"citations":{"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":100.0},"text":"The UAE's Green Economy Initiative and Saudi Arabia's Green Initiative are key policies aimed at building diversified, sustainable economies."},{"citations":{"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117":100.0},"text":"The MENA Solar Conference 2023, held in Dubai, focused on advancing solar energy technologies, including photovoltaics and hybrid tandem solar cells."},{"citations":{"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117":100.0},"text":"The Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park was showcased at the WETEX and Dubai Solar Show 2023 as a flagship renewable energy project."}],"references":["7ec19ba5-524f-4f3d-b2cf-df9cea4378e7_857676748","b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086","a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704","7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014","af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117","06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952","292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900"],"documents":{"7ec19ba5-524f-4f3d-b2cf-df9cea4378e7_857676748":{"id":"7ec19ba5-524f-4f3d-b2cf-df9cea4378e7_857676748","text":"Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) issues have become increasingly prominent on the global stage as organisations recognise the need to integrate sustainability into their operations.\n\nAs the Middle East moves towards a low carbon future, sustainability has become a top priority for organisations and governments across the region.\n\nSheikh Mohammad bin Rashid, Prime Minister and Ruler of Dubai announced while launching the National Hydrogen Strategy that the UAE is to invest up to AED 200 billion ($54.5 billion) in renewable energy.\n\nThe launch of a AED 4 billion renewable energy plant in Dubai,\u00a0 and the world\u2019s largest waste-to-energy plant are proof of sustainability climbing the agenda.\n\nWith COP 28 being held in the UAE this year, there is a renewed sense of urgency on climate change action, and the net-zero carbon target is being prioritised through policies and actions.\n\nAfter all, sustainability will boost the UAE\u2019s economic competitiveness, drive innovative policy and improve investment opportunities.\n\nThe region has seen notable sustainability innovations, including Saudi Arabia\u2019s rapid transition to a circular carbon economy, Bahrain\u2019s state oil company refinancing a $2.2 billion sustainability-linked corporate finance facility, and Oman\u2019s exploration of green hydrogen as a clean energy source.\n\nHowever, the Middle East faces its own unique challenges in implementing ESG practices, especially around accurate sustainability reporting and implementing early regulations to fill in previous gaps.\n\nOther challenges that hinder the progress of the region\u2019s ESG agenda include the talent gap, how corporates in the region address the need to implement ESG practices, as well as data availability.\n\nRegulatory frameworks\n\nWhile standardised frameworks and reporting guidelines begin to form, the lack of clear regulations can hinder consistent measurement and disclosure of ESG performance.\n\nGlobal frameworks have now become more widely adopted in the region such as the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI), the Sustainability Accounting Standards Board (SASB), and the newly published International Sustainability Standards Board (ISSB).\n\nThe gap in standardisation previously posed challenges for investors and stakeholders who relied on transparent and comparable ESG data for decision-making, however, we are starting to see drastic changes in this area.\u00a0\n\nData availability\n\nMany companies in the Middle East still face challenges in collecting, managing, and reporting ESG data, which can hinder their ability to effectively assess and manage their sustainability performance.\n\nData is the first step to measure any status, but also measure progress. Improving data collection mechanisms and investing in robust reporting systems will be instrumental in addressing this challenge.\n\nESG talent gap\n\nOrganisations need individuals with specialised knowledge and expertise in ESG practices to drive sustainable strategies effectively. Alongside this specialised knowledge, the industry also needs innovators, risk takers, agitators for change, mentors, and communicators in the field. There is however, a shortage of skilled professionals in the region with a deep understanding of ESG principles to drive innovative solutions.\n\nBridging this gap requires investment in education and training programmes to build a skilled workforce capable of integrating ESG considerations into business practices. Universities and training institutions are therefore increasingly offering courses and programmes on sustainability and ESG and businesses are partnering with academic institutions to develop tailored training initiatives and internships, nurturing a pipeline of talent equipped with the required knowledge and skills.\n\nThese efforts will cultivate a sustainable workforce capable of implementing and driving ESG practices in the Middle East.\n\nImplementation by region\u2019s corporates\n\nDespite the challenges, corporations in the Middle East are embracing ESG practices, recognising the importance of sustainability and responsible business conduct. We see this through accelerated electrification and the increase of decarbonizing energy supply.\n\nThe GCC\u2019s oil-producing nations have made efforts to diversify energy sources, transitioning towards net-zero carbon fuels for transportation. Investments in renewable energy, such as solar and wind, aim to mitigate environmental impacts and promote a low-carbon economic future transforming the economic system and supply chain.\u00a0\n\nAdditionally, social considerations are gaining prominence. Companies are addressing social issues through initiatives that promote diversity, inclusion, and employee welfare.\n\nGovernance practices are also being strengthened to ensure transparency, accountability, regulatory reforms and ethical conduct.\n\nWhile obstacles in integrating ESG practices persist in the Middle East, corporates in the region are proactively embracing sustainability and responsible business practices.\n\nThat the Middle East is emerging as a leader in ESG adoption is apparent through their fullfillment of the UN SDG goals which has driven positive environmental, social, and governance outcomes for businesses and society as a whole.","url":"https://www.zawya.com/en/opinion/business-insights/the-middle-east-is-prioritising-esg-at-the-forefront-but-what-are-the-challenges-y80wo2x2"},"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117":{"id":"af849aa9-6941-470d-adfa-3ade81c5f04d_893378117","text":"Dubai: A first-of-its-kind conference in the region taking place in Dubai is exploring the benefits of perovskite solar cells to to enhance photovoltaic systems in the MENA region\u2019s climate conditions.\n\nA line-up of international researchers, scientists and specialists at the first Middle East and North Africa Solar Conference (MENA-SC) 2023, are presenting the latest scientific and technical progress of organic and organic-inorganic hybrid perovskite cells.\n\nThey are also discussing methods of testing photovoltaic solar panels to ensure their reliability and suitability for the climate and atmosphere of the MENA region, for optimal performance in different climate conditions.\n\nDubai Electricity and Water Authority (DEWA) is organising MENA-SC from November 15 to 18 at the Dubai World Trade Centre. The conference is the first scientific and technical conference of its kind in the region, specialising in solar energy systems.\n\nIt focuses on all areas of photovoltaics with a rich programme on PV materials and devices, future technologies, PV reliability and forecasting for performance assessment. Areas extend to system operation, concentrated solar power and grid integration, all of which are key in accelerating the green energy transformation.\n\nClean energy\n\nSaeed Mohammed Al Tayer\n\n\u201cWe strive to achieve the wise directives of His Highness Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Vice President and Prime Minister of the UAE and Ruler of Dubai, to consolidate Dubai\u2019s global position in renewable and clean energy, and sustainability,\u201d said Saeed Mohammed Al Tayer, MD and CEO of DEWA.\n\n\u201cThe conference creates additional momentum for the renewable and clean energy sector in the MENA region.\u201d\n\nAl Tayer said this is through encouraging innovation, research, and development and by showcasing the latest innovations, research papers, and scientific discoveries in solar energy.\n\nThe conference is also attracting scientists, researchers, investors, and international keynote speakers to exchange knowledge, and insights, and discuss breakthrough ideas and the latest innovative technologies and solutions to accelerate the development of the solar photovoltaic systems industry, and deliver the expected Return on Investment for all stakeholders along the value chain, Al Tayer pointed out.\n\nRead More\n\nPerovskite and organic materials\n\nThe research papers at MENA SC focus on the most prominent scientific and technical progress of perovskite, organic, and hybrid solar cells, which are rising stars for solar cell and optoelectronic applications for their outstanding features.\n\nThe conference explores the horizons of these emerging PV technologies, which are low-cost, lightweight, flexible, and eco-friendly. They also combine efficiency and stability.\n\nThe conference is also holding discussions on organic and dye-sensitised solar cells, high-performance hybrid tandem or multijunction solar cells, PV module and system reliability in the MENA region, effects and mitigation of soiling on PV Systems and module and system reliability in the circular economy. The MENA-SC 2023 conference is held in conjunction with the 25th Water, Energy, Technology, and Environment Exhibition (WETEX) and Dubai Solar Show 2023.\n\nDEWA at WETEX and DSS\n\nMeanwhile, DEWA is showcasing its key projects, initiatives, and digital services at its stands at WETEX and DSS 2023.\n\nSome of the most prominent projects being featured by DEWA include the following: The Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park, Green Hydrogen Project, Hassyan SWRO IWP Project, DEWA\u2019s Space-D programme, Pumped-storage hydroelectric power plant in Hatta, Dubai Mountain Peak, Aquifer Storage and Recovery (ASR) project, the Green Charger initiative, Smart Grid, Rammas (DEWA\u2019s virtual employee supported by ChatGPT) and the Duroob smart app.\n\nOrganised by DEWA under the directives of His Highness Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Vice President and Prime Minister of the UAE and Ruler of Dubai, the events are held under the theme \u2018At the Forefront of Sustainability.\u2019\n\nThe current edition of WETEX & DSS has attracted around 2,600 companies from 62 countries. The exhibition is spread over 78,000 square metres and includes 24 international pavilions.","url":"https://gulfnews.com/uae/environment/dubai-conference-at-wetex-explores-benefits-of-perovskite-solar-cells-1.99433458"},"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900":{"id":"292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb_265707900","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEconomy: Benban and the Gulf of Suez are among the largest renewable energy projects\nEconomic Middle East magazine, which specializes in economics and energy, said that the Benban solar park and the Gulf of Suez wind project in Egypt are considered among the largest renewable energy projects in the Middle East.\nRenewable Energy Projects in the Middle East\nThe Middle East has long relied on oil and gas, not only for revenue but also for power generation, but in the past years, the region has positioned itself as a leader in the renewable energy sector, boasting numerous renewable energy projects.\nFrom 2023 to 2028, Mordor Intelligence expects the renewable energy market in the Middle East to grow by 13.43% annually.\nThe Arab Clean Energy Initiative was launched by the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), and during the Arab Economic and Social Development Summit of 2013, the League of Arab States adopted the initiative, with leaders pledging to increase renewable energy generation capacity in the region from 12 GW in 2013 to 80 GW by 2030.\nBenban Solar Park\nLocated in Aswan, Egypt with a capacity of 1,800 megawatts, Benban Solar Park is valued at $4 billion and includes 41 solar power plants, one of the largest solar PV parks in the world, spanning 37 square kilometers and containing 7 million photovoltaic panels, this initiative is a component of Egypt \u2019 s Renewable Energy Feed Tariff (FiT) program, which was unveiled in September 2014.\nGulf of Suez Wind Power Project\nIn November last year, ACWA Power and the Sovereign Fund of Egypt (TSFE) signed a memorandum of understanding, and together they will invest in a 1100 MW wind power project in Jebel Zeit and the Gulf of Suez. The project is one of the largest onshore wind farms in the world, and aims to provide power to more than one million households and reduce annual CO2 emissions by 2.4 million tons.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0035.json.gz:73254","uncompressed_offset":265707900,"url":"www.dostor.org/4582287","warc_date":"2023-12-16T09:25:55.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:292e2ff7-2382-4c0b-90aa-eb33e197caeb>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4582287"},"created":"2023-12-16T09:46:14.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704":{"id":"a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17_688584704","text":"The Guardian: The Middle East is facing a \u2018 resurrection \u2019\nAnd Mecca may not be livable by the end of the century.\nFriday 29 October 2021 05: 27 pm / Jerusalem time + 2GMT\nLondon / Sama /\nTitled \u201cResurrection Soon: A Reluctant Middle East Forced to Awareness of the Climate Crisis, \u201d The Guardian \u2019 s diplomatic editor Patrick Wintour said that Hurricane Shaheen hit Oman some time ago, the first tropical cyclone to reach this point west into the Gulf.\nIn Basra, southern Iraq, power has been cut off frequently as a result of this summer \u2019 s temperature of 50 degrees Celsius, forcing residents to move in their cars to get cold.\nKuwait broke the record for the hottest day of 2016 of 53.6 degrees Celsius, and this summer temperatures were very high, with floods in Jeddah and more recently in Mecca at a time when temperatures in Saudi Arabia have increased by 2 percent and the maximum temperature of 2.5 percent since the 1980s.\nQatar is the world \u2019 s highest emitting country and the world \u2019 s largest producer of liquefied gas (LNG), and public spaces are equipped with air conditioners.\nIn Tehran, pollution annually kills 4,000 people a year, and in Khuzestan province, citizens have blocked streets and burned tires due to drought as a result of mismanagement, U.S. sanctions and a deadly atmosphere.\nIn the United Arab Emirates, the climate crisis is estimated to cost $6 billion a year, the highest in terms of health costs.\nThe salinity of the Gulf increased with the proliferation of desalination plants by 20%, which affected marine life and biodiversity.\nConditions are expected to worsen at a time of rising temperatures, humidity and sea levels.\nWarming rates in the Middle East are twice as high as in the world.\nBy the end of the century, if the dangerous predictions are correct, Mecca may not be fit for life, making the Hajj season dangerous if not catastrophic.\nLarge swaths of the Middle East have come to resemble the Afar region of Ethiopia, a vast area without human settlement that pushes towards the Red Sea.\nThe glittering cities of the Gulf may face the dilemma of rising water levels themselves.\nWe do not speak of the day of judgment, but of the day of judgment.\nJim Crane, an energy researcher at Rice University in Houston, said: \u201cThis is really a difficult topic because the interests of the ruling elites are at odds with the interests of the citizens.\nThe ruling elite depends on oil resources for the survival of their regimes.\nThey want to keep the oil trade in order to keep them in power.\nTheir system is based on oil leasing, but the population \u2019 s ultimate interests lie in a sustainable climate. \u201d\nZeina Khalil Haj, founder of Greenpeace in the Middle East, believes that the region is suffering from double pressure: \u201cWith increasing demands for energy change, a region that relies on fossil energy, oil and carbon for its economic survival, but cannot continue this dependency.\nThere will be no oil market but with climate change, they are required to increase efforts to survive.\nThe extreme climate is changing people \u2019 s lives on a daily basis and there is no choice but to go green. \u201d\nThe West \u2019 s persistent appetite for fossil energy has led the region to build car-based cities, shiny skyscrapers filled with air conditioners and shopping malls.\nIt must look for ways to avoid self-destruction, and it must be, according to Thomas Friedman, the Prometheus moment for the Middle East and the search for creative and creative ways.\nIn fact, the region has been reminded for a decade that it has to make the transition from oil.\nAlthough the moment when oil demand will reach its highest point remains controversial, and depends on a number of assumptions about regulation, technology and customer behavior, the point I mentioned is 2040, after which demand will decline.\nBut the International Energy Organization \u2019 s \u201cNet Zero \u201d report sees the peak as 2050 and by comparison suggests a reduction in oil demand from 88 million barrels per day in 2020 to 72 million barrels per day by 2030, and 24 million barrels per day in 2050, a 75% decline between 2020-2050.\nThe report argues that the Gulf has three factors underpinning the transformation: capital, sun, and vast, empty spaces.\nUntil recently, the Gulf states, including Iran, did not feel the desire to shift away from fossil energy to this extent.\nWhen asked, Saudi Oil Minister Prince Abdulaziz bin Salman said it was \u201ca sequel to La La Land, \u201d meaning that the report and its writers do not know what is happening.\n\"If I wanted to worry about the IEA's expectations, I would be on Prozac all the time,\" he said.\nQatar \u2019 s Energy Minister Saad al-Kaabi said reducing oil and gas production levels would affect the supply process and laughed at \u201cthe enthusiasm surrounding the transition. \u201d\nThe Organization of Petroleum Producing and Exporting Countries (OPEC) forecasts that the process of oil demand will increase significantly through 2045 and the share of oil in global energy demand will fall from 30% to 28%, which is not a green revolution.\nGulf states still rely on gas and oil exports, accounting for 70 percent of goods exported from Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and Oman.\nOil resources account for more than 70% of the total resources of Kuwait, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain.\nIn Vision 2030, published by Prince Mohammed bin Salman in 2016, he promised to turn the country into an important industrial hub.\nWorld Bank figures show that Saudi Arabia relies on 75% of its oil resources for its budget.\nAramco, which is making its mark on global carbon emissions, is not diversifying at the same pace as Shell or BP.\nInstead, it announced it would increase crude oil production capacity from 12 million barrels per day to 13 million barrels per day by 2027.\nHaj believes that the shift away from oil may require a psychological shift from the consumer mentality, \u201cThe Gulf has not yet reached this kind of discussion.\nIf you see the way of life in the UAE and Qatar, it is based on inexhaustible consumption, and I fear we are still a long way from that in terms of politics and readiness. \u201d\nIran is the largest country in the world in terms of carbon emissions by population, followed by the UAE in second place and Saudi Arabia in 13th place.\nOf course, Gulf rulers at events such as the Glasgow climate conference can defend themselves by saying that their region is not the primary source of carbon emissions, and historically, collectively, accounts for 4.7% less than carbon emissions and pollution from the United States, Europe and China.\nThe Middle East exports oil, but pollution is the responsibility of those who import it.\nBut the region \u2019 s leaders have come to grips with the problem not because of Western pressure but in response to citizens \u2019 demands, the goose has realized that the eggs, the oil, are no longer golden but brown.\nThe UAE is the first country to say it has moved to ratify the Paris Treaty and is the least dependent Gulf state on oil for its government resources.\nLast week, she announced the \u201cNet Zero by 2050 Initiative \u201d with an initial investment budget of $163 billion and appointed the Minister of Climate Change and Environment, Maryam Al Muhairi.\nThe announcement came after the government ordered awareness sessions in all its ministries since June for 80 days.\nIt was the first country in the Gulf to adopt a net zero domestic consumption policy.\nThe plan is still in its infancy and some of its features are unclear, but the direction is clear.\nIt promised to rely on renewable and nuclear energy by 50% to generate electricity by 2050.\nAbu Dhabi \u2019 s national oil company said it would get 100 percent of its electricity from the nuclear reactor and solar power.\nThe Mohammed bin Maktoum Solar Park will be the largest in the world with a capacity of 5,000 megawatts.\nGulf states are competing with each other, with news reports that Qatar has appointed a climate minister, Bahrain aiming for net zero carbon by 2050 and Kuwait announcing a plan to reduce carbon emissions.\nSaudi Arabia does not like to be late.\nIt announced that it would increase the proportion of renewable energy from 0.3% to 50% by 2030.\nThe plan is to plant 10 million trees in the coming decades.\nOver the weekend, the kingdom organized a summit of the Green Middle East Initiative, attended by John Kerry and Britain \u2019 s Prince Charles.\nIt promised to reach net zero carbon emissions in its territory by 2060.\nThe main reason the Gulf states have been slow to shift away from oil and its commodities is that they have made them rich and helped them anesthetize their citizens.\nTheir loyalty was bought through a series of subsidies for water, electricity, fuel and tax breaks.\nThese dynamics were different from Iraq, Lebanon and to a lesser extent Iran, but the situation is changing with the emergence of local environmental groups.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0031.json.gz:29938","uncompressed_offset":688584704,"url":"samanews.ps/ar/post/493970/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D8%B3%D8%B7-%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AC%D9%87-%E2%80%9C%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A9%E2%80%9D-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%82%D8%AF-%D9%84%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%AD-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%B4-%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B1%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A","warc_date":"2021-10-29T15:21:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a69b44b9-f260-4b60-aefb-0e17361e7f17>","warc_url":"https://samanews.ps/ar/post/493970/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D8%B3%D8%B7-%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AC%D9%87-%E2%80%9C%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A9%E2%80%9D-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%82%D8%AF-%D9%84%D8%A7-%D8%AA%D8%B5%D9%84%D8%AD-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%B4-%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B1%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A"},"created":"2021-10-29T15:49:04.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086":{"id":"b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2_343469086","text":"New technologies to achieve sustainability goals and address climate change\nScience and Technology\nHuawei\nCopy Link https: / / en.rt.com / u0x4\nExisting renewable energy initiatives in the Middle East are strengthening their role in supporting international efforts to address climate change.\nIn particular, the region is one of the largest contributors to the oil and gas sector globally, and at the same time is the cradle of a number of major and ambitious initiatives and projects aimed at enhancing the reliance on clean energy.\nIn the UAE, the Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park is the world \u2019 s largest IPP solar site, and the Al Dhafra Solar PV Plant is being built as the world \u2019 s largest solar power plant with a capacity of 2 GW.\nMasdar City is the most sustainable urban community in the world.\nADFD is committed to funding innovative projects to accelerate access to sustainable energy as part of a joint initiative with the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA).\nIn Saudi Arabia, Neom recently launched The Line, the world \u2019 s first car-free, carbon-free city with 100% renewable energy.\nKing Abdullah University of Science and Technology (KAUST) leads green energy projects designed to manage the recycling of grey water for reuse for plant irrigation and other purposes, and also has large area photovoltaic panels that produce clean electricity.\nIn Egypt, hydropower is the second source of energy after thermal, wind and solar, and the country has developed a number of future projects that seek to exploit solar energy and replace non-renewable energy.\nOther green projects in Egypt include the cities of Jebel Galala and El Alamein.\nThe Bahrain World Trade Centre is one of the world \u2019 s leading examples of sustainable architecture, taking the lead in being the first skyscraper in the world to introduce wind turbines to provide total energy consumption.\nMorocco, famous for its huge and world-leading solar arrays, has made a big name for itself as a leader in the fight against climate change, renewable energy makes up nearly two-fifths of the country \u2019 s electricity, and the country implements some of the world \u2019 s largest clean energy projects.\nSince 2012, Jordan has turned to solar power to generate electricity and government policies have pushed citizens and investors to turn to renewable energy to reduce carbon dioxide emissions, by offering financial facilities to investors and reducing the electricity bill.\nSustainability initiatives in the Arab countries contribute effectively to building a diversified digital economy that achieves the national visions of these countries, and the green economy initiative launched by the UAE, and the Saudi Green Initiative is a good example of this.\nToday, the ICT sector is increasingly playing a role in achieving sustainability through new technologies such as 5G, cloud computing and artificial intelligence that will play a key role in implementing clean energy initiatives as they enhance productivity, improve efficiency, reduce costs and waste, evaluate business systems, analyze waste, track problems and develop solutions.\nThe International Telecommunication Union (ITU) says ICT will contribute to achieving the UN \u2019 s Sustainable Development Goals and improving the quality of life.\nAccording to the United Nations, ICT can be relied upon in two ways: reliance on clean information and communication technology, and clean energy generation based on information and communication technology.\nIn the first scenario, ICT solutions that contribute to environmental safety and carbon reduction are designed.\nIn the second scenario, ICT solutions such as those in grids, buildings, smart logistics and industrial processes help promote sustainability and energy efficiency.\nThe sustainability efforts of tech companies have been recognized globally, Huawei is an example of companies that have adjusted their business in line with sustainability goals, and recently received an award from the International Mobile Phone Association for their contributions to achieving the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals through mobile devices.\nThe company aims to rely on innovative technologies to drive clean development across various sectors and industries, and in 2021 it used more than 300 million kWh of electricity produced from renewable sources, an increase of 42.3% compared to 2020.\nHuawei \u2019 s digital power solutions have generated 482.9 billion kilowatt-hours of clean energy and reduced electricity consumption by 14.2 billion kilowatt-hours, equivalent to 230 million tons of carbon emissions.\nIn parallel with efforts to promote a sustainable approach to technology, the ICT industry must not lose sight of the issue of enhanced security.\nTechnology providers should focus on protecting user privacy when working to provide modern, seamless technology and communications.\nCertainly, we will not be able to grow the business and ensure its sustainability if we do not provide safe and reliable technologies to protect cybersecurity, which is a shared responsibility of all stakeholders involved in sustainability.\nThe current digital divide could isolate millions of people around the world from contributing to the development of a clean economy.\nTech companies can contribute to making technology accessible to all thanks to their technical capabilities and resources.\nThrough initiatives such as TECH4ALL, Huawei has relied on digital technologies to implement programs aimed at enhancing the leadership capabilities of more than 110,000 people in 2021.\nThe digital divide in global talent could undermine sustainability efforts, so greater emphasis should be placed on redressing it and priority should be given to strengthening collaboration between tech companies, academia and government institutions in order to bridge the digital skills gap.\nBy investing in programs to prepare local technical cadres, hone skills and enhance practical experience, more bridges of cooperation between the public and private sectors can be built to prepare the future generation of sustainability leaders with the help of technology.\nHuawei has established 163 ICT academies in the Middle East.\nMore than 3,500 students participated in the Seeds for the Global Future program, while more than 37,000 students received Huawei certifications.\nThe company has also provided training to more than 120,000 ICT talents in the region who are expected to contribute to the advancement of sustainability in the countries of the region by making the most of technology.\nIn light of the increasing challenges of reducing carbon emissions facing various countries around the world, we all have a responsibility to strengthen cooperation and work together to build a sustainable and prosperous future for future generations.\nBy: Ammar Taba, Huawei Vice President for Public Relations and Media in the Middle East\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0031.json.gz:28019","uncompressed_offset":343469086,"url":"arabic.rt.com/technology/1400872-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AB%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%8A%D9%82-%D8%A3%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AC%D9%87%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%BA%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AE%D9%8A/","warc_date":"2022-10-21T14:06:55.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b38f7e84-4a58-4949-9f58-e8488e7d1ca2>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/technology/1400872-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AB%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%82%D9%8A%D9%82-%D8%A3%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AC%D9%87%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%BA%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AE%D9%8A/"},"created":"2022-10-21T14:22:06.000Z","lang":"eng"},"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952":{"id":"06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7_580588952","text":"Sunday, 24 September 2023 02: 03 GMT\n2030 Arab Goal to Advance Renewable Energy Capabilities Globally\n(MENAFN- Al-Bayan) $(resize) .css ('font-size', newFontSize); return false;});});\nSeveral Arab countries are accelerating to keep pace with the international aspiration to achieve the goal of tripling global renewable energy capacity by 2030, which is receiving widespread attention, amid various plans and strategies at national levels in many countries.\nThe Arab countries that are likely to play the largest role in this regard, according to industry experts, are the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Kuwait, Egypt, Jordan, Algeria and Morocco, by injecting more investments into this vital and promising sector.\nDuring the recent G20 summit in New Delhi in September, G20 leaders expressed their support for all efforts to increase renewable energy capacity and pledged to accelerate measures to address environmental crises and challenges.\nWith this growing international interest in the energy transition, the plans are facing many challenges, including (but not limited to) access to finance, especially for low- and middle-income countries, with significant investment required over the coming years.\n(Al-Bayan), a group of American academics and specialists in the renewable energy sector were surveyed about the main opportunities and challenges on the way to increase the desired capacity, the investments required to achieve that goal, and the extent of its expected environmental and economic repercussions.\nHuge spikes.\nAchieving the ambitious goal of doubling global renewable energy capacity in the near term will be reflected concretely in several contexts, explains Gregory Nemet, a specialist in the analysis of international energy systems and environmental policies at the University of Wisconsin. By 2030, it will deliver significant benefits in terms of jobs, economic development, and improved air quality, as well as putting the world on the path to addressing climate change in the long term.\n\u201cThe costs of renewable energy, especially solar and wind, have dropped dramatically over the last 10 years, and most experts expect them to continue to fall, \u201d says Nemet, explaining that a clean, affordable source of energy creates huge opportunities, allowing global renewable energy capacity to be tripled by taking full advantage of it.\nAccording to Nemet, the 3-fold increase also presents challenges, such as \u201caccess to finance for low- and middle-income countries, and investments in electricity grids to accommodate this growth \u201d, stressing that\u201c challenges can be overcome through sustained efforts and supportive policies, as we have seen many examples in the recent past. \u201d A sign of broad international cooperation is required in this regard.\nLast year, renewable energy capacity (globally) increased by 9.6 percent to 3,372 gigawatts, an increase of a record 295 gigawatts, despite global uncertainty in light of geopolitical developments and the Ukrainian war, according to data published by the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) on March 22.\nAlmost half of the new capacity from renewable energy in Asia has been added, with China contributing more than 141 gigawatts to the new capacity of the entire continent.\nRenewable energy sources in Europe and the United States grew by 57.3 gigawatts and 29.1 gigawatts respectively.\nAfrican capacity increased slightly by 2.7 gigawatts.\nAccording to IRENA data, although hydropower accounts for the largest share of total global renewable energy capacity at 1,250 gigawatts, solar and wind power continue to dominate new capacity, contributing 90% of total capacity last year.\nSolar capacity came first with an increase of 22%, followed by wind power with an increase of 9%.\nPolicies and Incentives\nUniversity of Massachusetts academic David Turcotte, whose research interests include climate change and environmental justice, believes that there are many opportunities in the context of increasing global renewable energy capacity, due to increases in oil prices as a result of the Ukrainian crisis, which makes renewable energy sources more cost-effective, as well as worsening economic and human costs. Recurrent, more severe climate change disasters.\n\u201cMany developed countries have expanded policies and incentives to encourage increased capacity to produce renewable energy.\nHowever, we still face a lot of challenges [\u2026]\nThat threatens to derail efforts to increase renewable energy capacity, and the transition to a clean energy economy.\nAmong these challenges is the lack of adequate funding to support increases in renewable energy capacity in developing countries, a challenge he described as \u201cserious. \u201d\nWhile international efforts are accelerating to target investments in the context of increasing global renewable energy capacity, those investments are still below the 1.5 \u00b0 C target.\nThis is shown by data from IRENA and the Climate Policy Initiative (CPI) released in February, which estimate the total volume of investments in renewable energy sectors during 2022 at $499 billion, up from $430 billion in the previous year 2021.\nDevelopments in the world over the past year, especially with the start of the Russian military operation in Ukraine in February 2022, have also encouraged many countries to move more towards renewable energy sources, to overcome the energy crisis caused by the consequences of the war, in the interest of the desired goal of increasing capacity.\nRequired investments\nJohn Hall, Professor of Mechanical Engineering at the Center for Energy Production and Infrastructure, University of North Carolina, United States, notes that \u201cthe goal of tripling global renewable energy capacity by 2030 is a challenge, and achieving the goal requires an intensive global strategy, focused on significant financial investment, technological innovation targeting these communities, inclusive policies, and collaborative efforts. \u201d\nSpeaking with Al-Bayan, he stressed that community participation and infrastructure development in underserved areas should be central to the strategy, leading not only to the promotion of the energy transition, but also to economic upgrading.\nThe International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) estimates that $4 trillion per year will be required in the clean energy sector until 2030 to strengthen global capacity in this regard.\nLogistical challenges\nWarren Mabey, an academic at Queen \u2019 s University who specialises in energy policy and natural resource management, told Al Bayan that \u201cit is technically possible to triple global renewable energy capacity over the next six years, and this will put enormous pressure on the global supply chains that support the sector. and manufactured goods, necessary for the transformation process).\nMabe believes that \u201cthe cost will be enormous, and the logistical challenge may be too great to overcome \u201d, stressing the need for\u201c strong and consistent leadership from countries around the world to achieve this. \u201d\nArabic Steps\nAt the Arab level, five Arab countries (Egypt, Morocco, Oman, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates) are expected to account for about 72% of the region \u2019 s total growth in renewable energy, according to the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC), which expects renewable energy capacity to reach 45 gigawatts by 2027, an increase of 3 times. Compared to the last five years.\nThe International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) estimates that in 2022, the Middle East saw the highest increase in renewables ever, with 3.2 gigawatts of new capacity added last year, a 12.8 percent increase over the previous year.\nAccording to the Arab Renewable Energy Authority (AREA), the volume of investments by Arab countries in renewable energy projects is expected to reach $1 trillion by 2040, in light of the interest of Arab governments in this file, to achieve global environmental goals.\nA Great Leap in 10 Years\nAccording to the current data, the renewable energy sector in the region is expected to witness a huge leap in the next 10 years, at a time when eight Arab countries are leading this trend, according to the researcher in international relations and political economy, Abu Bakr al-Deeb, adviser to the Arab Center for Studies and Research, who tells Al-Bayan that the countries strongly candidate to move in this direction are:, Kuwait, Egypt, Jordan, Algeria and Morocco).\nAldeeb also cites the volume of electricity generated from renewable sources in the Middle East and Arab countries, which is expected to increase six-fold in 10 years through heavy reliance on solar photovoltaic energy, noting that the Arab region has \u201cgreat potential \u201d to help launch major projects to produce energy from the sun. And wind, among these possibilities or advantages (the right climate, the bright sun most days of the year, as well as human expertise, and financial capabilities also for some countries).\nThe UAE is at the top of the list of Arab countries that produce electricity from solar energy, while Egypt is the largest country in the Arab world in terms of electricity production from wind energy, according to a report issued by (Global Energy Monitor), which Al-Deeb cites when explaining the progress made by some Arab countries in this sector, The UAE, Egypt, Jordan and Morocco are among the first Arab countries to establish solar and wind power plants.\nAccording to the report, renewable power plant projects for Arab countries are likely to achieve 92% of the region \u2019 s total target by 2030 when completed.\nOne of the most reliable projects in this regard is the Green Hydrogen projects, through which the Middle East is seeking global leadership, with export revenues likely to reach $200 billion by 2050 for the Gulf countries, according to a study by Dii Desert Energy.\nIn this context, Al-Deeb notes the abundance of renewable energy resources, clean hydrogen, human expertise, capital, and their geographical proximity to the European market, all of which provide them with important and growing opportunities.\nMENAFN24092023000110011019ID1107129201\nLegal Disclaimer:\nMENA Financial Services Network provides information \"as is\" without any representations or warranties...\nThis disclaims our responsibility for the privacy practices or content of the sites included in our network, including images and videos.\nFor any queries regarding the use and reuse of this source of information, please contact the provider of the above article.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0027.json.gz:80580","uncompressed_offset":580588952,"url":"menafn.com/arabic/1107129201/2030-%D9%87%D8%AF%D9%81-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%84%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D9%88%D8%B6-%D8%A8%D9%82%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7","warc_date":"2023-09-24T10:17:32.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:06220c37-9eba-4b15-a2f4-e6f3edec97e7>","warc_url":"https://menafn.com/arabic/1107129201/2030-%D9%87%D8%AF%D9%81-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%84%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D9%88%D8%B6-%D8%A8%D9%82%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A7"},"created":"2023-09-24T14:03:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014":{"id":"7eaa21a6-b91e-42bd-9751-d884baa45975_948500014","text":"MUSCAT: Renewable capacity expansion in the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) is projected to grow three-fold over the next five years (2023 \u2013 2028), with the Sultanate of Oman ranked among the front-runners in driving this growth. According to a new report by the International Energy Agency (IEA), Oman\u2019s renewables capacity growth is set to be the fourth largest in the region after Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Morocco.\n\nThese countries will account for the lion\u2019s share of the 62 gigawatt (GW) increase in renewables capacity anticipated in the region by 2028, the Paris-based intergovernmental agency noted in its newly published report. \u201cOver the next five years, the pace of growth is expected to accelerate to more than three times the previous five-year period, with solar PV making up over 85 per cent of the increase. Onshore wind and concentrated solar power also contribute,\u201d said the IEA in its report, titled \u2018Renewables 2023: Analysis and forecast to 2028\u2019.\n\nDriving much of this growth will be efforts by individual countries to decarbonize their electricity generation, but green hydrogen production is set to play a major role as well, according to the report. This is particularly the case in Saudi Arabia, UAE and Oman, it pointed out. \u201cIn fact, hydrogen accounts for more than 13 per cent of the region\u2019s renewable capacity growth thanks to government policies to stimulate development for trade. Good solar resources, land availability and existing port infrastructure create favourable conditions for economically attractive renewable hydrogen to be shipped to demand centres in Europe and Asia,\u201d the agency further stated.\n\nAdditionally, the report reaffirmed Oman\u2019s positioning among the world\u2019s top exporters of renewable hydrogen. It said: \u201cBy 2028, potential export countries could account for over one-fifth of hydrogen-driven renewable capacity deployment, led by Saudi Arabia, Australia, Oman and the United Arab Emirates. With the prospect of producing economically attractive renewable hydrogen to ship to potential demand centres in Europe and Asia, these countries aim to become major exporters of renewable hydrogen and hydrogen-based fuels.\u201d\n\nA revised Renewable Energy Plan enshrined in Oman\u2019s 2040 Vision seeks to secure 16 per cent of electricity from renewables by 2025, rising to 30 per cent by 2030. Clean energy capacity is projected to rise to 2.6 GW by 2025 under the National Energy Master Plan. Supplementing this strategy is a commitment to embracing green hydrogen to, on the one hand, decarbonise the economy, and on the other to evolve into a major producer and exporter of renewable hydrogen. Green hydrogen output is targeted at around 1 million tonnes per annum by 2030.\n\n2022 \u00a9 All right reserved for Oman Establishment for Press, Publication and Advertising (OEPPA) Provided by SyndiGate Media Inc. (Syndigate.info).","url":"https://www.zawya.com/en/business/energy/oman-among-frontrunners-of-renewables-growth-in-mena-iea-pnww9jd8"}}}
