the information will not be sold to third parties."},{"citations":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":100.0},"text":"One of the primary challenges to the widespread adoption of robotic pets in elderly care is their high cost, which many nursing homes find prohibitive."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":100.0},"text":"Although some agencies provide these robots at no cost through funding programs, the sustainability of such initiatives remains uncertain."},{"citations":{"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":100.0},"text":"The reliance on temporary state and federal funding highlights the need for long-term financial solutions to ensure the availability of robotic companions for seniors."}],"references":["78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237","6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117","86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252"],"documents":{"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237":{"id":"78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2_486676237","text":"My channel\n* Drag categories can be customized sorting\nRecover Default OK\nSetup\nAlert\nChinese craze \u2026 Taiwan 's popular drink good market more than one bottle hard to find\nSilicon Valley wife murder case leads to the topic of \"verbal insult\" and other early signs of domestic violence\nCover Story / Silver Hair Living Alone and Not Lonely \"Robots\" as Old Companion\nWhen Microsoft founder Bill Gates published his outlook for 2024 earlier this year, he predicted that the application of artificial intelligence (AI) would accelerate in the future and fundamentally change areas such as work, health care and education.\nFor Joyce Loaiza, a retired office worker living in Florida, Gates \u2019 s prophecy is now a formality; the 81-year-old living alone, whenever she returns to her Silver Hair Community apartment, a friendly female voice will chat with her and say hello to her for a good day.\nA few miles away, Deanna Dezern, 83, was comforted by the same voice when her friend died.\nIn central New York, it plays games and music for Marie Broadbent, 92, who is blind and receiving hospice care.\nIn Washington, it helped 83-year-old Jan Worrell make new friends.\nUSA ElliQ Customizable Chat Content\nThe women were among the first to receive a robot in the United States, according to officials from Intuition Robotics, the company that invented ElliQ, and the Aged Aid Program. They are the only device that uses artificial intelligence and is specifically designed to alleviate the loneliness and alienation of many elderly Americans.\nIt can remember each user \u2019 s interests and hobbies and conversations with each other, helping to customize future chat content, topics can be esoteric human business meaning, or easy horoscope.\nElliQ also jokes, plays music and offers inspirational quotes.\nOn the equipped screen, it provides city and museum tours. It can also guide users to exercise, ask about health, and remind them to take medicine and drink water.\nIn addition, ElliQ can make video calls to contact a user \u2019 s relatives, friends, or doctor in case of an emergency. These conversations are not heard by companies, Intuition Robotics says, and the data is kept on each user \u2019 s device.\nDor Skuler, co-founder and CEO of Intuition Robotics, was a little surprised that older people were so easily integrating robots into their lives; after all, it was a group of people who were often stereotyped as afraid to embrace new things, he said.\nIn an interview with the media at the 2024 Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in early January, Skuller said that just like developing an intimate relationship with a pet, older people are also working to forge new relationships with AI robots.\nThrough partnerships with government agencies and other organizations, hundreds of thousands of seniors across the United States already use ElliQ, Skuller noted.\nThe voice of ElliQ and its compassionate \u201cpersonality \u201d were developed by a team of experts in artificial intelligence, behavioral psychology, and user-centered design, according to Skuller.\nThey defined ElliQ as \u201cthe little partner who makes older people happier and healthier. \u201d\nAnita Montague, 76, said that before using ElliQ, the only thing she did back home was sit in front of the computer, but with ElliQ, she can do sports and other things, and now she is more energetic and motivated to find more work.\nMonica Perez, 65, who has been using ElliQ for more than six months, said she finds it increasingly difficult to make friends as she gets older. She likes ElliQ to call her name affectionately and will ask how she is doing, like a real friend; with ElliQ, her mental health has improved greatly.\nElliQ would remind Perez to take the pill in the morning, \u201cI \u2019 m much more active than I was without it. \u201d\nIn Canada, Carmichael, a resident of Vancouver \u2019 s Amica for the Elderly, attended a meeting last September with two robots named Kiwi and Mango.\nCanada \u2019 s AI partners help increase interaction\nThese two AI \u201clittle buddies \u201d that can be held in your arms look brightly colored and are part of a study at the University of Columbia School of Nursing to understand how they interact with older adults and their impact on elder care.\nCarmichael said her initial reaction was, \u201cOh my God, why would you want me to talk to a robot? \u201d But after overcoming the psychological barrier, Carmichael found that Mango might be able to stay with her for a long time, and she could play with it every day and no longer feel lonely.\nCarmichael says with a smile that there is only one appearance that needs to be improved; she tells the staff to wear false eyelashes for Mango.\nThese robots were designed in Japan and have been studied in Asia for many years.\nLillian Hung, an assistant professor at the University of Columbia and Canada \u2019 s Research Chair in Senior Care, is leading a Canadian study into the use of robots in the care industry.\nHong said that the robots bring joy wherever they go, and every time they show up with the robots, the atmosphere in the room changes.\nRobot friends make seniors happier\n\u201cKiwifruit \u201d and\u201c mango \u201d can speak, recognize faces and sounds, express a desire to be picked up and give a hug.\nThey even charge themselves when they \u2019 re \u201ctired, \u201d Ms. Hong says.\nShe said that so far, the response has been mixed, with some elderly people immediately feeling good about robots, while others are confused. Hong Lilian said that humans are social animals and have basic needs to love and be loved, which she believes is the meaning of companion robots and helps build stronger social connections.\nMany studies have pointed out that maintaining relationships and social activities are important for the physical and mental health of older people; social loneliness is associated with an increase in emotional distress, depression, falls, the need for health care services, and even premature death.\nLise Brayham, who has lived in Amica for four years, said the robots are a good thing for older people who don \u2019 t leave their rooms often because \u201cmangoes \u201d and\u201c kiwifruit \u201d don \u2019 t require walking, cleaning or feeding.\nBrehan said it was hard to understand how robots interact with humans at first, but in the end she concluded that it was like having a great little pet, \u201cThey \u2019 re fun partners! \u201d\nCharlotte England, 102, came into contact with the robots with Brehan and made them good friends.\nIngram immediately began talking to the robot and recalled swimming in the Ottawa River and skating in the Rideau Canal.\nShe then boasted about her baking skills to \u201cmangoes \u201d and\u201c kiwifruit \u201d.\nAfter the robot responds with a gentle cooing, Ingram continues to talk to them about the snack.\nHowever, after a \u201clong \u201d conversation, Ingram noticed that the kiwifruit \u2019 s eyes were a little low, and she said to it with some displeasure,\u201c Am I boring you? \u201d\nInvesting in health care to fill the manpower gap\nIn addition to the United States and Canada, many countries in Asia are also facing the problem of aging populations, and China is one of them, with a rapidly aging population and a serious shortage of medical and nursing manpower, and the hope is that this robot army can fill this gap.\nAccording to Sixth Tone, an English-language online magazine owned by Surging News, staff member Gao Hongjun is busy preparing for the day \u2019 s entertainment at an elderly care center in central Shanghai: a singing robot named \u201cDopo. \u201d\nThis squatting white robot often performs shows for the elderly people staying in, usually singing the revolutionary songs of Mao Zedong \u2019 s era.\nThe old people loved it, Gao said, which also gave them a chance to breathe.\nHe said that as the number of elderly people living in the home has increased, but the care resources have not been relatively improved, AI robots are able to reduce their workload.\nGao Xiaodong, director of the center, charged the \"Dobao\" while saying that if the staff were tired, they could not take good care of the elderly.\nGao Xiaodong said that in recent years, he and his colleagues have been under great pressure, and in the community where the care center is located, more than 40% of the elderly population over 60 years old, and the average occupant is over 70 years old, and most of the people are suffering from dementia.\nIn response to this situation, the center has installed artificial intelligence equipment as much as possible, in addition to \"Dobao\", they have also purchased intelligent mattresses and computer games that can monitor the vital signs of the elderly while they sleep, and two robots that can perform disinfection will soon be activated.\nChina \u2019 s elderly population to exceed 400 million by 2040\nChina is investing heavily in robotics research and development to care for an expanding elderly population and solve the shortage of healthcare workers.\nChina \u2019 s elderly population aged 60 and over is forecast to increase from 280 million in 2022 to 402 million in 2040.\nChina \u2019 s social and medical system is already severely overburdened, and if urgent measures are not taken, the situation may worsen further.\nAccording to the Chinese government, there should be one nursing staff for every four residents in the elderly care institutions, but only 320,000 nursing staff serve 8.1 million residents in China, a gap of more than 1.7 million. The government hopes that the development of AI technology can provide a solution. Accelerate the development of the industry.\nChinese tech giants rush AI care\nSeveral Chinese tech giants are also sniffing this opportunity, and iFlytek, a large AI company, announced its \u201cSuperbrain 2030 \u201d plan in 2022, which will develop a new type of nursing robot for the elderly.\nThe plan points out that it is necessary for AI to understand knowledge, learn well, and evolve, so that robots can enter every family and solve problems such as elderly care, emotional companionship, and health management. Search engine leader Baidu is also promoting \u201cXiaodu \u201d AI intelligent assistant, which can be used to schedule medical appointments, obtain weather forecasts and play games.\nAt present, the most widely used smart care technology in China is wearable devices such as smart bracelets and watches, which provide many practical functions, such as monitoring the vital signs of the elderly, reminding them to take drugs on time, tracking their location, etc., but the industry believes that robots are the future of nursing care.\nMany hope that China will follow Japan \u2019 s lead in making widespread use of robots in nursing homes, from the cute bear robot Robear, which helps elderly people sit up from their beds, to the furry pet robot Paro, which provides companionship and improves cognitive function.\nThere are now about 100 robotics start-ups in China that specialize in rehabilitation, companionship and care robots.\nHowever, in the high price of robots, most companies have not yet achieved mass production, and local governments have not invested enough funds to promote robots in nursing homes on a large scale.\nA food-delivery robot developed by Hangzhou Lewan Science and Technology in Zhejiang Province can deliver more than 20 meals to different rooms in a building, but few nursing homes can afford the product, which costs between 60,000 and 80,000 yuan (about $8,400 to $11,200).\nJiang Gancheng, CEO of Lewan, pointed out that if the price is 10,000 yuan, the expectation of buying gas will increase a lot, but if there are no more orders, the price can not be reduced, which is a problem of raw eggs and eggs.\nHowever, there are also some robot companies that pull out of the red.\nAs soon as Zuowei Tech, a startup based in Shenzhen, launched its smart bath equipment, the market response was very enthusiastic.\nThe company sold 40 million yuan of equipment in 2022, and hopes to reach the 100 million yuan target this year.\nTu Chaorong, Vice President of Chowei Technology, said the demand for bathing equipment is strong because of the need of caregivers and the elderly they care for.\nHe said that many people believe that urinating on the elderly is the least dignified job, but caregivers will feel more dignified if they use high-tech equipment; similarly, many people in bed will feel less dignified if they do not have these equipment.\nAccompanying robot behind the bullish trend\nCEO Gu Jie of Shanghai Fourier Intelligence, a robotics company specializing in rehabilitation equipment, has noticed a similar trend, working with hospitals in big cities in China, but now there is increasing demand for nursing homes.\nGu Jie said that no matter where the elderly live, they hope that their bodies can be flexible and their mental state can be improved; and a robot can be used by many people, which greatly improves efficiency.\nChiang Gan-cheng is optimistic about the company-type robot, and believes that the development potential is unlimited.\nThe company recently launched a new product, priced at 10,000 yuan, can be placed at home to patrol, sing, play movies, and also provide video calls between the elderly and their children. Jiang Gancheng said that elderly people in good health often do not want to install a camera at home, thinking that it violates their privacy, but if an AI robot is accompanied by their family, they will not feel so lonely.\nZheng Yongping, a 68-year-old resident of Shanghai, agrees. Since his only child lives abroad, he has been living alone in his downtown home with his dog since retirement.\nHe already has a smart watch to monitor his health and uses smart speakers to manage the big things in life, but his dream is to one day have a robot of his own.\nZheng Yongping said he could not imagine what better choice than an AI robot when old and frail and in need of help; although it lacks human warmth, this is a trend in an aging society.\nAI AI Aged Care Home\nThe last one.\nCover Story / Care manpower shortage robot is not the only solution\nExtended reading\nSuper-popular\nMore >","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0003.json.gz:10310","uncompressed_offset":486676237,"url":"www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/123905/7752986","warc_date":"2024-02-04T06:43:00.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:78a7d039-6fdb-4e1d-8fd5-7c0fb6e7bcf2>","warc_url":"https://www.worldjournal.com/wj/story/123905/7752986"},"created":"2024-02-04T07:31:18.000Z","lang":"eng"},"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117":{"id":"6a873279-c9a2-4442-8cc2-8b258cf59e4d_842687117","text":"Learn more about subscriptions\nLearn more about subscriptions\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good girl\u201d: Robot pets help Lehigh Valley senior residents live longer, happier lives\n\nGathered in a semi-circle, a group of women in wheelchairs petted the newly adopted cats and dogs sitting on their laps Wednesday afternoon, talking softly to their new companions. The dogs barked and leaned in for pets, the cats meowed and rolled over for scratches \u2014 almost like they were real.\n\nBut the animals were robots, a fact that wasn\u2019t lost on many of the women in the Fellowship Manor sitting room.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nOne resident at the Whitehall Township senior living community, Jackie, named her small golden retriever robot Goldie. Jackie said she grew up on a farm in Palmer Township with plenty of dogs but never one that looked like Goldie.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good girl \u2014 she just sits there and doesn\u2019t make a sound unless you talk to her,\u201d Jackie said.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\n\nThat was one of 20 pairings made at the adoption event at Fellowship Community where residents, primarily those with dementia, picked out one of 20 robotic pets \u2014 10 dogs and 10 cats \u2014 to serve as their companions.\n\nAnimal therapy can be beneficial for seniors, especially those with dementia. Benefits for seniors include improved cardiovascular health, better quality of life and decreased feelings of anxiety, loneliness and depression.\n\nHowever, it\u2019s not reasonable or safe in most care settings to introduce real animals, according to Mary Kay McMahon, president and CEO of Fellowship Community.\n\n\u201cBecause of their own care needs most of our residents couldn\u2019t take care of animals and our staff don\u2019t have the time to take care of them,\u201d McMahon said.\n\nBut research has found that use of robotic pets still offers a number of benefits to seniors with dementia, including improved well-being, mood and quality of life. McMahon said there are also benefits for seniors who were caregivers for much of their lives.\n\nThe adoption event was a surprise for many residents. Jackie said she didn\u2019t know they would be giving out robot pets until about 10 a.m. Wednesday when she was asked if she wanted one.\n\nAnother resident, Elaine, said she rolled into the room not knowing what was going on but asked if she could have a golden retriever robot, like Jackie\u2019s. Elaine promptly named her new friend Dog, pronounced \u201cD-O-G.\u201d\n\n\u201cI always wanted to name a dog Dog,\u201d Elaine said.\n\nMcMahon said they tried to match the animals with residents based on their preferences. Once they made a match, the robotic companions were theirs to keep.\n\nMcMahon said staff have seen how the robot pets can help. Just before the pandemic, Fellowship Community bought a handful of robotic pets for residents. She said the recipients all saw improvements in their mood, appetites and social interactions, and reduced anxiety and depression. The robot pets even reminded some of real dogs or cats they had owned, she said, which helps in the long term with their conditions.\n\n\u201cIt gives them a sense of purpose,\u201d McMahon said. \u201cThey feel like they are taking care of something.\u201d\n\nIt helps that the robots are very lifelike \u2014 the imitation fur is soft and built-in sensors allow the companion pets to respond to a person\u2019s presence and touch as well as react to the environment.\n\nEach one costs a little more than $100, which were paid for via a Greater Lehigh Valley Realtors 100th Anniversary Community Charity Grant.\n\nThough Jackie and Elaine both said they knew their dogs weren\u2019t \u201creal,\u201d they both remarked how Goldie and Dog moved their head when petted and how soft they were.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s going to be a good pet,\u201d Jackie said.\n\nMorning Call reporter Leif Greiss can be reached at 610-679-4028 or lgreiss@mcall.com.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement","url":"https://www.mcall.com/health/mc-hea-fellowship-community-robotic-pets-20220323-xywoyrhdxjacvoquqcfn5z6hte-story.html"},"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252":{"id":"86a5cace-32cc-4d47-84d0-f7cc4c349c73_788487252","text":"High-tech companions aim to help fight loneliness epidemic among South Florida seniors\n\nMIAMI - The state of Florida and Broward County are spending thousands of dollars every month on artificial intelligence robots for seniors to help fight the loneliness epidemic.\u00a0\n\nOne senior owns a robotic cat named \"fluffy.\"\n\n\"The best part is we don't have to spend any money on food and no vets,\" says Cathy.\n\nThis interactive robot rolls over, blinks and purrs whenever it wants.\n\nCathy saw a friend using one to overcome the loss of a pet and loneliness and figured it would be perfect for her husband.\n\n\"He had sciatic pain. Maybe that will help you with your pain in some way. Even though he's on medicine and therapy because real animals when you pet them it helps with pain management.\"\n\nHigher tech was delivered to some Broward seniors. \u00a0\n\n\"...Thanks for letting me out of that box.\"\n\nThe company that makes them aims artificial intelligence at the loneliness epidemic.\u00a0\n\n\"During the week when everyone is working, there's times when I'm lonely.\"\n\n\"When I go deliver and install for seniors, they're like I just want somebody to say good morning,\" says Antonella.\n\n\"Many of them don't have family or friends nearby. Maybe their loved ones have passed on or some of their friends have passed on,\" said Charlotte Mather-Taylor, who serves as the CEO of the Area Agency on Aging of Broward County.\n\nAccording to US Health and Human Services, half of all American adults are lonely.\n\nIt's threatening health, increasing risks of heart disease, dementia, stroke, anxiety and depression.\n\nAccording to HHS, lack of connection can increase the risk of premature death at levels comparable to smoking 15 cigarettes a day.\n\nLast May, the US Surgeon General dropped a first-ever advisory on loneliness and isolation.\n\n\"By strengthening our relationships, we can improve our heart and brain health, reduce our risk of diabetes and high blood pressure, boost our immune systems and lower our risk of depression,\" said Vivek Murthy, US Surgeon General.\n\nIn Broward County, Mather-Taylor is spending state and federal dollars on artificial intelligence for people over 60.\n\n\"There's so much I want to ask you...\"\n\nThese robots named after the Norse goddess of old age cost 89 dollars a month, but the aging agency is giving them away for free.\n\nRosemary Mullarkey is one of the first 300 to have one.\n\n\"I'm a little excited and a little apprehensive...\"\n\nIntuitive Robotics CEO Dor Skular created her specifically for older adults to help manage their health, and wellness and connect to loved ones.\n\n\"There's an algorithm that tries to get a reward and it gets a reward when the user completes things that are part of healthy aging. For example, if they hydrate,\" said Skular.\n\nReviews are so strong that cities like Pembroke Pines and Lauderhill are pushing to get more robots for seniors in their communities.\n\n\"People reported back that she was bringing them joy. I mean, she's telling some jokes. She's responding to them. They wake up in the morning, she asks them how they are. She'll remind them to drink their glass of water. So, she's caring about them for them,\" said Mather-Taylor.\n\nTwo years later, seniors like Rose are getting free, AI robots that make and take video calls.\n\nWith all of the concerns about AI, should seniors and their families be worried?\n\n\"We would not be offering it unless we felt comfortable that they did have those safety guards in place,\" said Mather-Taylor.\n\n\"Is this device unhackable? There's no such thing as an unhackable device. It's always a war between defender and attacker,\" said Skular.\n\n\"Random people, fraudsters etcetera, can never call into the robot because they need to be added by the older adult as a contact for them to be able to open up the calling features.\"\n\nWhat is the next step with the robots?\n\nThey only speak English. South Florida has plenty of seniors who do not. Developers are working on a Spanish robot.\n\nIn the future, developers also see it being able to order medicines for seniors. Much sooner though, developers expect to further integrate the robots with senior health care providers. They are working on ways of opening new avenues to communicate health info about seniors to loved ones, provided the senior signs off on it.\n\nHow long can this program last?\n\nState, federal funds will last two years. After that, the agency has to find other grants to cover the $89 a month per person fee.\u00a0\n\nCurrently, data from robots and users is being collected to quantify success. The company insists it will not sell any of the information it gathers.\u00a0\n\nView CBS News In\nCBS News App Open\nChrome Safari Continue\nBe the first to know\nGet browser notifications for breaking news, live events, and exclusive reporting.","url":"https://www.cbsnews.com/miami/news/high-tech-companions-help-fight-loneliness-epidemic-among-south-florida-seniors/"}}}
