pace of climate warming during this period was a critical factor, as mammoths were unable to adapt quickly enough to the drastic changes in their landscapes and food sources."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":100.0},"text":"Researchers have demonstrated that changes in rainfall patterns directly influenced vegetation, further impacting the survival of mammoth populations."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":100.0},"text":"The retreat of glaciers at the end of the Pleistocene, approximately 12,000 years ago, led to the formation of rivers, lakes, and marshes, which decreased the volume of vegetation capable of sustaining mammoth populations."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":100.0},"text":"As the climate warmed, mammoth pastures were replaced by trees and swamp plants, leading to a reduction in their primary food sources."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":100.0},"text":"An international team of researchers concluded that sharp climate changes, rather than human activity, were the primary drivers of mammoth extinction in Siberia."},{"citations":{"074b2976-a44d-4f0e-a2e7-dbdf8e0f8b07_764530440":100.0},"text":"Human hunting has also been implicated as a contributing factor to the extinction of woolly mammoths, with evidence suggesting that early humans relied on mammoths for meat, hides, and bones."},{"citations":{"d0fdd296-9dbe-4774-a00b-b9fe01772cb1_668789018":100.0},"text":"The Berelekh 'mammoth graveyard' in Siberia contains thousands of disarticulated mammoth bones, along with evidence of human activity such as hearths and worked mammoth tusks."},{"citations":{"d0fdd296-9dbe-4774-a00b-b9fe01772cb1_668789018":100.0},"text":"Researchers propose that the mass accumulation of mammoth bones at Berelekh was likely caused by human predation and scavenging, as there is no evidence of natural processes leading to such deposits."},{"citations":{"0e0119f8-