018":100.0},"text":"Woolly mammoths experienced population expansion during the Pleistocene but dwindled to isolated populations in Siberia and Alaska as the climate changed."},{"citations":{"c1e6db3c-0326-4e04-a106-0a4c7aad96bb_386798691":100.0},"text":"Genetic studies of Wrangel Island mammoths suggest that inbreeding was not the primary cause of their extinction, as natural selection purged highly deleterious mutations."},{"citations":{"c1e6db3c-0326-4e04-a106-0a4c7aad96bb_386798691":100.0},"text":"The Wrangel Island mammoth population, which started with fewer than 10 individuals, grew to 200-300 over 6,000 years, demonstrating resilience despite genetic challenges."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":100.0},"text":"Over time, mammoth populations and genetic diversity became smaller, making their survival increasingly difficult in the face of environmental and anthropogenic pressures."},{"citations":{"c1e6db3c-0326-4e04-a106-0a4c7aad96bb_386798691":100.0},"text":"Rising sea levels approximately 10,000 years ago isolated the last population of woolly mammoths on Wrangel Island from the Siberian mainland."},{"citations":{"c1e6db3c-0326-4e04-a106-0a4c7aad96bb_386798691":100.0},"text":"Possible causes of extinction for Wrangel Island mammoths include disease outbreaks, tundra fires, or short-term climatic perturbations that disrupted plant growth."},{"citations":{"c1e6db3c-0326-4e04-a106-0a4c7aad96bb_386798691":100.0},"text":"The study of Wrangel Island mammoths has provided insights for modern conservation efforts, such as the importance of maintaining genetic diversity in isolated populations."},{"citations":{"13ea93b3-b90a-433c-83f5-d01dbdf2cf08_453229130":100.0},"text":"A study of a mammoth tusk revealed that the animal traveled approximately 70,000 kilometers over its lifetime, highlighting their high degree of mobility."},{"citations":{"13ea93b3-b90a-433c-83f5-d01dbdf2cf08_453229130":100.0},"text":"This mobility may have been part 