cessing of specific waste types while adhering to strict environmental standards."},{"citations":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":100.0},"text":"Organic waste in Finland is composted in isolated containers to prevent environmental pollution and odor issues."},{"citations":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":100.0},"text":"The Vantaa incineration plant, operated by Vantaan Energia, processes unsorted waste and generates 920 gigawatt hours of district heating and 600 gigawatt hours of electricity annually."},{"citations":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":100.0},"text":"The plant uses advanced German technology to minimize harmful emissions and reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 20% compared to traditional fossil fuel plants."},{"citations":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":100.0},"text":"Finland's waste management reform benefited from learning from other countries' experiences, allowing it to avoid common mistakes and adopt best practices."},{"citations":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":100.0},"text":"Energy companies in Finland actively participate in waste recycling, treating waste as a strategic resource for energy production."},{"citations":{"1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3_1071516282":100.0},"text":"Almost all Finnish citizens participate in sorting garbage, contributing to a 99% recycling rate for household waste."},{"citations":{"1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3_1071516282":100.0},"text":"Finland's success in waste management is attributed to the interaction of central and local authorities and the awareness of citizens."}],"references":["7f0f2b83-6e1c-45a2-be49-8b6ff632880f_215947951","47749b30-d2a2-4bf4-a08c-0c4e10834605_126855345","e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268","56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552","1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3_1071516282"],"documents":{"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552":{"id":"56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071_200811552","text":"Finland is the European leader in municipal solid waste recycling\nToday, 11: 56 AM\nPhoto: vantaanenergia.fi\nIt took a little more than 20 years for Finland to almost completely abandon the landfill of solid municipal waste.\nAt the same time, giant landfills, even if they are closed, are not reclaimed here, in the Russian sense of the word, but turned into a source of income.\nCurrently, 99% of the country \u2019 s garbage is sorted and recycled.\nOnly 1% of the total amount of MSW produced has a chance to end up in a landfill.\nOne of the largest closed landfills is located in the satellite city of Helsinki \u2013 Espoo.\nIts area is comparable to 280 football fields and is almost 200 hectares.\nIt is not surprising that after the closure, an industrial center was formed on its territory, in which enterprises for the generation of electricity and heat from landfill gas, as well as enterprises engaged in the processing of certain types of secondary raw materials (waste paper and glass) are concentrated.\nIn Ekpoo is the headquarters of the famous Finnish energy company Fortum.\nIt occupies a special place in the circular economy of waste.\nIn particular, it is engaged in the processing of plastic.\nUp to 95% of the plastic in the waste generated by the Finns goes to its plant in another satellite city of Helsinki, Riihim\u00e4ki.\nHere, in automated production, plastic is sorted, cleaned, crushed and granulated.\nAccording to experts, about 22 percent of all plastic waste is recycled in Finland.\nThe maximum percentage of plastic that can be recycled reaches about 80 percent, and they are striving to come to this figure in the coming years.\nNon-recyclable plastic waste enters the furnace, where during combustion, heat is released, which, thanks to turbines and a water heating system, becomes electricity and hot water.\nContainers without garbage trucks and five containers on chips\nOne often hears the astonished stories of relatives and friends living in St. Petersburg about how separate garbage collection is organized in Helsinki.\nVisiting the Finnish capital in recent years has not been difficult.\nOf course, a simple tourist is not up to landfills and thoughts about where and who takes waste, but there is something that will not remain without the attention of travelers.\nA resident of St. Petersburg, Alexander often went on business trips to the capital of Finland, Helsinki.\nHe says that in some neighborhoods of the city there are containers that are not serviced by garbage trucks.\nOur company for business trips often rented apartments, garbage from them had to be taken out by yourself.\nYou know, it is very unusual, not only to sort waste into five types (biomass, paper, mixed waste, cardboard and plastic), how much to understand that the containers are equipped with sensors that, when filled, report this to the waste control panel and the garbage is pumped out of the container via a pneumatic pipe, immediately getting to the recycling point.\nNot everyone has access to such containers, but only residents of the microdistrict, since a special key-chip is needed to open it, - Alexander.\nSuch a waste sorting and collection system has been developed and implemented by the Finnish company Marimatic.\nThe technology is called MetroTaifun.\nSo far, it is only available in one suburb of the capital.\nAs its developers write, the entire system is automated, from each container its own pneumatic pipe delivers waste directly to the plant, where when raw materials arrive, its processing begins (additional sorting, grinding, pressing, etc.).\nPerhaps, this will look like in the future the treatment of municipal waste in large megacities.\nIt's tomorrow's business.\nWhat's today?\nLarge metropolis surrounded by recycling facilities\nThe peculiarity of the \u201cgarbage reform \u201d in Finland is that the country started it later than other European countries, so it could take advantage of other people \u2019 s experience and avoid mistakes.\nThe main thing on which the bet was made was to find ways to prevent waste from reaching landfills.\nTo do this, a separate collection of waste was introduced, which captured not only container sites and households, but also stores, as well as the manufacturers of goods themselves.\nIn cities, waste-free fast food and restaurants are not uncommon, hundreds of entrepreneurs find new niches for the use of secondary resources (for example, they produce fabrics from threads of previously used things), open second-hand and much more.\nIn almost every shopping center there are vending machines for receiving containers.\nAround Helsinki, in its cities satellites built a network of sorting stations.\nThey specialize in certain types of waste.\nAll stations are located almost within the city limits.\nOrganic waste, which is usually the source of the garbage smell, is immediately taken to the plant for composting.\nThe whole process here is automated and produced in containers isolated from the environment.\nResidents of neighboring high-rise buildings do not even think about what kind of object for sorting, recycling or recycling is located nearby.\nThe strict sanitary and environmental standards adopted in the country do not give any chance for environmental pollution.\nUnsorted waste and so-called \"tails\" in the metropolitan area are taken to the incinerator in Vantaa.\nThere, the first incineration line was launched in 2014, the second in 2020.\nThe construction was not cheap - 300 million euros.\nThe plant is operated by Vantaan Energia.\nEvery day it receives up to 150 tons of waste.\nAccording to the company on the website, the plant can burn up to 400 cubic meters of waste per second.\nEvery five seconds, he burns the annual volume of garbage produced by a Finnish family of three.\nThe German technology known as the D\u00fcsseldorf System is used here: the combustion temperature is about 1000 degrees Celsius, from the waste receiving bin it enters the rolls, where it is crushed and gradually lowered into the combustion chamber.\nThus, the filtration system eliminates harmful emissions.\nEvery year about 700 tons of various materials, mostly heavy metals, are extracted from flue gases and disposed of by Ekokem in Riihim\u00e4ki (another suburb of Helsenki).\nSlag is exported to the Emmassuo landfill, and gravel bottom slag is used in earthworks.\nNow the company is testing a technology that allows the use of the ash formed.\nThe main difference from the German analogue - ignition is made by gas, not fuel oil.\nThe plant has built a bunker that allows you to store waste in reserve so that the technological process does not stop.\nAfter all, the incinerator is also a thermal power plant, which produces 920 gigawatt hours of district heating per year, which is almost half of the needs of the city of Vantaa, and 600 gigawatt hours of electricity, which is 30% of the needs of Vantaa per year.\nAccording to environmentalists, such production is more economical refers to resources, since fossil fuels are practically not used here.\nThe combined effect of producing such a volume of heat and electricity allows us to talk about a reduction in carbon dioxide emissions by 20%, compared with the fact that the TPP operated on traditional fuels.\nThe reasons for this success were commented by the co-chairman of the Green Shield environmental society, editor-in-chief of the Ural Meridian news agency Alexander Anikin.\nThe main distinguishing feature of Finnish reform is the correct emphasis.\nGarbage was immediately considered as a source of energy.\nTherefore, energy companies have joined the recycling process, which are used to being responsible for both the quality of services and environmental friendliness.\nThe tasks were immediately global - to sort and return to circulation secondary resources, as well as to prevent the simple storage of waste at landfills.\nIt is this approach that radically changed the industry, making it strategic from purely communal.\nInnovation and technology can and should be adopted, as our northern neighbor does.\nIt \u2019 s also a lesson we need to learn.\nSign up now","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0026.json.gz:127783","uncompressed_offset":200811552,"url":"tagilcity.ru/news/2022-09-06/finlyandiya-evropeyskiy-lider-v-pererabotke-tverdyh-kommunalnyh-othodov-1259709","warc_date":"2022-09-06T08:44:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:56adfbca-a2b9-402a-8105-b7e282865071>","warc_url":"https://tagilcity.ru/news/2022-09-06/finlyandiya-evropeyskiy-lider-v-pererabotke-tverdyh-kommunalnyh-othodov-1259709"},"created":"2022-09-06T08:57:39.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3_1071516282":{"id":"1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3_1071516282","text":"Ukraine will deepen cooperation with Finland in the direction of household waste management.\nAccording to the press service of the Ministry of Regional Development, this was announced by the Minister of Communities and Territories Alexey Chernyshov during a meeting with the Ambassador of the Republic of Finland to Ukraine P\u00e4ivi Laine.\nIt is noted that in Finland, only 1% of waste ends up in landfills, the vast majority is recycled.\nThis is the result of the interaction of the central and local authorities, as well as the awareness of citizens\nUkraine is also planning to adopt this experience.\n\u201cFinland is a country that demonstrates high standards of environmental waste management.\nAlmost all the citizens of this country sort the garbage.\nAs a result, 99% of household waste is recycled.\nThis experience will be useful for Ukraine.\nSo, a similar process is already underway in hromadas - in 1725 settlements of our state, a separate collection of household waste has been introduced.\nBut it is necessary to scale this direction and introduce useful practices of international partners in the country, \"Chernyshov said.\nRead alsoIn the Odessa region on the Danube, the dam is destroyed - under it meter voids In the press service reminded that thanks to the implementation of separate collection of garbage in 2020, about 6.3% of household waste was recycled and disposed of in Ukraine.\nIn turn, Laine noted that Finland is ready to share experience and help Ukrainian communities to implement waste processing projects.\n\u201cWe also have companies that recycle waste into energy.\nIn such a comprehensive way, we improve the ecology of our country, \u201d she added.\nWaste recycling in Ukraine\nAs UNIAN reported, in July 2020, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted in the first reading the draft law No. 2207-1-d \u201cOn waste management \u201d.\nThe document establishes the procedure for the collection, removal and treatment of waste, ensures the introduction of their separate collection and recycling, provides for the requirements for the quality of the provision of waste management services and the charging of fees for such a service.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0034.json.gz:51155","uncompressed_offset":1071516282,"url":"www.unian.net/ecology/ukraina-i-finlyandiya-budut-sotrudnichat-v-sfere-pererabotki-bytovyh-othodov-11619481.html","warc_date":"2021-11-23T22:37:12.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:1d3e986d-cbde-4b2c-b555-bbeb731eece3>","warc_url":"https://www.unian.net/ecology/ukraina-i-finlyandiya-budut-sotrudnichat-v-sfere-pererabotki-bytovyh-othodov-11619481.html"},"created":"2021-11-23T23:40:11.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":{"id":"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268","text":"Hong Kong \u2019 s slow progress in environmental governance \u2013 why not look at the Greater Bay Area and the world?\nAuthor: Liu Mengting\nPublished: Updated:\nIn 2005, the SAR Government proposed to develop a recycling economy, that is, to reduce the environmental burden by repairing, recycling and extending the service life of materials, to find a way out for recycling recyclable materials, and to promote the development of related industries and promote economic diversification.\nHowever, more than a decade later, Hong Kong \u2019 s circular economy has not made much progress.\nIn this regard, some scholars suggest leveraging the advantages of the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area.\nAt the same time, Hong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy is not yet climate, and we must match the experience of \u201ctop students \u201d such as Korea, Taiwan and Singapore.\nCircular Economy Enemies the Greater Bay Area\nProfessor Patrick Poon, Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, The Hong Kong Polytechnic University, has been developing a patented technology for converting waste glass into environmentally friendly bricks since the 1990s, with a view to improving the recycling efficiency of waste glass.\nGreen brick is a kind of concrete brick, can effectively use construction waste and waste glass, the third generation of green brick has been put into the market as paving brick.\nFor more than 20 years, the technology has been optimized by scholars to the fifth generation, but it is still \u201ctechnology without market \u201d.\nIn an interview with \"Hong Kong 01\" recently, Poon mentioned the two main reasons why the development of the local green brick industry is hindered, which is also the dilemma faced by Hong Kong's circular economy.\nPan Chih-sheng says that the research on green bricks has been successful, but the price is not competitive. (photo by O'Cara)\nOne of the main reasons is that local manufacturing has caused the high enterprise products to lose market advantage. Poon analysis, because the whole production process of environmentally friendly bricks produced in Hong Kong is completed in Hong Kong, and the land price and labor in Hong Kong are very high, and the price has also risen with the water. It is necessary to open up the market to achieve maximum trade liberalization, so the possibility of contractors choosing Hong Kong materials for profit considerations is very low.\nOn the other hand, the Hong Kong government has not introduced relevant policies to require the actual use of environmentally friendly materials, in the absence of just the premise, the market share of environmentally friendly bricks is unstable, and the current use of the third generation of environmentally friendly bricks is about 20% more expensive than natural sand bricks, so the project side may not consider the use of environmentally friendly bricks.\nAnother major obstacle is that the government did not help. Pan Zhisheng pointed out that environmental protection bricks are made of recycled materials, although the quality and performance of the bricks are not lost to natural sand and stone, but the quality difference is greater.\nHowever, according to the existing government regulations, the two are regarded as the same, that is, the quality of environmentally friendly materials is too high, but it may still be regarded as unqualified due to the degree of quality difference. This single regulation is a constraint for the application of environmentally friendly bricks. If the outlook does not improve, it will be more difficult to attract investors.\nUnder such a vicious cycle, the government has no intention to invest or give support, and the environmental protection brick industry chain has become a dead end.\nThe recycling rate of local waste in Hong Kong is low, and exports are facing many restrictions.\nIn an interview with Hong Kong 01, Wong Woon-chung, director of the Johan Centre for Applied Forestry Research in the Pearl River Delta (PRD), Hong Kong Baptist University, pointed out that the land resources in Hong Kong are tight, such as the opening of a recycling plant for recycled materials will double the cost.\nMr Wong stressed that the circular economy requires complementary advantages from different regions. There is no way out if the development vision is limited to Hong Kong. (photo by Mr Cheng Tze-feng)\nWaste management in Hong Kong is inefficient and should be seen around the world\nSouth Korea, Singapore and Taiwan implemented waste levies in 1995, 1996 and 2000 respectively. Since then, they have gradually developed comprehensive and mature environmental policies with local characteristics.\nHong Kong's waste management system has been fragmented for many years, and it is time to look at the world and learn from advanced experience and thinking.\nHong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy has not been good for many years, and the climate should be on par with other regions. (Photo by Tsai Cheng-pong)\nKorea has introduced waste utilization measures in a multi-pronged manner to achieve long-term management, so the Korean waste management system is at the forefront of Asia.\nFor example, the city of Seoul, which has achieved the most remarkable results, introduced a series of supporting measures in a few years to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste and living habits after the implementation of the garbage levy system in 1995.\nIn contrast, the Hong Kong Government is always \"discussing\" with the industry and \"considering\" the initiatives of environmental protection groups.\nTaiwan is also a leader in waste management in Asia.\nThe Taiwan government sent a special cleaning team to collect household waste from residents using two types of recycling trucks \u2013 yellow garbage trucks are used to collect general waste from residents using official garbage bags, and white garbage trucks are used to collect raw and cooked food waste, plastic and other recyclable resources.\nAs early as 1997, the Taiwan Environmental Protection Agency launched the \"Resource Recovery 4-in-1 Program\", which fully mobilized the role of the government, manufacturers, consumers and licensed recycling enterprises in waste management, not only to skillfully distribute the financial costs, but also to reflect the principle of impartiality.\nSingapore has a small population, similar to Hong Kong, but the waste recycling work is more professional and centralized.\nIn Singapore, three waste management enterprises are licensed by the National Environment Agency (NEA) to provide waste collection and recycling services to residents in different parts of the country. The waste is meticulously classified into paper, plastic, glass and metal, and the garden waste is collected separately.\nIn the recycling process, incineration plants reduce the volume of waste by 90%, and then use 3% of non-incineration and non-recyclable waste to landfill to reduce the environmental burden.\nAccording to statistics, Singapore \u2019 s solid waste recycling rate reached 51.7% in 2020, a model that Hong Kong can learn from.\nAs for the administrative efficiency of the Mainland, it is also worth reflecting on the Hong Kong government. In July 2019, Shanghai implemented what has been described as the \u201cworld \u2019 s most stringent \u201d waste separation measure.\nFirst of all, its domestic waste is strictly divided into four categories, namely recyclables, hazardous waste, wet waste and dry waste; secondly, if individuals or units do not dispose of garbage in accordance with the classification, they will be punished with severe high fines.\nUnder the mandatory implementation of the government, Shanghai residents have achieved good environmental protection results after experiencing \"pain\".\nThe Garbage Levy Ordinance has already been introduced, but the Government must not be complacent about it, but must think about how to tie in with the Ordinance in the next step, and adopt a systematic and comprehensive thinking to achieve long-term waste management.\nLeave a comment...","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0029.json.gz:3319","uncompressed_offset":233172268,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C","warc_date":"2021-10-07T10:31:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C"},"created":"2021-10-07T10:41:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"47749b30-d2a2-4bf4-a08c-0c4e10834605_126855345":{"id":"47749b30-d2a2-4bf4-a08c-0c4e10834605_126855345","text":"Bauhinia Party \uff5c The Dilemma and Countermeasures of Hong Kong \u2019 s Waste Management System\nAuthor: 01 Forum\nPublished: Updated:\nAuthor \uff1a Shi Lei\nThe author believes that many of the current garbage collection disputes have been implemented to the feasibility level, in fact, are related to the inadequacy of the behavior system of residential areas to place garbage, and some of the shortcomings have not been collected garbage bags to make up for.\nIts shortcomings mainly include: almost all residents of the garbage can be carried out 24 hours (such as a fixed garbage room and a long \"business hours\"), each residents of the garbage room often let the residents put garbage into (super) large garbage bins, and each garbage room corresponding to the number of residents, resulting in if there is a \"black sheep\" do not buy a levy garbage bag to throw garbage, they can walk without obstruction.\nProperty companies or FEHD contractors may have to wait for a long time before they find a \"bad horse\" in the process of comprehensive garbage disposal, but at this time it is difficult to claim responsibility, which leads to the \"polluter pays\" principle in fact is empty words.\nThe recent Jordan fire has also reminded all walks of life in Hong Kong that there are a large number of \"trivial\" old tenements in the most prosperous city center in Hong Kong, with chaotic personnel, lack of property services, and unethical behavior, resulting in a large number of public safety risks.\nIn these places, even property fees are difficult to ensure that the tenants pay in full, and how can the executive power to ensure the implementation of the levy garbage bag system? If the measures to effectively and timely remove the \"black sheep\" from the institutional level can not be designed, and the implementation level will be discounted for various \"objective reasons\", then it will form the behavior of \"bad money driven away from good money\".\nSoon, no one will follow the requirements of the levy garbage bag system to do, and the criticism is rife, may the next government will abolish the annoying garbage collection system as a \"moral government\".\nRefer to the garbage disposal policies of representative regions of the world, you can see that their garbage classification, collection of garbage bags and other systems are \"devil in the details\", often in the geographical environment, the unwritten rules of behavior in the residential community, and institutional protection, etc., to ensure that timely detection, isolation and failure to classify, pack and dispose of garbage according to the system requirements, and minimize the possibility of \"black sheep\".\nFor example, in the European Union, Belgium, where I lived, they have long promoted charging garbage bags.\nSimilar to Japan, Korea and Taiwan, residents have a fixed time to throw garbage (usually early in the morning on certain days), and garbage bags containing garbage should be placed in designated places.\nIt can be imagined that there is no requirement for garbage bags to be filled with garbage, but the specified bags are filled with garbage that should not be loaded or excessive garbage will be rejected.\nThe main way of living in the city of Leuven, where the author was at the time, was a single building or an apartment building (but the floor is usually no more than 10 floors, and the residents do not exceed 50 households). Once the garbage bags are found to be not in compliance with the regulations, whether it is the city government or the apartment manager, the difficulty of tracing is not great, and the surrounding residents will actively cooperate.\nFor example, Japan, Korea and Taiwan are using garbage levies to regulate the classification of citizens and reduce waste. The above areas must use the volume charge, through the use of garbage charging plastic bags to implement polluter pays.\nIn addition to requiring residents to place garbage (in the correct bag) in the designated location at the specified time, Japanese and Korean garbage bags are more meticulous in sorting.\nFor example, Japan, which is more familiar to Hong Kong people, requires transparent bags (not limited to specific models but must be transparent, can be tied) to quickly confirm that the garbage classification is correct, and the bag is combustible garbage, plastic, metal cans, etc., or non-recyclable and non-combustible waste.\nRecyclable waste paper, etc., does not need to buy a separate garbage bag, but needs to be properly wrapped. Although Japan has a much higher density of living than EU countries, neighbors will pay more attention to not sorting garbage and will not delay the action.\nSouth Korea's recycling rate is also more than 50%, the main reason is the strict classification of garbage bags, different from a kind of paid garbage bags in Hong Kong, South Korea is a variety of paid garbage bags, and each garbage bag can only contain one kind of material, and according to the difficulty of recycling to determine the price of garbage bags, the more difficult the recovery, the higher the price of garbage bags.\nAs a result, South Korea \u2019 s recovery rate is higher.\nAs for the Taiwan region, in addition to adopting a regular garbage collection mode similar to Japan, in the area where there are no conditions to set up a garbage room, there is a garbage truck and recycling truck every night, and the song of the snow truck comes to the small area.\nThis requirement is even higher, and residents need to actively show up at a specific time, so recycling workers can more accurately and timely eliminate the \"black sheep\" that do not pack garbage according to regulations, and therefore refuse to accept or take other measures.\nIt is worth pointing out that I have only visited Japan, Korea and Taiwan on short trips, and only stayed in commercial hotels.\nTherefore, details such as the garbage system in residential areas are indirectly obtained through online KOL sharing, live scene dramas and other channels.\nPlease note that there are errors.\nFrom this, it can be seen that the problems existing in Hong Kong's current waste management system and the waste management experience of advanced regions abroad have produced the following suggestions that deserve serious consideration and reference by the Hong Kong Government and relevant departments:\n1. Improve the behavior system of residents throwing garbage.\nFirst of all, the public garbage room and the garbage disposal place in the residential area should no longer be allowed to throw garbage 7x24 hours.\nTo consider formulating standards, such as limited delivery time and designated delivery points, for the reference of the entire Hong Kong property management industry, the FEHD will implement them to prevent the \"black sheep\" from evading garbage bag charges.\n2. Strengthen the management of \"no matter\" areas, standardize the premises and methods of refuse collection in areas where property services are lacking, and ensure that the refuse charging system can be effectively implemented even in these problem areas.\n3, with reference to the practices of Japan, Korea, Taiwan and other places, after the successful implementation of the garbage collection system, it continues to optimize, the implementation of more detailed garbage classification management, according to different materials and recycling difficulties to carry out differentiated charges.\nThis will increase the willingness of the environmental protection industry to handle high-difficulty waste, while increasing the residents \u2019 enthusiasm for sorting and waste reduction.\nCritics may think that the institutional construction of these areas requires a long period of time and a large amount of resources to invest, and may not be able to be directly replicated in the real environment of Hong Kong.\nMoreover, the improvement of the relevant system requires no small investment of resources.\nPerhaps this is precisely the original intention of the SAR Government to levy a \"short and fast\" garbage levy.\nHowever, it is already clear that the \"short and fast\" has only attracted doubts, and even if it is forced to push forward, it will also be at the expense of the government's recognition.\nMoreover, the \"black sheep\" can not be effectively eradicated in a timely manner, which will inevitably make the garbage collection system become \"half suspended\". Only a few able and willing citizens are willing to do so (such as cooperating with \"green in the area\", and working hard even in the hot sun at the recycling point to deliver their own recyclable plastic waste to the recycling point of respectable citizens). Go your own way, the system cost has been paid a lot, and the problem to be solved by the garbage levy is still the same.\nNo matter what kind of solution is adopted, the government will need some time to refine the design of the refuse collection system and promote it more vigorously.\nThe implementation of the principle of garbage collection in the European Union, Japan and Korea, and Taiwan is not completed in three or two months.\nGarbage collection needs the long-term cooperation of residents, change the long-term behavior habits can be completed in a few months?\nHow can this be called good governance and good governance? If you cook for the government, you can't be anxious and work hard for the government for a long time, you can only make a well-intentioned system truly have the positive meaning it should have.\nThe author is a researcher at the Bauhinia Institute for Policy Studies.\nThe article is only the opinion of the author and does not represent the position of Hong Kong 01.\nPlease email us at 01view @ hk01.com.\nPlease attach the author \u2019 s real name and contact details.\nIf not applicable, no notice will be given.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0010.json.gz:8621","uncompressed_offset":126855345,"url":"www.hk01.com/01%E8%AB%96%E5%A3%87/1010622/%E7%B4%AB%E8%8D%8A%E9%BB%A8-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E5%9E%83%E5%9C%BE%E7%AE%A1%E7%90%86%E5%88%B6%E5%BA%A6%E7%9A%84%E5%9B%B0%E5%A2%83%E8%88%87%E5%B0%8D%E7%AD%96","warc_date":"2024-04-17T00:47:45.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:47749b30-d2a2-4bf4-a08c-0c4e10834605>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/01%E8%AB%96%E5%A3%87/1010622/%E7%B4%AB%E8%8D%8A%E9%BB%A8-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E5%9E%83%E5%9C%BE%E7%AE%A1%E7%90%86%E5%88%B6%E5%BA%A6%E7%9A%84%E5%9B%B0%E5%A2%83%E8%88%87%E5%B0%8D%E7%AD%96"},"created":"2024-04-17T00:44:22.000Z","lang":"eng"},"7f0f2b83-6e1c-45a2-be49-8b6ff632880f_215947951":{"id":"7f0f2b83-6e1c-45a2-be49-8b6ff632880f_215947951","text":"Producer Responsibility System Waste Reduction Policy Package in Place\nComments \u2027 World Situation 2022 / 08 / 06\nShare:\nShare:\nOn average, more than 5 million plastic beverage bottles are disposed of in landfills in Hong Kong every day, reflecting the poor results of plastic reduction and recycling.\nUnder the long-term initiative of environmental organizations such as Green Earth, the environmental protection department is preparing to introduce relevant producer responsibility schemes (PRS) to respond.\nIn simple terms, PRS usually uses financial means, such as bottle fees and glass bottle levies, to induce \"producers\" such as manufacturers, retailers and even consumers to shoulder their due environmental responsibility.\nEffective laws and regulations are indispensable to improve the industrial chain\nPRS This waste management regulation is slightly different from the common pollution control regulations. To promote source waste reduction and recycling, effective regulations and the support of the entire recycling industry chain are indispensable.\nFirst, the recycling industry chain, which includes high-coverage front-line collection points, large and small transport fleets, adequate recycling and recycling plants, a market for valuable recycled materials, and PRS system managers.\nTo promote the formation and effectiveness of the recycling industry chain, we must first have \"smart\" regulations, in which the setting of ambitious recycling targets, attractive economic incentives (such as refunds by bottle or bottle), and a reward and punishment mechanism for manufacturers are all key elements.\nFor example, the EPD recently proposed that each plastic bottle should be given a refund of at least one dime, hoping to achieve a recovery rate of 40% in the first year and 75% in five years.\nIs there a \u201ctooth \u201d for this purpose?\nHong Kong 's plastic recycling performance is poor PRS International\nGreen Earth analyzed a number of countries and regions that use PRS to manage beverage containers, and concluded that the average refund amount for each plastic bottle is more than HK $1, which is 10 times less than the corner of Hong Kong.\nAs for the average recovery rate target for the first year of PRS, the international average is above 70%, of which 80% in South Korea in Asia and 90% in the three Nordic countries are high; even if the target is lower, Lithuania and Slovakia are also 55% and 60% respectively, which are much more positive than Hong Kong's 40%.\nThe reason why PRS is called producer responsibility, the key word is the word \"producer\", which means that this stakeholder is responsible.\nI would like to remind the environmental protection department that the recycling responsibilities of manufacturers and importers must not be missed.\nThe most direct approach is to set up an adequate reward and punishment mechanism to ensure that if the manufacturer fails to meet the recycling target, it must bear the responsibility, so that it can be matched with the \"responsibility system\".\nSet up incentive mechanism to encourage manufacturers to respond positively\nSouth Korea, a model student of high plastic bottle recycling, has adopted the Pigouvian Tax: if the market fails to meet the 80% recycling target, producers, importers and PRS system administrators have to pay the corresponding punitive tax on a proportional basis.\nThe author also believes that, in fairness, if the recycling rate exceeds the target, or the market adopts a considerable plastic reduction package (such as naked buy, reuse container sales), there should be corresponding incentives to promote the positive response of manufacturers and create a source of plastic reduction culture.\nAt a time when the Government has not yet submitted the PRS Bill to the Legislative Council, the Legislative Council (especially the Panel on Environmental Affairs) has the responsibility to monitor the quality of the policy and request the Administration to respond positively to the following key points:\n1. Disclose the results of the EPD \u2019 s 2021 plastic bottle public consultation, including supporting the proportion of different refund amounts;\n2. Keep up with the international standard, the minimum refund amount should start at HK $1;\nThird, update the recovery rate target: 70% in the first year of policy implementation, and increase to 90% in three years;\nFourth, set up a review mechanism: if the recycling target is not reached within the deadline, then increase the legal minimum amount of refunded bottles, increase the economic incentive; at the same time, compared with the Piguet tax, manufacturers, importers, PRS system managers must be jointly responsible for the failure to meet the target.\nAuthor: Liu Zhaolang Senior Project Director, Green Earth\nColumn name: GREEN FORUM\nFollow the latest financial news analysis, like hket Facebook","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0023.json.gz:22963","uncompressed_offset":215947951,"url":"paper.hket.com/article/3321071/%E7%94%9F%E7%94%A2%E8%80%85%E8%B2%AC%E4%BB%BB%E5%88%B6%E6%B8%9B%E5%BB%A2%20%E6%94%BF%E7%AD%96%E9%85%8D%E5%A5%97%E9%A0%88%E5%88%B0%E4%BD%8D","warc_date":"2022-08-05T17:44:07.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7f0f2b83-6e1c-45a2-be49-8b6ff632880f>","warc_url":"https://paper.hket.com/article/3321071/%E7%94%9F%E7%94%A2%E8%80%85%E8%B2%AC%E4%BB%BB%E5%88%B6%E6%B8%9B%E5%BB%A2%20%E6%94%BF%E7%AD%96%E9%85%8D%E5%A5%97%E9%A0%88%E5%88%B0%E4%BD%8D"},"created":"2022-08-05T17:54:12.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1091","request_id":"1091","narrative_id":"1091"},"responses":[{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Brittney Griner, a WNBA star and two-time Olympic champion, was arrested in February 2022 at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport after vape cartridges containing cannabis oil were found in her luggage, leading to her detainment and subsequent legal proceedings in Russia."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Griner pleaded guilty to the charges, explaining that she had inadvertently packed the cartridges, but faced a harsh nine-year sentence in a Russian penal colony under a judicial system with no presumption of innocence."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Her arrest occurred during heightened geopolitical tensions amid Russia's invasion of Ukraine, with experts suggesting her high profile made her a valuable political pawn in a larger geopolitical conflict."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"The U.S. government declared Griner 'wrongfully detained' in May 2022, intensifying efforts to negotiate her release, including a proposal for a prisoner swap involving Russian arms dealer Viktor Bout."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, Griner was freed in December 2022 through a one-for-one exchange for Bout, a deal criticized for excluding another detained American, Paul Whelan, and raising concerns about future hostage-taking."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"During her incarceration, Griner endured harsh conditions in a penal colony known for forced labor and limited communication, describing the experience as traumatic and mentally taxing."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Her handwritten letter to President Biden highlighted her fear of spending her life in prison and urged the administration to prioritize her release alongside other detained Americans."},{"citations":{"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":100.0},"text":"Public advocacy played a significant role, with rallies, social media campaigns, and calls to action from figures like Dawn Staley keeping Griner\u2019s case in the spotlight and pressuring officials to act."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Since her return, Griner has been adjusting to life back home, resuming her basketball career and reflecting on her resilience during the ordeal, which has amplified her cultural significance as a trailblazer in sports and gender advocacy."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Brittney Griner, a WNBA star and two-time Olympic champion, was arrested in February 2022 at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport after vape cartridges containing cannabis oil were found in her luggage, leading to her detainment and subsequent legal proceedings in Russia."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Griner pleaded guilty to the charges, explaining that she had inadvertently packed the cartridges, but faced a harsh nine-year sentence in a Russian penal colony under a judicial system with no presumption of innocence."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Her arrest occurred during heightened geopolitical tensions amid Russia's invasion of Ukraine, with experts suggesting her high profile made her a valuable political pawn in a larger geopolitical conflict."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"The U.S. government declared Griner 'wrongfully detained' in May 2022, intensifying efforts to negotiate her release, including a proposal for a prisoner swap involving Russian arms dealer Viktor Bout."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, Griner was freed in December 2022 through a one-for-one exchange for Bout, a deal criticized for excluding another detained American, Paul Whelan, and raising concerns about future hostage-taking."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"During her incarceration, Griner endured harsh conditions in a penal colony known for forced labor and limited communication, describing the experience as traumatic and mentally taxing."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Her handwritten letter to President Biden highlighted her fear of spending her life in prison and urged the administration to prioritize her release alongside other detained Americans."},{"citations":{"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":100.0},"text":"Public advocacy played a significant role, with rallies, social media campaigns, and calls to action from figures like Dawn Staley keeping Griner\u2019s case in the spotlight and pressuring officials to act."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Since her return, Griner has been adjusting to life back home, resuming her basketball career and reflecting on her resilience during the ordeal, which has amplified her cultural significance as a trailblazer in sports and gender advocacy."}],"references":["fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896","72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512","956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289","530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971","027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127","32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841"],"documents":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":{"id":"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841","text":"Categories\nFinance\n\nInside Joe Biden\u2019s Faustian pact with Russia to secure Brittney\n\n\nThree weeks ago, the American basketball star Brittney Griner arrived at a Russian penal colony known for torture, beatings and slave labour to begin a nine-year sentence following her arrest at a Moscow airport in February for possession of vaping cartridges containing hashish oil.\n\nBut in a stunning twist on Thursday, Griner\u2019s plight as an unwitting pawn in a high-stakes geopolitical struggle came to an abrupt end, as she arrived in Abu Dhabi from Moscow and boarded a plane home to reunite with her family. She landed in San Antonio, Texas, early Friday morning.\n\nIn exchange for Griner\u2019s release, the US released Viktor Bout, a notorious arms trafficker who was serving a 25-year sentence for conspiring to kill US citizens and aiding a terrorist organisation.\n\nThe deal was met with jubilation from Griner\u2019s family and supporters. But the controversial swap for Bout \u2014 as well as the exclusion of Paul Whelan, another US citizen imprisoned in Russia \u2014 also drew criticism and raised questions about how America\u2019s adversaries might leverage arrests of its citizens in the future.\n\nUS officials began working toward Griner\u2019s release as soon as she was apprehended in Russia in February, but the effort became more concentrated on prisoner swap negotiations once the State Department declared in May that she had been wrongfully detained.\n\nIn July, US secretary of state Antony Blinken and Russian foreign minister Sergei Lavrov spoke on the phone for the first time since Russia\u2019s full-scale invasion of Ukraine in February. During the call, Blinken pressed Lavrov to accept a \u201csubstantial proposal\u201d from Washington to release Griner and the former marine Whelan, who has been detained in Russia since 2018 on what the US and his family say are trumped-up espionage charges.\n\nAmericans had offered to free Bout, people familiar with the discussions said, but the Russians said they also wanted the release of Vadim Krasikov, a former colonel from Russia\u2019s domestic spy agency who was convicted of murder in Germany last year.\n\nIn the ensuing months, officials said, Washington made a number of offers to Russia in an attempt to secure the release of Griner and Whelan.\n\nHowever, Biden administration officials said that in recent weeks it became clear that Moscow would only accept a one-for-one swap. According to one senior administration official, \u201cthe choice was bringing Brittney Griner home right now or bringing no Americans home from Russia right now\u201d.\n\nDespite the Biden administration\u2019s insistence that they had no choice but to exclude Whelan from the deal, Republican lawmakers and others denounced the decision, as well as facilitating the release of Bout, who is also known as \u201cthe merchant of death\u201d.\n\n\u201cThe Biden administration has allowed Viktor Bout, a dangerous arms dealer who was convicted of conspiring to kill American law enforcement, to walk free,\u201d said Mike Rogers, the top Republican on the House Armed Services Committee.\n\n\u201cThis move to appease Vladimir Putin will only encourage further hostage taking by Russian security forces,\u201d he added.\n\nUS officials described Biden\u2019s choice as a painful one, adding that they would continue to work for Whelan\u2019s release. Washington previously secured the release of Trevor Reed, another former marine, via a prisoner swap in April.\n\nPeople familiar with Thursday\u2019s prisoner exchange likened the episode to \u201ca scene from the Cold War\u201d, with Russian and American planes meeting on the tarmac at an airport in Abu Dhabi.\n\nThe Russian plane carrying Griner arrived first, one of the people said. American officials and people familiar with the events said the basketball star was upbeat on the tarmac, saying she was looking forward to returning home.\n\nThe Griner-Bout swap marks a rare instance in which the US and Russia have been able to find common ground since Putin ordered the full-scale invasion of Ukraine, sending the west\u2019s relationship with Moscow to its lowest ebb since the Cuban missile crisis.\n\nAccording to people familiar with the matter, the Americans and Russians directly negotiated the details of the swaps, with UAE officials including president Sheikh Mohammed bin Zayed al-Nahyan helping to facilitate the mechanics of the transfer.\n\nIt is not unusual for third countries to aid in brokering international diplomatic agreements such as prisoner swaps between hostile countries.\n\nSheikh Mohammed and Putin discussed the matter when they met in Russia in October, and they spoke on the phone on Wednesday, people familiar with the meetings said. Yousef al-Otaiba, UAE ambassador to the US, was present for the exchange on Thursday and had helped to co-ordinate details on the American side.\n\nOn Thursday, some pro-Kremlin commentators hailed the swap as a return to diplomacy. \u201cEveryone sees through this exchange that Moscow and Washington are holding secret negotiations and can make a deal,\u201d Sergei Markov, a political scientist and former member of Russia\u2019s parliament, wrote on Telegram. \u201cAnd everyone hopes that means Moscow and Washington can make a deal to end the war in Ukraine.\u201d\n\nHowever, analysts and US officials said that while the breakthrough was a sign that the two sides could get things done when their interests align, it was not evidence of any larger thaw in relations. Biden administration officials added that the recent conversations with Russia about Griner and other prisoners were limited to the release of wrongfully detained Americans.\n\n\u201cThe exchange doesn\u2019t do anything to change the situation for bilateral relations. There are lots of issues where they are in open confrontation,\u201d said Alexander Gabuev, a senior fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.\n\nHe said the otherwise dire state of relations between Russia and the west was thrown into sharp relief last week, when Moscow abruptly pulled out of talks on renewing the New Start treaty, the only remaining agreement governing the countries\u2019 nuclear arsenals.\n\n\u201cThis is a global stability issue: the last remainders of arms control are falling apart, which could lead to an arms race and a higher risk of dangerous incidents,\u201d he said. \u201cThe trajectory we\u2019re on is making that all the more likely.\u201d\n\n\n\nSource link","url":"https://newslanes.com/2022/12/09/inside-joe-bidens-faustian-pact-with-russia-to-secure-brittney/"},"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":{"id":"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127","text":"Diplomat Sparks Renewed Hope For Brittney Griner Prisoner Exchange\n\nThe situation surrounding Brittney Griner's case is looking a little less bleak, thanks to the recent developments brought about by negotiations between the U.S. and Russia.\n\nIn early November,\u00a0the WNBA star had been transferred to a penal colony in the Russian republic of Mordovia.\u00a0There, she began fulfilling her nine-year sentence for drug possession. As reported by\u00a0Reuters,\u00a0authorities initially arrested Griner in February 2022 after vape cartridges containing cannabis oil were discovered in her luggage\u00a0at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport.\u00a0While she attempted to appeal the ruling, it was ultimately upheld by a Russian court.\n\n\"This has been [a] very traumatic experience, waiting for this day, waiting for the first court, and getting nine years for a crime that I was barely over the significant amount,\"\u00a0she said at the hearing (via CBS News). \"I don't understand the first court's decision to give one year less than the max when I've been here almost 8 months, and people with more severe crimes have gotten less than what I was given... I really hope that the court will adjust this sentence, because it's been very, very stressful and very traumatic to my mental and psyche, being away from my family and not being able to communicate.\" However, there is now renewed hope that Griner could be released, with a Russian diplomat claiming that a swap could happen sometime in the future.\n\nRussian diplomat says there's 'always a chance' for a swap\n\nNot all hope is lost, after all. According to Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergei Ryabkov, Russia is not turning its back on the possibility of a prisoner exchange with the U.S. As reported by the New York Post,\u00a0Ryabkov told reporters that there is \"always a chance\" when asked about the likelihood of a swap taking place before the end of the year. However, he noted that in the past, there had been multiple instances when it seemed as if Russia would agree to a swap, only for the plan to fall apart. If the prisoner swap does take place,\u00a0Ryabkov said it would \"send a positive signal that not everything is hopeless in Russian-American relations.\"\n\nIn the meantime, it looks like Brittney Griner has her work cut out for her. Maria Alyokhina, a former member of the band Pussy Riot, didn't mince words when she spoke to NPR about her own experience at a Russian penal colony.\u00a0\"It has a bit better conditions than [the] original gulag system from the 1950s,\" she said, but added that it's still \"a labor camp.\" She described the grim reality she endured while serving out her own sentence, calling it inhumane. \"For 100 women, there are like three toilets and no hot water,\" she recalled, adding that the penal colony is merely a \"legal slavery system.\"\n\nAccording to a statement released by her lawyers (via BBC), she is trying her best to survive and is \"doing as well as could be expected and trying to stay strong as she adapts to a new environment.\"","url":"https://www.nickiswift.com/1120961/diplomat-sparks-renewed-hope-for-brittney-griner-prisoner-exchange/"},"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":{"id":"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512","text":"The problem is not just what happened to Brittney Griner. The problem is that we don\u2019t know what is happening to Brittney Griner now. The WNBA superstar was allegedly caught with hashish oil in her luggage at a Russian airport and has been in custody for several weeks. For those first couple of weeks, it was as if no one noticed she was missing, no small feat for an athlete who is six foot nine and one of the most recognizable players in the history of the game. She also is also well-known in Russia, where she plays for UMMC Ekaterinburg in the WNBA off season. In 2021 she helped the Russian team win its fifth EuroLeague Women\u2019s championship. (Many WNBA players hoop in Russia during the off-season, as they need to supplement their income, an injustice in and of itself.)\n\nAlmost certainly, instead of creating an immediate public outcry following her arrest, there were efforts behind the scenes to get her out of Russia, which, we know now, was preparing to invade Ukraine. The goal would have been to make this go away without provoking an international incident. Well, it\u2019s too late for that now. There are online petitions and a predictable uproar given the anti-Putin sentiment in the States. Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle Griner, posted a picture of them together on Instagram as the news spread over the weekend. She thanked their fans and then wrote, \u201cI understand that many of you have grown to love BG over the years and have concerns and want details. Please honor our privacy as we continue to work on getting my wife home safely.\u201d\n\nIn other words, delicate negotiations to get Griner home are almost certainly ongoing in a situation that is spiraling. Griner is detained in Russia at a moment when US-Russian relations are at their worst since Ronald Reagan joked, \u201cWe begin bombing in five minutes.\u201d When and how she gets home and how she is being treated right now are anyone\u2019s guess. As basketball writer Tom Ziller put it, \u201cWe don\u2019t have an idea as the public WNBA fandom where Griner is, or how she is doing, or how long she has been detained, or the circumstances of her custody, or what she knows about a timeline for being released, or what she\u2019s being told. We don\u2019t really know anything, and we don\u2019t know whether she or those close to her know anything.\u201d\n\nWhether it started this way or not, we need to understand Griner as a political prisoner. It may have started with airport racial profiling and the idiotic war on cannabis. But now, by the nature of this perilous moment, she has become a chit, a leverage point, in a larger political war.\n\nThe WNBA and Griner\u2019s team, the Phoenix Mercury, are being tight-lipped about the situation\u2014as is the US State Department. But I did reach the coauthor of Griner\u2019s 2014 memoir In My Skin: My Life On and Off the Basketball Court, Sue Hovey. The former ESPN The Magazine executive editor told me: \u201cBrittney Griner is one of the most resilient, mentally tough athletes I\u2019ve ever met. When she led Baylor to a perfect season and the national championship in 2012, she did so while having to endure a torrent of vicious verbal attacks from opposing fans and online trolls. People forget that when she graduated from Baylor in 2013 and publicly came out as gay upon entering the WNBA, that was still a big deal at the time; it wasn\u2019t nearly as common as it is today for athletes to reveal their authentic selves. Brittney was, and continues to be, a trailblazer in eschewing gender norms. Even eight years after her memoir was published, I still get the occasional Twitter message from a college student who read her book in a gender studies class, or just a fan expressing gratitude for Brittney sharing her story. Like many athletes, she has had some stumbles and controversy along the way, but she always takes accountability and shows a willingness to learn and grow. And in an age of curated social media content, there\u2019s something refreshing about a high-profile athlete who gives us that three-dimensional view. She\u2019s relatable and human, and that resonates with people.\u201d\n\nIt is absolutely true that Griner resonates with people, and now many of her fans are up in arms. If the goal was to quietly negotiate Griner\u2019s return, those days are done. At this point, there is really no choice but to shine the brightest possible light on this political injustice and demand that she be sent home. Political prisoners are rarely freed easily. It requires\u2014and demands\u2014an international response. Brittney Griner is a basketball titan who deserves more than to be treated like a pawn.","url":"https://www.thenation.com/article/society/brittney-griner-russia/"},"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":{"id":"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971","text":"Sports\n\nActions\n\nFormer Olympic coach pushes for Brittney Griner's safe return as Russian trial begins\n\nPosted at 5:55 AM, Jul 01, 2022\nand last updated 2022-07-01 09:08:18-04\n\nAs Phoenix Mercury star Brittney Griner\u2019s trial begins in Russia, many are working to keep her story top of mind here in the United States.\n\nABC15 spoke to Griner\u2019s former Olympic coach, Dawn Staley, who\u2019s taken to social media almost daily to try to keep Griner\u2019s case at the forefront.\n\nStaley\u2019s posts are similar: a photo of her shirt she\u2019s wearing that day with a pin that reads, \u201cWe Are BG,\u201d along with a caption numbering the days Griner has been in detainment.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good person. She has a great heart. She is, you know, someone that looks out for the voiceless. She supplies sneakers to the homeless, to the needy, and I don\u2019t think we\u2019re hearing enough about that,\u201d Staley said. \u201cI don\u2019t think we\u2019re hearing enough about what\u2019s been happening to get her released.\u201d\n\nStaley is currently the head women\u2019s basketball coach for the South Carolina Gamecocks, but also helped coach Griner through two gold medals for Team USA.\n\nStaley said she considers Griner and her wife, Cherelle, to be friends of hers. She\u2019s known Griner for about a decade.\n\n\u201cI want Brittney home. I just feel for her family. I feel for her. I feel for our women\u2019s basketball community. I feel for her friends,\u201d Staley said.\n\nIf convicted, the star center could face up to a decade in a Russian prison. She\u2019d then need the United States government to make a prisoner exchange with Russia involving her.\n\nCoach Staley said she hopes people here in America keep the pressure and the attention on BG\u2019s case to bring her home, and every American prisoner being wrongfully detained home as well.\n\n\u201cThey all need to get home to their families,\u201d Staley said. \u201cI just hope that people can find it in their hearts to put good energy into bringing Brittney home.\u201d\n\nStaley encouraged people to call their representatives in Congress, call the White House, and go support the Mercury by going to their games and holding up signs in support of Griner to keep the spotlight on her case.\n\nIt\u2019s notable to say that 99 percent of cases in Russia are convictions.\n\nLast weekend, Secretary of State Antony Blinken told CNN he would not comment in detail on what they\u2019re doing as far as Griner\u2019s situation and other American prisoners wrongfully detained, other than that it is a top priority for the Biden administration.","url":"https://www.abc15.com/sports/former-olympic-coach-pushes-for-brittney-griners-safe-return-as-russian-trial-begins"},"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":{"id":"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289","text":"PHOENIX (AP) \u2014 They shared laughs, smiles, memories. There also were tears, fears, unease.\n\nThrough the range of emotions, one common thread bonded them together: Brittney Griner.\n\nWearing \u201cBG\u201d shirts and holding signs, several hundred fans gathered for a public rally in support of Griner on Wednesday, hoping their sentiments would reach the WNBA player 6,000 miles away in a Russian jail cell.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s really painful and hard to watch, and it\u2019s really taken a toll on a lot of us,\u201d said Kelly Gedney of Surprise, Arizona. \u201cWe can feel the fear that she has. It\u2019s scary to me that she\u2019s in a cage when she is traveling to her court cases. She\u2019s been wrongfully detained and we\u2019re going to do everything we can to get her home.\u201d\n\nGriner has spent the past four months in a Russian prison and is currently on trial. She\u2019s accused of possessing vape cartridges containing cannabis oil when she arrived at the Moscow airport while returning to play for her Russian team, facing a prison term of up to 10 years if convicted.\n\nThe WNBA and U.S. officials have worked to free Griner, without success. Griner was able to send a handwritten letter to President Joe Biden, saying she feared spending the rest of her life in prison while pushing the administration to not forget about other American detainees.\n\nPresident Biden called Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle, on Wednesday to tell her that he is working to free her as soon as possible.\n\n\u201cOne hundred thirty-nine days have passed since my wife has been able to speak to me, to our family and our friends,\u201d Cherelle Griner said during the rally, stopping to compose herself several times. \u201cI\u2019m frustrated my wife is not going to get justice. I know you all are frustrated, too. That\u2019s why you\u2019re here.\u201d\n\nThe rally at the Footprint Center, home of the Phoenix Mercury and Suns, was part celebration of Griner\u2019s accomplishments on and off the court with a call to action.\n\nThe rally featured videos of Griner giving back to the community, dancers and a dramatic poem reading as many of Mercury teammates sat together in chairs on the right side of the court.\n\nPhoenix Suns player Torey Craig spoke, as did Mercury player Brianna Turner.\n\n\u201cTo know BG is to know such a kind spirit, a nice person, such a giver \u2014 I can go on and on about the type of person she is,\u201d said Turner, who also was able to exchange letters with Griner. \u201cWe need to get her back home. She deserves to be home. She needs to be back with her family and friends. We are BG.\u201d\n\nArizona Congressman Greg Stanton, the former Phoenix mayor, also was on hand after pushing a resolution calling for Griner\u2019s immediate release passed by the U.S. House of Representatives earlier this week.\n\n\u201cToday was important, a show of unity, speaking in one voice that we expect our president, our administration to do what it takes to bring our fellow American back home,\u201d Stanton said.\n\n___\n\nTo see more AP stories on Griner: https://apnews.com/hub/brittney-griner","url":"https://www.myhighplains.com/sports/mercury-hold-public-rally-in-support-of-brittney-griner/"},"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":{"id":"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896","text":"Britney Grenier \u2019 s trial could end in conviction, experts say\nMore than four months after her first arrest, WNBA star Britney Greiner is expected to appear in the Russian courtroom on Friday to begin a drug trial that legal experts say will almost certainly end with a conviction despite the hype in the United States for her release.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s mostly biased because the Russian judicial system says they can \u2019 t be tried until the defendant is found guilty, \u201d said William Pomerantz, acting director of the Kennan Institute and an expert on Russian law.\nThere is no real idea or expectation that the accused is innocent.\nThere is no presumption of innocence. \u201d\nRussian customs officials said they found e-cigarette cartridges with traces of cannabis oil in Griner \u2019 s luggage as it passed through a checkpoint at an airport near Moscow on February 17.\nColony.\nGrenier \u2019 s lawyer Alexander Boykov said Monday that he expects the trial to begin on Friday and last up to two months.\n\u201cAt this point, we don \u2019 t know what evidence they have, \u201d Pomerance said.\n\u201cWe don \u2019 t know how many volumes of evidence they want to read in the registry, but usually in such cases they are huge and significant. \u201d\nGreiner \u2019 s arrest was an important geopolitical moment during Russia \u2019 s ongoing invasion of Ukraine and amid Russia \u2019 s strained diplomatic relations with the United States and some European countries.\nFrom the very beginning of Greiner \u2019 s arrest, his supporters feared that Russia would use him during a global conflict.\nIn May, the U.S. State Department confirmed these concerns by declaring Greiner \u201cunjustly detained. \u201d\nAs a result, responsibility for this case was transferred to the Government Office, which directs and coordinates U.S. diplomatic and strategic efforts on hostage taking abroad.\nBritney has been classified as unjustly detained since April 29, meaning that the US government has established that she is being used as a political tool and, as a result, is negotiating her release regardless of the trial.\nThis was reported by Agent Greener Lindsay Kagawa Kolas in an email on Wednesday.\n\u201cSo our expectations, including Britney \u2019 s family, remain that President Biden will make a deal to bring her home. \u201d\nQatar-2022: World Cup leaders responded to Norway at the incendiary FIFA conference | football news\nThe Griner family and their supporters are increasingly turning to President Biden and the U.S. government to seek Griner \u2019 s release.\nKagawa Kolas recently agreed a letter to Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris, signed by groups such as the National Women's Organization, the Human Rights Campaign, the National Urban League and the National Action Network.\nThe letter calls on the government to make a deal to release Greiner.\nIn April, by agreeing to a prisoner exchange, Russia released Trevor Reed, a former U.S. Marine who was sentenced to nine years in prison on charges of endangering Russian police during an altercation.\nKimberly St. Julian-Farnon, Ph.D., said Reed \u2019 s deteriorating health in Russia was likely a factor in Moscow \u2019 s willingness to release him.\nShe is a student of history at the University of Pennsylvania, whose field of study is the experience of African Americans in the Soviet Union, Ukraine and Russia.\n\u201cThe problem is that politically, Britney is worth a lot more in terms of prisoner trafficking than Trevor Reed, because of her profile, \u201d said St. Julian-Farnon, who advised the WNBA Players Association on Grenier \u2019 s detention.\nButt, an international arms dealer, was convicted by an American court and sentenced to 25 years in prison.\nRussia is also interested in the release of Roman Seleznev, a hacker who was convicted in the United States for conducting a large-scale operation to steal credit cards and personal data and sentenced to 27 years in prison.\nIn addition to Greiner, Russia has also detained Paul Whelan, a former U.S. Marine sentenced to 16 years in prison for espionage.\n\u201cThis is a classic dilemma in hostage-taking cases, \u201d said Thomas Firestone, a former Justice Department official who worked as a lawyer in Moscow.\n\u201cIf you negotiate a release, you can encourage hostage-taking in the future.\nIf you don \u2019 t, a person may never be released. \u201d\nPolarizing \u201cchess player \u201d Medvedev harbors a dark side\nJake Sullivan, Biden \u2019 s national security adviser, told reporters on Tuesday that he and Secretary of State Anthony Blinken had spoken in recent days with Greiner \u2019 s wife Cheryl Greiner.\n\"The United States government is actively trying to solve this problem and bring Britney home,\" Sullivan said.\n\u201cHe enjoys the full attention of the president and all senior members of his diplomatic and national security team, \u201d he added.\n\"We are actively working to find a solution to this problem and will continue to do so without rest until Britney returns home safely.\"\nRussia announced on Tuesday that it had barred Biden, First Lady Jill Biden and others from entering the country in response to wide-ranging sanctions.\nThe list includes four senators: Republican Mitch McConnell from Kentucky, Susan Collins from Maine, Ben Sass from Nebraska and Democrat Kirsten Gillibrand from New York.\n\"Release Britney Grenier,\" Sassi said in a statement.\n\u201cIt doesn \u2019 t matter when Putin throws a tantrum and blocks Americans from entering Russia, but we have a problem when he captures an American. \u201d\nGriner is one of the most titled basketball players in the world \u2013 a seven-time participant of the WNBA All-Star Game, a two-time Olympic champion and the first openly gay athlete to sign an advertising contract with Nike.\nI went to Russia after a two-week break to play for UMMC-Yekaterinburg, the women \u2019 s professional basketball team.\nSince then, news about Griner has been rare and has mostly been spread by Russian state media, according to the Associated Press.\nBut Cheryl Greiner told AP that the long-planned telephone conversation between the two had not taken place due to a logistical error at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.\n\u201cI find this unacceptable and I don \u2019 t have confidence in our government right now, \u201d Cheryl Greiner told The Associated Press in late June.\n\u201cIf I can \u2019 t trust you to call on a Saturday outside of office hours, how can I trust you to negotiate on behalf of my wife to come home? \u201d\nHow Russia and Ukraine became the heroines of the smear campaign.\nIn a radio interview Wednesday with Reverend Al Sharpton, who is also the founder of the National Action Network, Cheryl Greiner said she had not spoken to her wife since February but had received messages.\n\u201cShe told me she was okay, \u201d Cheryl Grainer said of her wife \u2019 s letters.\nShe's like, \"I'm fine, baby.\nI'm tough.\nI'm not me now.\nWhen I get home, it'll take me a minute to recover, but I'm holding on.\nI'm not gonna break until I get home.\nI won't let them break me.\nI know they \u2019 re trying, but I \u2019 ll do my best to keep going until I can get home. \u201d\nParis Hatcher was horrified to learn of the extension of Britney Grenier \u2019 s detention on Monday and to see a photo of Grenier circulated in Russian state media.\n\u201cShe looks scared, \u201d said Hatcher, whose organization Black Feminist Future created the online campaign # BringBrittneyHome.\nIt's about dignity.\nIt is about human humanity.\nShe deserves to be in touch with her family. \u201d\nSt. Julian-Varnon said the rights of defendants in Russia are dramatically different from those of a person accused of committing a crime in the United States.\n\"You have no right to a jury trial,\" said St. Julian-Varnon.\nYour lawyer has no right to call any witnesses they want.\nThe whole case against you and the case in your support is based on the evidence gathered by the state. \u201d\nHowever, St. Julian-Varnon said she remained cautiously optimistic that Greiner could eventually be released either as a result of an exchange of prisoners or as a result of a conviction on a less serious charge and agreeing to a large fine.\n\u201cThere are a lot of moving figures here, \u201d St. Julian-Varnon said.\n\u201cI want to be optimistic because it \u2019 s still her life.\nIt's Britney's life.\nIt's Cheryl's life. \"","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0019.json.gz:126231","uncompressed_offset":532975896,"url":"autospynews.net/%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8C%D0%B5-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B5%D1%82-%D0%B7%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C/","warc_date":"2022-06-30T10:12:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09>","warc_url":"https://autospynews.net/%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8C%D0%B5-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B5%D1%82-%D0%B7%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C/"},"created":"2022-06-30T10:34:17.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1092","request_id":"1092","narrative_id":"1092"},"responses":[{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Brittney Griner, a professional basketball player for the Phoenix Mercury and one of the most accomplished athletes in American sports, was detained in Russia in February 2022 after customs officials at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport found vape cartridges containing cannabis oil in her luggage."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"Griner explained that she had inadvertently packed the vape cartridges in her luggage and had no intention of breaking Russian law."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"Under Russian law, Griner faced charges of large-scale transportation of drugs, which carried a potential sentence of up to 10 years in prison."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"The Russian judicial system, which operates without a presumption of innocence, made a conviction in Griner's case highly likely, according to legal experts."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"In July 2022, Griner pleaded guilty to the charges, stating that her actions were unintentional and that she had no desire to violate Russian laws."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Despite her guilty plea, Griner was sentenced to nine years in a Russian penal colony, a ruling she unsuccessfully appealed."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Her arrest and subsequent trial occurred during a period of heightened geopolitical tensions, as Russia's invasion of Ukraine had severely strained relations with the United States."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Supporters and experts feared from the outset that Griner's high profile as a two-time Olympic champion and WNBA star made her a valuable political asset for Russia, potentially using her as leverage in diplomatic negotiations."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s detention has been described as her becoming a political prisoner and a leverage point in a larger geopolitical conflict between the United States and Russia."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"The timing of her arrest, just days before Russia launched its full-scale invasion of Ukraine, further underscored the political undertones of her case."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Efforts to secure Griner\u2019s release initially aimed to avoid provoking an international incident, but the situation quickly escalated into a public and political issue."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"In May 2022, the U.S. State Department declared Griner 'unjustly detained,' transferring her case to the Office of the Special Presidential Envoy for Hostage Affairs."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Griner sent a handwritten letter to President Joe Biden, expressing her fear of spending the rest of her life in prison and urging the administration not to forget about other American detainees."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The Biden administration began working toward Griner\u2019s release immediately after her arrest, with efforts intensifying after the State Department's declaration of her wrongful detention."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"In July, U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken pressed Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov to accept a proposal to release both Griner and Paul Whelan, another American detained in Russia."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, the Biden administration agreed to a one-for-one prisoner swap, exchanging Griner for Viktor Bout, a notorious Russian arms trafficker serving a 25-year sentence in the United States."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The decision to exclude Paul Whelan from the exchange drew criticism and raised concerns about the potential for future leverage over American citizens."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The prisoner exchange was facilitated by UAE officials, including President Sheikh Mohammed bin Zayed al-Nahyan, who helped coordinate the transfer in Abu Dhabi."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The swap, which involved Russian and American planes meeting on the tarmac in Abu Dhabi, was reminiscent of Cold War-era exchanges."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Biden administration officials emphasized that the negotiations with Russia were limited to the release of wrongfully detained Americans and did not signal a broader thaw in relations."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s release marked a rare instance of cooperation between the U.S. and Russia amidst heightened tensions following Russia's invasion of Ukraine."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"During her incarceration, Griner was transferred to a penal colony in Mordovia, a region known for its harsh and inhumane prison conditions."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Russian penal colonies have been described as labor camps with inhumane conditions, including limited access to toilets and no hot water."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s lawyers stated that she was trying to stay strong and adapt to the harsh environment of the penal colony."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"In letters to her wife, Griner revealed her determination to remain resilient despite the mental and physical toll of her detention."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Her experience in the penal colony was described as traumatic and stressful, particularly given the severity of her sentence compared to others with more severe crimes."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s detention and trial highlighted the intersection of sports, gender, and politics, as her identity as a 6-foot-9 Black gay American woman made her a powerful cultural symbol."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"The WNBA\u2019s low salaries have forced players like Griner to play overseas during the off-season, where they can earn significantly more money than in the league."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"Griner was playing for UMMC Ekaterinburg in Russia, a team that has historically paid WNBA players far more than their league salaries."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"In 2021, she helped UMMC Ekaterinburg win its fifth EuroLeague Women\u2019s championship, further cementing her status as one of the most accomplished athletes in basketball."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s story has resonated with fans and students, with her memoir being used in gender studies classes and inspiring gratitude for her openness about her identity."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Her detention also sparked public advocacy, with several hundred fans gathering at a rally in Phoenix to support her and call for her release."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"The rally featured videos of Griner\u2019s community contributions, performances, and speeches from her teammates and supporters, including Phoenix Suns player Torey Craig."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle, expressed frustration and heartbreak during the rally, noting the emotional toll of being separated for 139 days."},{"citations":{"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":100.0},"text":"Dawn Staley, Griner\u2019s former Olympic coach, actively used social media to keep her case in the public eye and encouraged Americans to contact their representatives."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s release brought relief to her supporters, but her story remains a stark reminder of how sports, identity, and geopolitics can intersect in complex and often troubling ways."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Brittney Griner, a professional basketball player for the Phoenix Mercury and one of the most accomplished athletes in American sports, was detained in Russia in February 2022 after customs officials at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport found vape cartridges containing cannabis oil in her luggage."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"Griner explained that she had inadvertently packed the vape cartridges in her luggage and had no intention of breaking Russian law."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"Under Russian law, Griner faced charges of large-scale transportation of drugs, which carried a potential sentence of up to 10 years in prison."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"The Russian judicial system, which operates without a presumption of innocence, made a conviction in Griner's case highly likely, according to legal experts."},{"citations":{"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":100.0},"text":"In July 2022, Griner pleaded guilty to the charges, stating that her actions were unintentional and that she had no desire to violate Russian laws."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Despite her guilty plea, Griner was sentenced to nine years in a Russian penal colony, a ruling she unsuccessfully appealed."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Her arrest and subsequent trial occurred during a period of heightened geopolitical tensions, as Russia's invasion of Ukraine had severely strained relations with the United States."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"Supporters and experts feared from the outset that Griner's high profile as a two-time Olympic champion and WNBA star made her a valuable political asset for Russia, potentially using her as leverage in diplomatic negotiations."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s detention has been described as her becoming a political prisoner and a leverage point in a larger geopolitical conflict between the United States and Russia."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"The timing of her arrest, just days before Russia launched its full-scale invasion of Ukraine, further underscored the political undertones of her case."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Efforts to secure Griner\u2019s release initially aimed to avoid provoking an international incident, but the situation quickly escalated into a public and political issue."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"In May 2022, the U.S. State Department declared Griner 'unjustly detained,' transferring her case to the Office of the Special Presidential Envoy for Hostage Affairs."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Griner sent a handwritten letter to President Joe Biden, expressing her fear of spending the rest of her life in prison and urging the administration not to forget about other American detainees."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The Biden administration began working toward Griner\u2019s release immediately after her arrest, with efforts intensifying after the State Department's declaration of her wrongful detention."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"In July, U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken pressed Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov to accept a proposal to release both Griner and Paul Whelan, another American detained in Russia."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Ultimately, the Biden administration agreed to a one-for-one prisoner swap, exchanging Griner for Viktor Bout, a notorious Russian arms trafficker serving a 25-year sentence in the United States."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The decision to exclude Paul Whelan from the exchange drew criticism and raised concerns about the potential for future leverage over American citizens."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The prisoner exchange was facilitated by UAE officials, including President Sheikh Mohammed bin Zayed al-Nahyan, who helped coordinate the transfer in Abu Dhabi."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"The swap, which involved Russian and American planes meeting on the tarmac in Abu Dhabi, was reminiscent of Cold War-era exchanges."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Biden administration officials emphasized that the negotiations with Russia were limited to the release of wrongfully detained Americans and did not signal a broader thaw in relations."},{"citations":{"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s release marked a rare instance of cooperation between the U.S. and Russia amidst heightened tensions following Russia's invasion of Ukraine."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"During her incarceration, Griner was transferred to a penal colony in Mordovia, a region known for its harsh and inhumane prison conditions."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Russian penal colonies have been described as labor camps with inhumane conditions, including limited access to toilets and no hot water."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s lawyers stated that she was trying to stay strong and adapt to the harsh environment of the penal colony."},{"citations":{"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":100.0},"text":"In letters to her wife, Griner revealed her determination to remain resilient despite the mental and physical toll of her detention."},{"citations":{"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":100.0},"text":"Her experience in the penal colony was described as traumatic and stressful, particularly given the severity of her sentence compared to others with more severe crimes."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s detention and trial highlighted the intersection of sports, gender, and politics, as her identity as a 6-foot-9 Black gay American woman made her a powerful cultural symbol."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"The WNBA\u2019s low salaries have forced players like Griner to play overseas during the off-season, where they can earn significantly more money than in the league."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":100.0},"text":"Griner was playing for UMMC Ekaterinburg in Russia, a team that has historically paid WNBA players far more than their league salaries."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"In 2021, she helped UMMC Ekaterinburg win its fifth EuroLeague Women\u2019s championship, further cementing her status as one of the most accomplished athletes in basketball."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s story has resonated with fans and students, with her memoir being used in gender studies classes and inspiring gratitude for her openness about her identity."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Her detention also sparked public advocacy, with several hundred fans gathering at a rally in Phoenix to support her and call for her release."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"The rally featured videos of Griner\u2019s community contributions, performances, and speeches from her teammates and supporters, including Phoenix Suns player Torey Craig."},{"citations":{"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle, expressed frustration and heartbreak during the rally, noting the emotional toll of being separated for 139 days."},{"citations":{"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":100.0},"text":"Dawn Staley, Griner\u2019s former Olympic coach, actively used social media to keep her case in the public eye and encouraged Americans to contact their representatives."},{"citations":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":100.0},"text":"Griner\u2019s release brought relief to her supporters, but her story remains a stark reminder of how sports, identity, and geopolitics can intersect in complex and often troubling ways."}],"references":["fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896","3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777","72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366","72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512","956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289","530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971","027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127","32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841"],"documents":{"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366":{"id":"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_1069938366","text":"games\n\nWhy Isn\u2019t Brittney Griner the Biggest Sports Story in the Country?\n\nPhoto: Kevin C. Cox/Getty Images\n\nThe second-best player in every sport is a superstar at a level that 99.999 percent of professional athletes \u2014 who are already the elite of the elite of the elite \u2014 will never come close to achieving. Joel Embiid finished second in NBA MVP voting last year; in baseball (a sport once actively played in this country), it was Vladimir Guerrero Jr.; and in football, it was Tom Brady.\n\nIn the WNBA, the Phoenix Mercury\u2019s Brittney Griner earned this distinction last year. She was second in scoring, sixth in rebounds, first in blocks (she\u2019s on track to become the WNBA\u2019s all-time leader in that category), and, according to most advanced metrics, the best offensive player in the league. Her r\u00e9sum\u00e9 is glittering: She won an NCAA national championship for Baylor in 2012, the same year she captured college basketball\u2019s Player of the Year Award. She then won a WNBA championship in 2014 and was selected as one of the best 25 players in league history in 2021. She has two Olympic gold medals to her name. In the gold-medal game against Japan in Tokyo last summer, she dominated, scoring 30 points to clinch an easy victory. She is the apex of her sport. She is the best of the best. She is a legend.\n\nAnd for more than a month now, she has been in the custody of the Russian government. Yet\u00a0until Russian officials released a statement over the weekend saying they had detained Griner after finding hashish oil in her airport bag, it seemed that nobody had noticed. And the reaction since the arrest has been stunningly quiet. One of the greatest athletes in American sports \u2014 a gold-medal winner, a superstar, a champion \u2014 was arrested in a dangerous and volatile country that has suddenly become a pariah on the world stage. Making equivalences between sports only takes you so far here, but seriously: Imagine if Tom Brady were being held by Russian officials right now.\n\nIt is unclear how directly Griner\u2019s plight connects to the catastrophic Russian invasion of Ukraine, and her detention has been overshadowed by the death and destruction wrought by Putin. And part of the muted response is likely due to sensitivity of the negotiations between Russian and American officials. Griner\u2019s wife asked for privacy on Instagram, and it\u2019s clear the precariousness of the situation has led to a certain institutional resistance to even mentioning it: That WNBA.com doesn\u2019t include a single story about one of the organization\u2019s best players being detained speaks to this dynamic. It is also worth remembering, as ESPN\u2019s T.J. Quinn did on Monday, that Griner, whatever the specifics, is likely in some danger; Quinn noted that \u201cas a 6-9 Black gay American woman, she\u2019s a powerful cultural symbol,\u201d and \u201ceven in the best case, she\u2019s in for a long legal slog in the Russian criminal justice system. And there\u2019s little the US govt can do about it.\u201d\n\nAnother motive the WNBA may have for staying quiet is its own culpability in the situation. The reason Griner was in Russia in the first place \u2014 to play off-season basketball, as she has done there for years \u2014 is that the league does not pay its superstars the way other sports leagues do. As Tom Ley from Defector pointed out:\n\nThe league\u2019s low salaries and minimal efforts towards player support have for years forced even its biggest stars to treat their time in the WNBA as a part-time job. The maximum WNBA salary in 2022 was just over $228,000, and players can make far more than that playing in leagues overseas. In 2015, Diana Taurasi was paid $1.5 million to skip the WNBA season entirely and play for UMMC Ekaterinburg, and Liz Cambage\u00a0recently revealed that she has made \u201cfive to eight times\u201d\u00a0as much money playing overseas than she has in the WNBA.\n\nBefore you say, \u201cWell, the WNBA isn\u2019t as popular in the NBA; of course Griner wouldn\u2019t make as much as LeBron,\u201d remember this: The WNBA has a salary cap, and one that\u2019s particularly suppressive of superstar wages. Griner only made $221,450 for the 2021\u20132022 season, which is less than a third of the minimum salary in the NHL, but nevertheless classifies her as the fourth-highest-paid player in the WNBA. A new CBA signed two years ago was supposed to address these issues, yet there was Griner, making a mint playing for UMMC Ekaterinburg in Russia. The WNBA\u2019s MVP last year,\u00a0Connecticut Sun forward Jonquel Jones, plays for the same Russian team.\u00a0She got out of the country just after the invasion of Ukraine began.\n\nLiz Cambage, a star for the Los Angeles Sparks, has noted that players can make \u201cfive to eight times more money\u201d for Russian teams than they do in the WNBA, despite the league being by far the most high-profile women\u2019s basketball league in the world. And restricted cash flow isn\u2019t the only problem for players: Just last week, the league fined the New York Liberty $500,000 for chartering flights to games, claiming this gave the Liberty a \u201ccompetitive advantage.\u201d (For perspective, almost every team in the collegiate NCAA tournament next week will arrive at their destinations via chartered flight.) Griner didn\u2019t choose to go play in Russia. The league left her no choice.\n\nThe precarity of Griner\u2019s position in Russia may give the WNBA a good reason to stay quiet about her case. But perhaps the league would also prefer not to dwell on how she ended up in this situation in the first place.\n\nIn any case, it\u2019s not just the WNBA downplaying this story. There was also no mention of Griner on the front pages of ESPN.com, CBS Sports, and SI.com just 48 hours after news of her arrest landed.\n\nThis strange reaction comes at a time when the WNBA has surged in popularity. Last year\u2019s finals, featuring Griner\u2019s Mercury, put up the highest ratings ever, a full 49 percent jump from 2020. This is partly because of the league\u2019s activism, which has increased its visibility in a dramatic way. And Griner has been right in the middle of it all, wearing Breonna Taylor\u2019s name on her jersey and speaking out in favor of LGBTQ+ issues since before she even entered the NBA. She was also the first openly gay athlete ever signed to an endorsement deal with Nike. Her teammate Diana Taurasi, perhaps the best player in WNBA history, called Griner \u201ca pioneer.\u201d\n\nAnd still, relative silence.\n\nAs Griner sits in detention in Russia, as a result of a system that is set up to devalue her and other stars at every corner, it would be nice if her plight received attention commensurate with its seriousness.\n\nWhy Isn\u2019t Brittney Griner the Biggest Sports Story?","url":"https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/03/why-isnt-brittney-griner-the-biggest-sports-story.html"},"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289":{"id":"956ac73a-190c-4269-b292-50a1de4adb6d_31039289","text":"PHOENIX (AP) \u2014 They shared laughs, smiles, memories. There also were tears, fears, unease.\n\nThrough the range of emotions, one common thread bonded them together: Brittney Griner.\n\nWearing \u201cBG\u201d shirts and holding signs, several hundred fans gathered for a public rally in support of Griner on Wednesday, hoping their sentiments would reach the WNBA player 6,000 miles away in a Russian jail cell.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s really painful and hard to watch, and it\u2019s really taken a toll on a lot of us,\u201d said Kelly Gedney of Surprise, Arizona. \u201cWe can feel the fear that she has. It\u2019s scary to me that she\u2019s in a cage when she is traveling to her court cases. She\u2019s been wrongfully detained and we\u2019re going to do everything we can to get her home.\u201d\n\nGriner has spent the past four months in a Russian prison and is currently on trial. She\u2019s accused of possessing vape cartridges containing cannabis oil when she arrived at the Moscow airport while returning to play for her Russian team, facing a prison term of up to 10 years if convicted.\n\nThe WNBA and U.S. officials have worked to free Griner, without success. Griner was able to send a handwritten letter to President Joe Biden, saying she feared spending the rest of her life in prison while pushing the administration to not forget about other American detainees.\n\nPresident Biden called Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle, on Wednesday to tell her that he is working to free her as soon as possible.\n\n\u201cOne hundred thirty-nine days have passed since my wife has been able to speak to me, to our family and our friends,\u201d Cherelle Griner said during the rally, stopping to compose herself several times. \u201cI\u2019m frustrated my wife is not going to get justice. I know you all are frustrated, too. That\u2019s why you\u2019re here.\u201d\n\nThe rally at the Footprint Center, home of the Phoenix Mercury and Suns, was part celebration of Griner\u2019s accomplishments on and off the court with a call to action.\n\nThe rally featured videos of Griner giving back to the community, dancers and a dramatic poem reading as many of Mercury teammates sat together in chairs on the right side of the court.\n\nPhoenix Suns player Torey Craig spoke, as did Mercury player Brianna Turner.\n\n\u201cTo know BG is to know such a kind spirit, a nice person, such a giver \u2014 I can go on and on about the type of person she is,\u201d said Turner, who also was able to exchange letters with Griner. \u201cWe need to get her back home. She deserves to be home. She needs to be back with her family and friends. We are BG.\u201d\n\nArizona Congressman Greg Stanton, the former Phoenix mayor, also was on hand after pushing a resolution calling for Griner\u2019s immediate release passed by the U.S. House of Representatives earlier this week.\n\n\u201cToday was important, a show of unity, speaking in one voice that we expect our president, our administration to do what it takes to bring our fellow American back home,\u201d Stanton said.\n\n___\n\nTo see more AP stories on Griner: https://apnews.com/hub/brittney-griner","url":"https://www.myhighplains.com/sports/mercury-hold-public-rally-in-support-of-brittney-griner/"},"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896":{"id":"fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09_532975896","text":"Britney Grenier \u2019 s trial could end in conviction, experts say\nMore than four months after her first arrest, WNBA star Britney Greiner is expected to appear in the Russian courtroom on Friday to begin a drug trial that legal experts say will almost certainly end with a conviction despite the hype in the United States for her release.\n\u201cIt \u2019 s mostly biased because the Russian judicial system says they can \u2019 t be tried until the defendant is found guilty, \u201d said William Pomerantz, acting director of the Kennan Institute and an expert on Russian law.\nThere is no real idea or expectation that the accused is innocent.\nThere is no presumption of innocence. \u201d\nRussian customs officials said they found e-cigarette cartridges with traces of cannabis oil in Griner \u2019 s luggage as it passed through a checkpoint at an airport near Moscow on February 17.\nColony.\nGrenier \u2019 s lawyer Alexander Boykov said Monday that he expects the trial to begin on Friday and last up to two months.\n\u201cAt this point, we don \u2019 t know what evidence they have, \u201d Pomerance said.\n\u201cWe don \u2019 t know how many volumes of evidence they want to read in the registry, but usually in such cases they are huge and significant. \u201d\nGreiner \u2019 s arrest was an important geopolitical moment during Russia \u2019 s ongoing invasion of Ukraine and amid Russia \u2019 s strained diplomatic relations with the United States and some European countries.\nFrom the very beginning of Greiner \u2019 s arrest, his supporters feared that Russia would use him during a global conflict.\nIn May, the U.S. State Department confirmed these concerns by declaring Greiner \u201cunjustly detained. \u201d\nAs a result, responsibility for this case was transferred to the Government Office, which directs and coordinates U.S. diplomatic and strategic efforts on hostage taking abroad.\nBritney has been classified as unjustly detained since April 29, meaning that the US government has established that she is being used as a political tool and, as a result, is negotiating her release regardless of the trial.\nThis was reported by Agent Greener Lindsay Kagawa Kolas in an email on Wednesday.\n\u201cSo our expectations, including Britney \u2019 s family, remain that President Biden will make a deal to bring her home. \u201d\nQatar-2022: World Cup leaders responded to Norway at the incendiary FIFA conference | football news\nThe Griner family and their supporters are increasingly turning to President Biden and the U.S. government to seek Griner \u2019 s release.\nKagawa Kolas recently agreed a letter to Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris, signed by groups such as the National Women's Organization, the Human Rights Campaign, the National Urban League and the National Action Network.\nThe letter calls on the government to make a deal to release Greiner.\nIn April, by agreeing to a prisoner exchange, Russia released Trevor Reed, a former U.S. Marine who was sentenced to nine years in prison on charges of endangering Russian police during an altercation.\nKimberly St. Julian-Farnon, Ph.D., said Reed \u2019 s deteriorating health in Russia was likely a factor in Moscow \u2019 s willingness to release him.\nShe is a student of history at the University of Pennsylvania, whose field of study is the experience of African Americans in the Soviet Union, Ukraine and Russia.\n\u201cThe problem is that politically, Britney is worth a lot more in terms of prisoner trafficking than Trevor Reed, because of her profile, \u201d said St. Julian-Farnon, who advised the WNBA Players Association on Grenier \u2019 s detention.\nButt, an international arms dealer, was convicted by an American court and sentenced to 25 years in prison.\nRussia is also interested in the release of Roman Seleznev, a hacker who was convicted in the United States for conducting a large-scale operation to steal credit cards and personal data and sentenced to 27 years in prison.\nIn addition to Greiner, Russia has also detained Paul Whelan, a former U.S. Marine sentenced to 16 years in prison for espionage.\n\u201cThis is a classic dilemma in hostage-taking cases, \u201d said Thomas Firestone, a former Justice Department official who worked as a lawyer in Moscow.\n\u201cIf you negotiate a release, you can encourage hostage-taking in the future.\nIf you don \u2019 t, a person may never be released. \u201d\nPolarizing \u201cchess player \u201d Medvedev harbors a dark side\nJake Sullivan, Biden \u2019 s national security adviser, told reporters on Tuesday that he and Secretary of State Anthony Blinken had spoken in recent days with Greiner \u2019 s wife Cheryl Greiner.\n\"The United States government is actively trying to solve this problem and bring Britney home,\" Sullivan said.\n\u201cHe enjoys the full attention of the president and all senior members of his diplomatic and national security team, \u201d he added.\n\"We are actively working to find a solution to this problem and will continue to do so without rest until Britney returns home safely.\"\nRussia announced on Tuesday that it had barred Biden, First Lady Jill Biden and others from entering the country in response to wide-ranging sanctions.\nThe list includes four senators: Republican Mitch McConnell from Kentucky, Susan Collins from Maine, Ben Sass from Nebraska and Democrat Kirsten Gillibrand from New York.\n\"Release Britney Grenier,\" Sassi said in a statement.\n\u201cIt doesn \u2019 t matter when Putin throws a tantrum and blocks Americans from entering Russia, but we have a problem when he captures an American. \u201d\nGriner is one of the most titled basketball players in the world \u2013 a seven-time participant of the WNBA All-Star Game, a two-time Olympic champion and the first openly gay athlete to sign an advertising contract with Nike.\nI went to Russia after a two-week break to play for UMMC-Yekaterinburg, the women \u2019 s professional basketball team.\nSince then, news about Griner has been rare and has mostly been spread by Russian state media, according to the Associated Press.\nBut Cheryl Greiner told AP that the long-planned telephone conversation between the two had not taken place due to a logistical error at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.\n\u201cI find this unacceptable and I don \u2019 t have confidence in our government right now, \u201d Cheryl Greiner told The Associated Press in late June.\n\u201cIf I can \u2019 t trust you to call on a Saturday outside of office hours, how can I trust you to negotiate on behalf of my wife to come home? \u201d\nHow Russia and Ukraine became the heroines of the smear campaign.\nIn a radio interview Wednesday with Reverend Al Sharpton, who is also the founder of the National Action Network, Cheryl Greiner said she had not spoken to her wife since February but had received messages.\n\u201cShe told me she was okay, \u201d Cheryl Grainer said of her wife \u2019 s letters.\nShe's like, \"I'm fine, baby.\nI'm tough.\nI'm not me now.\nWhen I get home, it'll take me a minute to recover, but I'm holding on.\nI'm not gonna break until I get home.\nI won't let them break me.\nI know they \u2019 re trying, but I \u2019 ll do my best to keep going until I can get home. \u201d\nParis Hatcher was horrified to learn of the extension of Britney Grenier \u2019 s detention on Monday and to see a photo of Grenier circulated in Russian state media.\n\u201cShe looks scared, \u201d said Hatcher, whose organization Black Feminist Future created the online campaign # BringBrittneyHome.\nIt's about dignity.\nIt is about human humanity.\nShe deserves to be in touch with her family. \u201d\nSt. Julian-Varnon said the rights of defendants in Russia are dramatically different from those of a person accused of committing a crime in the United States.\n\"You have no right to a jury trial,\" said St. Julian-Varnon.\nYour lawyer has no right to call any witnesses they want.\nThe whole case against you and the case in your support is based on the evidence gathered by the state. \u201d\nHowever, St. Julian-Varnon said she remained cautiously optimistic that Greiner could eventually be released either as a result of an exchange of prisoners or as a result of a conviction on a less serious charge and agreeing to a large fine.\n\u201cThere are a lot of moving figures here, \u201d St. Julian-Varnon said.\n\u201cI want to be optimistic because it \u2019 s still her life.\nIt's Britney's life.\nIt's Cheryl's life. \"","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0019.json.gz:126231","uncompressed_offset":532975896,"url":"autospynews.net/%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8C%D0%B5-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B5%D1%82-%D0%B7%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C/","warc_date":"2022-06-30T10:12:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fa020cfe-e092-475b-ab96-43285fc40c09>","warc_url":"https://autospynews.net/%D1%81%D1%83%D0%B4-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8C%D0%B5-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B5%D1%82-%D0%B7%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BD%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C/"},"created":"2022-06-30T10:34:17.000Z","lang":"eng"},"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127":{"id":"027aa1fd-eb65-4c92-8094-4fd8e40aadef_204954127","text":"Diplomat Sparks Renewed Hope For Brittney Griner Prisoner Exchange\n\nThe situation surrounding Brittney Griner's case is looking a little less bleak, thanks to the recent developments brought about by negotiations between the U.S. and Russia.\n\nIn early November,\u00a0the WNBA star had been transferred to a penal colony in the Russian republic of Mordovia.\u00a0There, she began fulfilling her nine-year sentence for drug possession. As reported by\u00a0Reuters,\u00a0authorities initially arrested Griner in February 2022 after vape cartridges containing cannabis oil were discovered in her luggage\u00a0at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport.\u00a0While she attempted to appeal the ruling, it was ultimately upheld by a Russian court.\n\n\"This has been [a] very traumatic experience, waiting for this day, waiting for the first court, and getting nine years for a crime that I was barely over the significant amount,\"\u00a0she said at the hearing (via CBS News). \"I don't understand the first court's decision to give one year less than the max when I've been here almost 8 months, and people with more severe crimes have gotten less than what I was given... I really hope that the court will adjust this sentence, because it's been very, very stressful and very traumatic to my mental and psyche, being away from my family and not being able to communicate.\" However, there is now renewed hope that Griner could be released, with a Russian diplomat claiming that a swap could happen sometime in the future.\n\nRussian diplomat says there's 'always a chance' for a swap\n\nNot all hope is lost, after all. According to Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergei Ryabkov, Russia is not turning its back on the possibility of a prisoner exchange with the U.S. As reported by the New York Post,\u00a0Ryabkov told reporters that there is \"always a chance\" when asked about the likelihood of a swap taking place before the end of the year. However, he noted that in the past, there had been multiple instances when it seemed as if Russia would agree to a swap, only for the plan to fall apart. If the prisoner swap does take place,\u00a0Ryabkov said it would \"send a positive signal that not everything is hopeless in Russian-American relations.\"\n\nIn the meantime, it looks like Brittney Griner has her work cut out for her. Maria Alyokhina, a former member of the band Pussy Riot, didn't mince words when she spoke to NPR about her own experience at a Russian penal colony.\u00a0\"It has a bit better conditions than [the] original gulag system from the 1950s,\" she said, but added that it's still \"a labor camp.\" She described the grim reality she endured while serving out her own sentence, calling it inhumane. \"For 100 women, there are like three toilets and no hot water,\" she recalled, adding that the penal colony is merely a \"legal slavery system.\"\n\nAccording to a statement released by her lawyers (via BBC), she is trying her best to survive and is \"doing as well as could be expected and trying to stay strong as she adapts to a new environment.\"","url":"https://www.nickiswift.com/1120961/diplomat-sparks-renewed-hope-for-brittney-griner-prisoner-exchange/"},"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841":{"id":"32944d88-35fe-46a8-b240-1dcb8d143d62_766118841","text":"Categories\nFinance\n\nInside Joe Biden\u2019s Faustian pact with Russia to secure Brittney\n\n\nThree weeks ago, the American basketball star Brittney Griner arrived at a Russian penal colony known for torture, beatings and slave labour to begin a nine-year sentence following her arrest at a Moscow airport in February for possession of vaping cartridges containing hashish oil.\n\nBut in a stunning twist on Thursday, Griner\u2019s plight as an unwitting pawn in a high-stakes geopolitical struggle came to an abrupt end, as she arrived in Abu Dhabi from Moscow and boarded a plane home to reunite with her family. She landed in San Antonio, Texas, early Friday morning.\n\nIn exchange for Griner\u2019s release, the US released Viktor Bout, a notorious arms trafficker who was serving a 25-year sentence for conspiring to kill US citizens and aiding a terrorist organisation.\n\nThe deal was met with jubilation from Griner\u2019s family and supporters. But the controversial swap for Bout \u2014 as well as the exclusion of Paul Whelan, another US citizen imprisoned in Russia \u2014 also drew criticism and raised questions about how America\u2019s adversaries might leverage arrests of its citizens in the future.\n\nUS officials began working toward Griner\u2019s release as soon as she was apprehended in Russia in February, but the effort became more concentrated on prisoner swap negotiations once the State Department declared in May that she had been wrongfully detained.\n\nIn July, US secretary of state Antony Blinken and Russian foreign minister Sergei Lavrov spoke on the phone for the first time since Russia\u2019s full-scale invasion of Ukraine in February. During the call, Blinken pressed Lavrov to accept a \u201csubstantial proposal\u201d from Washington to release Griner and the former marine Whelan, who has been detained in Russia since 2018 on what the US and his family say are trumped-up espionage charges.\n\nAmericans had offered to free Bout, people familiar with the discussions said, but the Russians said they also wanted the release of Vadim Krasikov, a former colonel from Russia\u2019s domestic spy agency who was convicted of murder in Germany last year.\n\nIn the ensuing months, officials said, Washington made a number of offers to Russia in an attempt to secure the release of Griner and Whelan.\n\nHowever, Biden administration officials said that in recent weeks it became clear that Moscow would only accept a one-for-one swap. According to one senior administration official, \u201cthe choice was bringing Brittney Griner home right now or bringing no Americans home from Russia right now\u201d.\n\nDespite the Biden administration\u2019s insistence that they had no choice but to exclude Whelan from the deal, Republican lawmakers and others denounced the decision, as well as facilitating the release of Bout, who is also known as \u201cthe merchant of death\u201d.\n\n\u201cThe Biden administration has allowed Viktor Bout, a dangerous arms dealer who was convicted of conspiring to kill American law enforcement, to walk free,\u201d said Mike Rogers, the top Republican on the House Armed Services Committee.\n\n\u201cThis move to appease Vladimir Putin will only encourage further hostage taking by Russian security forces,\u201d he added.\n\nUS officials described Biden\u2019s choice as a painful one, adding that they would continue to work for Whelan\u2019s release. Washington previously secured the release of Trevor Reed, another former marine, via a prisoner swap in April.\n\nPeople familiar with Thursday\u2019s prisoner exchange likened the episode to \u201ca scene from the Cold War\u201d, with Russian and American planes meeting on the tarmac at an airport in Abu Dhabi.\n\nThe Russian plane carrying Griner arrived first, one of the people said. American officials and people familiar with the events said the basketball star was upbeat on the tarmac, saying she was looking forward to returning home.\n\nThe Griner-Bout swap marks a rare instance in which the US and Russia have been able to find common ground since Putin ordered the full-scale invasion of Ukraine, sending the west\u2019s relationship with Moscow to its lowest ebb since the Cuban missile crisis.\n\nAccording to people familiar with the matter, the Americans and Russians directly negotiated the details of the swaps, with UAE officials including president Sheikh Mohammed bin Zayed al-Nahyan helping to facilitate the mechanics of the transfer.\n\nIt is not unusual for third countries to aid in brokering international diplomatic agreements such as prisoner swaps between hostile countries.\n\nSheikh Mohammed and Putin discussed the matter when they met in Russia in October, and they spoke on the phone on Wednesday, people familiar with the meetings said. Yousef al-Otaiba, UAE ambassador to the US, was present for the exchange on Thursday and had helped to co-ordinate details on the American side.\n\nOn Thursday, some pro-Kremlin commentators hailed the swap as a return to diplomacy. \u201cEveryone sees through this exchange that Moscow and Washington are holding secret negotiations and can make a deal,\u201d Sergei Markov, a political scientist and former member of Russia\u2019s parliament, wrote on Telegram. \u201cAnd everyone hopes that means Moscow and Washington can make a deal to end the war in Ukraine.\u201d\n\nHowever, analysts and US officials said that while the breakthrough was a sign that the two sides could get things done when their interests align, it was not evidence of any larger thaw in relations. Biden administration officials added that the recent conversations with Russia about Griner and other prisoners were limited to the release of wrongfully detained Americans.\n\n\u201cThe exchange doesn\u2019t do anything to change the situation for bilateral relations. There are lots of issues where they are in open confrontation,\u201d said Alexander Gabuev, a senior fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.\n\nHe said the otherwise dire state of relations between Russia and the west was thrown into sharp relief last week, when Moscow abruptly pulled out of talks on renewing the New Start treaty, the only remaining agreement governing the countries\u2019 nuclear arsenals.\n\n\u201cThis is a global stability issue: the last remainders of arms control are falling apart, which could lead to an arms race and a higher risk of dangerous incidents,\u201d he said. \u201cThe trajectory we\u2019re on is making that all the more likely.\u201d\n\n\n\nSource link","url":"https://newslanes.com/2022/12/09/inside-joe-bidens-faustian-pact-with-russia-to-secure-brittney/"},"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512":{"id":"72d0404c-dbc4-4f5b-842c-a0cde36325c2_751577512","text":"The problem is not just what happened to Brittney Griner. The problem is that we don\u2019t know what is happening to Brittney Griner now. The WNBA superstar was allegedly caught with hashish oil in her luggage at a Russian airport and has been in custody for several weeks. For those first couple of weeks, it was as if no one noticed she was missing, no small feat for an athlete who is six foot nine and one of the most recognizable players in the history of the game. She also is also well-known in Russia, where she plays for UMMC Ekaterinburg in the WNBA off season. In 2021 she helped the Russian team win its fifth EuroLeague Women\u2019s championship. (Many WNBA players hoop in Russia during the off-season, as they need to supplement their income, an injustice in and of itself.)\n\nAlmost certainly, instead of creating an immediate public outcry following her arrest, there were efforts behind the scenes to get her out of Russia, which, we know now, was preparing to invade Ukraine. The goal would have been to make this go away without provoking an international incident. Well, it\u2019s too late for that now. There are online petitions and a predictable uproar given the anti-Putin sentiment in the States. Griner\u2019s wife, Cherelle Griner, posted a picture of them together on Instagram as the news spread over the weekend. She thanked their fans and then wrote, \u201cI understand that many of you have grown to love BG over the years and have concerns and want details. Please honor our privacy as we continue to work on getting my wife home safely.\u201d\n\nIn other words, delicate negotiations to get Griner home are almost certainly ongoing in a situation that is spiraling. Griner is detained in Russia at a moment when US-Russian relations are at their worst since Ronald Reagan joked, \u201cWe begin bombing in five minutes.\u201d When and how she gets home and how she is being treated right now are anyone\u2019s guess. As basketball writer Tom Ziller put it, \u201cWe don\u2019t have an idea as the public WNBA fandom where Griner is, or how she is doing, or how long she has been detained, or the circumstances of her custody, or what she knows about a timeline for being released, or what she\u2019s being told. We don\u2019t really know anything, and we don\u2019t know whether she or those close to her know anything.\u201d\n\nWhether it started this way or not, we need to understand Griner as a political prisoner. It may have started with airport racial profiling and the idiotic war on cannabis. But now, by the nature of this perilous moment, she has become a chit, a leverage point, in a larger political war.\n\nThe WNBA and Griner\u2019s team, the Phoenix Mercury, are being tight-lipped about the situation\u2014as is the US State Department. But I did reach the coauthor of Griner\u2019s 2014 memoir In My Skin: My Life On and Off the Basketball Court, Sue Hovey. The former ESPN The Magazine executive editor told me: \u201cBrittney Griner is one of the most resilient, mentally tough athletes I\u2019ve ever met. When she led Baylor to a perfect season and the national championship in 2012, she did so while having to endure a torrent of vicious verbal attacks from opposing fans and online trolls. People forget that when she graduated from Baylor in 2013 and publicly came out as gay upon entering the WNBA, that was still a big deal at the time; it wasn\u2019t nearly as common as it is today for athletes to reveal their authentic selves. Brittney was, and continues to be, a trailblazer in eschewing gender norms. Even eight years after her memoir was published, I still get the occasional Twitter message from a college student who read her book in a gender studies class, or just a fan expressing gratitude for Brittney sharing her story. Like many athletes, she has had some stumbles and controversy along the way, but she always takes accountability and shows a willingness to learn and grow. And in an age of curated social media content, there\u2019s something refreshing about a high-profile athlete who gives us that three-dimensional view. She\u2019s relatable and human, and that resonates with people.\u201d\n\nIt is absolutely true that Griner resonates with people, and now many of her fans are up in arms. If the goal was to quietly negotiate Griner\u2019s return, those days are done. At this point, there is really no choice but to shine the brightest possible light on this political injustice and demand that she be sent home. Political prisoners are rarely freed easily. It requires\u2014and demands\u2014an international response. Brittney Griner is a basketball titan who deserves more than to be treated like a pawn.","url":"https://www.thenation.com/article/society/brittney-griner-russia/"},"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777":{"id":"3696778c-1413-4c29-8976-176bc7d22c08_1026083777","text":"Skip to main content\n\nBrittney Griner Reveals What Happened At Russian Airport\n\nWith Brittney Griner pleading guilty to drug charges in Russia, new details on what happened leading to her arrest have been revealed.\n\nAppearing in court this week, Griner pleaded guilty to bringing hashish oil into Russia. She asked the judge for mercy and said that she had done so inadvertently.\n\nGriner explained that she accidentally packed vape cartridges into her luggage, leading to her detainment. She said she had no intention of breaking the law.\n\n\"I'd like to plead guilty, your honor. But there was no intent. I didn't want to break the law,\" Griner said.\u00a0\n\nUnfortunately for Brittney Griner, pleading guilty won't mean the end for her court proceedings in Russia. Far from it.\n\nRussian courts can drag on the proceedings for months as the judge lists off charges and reads the full case record into.\u00a0\n\nGriner will give her full testimony on July 14 and faces up to 10 years in prison if convicted for large-scale transportation of drugs.\u00a0\n\nBut according to ESPN, this may be part of a diplomatic strategy to bring Griner home in a prisoner swap. Though it may also be an acknowledgement that an acquittal was impossible.\u00a0\n\nThe bar for being acquitted in Russia is already extremely high given the nation's high conviction rate. And even if found acquitted, Russian courts can overturn the acquittal anyway.\n\nWill this move get us any steps closer to bringing Brittney Griner back?","url":"https://thespun.com/more/top-stories/brittney-griner-reveals-what-happened-at-russian-airport"},"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971":{"id":"530d83be-f15c-4cbb-84ed-9a507a8e94fa_323326971","text":"Sports\n\nActions\n\nFormer Olympic coach pushes for Brittney Griner's safe return as Russian trial begins\n\nPosted at 5:55 AM, Jul 01, 2022\nand last updated 2022-07-01 09:08:18-04\n\nAs Phoenix Mercury star Brittney Griner\u2019s trial begins in Russia, many are working to keep her story top of mind here in the United States.\n\nABC15 spoke to Griner\u2019s former Olympic coach, Dawn Staley, who\u2019s taken to social media almost daily to try to keep Griner\u2019s case at the forefront.\n\nStaley\u2019s posts are similar: a photo of her shirt she\u2019s wearing that day with a pin that reads, \u201cWe Are BG,\u201d along with a caption numbering the days Griner has been in detainment.\n\n\u201cShe\u2019s a good person. She has a great heart. She is, you know, someone that looks out for the voiceless. She supplies sneakers to the homeless, to the needy, and I don\u2019t think we\u2019re hearing enough about that,\u201d Staley said. \u201cI don\u2019t think we\u2019re hearing enough about what\u2019s been happening to get her released.\u201d\n\nStaley is currently the head women\u2019s basketball coach for the South Carolina Gamecocks, but also helped coach Griner through two gold medals for Team USA.\n\nStaley said she considers Griner and her wife, Cherelle, to be friends of hers. She\u2019s known Griner for about a decade.\n\n\u201cI want Brittney home. I just feel for her family. I feel for her. I feel for our women\u2019s basketball community. I feel for her friends,\u201d Staley said.\n\nIf convicted, the star center could face up to a decade in a Russian prison. She\u2019d then need the United States government to make a prisoner exchange with Russia involving her.\n\nCoach Staley said she hopes people here in America keep the pressure and the attention on BG\u2019s case to bring her home, and every American prisoner being wrongfully detained home as well.\n\n\u201cThey all need to get home to their families,\u201d Staley said. \u201cI just hope that people can find it in their hearts to put good energy into bringing Brittney home.\u201d\n\nStaley encouraged people to call their representatives in Congress, call the White House, and go support the Mercury by going to their games and holding up signs in support of Griner to keep the spotlight on her case.\n\nIt\u2019s notable to say that 99 percent of cases in Russia are convictions.\n\nLast weekend, Secretary of State Antony Blinken told CNN he would not comment in detail on what they\u2019re doing as far as Griner\u2019s situation and other American prisoners wrongfully detained, other than that it is a top priority for the Biden administration.","url":"https://www.abc15.com/sports/former-olympic-coach-pushes-for-brittney-griners-safe-return-as-russian-trial-begins"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1093","request_id":"1093","narrative_id":"1093"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism is defined as the negative effects of excessive tourist activity in a destination, leading to environmental degradation and a decline in the quality of life for local residents."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"The phenomenon arises from decades of unchecked tourism growth, resulting in overcrowded landmarks, rising rent prices, and traffic congestion in many destinations."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Social media exacerbates overtourism by spotlighting specific hotspots, drawing large crowds to areas ill-equipped to handle such influxes."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Economically, overtourism can drive up housing costs due to multinational investments in tourist accommodations, making living conditions unaffordable for locals."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"While tourism generates jobs, these positions often fail to provide a living wage, leaving local communities economically vulnerable."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Socially, overtourism can lead to resource allocation favoring tourists over residents, sparking protests and backlash in affected areas."},{"citations":{"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":100.0},"text":"Environmentally, overtourism contributes to the climate crisis, accounting for approximately 8% of global emissions, and causes degradation of natural habitats and infrastructure."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Destinations like Venice, Italy, face subsidence and flooding due to overtourism, while measures such as tourist taxes have had limited success in curbing visitor numbers."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine ecosystems are particularly vulnerable, as seen in Taiwan\u2019s Penghu Island, where coral reefs suffer from overcrowding and harmful sunscreen ingredients."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Global hotspots such as Barcelona, Dubrovnik, and Iceland illustrate the widespread impacts of overtourism, including overcrowding and diminished visitor experiences."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Proposed solutions include proactive planning, tourist education, and regulatory measures like limiting visitor numbers and promoting sustainable practices."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine protected areas and ocean-friendly education initiatives are being implemented to safeguard ecosystems while enabling sustainable recreation."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism is defined as the negative effects of excessive tourist activity in a destination, leading to environmental degradation and a decline in the quality of life for local residents."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"The phenomenon arises from decades of unchecked tourism growth, resulting in overcrowded landmarks, rising rent prices, and traffic congestion in many destinations."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Social media exacerbates overtourism by spotlighting specific hotspots, drawing large crowds to areas ill-equipped to handle such influxes."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Economically, overtourism can drive up housing costs due to multinational investments in tourist accommodations, making living conditions unaffordable for locals."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"While tourism generates jobs, these positions often fail to provide a living wage, leaving local communities economically vulnerable."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Socially, overtourism can lead to resource allocation favoring tourists over residents, sparking protests and backlash in affected areas."},{"citations":{"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":100.0},"text":"Environmentally, overtourism contributes to the climate crisis, accounting for approximately 8% of global emissions, and causes degradation of natural habitats and infrastructure."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Destinations like Venice, Italy, face subsidence and flooding due to overtourism, while measures such as tourist taxes have had limited success in curbing visitor numbers."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine ecosystems are particularly vulnerable, as seen in Taiwan\u2019s Penghu Island, where coral reefs suffer from overcrowding and harmful sunscreen ingredients."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Global hotspots such as Barcelona, Dubrovnik, and Iceland illustrate the widespread impacts of overtourism, including overcrowding and diminished visitor experiences."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Proposed solutions include proactive planning, tourist education, and regulatory measures like limiting visitor numbers and promoting sustainable practices."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine protected areas and ocean-friendly education initiatives are being implemented to safeguard ecosystems while enabling sustainable recreation."}],"references":["b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965","044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629","4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106","a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654","70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688"],"documents":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":{"id":"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654","text":"\nMenu\n\nSedona Film Festival presents \u2018Crowded Out\u2019\n\n\n\u201cCrowded Out\u201d is a powerful short documentary exploring over-tourism, featuring interviews with local residents and global experts. (Image provided by SIFF)\n\n\nOriginally Published: September 14, 2022 8:43 p.m.\n\nThe Sedona International Film Festival is proud to present the third film in its four-week Sustainable Tourism Film Series. \u201cCrowded Out: The Story of Overtourism\u201d will show on Thursday, Sept. 22 at the Mary D. Fisher Theatre at 4 p.m. The event will also include a selection of \u201cSustainable Travel: Where Next?\u201d short films along with a panel discussion.\n\n\u201cCrowded Out\u201d is a powerful short documentary exploring overtourism, featuring interviews with local residents and global experts.\n\nOvertourism occurs when there are too many visitors to a particular destination. When rent prices push out local tenants to make way for holiday rentals, when narrow roads become jammed with tourist vehicles, when tourists cannot view landmarks because of the crowds \u2013 these are all signs of overtourism.\n\nAnd it is the backlash from local residents that has made overtourism news. Cities such as Barcelona, Venice and Dubrovnik, and places once thought of as remote such as Iceland and Skye have suffered firsthand, and the protests by local residents have spread.\n\nThere has been decades of virtually uncontrolled growth, and it has crossed a threshold: in many destinations, tourism now demonstrably creates more problems than benefits.\n\nThis special event will also include a selection of short films from \u201cSustainable Travel: Where Next?\u201d This series includes short-form documentary films, featuring insightful stories from the global travel and tourism sector showing how they are driving sustainable travel and protecting these precious destinations.\n\nFollowing the screenings, there will be a panel discussion with representatives the City of Sedona, the Sedona Chamber of Commerce, Keep Sedona Beautiful and the tourism and hospitality industry here.\n\n\u201cCrowded Out: The Story of Overtourism\u201d will be shown at the Mary D. Fisher Theatre on Thursday, Sept. 22 at 4 p.m. Tickets are $12, or $9 for Film Festival members. For tickets and more information, please call 928-282-1177. Both the theatre and film festival office are located at 2030 W. Hwy. 89A, in West Sedona. For more information, visit: www.SedonaFilmFestival.org.\n\nThe final film in the Sustainable Tourism Series is:\n\nThursday, Sept. 29 at 4 p.m. \u201cVendemmia\u201d","url":"https://www.verdenews.com/news/2022/sep/14/sedona-film-festival-presents-crowded-out/"},"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":{"id":"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106","text":"Point of view\nLin Chi-yin\nLin Chi-yin: \"Traveling Everywhere\" and \"Over-Travel\"\nEarlier, the Director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, Hsia Baolong, advocated the concept of \u201ctravel everywhere \u201d to fully explore Hong Kong \u2019 s tourism resources.\nTo speed up the implementation of the concept, the authorities are planning to set up a \"special class\" to bring together people inside and outside the Government for in-depth discussions.\nIn recent days, officials and legislators have expressed their views on the development of \"red tourism\", exploring new spots in the community, beautifying the streets, and presenting some scenes in the movies.\nSimply put, it may be the story behind the attraction, or the accumulated word of mouth on social media, and every tree and grass anywhere can become a tourist attraction.\nOf course, the author hopes that the \"class\" can launch various new ideas; and since the task of the class is to implement the concept of \"travel everywhere\", then how to implement the concept is the best for Hong Kong, the industry, the community and the public, the class can not ignore.\nThe University of Hong Kong campus has been forced by tourists, and the school has implemented reservation measures this month.\nHKU itself has a complete management structure, and the university can still implement crowd control according to the situation. However, if some scenic spots that go deep into the community or even close to residential buildings are really \"red hot\", it may not be easy to implement crowd control.\n\u201cEverywhere travel \u201d is a concept, the key to implementation lies in the ability of the authorities to foresee problems. If you rely only on\u201c see and see \u201d, it is very likely that good things will turn into bad things.\n\u201cAggressive \u201d Travel\nIn 2018, the word \u201covertourism \u201d was chosen as the Oxford English Dictionary \u2019 s word of the year, referring to the negative effects of overloading the area, declining quality of life and environmental damage caused by the influx of tourists to tourist attractions.\nFor example, Venice, Italy, which has long been affected by \u201covertourism \u201d, is not a\u201c once in a lifetime \u201d \u2013 the local population is only 50,000, and the number of daily tourists has exceeded the local population; during peak season, the number of daily visitors has even doubled.\nI have friends who visited the place more than a decade ago, and they all agreed to say that people are crowded and will not go again.\nIn addition to Venice, some European cities or small islands with a tourism-led economy (such as the Canarias in Spain) also face the problem of job opportunities, high prices, and a homogenization of shops. Multinational companies invest heavily in hotels and holiday cottages, which also lead to higher rents, which locals can \u2019 t afford.\nEven if tourism brings a lot of jobs to the region, it does not mean that the average person can earn a living wage.\nPeople in these places understand the importance of tourism to the local economy, but they do not want the tourism industry to be unlimited, resulting in the resources of the whole place are only for the service of tourists.\n\"Tourism Hazards\" and How to Deal with them\nIn Japanese society after the epidemic, a similar term, \"tourism nuisance\", has also appeared to describe problems such as traffic, noise, nuisance, and garbage pollution caused by too many tourists.\nThis phenomenon, in addition to the popularity of exchange rates, affordable air tickets, and people's desire to travel after the epidemic, social media will also have the effect of focusing on specific hot spots.\nIn the era of image-led, everyone can follow the picture, some places that were not originally planned as tourist attractions have begun to face sudden overcrowding.\nHong Kong people who love to visit Japan will not be unfamiliar with two \u201cattractions \u201d: the Daokou near Enojima Electric Railway \u2019 s Kamakura University Station, and a Lawson convenience store in Kawaguchi-cho.\nThe former is the \"holy place\" of the popular manga \"When Men are in the bottle\". In recent years, the crossing has been congested with traffic due to frequent visits by tourists to \"punch\", local people can not get on the electric train, and some tourists are dangerous for taking good photos. Lawson is also a \"punch\" attraction, and the picture is a convenience store with a beautiful view of Mount Fuji. of tourists are constantly crossing the road and parking without permission, causing local residents to feel troubled.\nToo many tourists can also lead to a decline in the quality of service, even in Japan, which values the spirit of \u201cwork people \u201d.\nWhen I visited Japan last year, I saw some shops find ways to deal with \u201ctourism hazards \u201d on their own, such as not allowing diners to take photos in the store, so that after the photos are uploaded to social media, it will cause more people to come and see them; limiting the number of diners to the number of people that the staff can serve, even if the seats are not full.\nHowever, some tourists always find it difficult to understand the intentions behind these arrangements, and I have heard some tourists complain: \"Obviously there is still a place, why not let us sit?\"\nWhen these conflicts can no longer be handled by businesses and residents themselves, how to strike a balance between \u201ctourism \u201d and\u201c public nuisance \u201d will gradually become a policy issue.\nThe most extreme way to deal with it is to \u201celiminate \u201d popular attractions \u2013 coincidentally, the authorities of Kawaguchiko recently erected a 20-meter-long and 2.5-meter-high\u201c black curtain \u201d in front of Lawson to drive away tourists who came to take photos.\nThe reason why the authorities have to take extreme measures is that management alone can not prevent tourists from rushing out of the road, which is actually to \"play the spot\".\nIn addition, there are more and more tourist cities and hotspots charging tourists \"admission fees\" or \"admission fees\", but this method can not play a large role.\nIn Venice, for example, the city has been charging a 5 euro entry fee (about HK $42) to \u201covernight \u201d travelers since last month.\nHowever, these fees simply cannot curb the huge demand for tourists, and the revenue is mainly used as a financial source to cope with \"excessive travel\", which can only cure the symptoms, not the root cause.\nThe Real Meaning of \u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d\nAt this point, some people may point out that the above problems will only become problems if we succeed in attracting tourists to Hong Kong; what we have to focus on is how to get more people to come to Hong Kong.\nHowever, how much tourism can bring to a city depends on the management and policies of the city, not on the remedial measures that can be taken.\nAlthough the share of tourism industry in Hong Kong's economy is far less than that of the \"tourist city\" mentioned above, Hong Kong can't wait to see that other places are looking for countermeasures for the \"tourism nuisance\", and even start to turn to attack, redefine the tourism industry from the planning level and actively promote tourist education.\nIn Amsterdam, the Netherlands, for example, the government announced last month that it would ban new hotels and limit the number of cruise ships to return the city to a livable and tourism-friendly city. In Kamakura, Japan, people are no longer concentrated at certain points by decentralizing transportation (such as the launch of electric tricycle rental business) and proactively promoting multiple circumnavigation routes (such as the travel routes at 13 locations of Kamakura Shogunate).\nThe main disadvantage of post-event remediation is that the difficulty and cost of solving the problem are greatly increased, which will also affect the experience of tourists. More than 10 years ago, the North District of Hong Kong also experienced a pharmacy every few steps, and the situation of residents in the North District driving out water consignors on their own, which hurt the feelings of the people of the two places.\nIn particular, there are many policy issues that can be foreseen in advance, and we do not have to go through them personally before we know what the problem is (for example, the legal problems faced by cleaners under the garbage levy will not be known until the moment of trial).\nSince there is a great deal of experience and policy measures in various places to refer to, the \u201cSpecial Class \u201d must also strike a balance between tourism and city operations when formulating tourist routes and supporting packages, otherwise the attraction will only lead to losses. After the city of Kamakura solved the problem of overcrowding of tourists, the tourism industry representative of Kanagawa Prefecture (that is, the seat of Kamakura City) pointed out:\u201c Attraction is not tourism. \u201d The amount of time it takes to win is certainly not appropriate.\n\u201cTravel Everywhere \u201d is not just about adding tourist attractions, but promoting quality tourism in a more nuanced and proactive way to avoid problems.\nThe author is a public policy consultant.\n\u25a0 Articles\n1.\nForum version is open park, welcome to submit.\nForum articles are limited to 2300 words. Please email to forum @ mingpao.com, fax: 2898 3783.\n2. The editor of this paper reserves the right to delete the article based on the space limit, but in order to maintain the main points and positions of the article as the principle; if you do not want the article to be deleted, please indicate.\n3.\nPlease attach the author's real name and contact information (can be published under a pen name), please do not submit one manuscript twice; if not applicable, without prior notice, except for those with postage return, this paper will not return the manuscript.\n4.\nNote to Contributors: Once an article is published, we have exclusive local rights to publish the article in Chinese. This right also includes the right to republish the article in local and overseas media (including electronic media, such as Internet sites).\nIn addition, we have the right to grant the right to use the copy of the article to the relevant copying authorizing companies and organizations.\nThe above rights in this paper do not affect the copyright of the contributor and their rights and interests.\n(Criticism of current affairs articles published by this website is aimed at pointing out errors or deficiencies in relevant systems, policies or measures, with the aim of correcting or eliminating such errors or deficiencies, and improving them through lawful means, with no intention of inciting hatred, dissatisfaction or hostility towards the Government or other communities)\n[Lin Chi-yin]\nPrevious / Next News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0014.json.gz:7215","uncompressed_offset":38011106,"url":"news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A7%80%E9%BB%9E/article/20240528/s00012/1716827737305/%E6%9E%97%E7%B7%BB%E8%8C%B5-%E3%80%8C%E7%84%A1%E8%99%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D%E8%88%87%E3%80%8C%E9%81%8E%E5%BA%A6%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D","warc_date":"2024-05-28T03:20:38.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9>","warc_url":"https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A7%80%E9%BB%9E/article/20240528/s00012/1716827737305/%E6%9E%97%E7%B7%BB%E8%8C%B5-%E3%80%8C%E7%84%A1%E8%99%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D%E8%88%87%E3%80%8C%E9%81%8E%E5%BA%A6%E6%97%85%E9%81%8A%E3%80%8D"},"created":"2024-05-28T03:25:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":{"id":"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965","text":"Ecology and Development Ocean Recreation Can Be Sustainable\nAs the COVID-19 pandemic slows, people return to social and natural environments, including recreational and sightseeing activities.\nIn Taiwan, surrounded by the sea, the popularity of water recreation activities can be expected.\nIn a world where isolation has ended, people have gone out in waves, and the term \u201cretaliatory travel \u201d has emerged, representing not only a doubling of recreational activities that could not be done during the past epidemic, but also the sudden impact of recreational activities on the economic, social and ecological environment.\nThe beautiful ocean attracts people to get close to each other, but with the rising tide of ocean recreation, how to maintain the balance between economic development and marine ecology is an important issue.\nThe pollution generated by a large number of marine recreational activities includes garbage and sewage. Can the basic services in coastal areas handle and accommodate this pollution? What is the impact on marine ecology?\nWhether it is from the perspective of passenger experience, environmental protection, or local residents, it will not be a happy situation.\nSince the epidemic slowed in 2022, popular marine activities such as Hsiao Liuchiu are facing an unprecedented influx of tourists. Visitors to the intertidal zone and water sports are almost filling the sea, not to mention the impact on the marine habitats in this area.\nFor example, millions of tourists visit Penghu Island, which has exceeded the water consumption that the local area can provide; a large number of tourists go into the water activities, but do not pay attention to whether sunscreen or cosmetics ingredients are friendly to the marine environment, and the crowd has led to more stampedes on coral reefs.\nAccording to Greenpeace \u2019 s August survey in Little Ryukyu, the coral around Little Ryukyu and its associated populations are gradually declining.\nTake snorkeling for all ages, for example, tourists are full of expectations to prepare for snorkeling, but they can see the water is full of people.\nIt was hard to squeeze into the water but found that the water only saw the hands and feet of other tourists, garbage and bleached dead coral; in the beautiful coral reef, the fish did not see a few, what is the mood? It must be a bad experience.\nIn addition to increasing development opportunities for local residents, the hotel also attracts external investment, such as a corporate group planning to build an international hotel in Hsiao Ryukyu. However, because the land area does not meet the standard of environmental evaluation, causing local residents to protest, and its impact on the marine ecology is also a hidden concern.\nIn order to take into account the development of marine recreation and marine ecology, it is necessary to carry out appropriate policy planning and implement management measures in existing marine protected areas or marine recreation spots.\nIn the case of Keelung Tidal Amusement Park, for example, because of the rapid increase in recreational population, marine recreational activities were started in 2023; for example, diving requires an international license and prior application to launch, and the total number of people allowed to swim is controlled.\nIn areas that do not have a clear management area, marine protection zones can be planned and relevant regulatory measures can be formulated to effectively manage pro-sea activities, avoid tourists from returning home, and reduce the damage to the living environment of local residents, so that the marine ecosystem can be sustainable.\nIt is important to develop marine education and cultivate the concept of ocean friendliness for all people to be close to the ocean in order to jointly safeguard the marine ecological environment.\nExtended reading\nChun-mi Zhou: Don 't doubt my determination to protect Ryukyu Island\nSmall Ryukyu ecological resources recession operators: the responsibility of tourism to reduce environmental impact\nFish Resource Depletion, Coral Ecosystem Decline Liuqiu Tourism Industry Raises Alert\nGuest Video Suddenly Out of Control Pants Chen Po-lin See 18 Banned Face Stunned\nRelated News\nJust ask for carbon. Just think again.\nSultan Al Jaber, chief executive of the global oil and gas giant Abu Dhabi National Oil Company and chairman of the United Nations Climate Conference (COP28) at the end of this year.\nEcology and Development Ocean Recreation Can Be Sustainable\nAs the COVID-19 pandemic slows, people return to social and natural environments, including recreational and sightseeing activities.\nIn Taiwan, surrounded by the sea on all sides, the popularity of water recreation activities can be expected.\nEnvironmental injustice in forest planting\nThe Financial Times reported that since 2019, Indonesia has combined multinational companies from the United States, China, Brazil and Hong Kong to destroy 23,000 hectares of forest in order to extract nickel.\nEnergy construction is ignorance or foolishness?\nDPP presidential candidate Lai Qingde yesterday launched energy policy ideas, he said that he will through the \"second energy transformation\", \"digital and green industry two-axis transformation\", \"promote sustainable green living\"...\nProduct recommendation\nudn Forum","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0030.json.gz:22956","uncompressed_offset":563043965,"url":"udn.com/news/story/7339/7517364","warc_date":"2023-10-19T20:56:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234>","warc_url":"https://udn.com/news/story/7339/7517364"},"created":"2023-10-19T21:21:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":{"id":"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nThe Guardian: Tourism contributes significantly to the climate crisis\nIt is a terrible paradox of the climate crisis that some of the most beautiful \u2013 and popular \u2013 places in the world are also the most vulnerable, especially as most of them have poor infrastructure, which means that with rising temperatures, increasing weather extremes, drying up water sources and the death of natural habitats, these places face another devastating loss, especially tourists.\nTourism contributes significantly to the climate crisis \u2013 around 8% of global emissions \u2013 and hordes of visitors cause many problems, including excessive development and degradation of natural areas.\nThe revenue generated by tourists can bring enormous economic benefits to these destinations, and many do not own other forms of industry or otherwise rely on extractive industries such as mining or logging.\nShe added that tourism can also spread awareness of environmental problems, such as bleaching coral reefs or endangered animal species, and provide funding for conservation efforts.\nThis complex relationship was highlighted during the coronavirus outbreak, when tourism stopped, carbon emissions dropped, wildlife flourished, and leatherback turtles in Thailand laid the largest number of eggs in two decades, but all this has come at a cost, with the global tourism industry taking a heavy toll, triggering an emergency in developing countries, families struggling to find food, illegal logging in some places has increased, and overfishing has increased.\nAs the rebuilding of tourism begins, it has become impossible to ignore that the future of the industry is inextricably linked to the climate crisis.\nInstead of becoming a major cause of the climate crisis, tourism can be used to raise awareness, increase tourism resources and improve infrastructure.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0035.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":604162629,"url":"www.dostor.org/3645314","warc_date":"2021-12-03T18:03:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/3645314"},"created":"2021-12-03T18:30:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":{"id":"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688","text":"For best browsing results, we recommend using Chrome, Firefox or Microsoft Edge browsers.\nPlease download from Edge official website, please download from FireFox official website, please download from Google official website\nLimitation level\nYou must be at least 18 years old to view the news content you are about to enter.\nIn accordance with the provisions of Paragraph 3 of Article 6 of the amended Regulations on the Classification and Processing of Computer Network Content, it has been marked on the homepage of the website or each of the restricted pages in accordance with the provisions of the Taiwan Website Rating Promotion Foundation.\nTICRF Website: http: / / www.ticrf.org.tw\nJapan 's Mount Fuji Exposed in 2024 \"9 Top Places to Avoid Visiting\"\nMount Fuji, Japan. (Photo, Euronews)\n2023 / 12 / 10 15: 45\nLi Xinjie / Editor-in-Chief\n[Real-Time News / Comprehensive Report] As 2024 approaches, many people are already excited to prepare for various plans to travel abroad.\nHowever, the well-known American travel magazine Fodor \u2019 s Travel (Fodor \u2019 s Travel) announced next year \u2019 s \u201c9 Best Places to Visit in the World \u201d, calling on tourists to carefully consider avoiding these famous but much-needed hot spots, and mentioning that these areas are affected by environmental pollution and tourism hazards.\nAmong them, Mount Fuji in Japan, which Taiwanese love, is also on the list.\nAccording to a comprehensive foreign media report, among the nine \u201cNo List \u201d listed by Fodor Travel on its official website in 2024, four of them are in Asia and the rest are in Europe and the United States.\nAccording to the official website, the original intention of the evaluation is not to deliberately suppress partial generalization, but to \"respect\" as the starting point of the declaration, this time to open the list of avoid visits, but also focus on tourists to nine tourist attractions and dependent local communities, resulting in \"excessive tourism\", \"excessive waste generation\", \"affect water resources\" these three major impacts.\nAt the same time, Fodor Tourism also pointed out that these nine tourist hotspots are deeply affected by the \"Instagram effect\", because the beauty of these places is circulating around the world, causing tourism.\nFinally, Fodor Tourism also calls on tourists around the world to let go of these areas when planning their 2024 travel plans, but also to be careful to protect the local environment and culture, and to respect the people and places everywhere.\nMount Fuji, Japan\nThe number of climbers at the site has skyrocketed in recent years, but local authorities and people have pointed out that many do not fully understand the risks involved in climbing Mount Fuji, resulting in overcrowding at the top of the sacred mountain and putting themselves at risk.\nIn addition, many climbers are unwilling to pay 1,000 yen (about NT $200) for safety and environmental maintenance, and even leave a lot of garbage and urine filled bottles, which can only be cleaned by volunteers, causing headaches.\nHa Long Bay, Vietnam\nThe local waters attract a large number of international tourists to vacation, including snorkeling, water sports and fishing activities, which also lead to the local garbage load, the waters are full of garbage and diesel, and the local government \u2019 s poor implementation of pollution policies, it is very easy to be avoided by operators, so that the natural ecology of the area is facing unbearable pollution.\nKoh Samui, Thailand\nThe island has been plagued by fresh water shortages for nearly a year, and the influx of tourists has consumed up to 70% of the region \u2019 s precious water resources, seriously exacerbating the island \u2019 s freshwater shortage.\nGanges, India\nThe river, regarded as the source of life for the people of India, has faced problems such as reduced flow, garbage pollution, and endangered freshwater dolphins in recent years, which have been exacerbated by the emerging luxury cruise industry.\nAthens, Greece\nThe lack of a tourism hazard management plan by the local government does not mean that the world heritage is in danger of being destroyed, but also that the traditional way of life of the local people is being destroyed by a large number of tourists.\nThe Acropolis has already implemented a daily visitor limit, which has been reduced from 23,000 to 20,000 per day, and the Parthenon Temple to 17,000.\nItaly (Venice)\nVenice has long been affected by subsidence, flooding, and the damage caused by the increasing number of tourists, adding to the stress of this ancient and fragile city, and adversely affecting the local environment and residents.\nAlthough the local government has taken several specific measures to try to reduce tourists, including charging a tourist tax of 5 euros (about NT $171) for all visitors over 14 years old who come to the city for a \u201cday trip \u201d between the end of April and mid-July next year, it is still considered unlikely to improve the problem.\nSan Gabriel Mountains National Monument, California\nThis \u201cnatural oasis \u201d in Los Angeles County, due to the number of tourists and lack of environmental awareness, not only is the monument graffiti by tourists, but even littering everywhere, causing the local environment to suffer a lot of damage.\nLake Superior (United States \u2013 Canada border)\nLake Superior, on the border between the United States and Canada, is the largest freshwater lake on the planet, and its ecology is now exposed to a variety of hazards due to human visits, including species invasion, rapid algal blooms, and fish consumption warnings.\nChile's Atacama Desert\nThe Atacama Desert, on the Pacific coast, is a spectacular natural beauty of deserts, geysers, lagoons, salt mines, cliffs and peaks, but the local environment is polluted by \"fast fashion\" and unfortunately becomes a landfill.\nNo need to smoke, no need to grab, now use the APP to watch the news, guarantee the daily winning point I download the APP\nRelated News\nInternational hot today.\n2024 Presidential Legislative Election\nSee more!\nPlease join the Free Times fan group.\nNetizens respond.\nThis page has been idle for more than 5 minutes. Please click on the transparent black bottom or the X button at the bottom right corner.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0035.json.gz:13336","uncompressed_offset":605618688,"url":"news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/4516465","warc_date":"2023-12-10T08:21:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e>","warc_url":"https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/4516465"},"created":"2023-12-10T09:04:09.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1094","request_id":"1094","narrative_id":"1094"},"responses":[{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism refers to the negative effects of overloading an area, including declining quality of life and environmental damage caused by an influx of tourists."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"It occurs when there are too many visitors to a particular destination, leading to issues such as rising rent prices, traffic congestion, and overcrowded landmarks."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Decades of virtually uncontrolled tourism growth have led to a point where tourism creates more problems than benefits in many destinations."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"European cities and small islands with tourism-led economies, such as the Canarias in Spain, face challenges like job opportunities, high prices, and homogenization of shops due to overtourism."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Multinational investments in hotels and holiday cottages in overtourism hotspots have driven up rents, making housing unaffordable for locals."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Despite tourism creating jobs, it does not always ensure a living wage for residents in affected areas."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism can result in local resources being disproportionately allocated to serve tourists, often at the expense of the local community's needs."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Local resident backlash against overtourism has become a prominent issue, with protests spreading in affected areas."},{"citations":{"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":100.0},"text":"Tourism contributes significantly to the climate crisis, accounting for around 8% of global emissions."},{"citations":{"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":100.0},"text":"Hordes of visitors cause problems such as excessive development and degradation of natural areas."},{"citations":{"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":100.0},"text":"Many popular tourist destinations are vulnerable due to poor infrastructure, rising temperatures, increasing weather extremes, drying water sources, and the death of natural habitats."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Mount Fuji in Japan has experienced overcrowding due to a surge in climbers, many of whom leave garbage and urine-filled bottles, creating environmental and safety concerns."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Ha Long Bay in Vietnam faces severe pollution issues, including garbage and diesel in the waters, exacerbated by poor enforcement of pollution policies."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Koh Samui in Thailand suffers from freshwater shortages, with tourists consuming up to 70% of the region's water resources, worsening the crisis."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"The Ganges River in India is dealing with reduced flow, garbage pollution, and threats to freshwater dolphins, worsened by the luxury cruise industry."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Athens, Greece, struggles with the impact of overtourism on its world heritage sites and the traditional way of life, prompting visitor limits at the Acropolis and Parthenon Temple."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Venice, Italy, faces subsidence, flooding, and environmental stress due to overtourism, despite measures like a tourist tax to reduce visitor numbers."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"The San Gabriel Mountains National Monument in California suffers from environmental damage caused by graffiti and littering by tourists."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Lake Superior, the largest freshwater lake on Earth, is threatened by species invasion, algal blooms, and fish consumption warnings due to human activity."},{"citations":{"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":100.0},"text":"Chile's Atacama Desert is polluted by fast fashion waste, turning parts of the natural landscape into a landfill."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine recreational activities in Taiwan, such as those in Hsiao Liuchiu, have faced an unprecedented influx of tourists since the pandemic slowed in 2022, leading to significant impacts on marine habitats."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Millions of tourists visiting Penghu Island have exceeded the local water consumption capacity, and activities like snorkeling have caused damage to coral reefs due to overcrowding and harmful sunscreen ingredients."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"A Greenpeace survey in Little Ryukyu found that coral populations are gradually declining due to the influx of tourists and associated environmental pressures."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Overcrowding in marine recreational areas has led to poor tourist experiences, with visitors encountering garbage, bleached coral, and a lack of marine life."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Venice, Italy, is a prominent example of overtourism, where the daily number of tourists often exceeds the local population of 50,000, doubling during peak seasons."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism in Venice has led to overcrowding, making the destination less appealing to visitors and negatively impacting the local community."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Cities such as Barcelona, Venice, and Dubrovnik, as well as remote destinations like Iceland and Skye, have experienced significant impacts from overtourism."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Social media contributes to overtourism by focusing attention on specific hotspots, leading to overcrowding in areas not originally designed for tourism."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"The term 'retaliatory travel' has emerged, representing a surge in recreational activities following the COVID-19 pandemic, which has caused sudden impacts on economic, social, and ecological environments."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Some businesses in Japan have implemented measures to mitigate overtourism impacts, such as limiting customer numbers and prohibiting photography to reduce social media-driven crowds."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Extreme measures, such as erecting barriers or charging entry fees, have been used in some hotspots to manage overtourism, though these often address symptoms rather than root causes."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Venice has introduced a 5 euro entry fee for day visitors, but this has not significantly curbed tourist demand and primarily serves as a financial resource for managing overtourism."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Amsterdam has implemented policies like banning new hotels and limiting cruise ships to restore balance between tourism and livability."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Kamakura, Japan, has decentralized transportation and promoted multiple travel routes to reduce overcrowding at specific attractions."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine protected areas and regulatory measures, such as controlling the number of swimmers and requiring international licenses for diving, are being implemented to manage recreational activities and protect ecosystems."},{"citations":{"b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234_563043965":100.0},"text":"Marine education and fostering ocean-friendly concepts are essential for safeguarding marine ecological environments while promoting sustainable recreation."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Proactive planning and tourist education are essential to managing overtourism and avoiding post-event remediation, which is often costly and disruptive."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Overtourism refers to the negative effects of overloading an area, including declining quality of life and environmental damage caused by an influx of tourists."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"It occurs when there are too many visitors to a particular destination, leading to issues such as rising rent prices, traffic congestion, and overcrowded landmarks."},{"citations":{"a90fed0f-41a3-49e4-85e1-ade7b9b5f6fa_334539654":100.0},"text":"Decades of virtually uncontrolled tourism growth have led to a point where tourism creates more problems than benefits in many destinations."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"European cities and small islands with tourism-led economies, such as the Canarias in Spain, face challenges like job opportunities, high prices, and homogenization of shops due to overtourism."},{"citations":{"4bd649f2-da29-4279-8605-12dc0f8367d9_38011106":100.0},"text":"Multinat