be a happy situation.\nSince the epidemic slowed in 2022, popular marine activities such as Hsiao Liuchiu are facing an unprecedented influx of tourists. Visitors to the intertidal zone and water sports are almost filling the sea, not to mention the impact on the marine habitats in this area.\nFor example, millions of tourists visit Penghu Island, which has exceeded the water consumption that the local area can provide; a large number of tourists go into the water activities, but do not pay attention to whether sunscreen or cosmetics ingredients are friendly to the marine environment, and the crowd has led to more stampedes on coral reefs.\nAccording to Greenpeace \u2019 s August survey in Little Ryukyu, the coral around Little Ryukyu and its associated populations are gradually declining.\nTake snorkeling for all ages, for example, tourists are full of expectations to prepare for snorkeling, but they can see the water is full of people.\nIt was hard to squeeze into the water but found that the water only saw the hands and feet of other tourists, garbage and bleached dead coral; in the beautiful coral reef, the fish did not see a few, what is the mood? It must be a bad experience.\nIn addition to increasing development opportunities for local residents, the hotel also attracts external investment, such as a corporate group planning to build an international hotel in Hsiao Ryukyu. However, because the land area does not meet the standard of environmental evaluation, causing local residents to protest, and its impact on the marine ecology is also a hidden concern.\nIn order to take into account the development of marine recreation and marine ecology, it is necessary to carry out appropriate policy planning and implement management measures in existing marine protected areas or marine recreation spots.\nIn the case of Keelung Tidal Amusement Park, for example, because of the rapid increase in recreational population, marine recreational activities were started in 2023; for example, diving requires an international license and prior application to launch, and the total number of people allowed to swim is controlled.\nIn areas that do not have a clear management area, marine protection zones can be planned and relevant regulatory measures can be formulated to effectively manage pro-sea activities, avoid tourists from returning home, and reduce the damage to the living environment of local residents, so that the marine ecosystem can be sustainable.\nIt is important to develop marine education and cultivate the concept of ocean friendliness for all people to be close to the ocean in order to jointly safeguard the marine ecological environment.\nExtended reading\nChun-mi Zhou: Don 't doubt my determination to protect Ryukyu Island\nSmall Ryukyu ecological resources recession operators: the responsibility of tourism to reduce environmental impact\nFish Resource Depletion, Coral Ecosystem Decline Liuqiu Tourism Industry Raises Alert\nGuest Video Suddenly Out of Control Pants Chen Po-lin See 18 Banned Face Stunned\nRelated News\nJust ask for carbon. Just think again.\nSultan Al Jaber, chief executive of the global oil and gas giant Abu Dhabi National Oil Company and chairman of the United Nations Climate Conference (COP28) at the end of this year.\nEcology and Development Ocean Recreation Can Be Sustainable\nAs the COVID-19 pandemic slows, people return to social and natural environments, including recreational and sightseeing activities.\nIn Taiwan, surrounded by the sea on all sides, the popularity of water recreation activities can be expected.\nEnvironmental injustice in forest planting\nThe Financial Times reported that since 2019, Indonesia has combined multinational companies from the United States, China, Brazil and Hong Kong to destroy 23,000 hectares of forest in order to extract nickel.\nEnergy construction is ignorance or foolishness?\nDPP presidential candidate Lai Qingde yesterday launched energy policy ideas, he said that he will through the \"second energy transformation\", \"digital and green industry two-axis transformation\", \"promote sustainable green living\"...\nProduct recommendation\nudn Forum","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0030.json.gz:22956","uncompressed_offset":563043965,"url":"udn.com/news/story/7339/7517364","warc_date":"2023-10-19T20:56:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b02f561f-2702-40d0-89c7-1262bbc6d234>","warc_url":"https://udn.com/news/story/7339/7517364"},"created":"2023-10-19T21:21:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629":{"id":"044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54_604162629","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nThe Guardian: Tourism contributes significantly to the climate crisis\nIt is a terrible paradox of the climate crisis that some of the most beautiful \u2013 and popular \u2013 places in the world are also the most vulnerable, especially as most of them have poor infrastructure, which means that with rising temperatures, increasing weather extremes, drying up water sources and the death of natural habitats, these places face another devastating loss, especially tourists.\nTourism contributes significantly to the climate crisis \u2013 around 8% of global emissions \u2013 and hordes of visitors cause many problems, including excessive development and degradation of natural areas.\nThe revenue generated by tourists can bring enormous economic benefits to these destinations, and many do not own other forms of industry or otherwise rely on extractive industries such as mining or logging.\nShe added that tourism can also spread awareness of environmental problems, such as bleaching coral reefs or endangered animal species, and provide funding for conservation efforts.\nThis complex relationship was highlighted during the coronavirus outbreak, when tourism stopped, carbon emissions dropped, wildlife flourished, and leatherback turtles in Thailand laid the largest number of eggs in two decades, but all this has come at a cost, with the global tourism industry taking a heavy toll, triggering an emergency in developing countries, families struggling to find food, illegal logging in some places has increased, and overfishing has increased.\nAs the rebuilding of tourism begins, it has become impossible to ignore that the future of the industry is inextricably linked to the climate crisis.\nInstead of becoming a major cause of the climate crisis, tourism can be used to raise awareness, increase tourism resources and improve infrastructure.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0035.json.gz:16397","uncompressed_offset":604162629,"url":"www.dostor.org/3645314","warc_date":"2021-12-03T18:03:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:044d6992-b71e-49ad-b4a4-f97ae3632c54>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/3645314"},"created":"2021-12-03T18:30:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688":{"id":"70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e_605618688","text":"For best browsing results, we recommend using Chrome, Firefox or Microsoft Edge browsers.\nPlease download from Edge official website, please download from FireFox official website, please download from Google official website\nLimitation level\nYou must be at least 18 years old to view the news content you are about to enter.\nIn accordance with the provisions of Paragraph 3 of Article 6 of the amended Regulations on the Classification and Processing of Computer Network Content, it has been marked on the homepage of the website or each of the restricted pages in accordance with the provisions of the Taiwan Website Rating Promotion Foundation.\nTICRF Website: http: / / www.ticrf.org.tw\nJapan 's Mount Fuji Exposed in 2024 \"9 Top Places to Avoid Visiting\"\nMount Fuji, Japan. (Photo, Euronews)\n2023 / 12 / 10 15: 45\nLi Xinjie / Editor-in-Chief\n[Real-Time News / Comprehensive Report] As 2024 approaches, many people are already excited to prepare for various plans to travel abroad.\nHowever, the well-known American travel magazine Fodor \u2019 s Travel (Fodor \u2019 s Travel) announced next year \u2019 s \u201c9 Best Places to Visit in the World \u201d, calling on tourists to carefully consider avoiding these famous but much-needed hot spots, and mentioning that these areas are affected by environmental pollution and tourism hazards.\nAmong them, Mount Fuji in Japan, which Taiwanese love, is also on the list.\nAccording to a comprehensive foreign media report, among the nine \u201cNo List \u201d listed by Fodor Travel on its official website in 2024, four of them are in Asia and the rest are in Europe and the United States.\nAccording to the official website, the original intention of the evaluation is not to deliberately suppress partial generalization, but to \"respect\" as the starting point of the declaration, this time to open the list of avoid visits, but also focus on tourists to nine tourist attractions and dependent local communities, resulting in \"excessive tourism\", \"excessive waste generation\", \"affect water resources\" these three major impacts.\nAt the same time, Fodor Tourism also pointed out that these nine tourist hotspots are deeply affected by the \"Instagram effect\", because the beauty of these places is circulating around the world, causing tourism.\nFinally, Fodor Tourism also calls on tourists around the world to let go of these areas when planning their 2024 travel plans, but also to be careful to protect the local environment and culture, and to respect the people and places everywhere.\nMount Fuji, Japan\nThe number of climbers at the site has skyrocketed in recent years, but local authorities and people have pointed out that many do not fully understand the risks involved in climbing Mount Fuji, resulting in overcrowding at the top of the sacred mountain and putting themselves at risk.\nIn addition, many climbers are unwilling to pay 1,000 yen (about NT $200) for safety and environmental maintenance, and even leave a lot of garbage and urine filled bottles, which can only be cleaned by volunteers, causing headaches.\nHa Long Bay, Vietnam\nThe local waters attract a large number of international tourists to vacation, including snorkeling, water sports and fishing activities, which also lead to the local garbage load, the waters are full of garbage and diesel, and the local government \u2019 s poor implementation of pollution policies, it is very easy to be avoided by operators, so that the natural ecology of the area is facing unbearable pollution.\nKoh Samui, Thailand\nThe island has been plagued by fresh water shortages for nearly a year, and the influx of tourists has consumed up to 70% of the region \u2019 s precious water resources, seriously exacerbating the island \u2019 s freshwater shortage.\nGanges, India\nThe river, regarded as the source of life for the people of India, has faced problems such as reduced flow, garbage pollution, and endangered freshwater dolphins in recent years, which have been exacerbated by the emerging luxury cruise industry.\nAthens, Greece\nThe lack of a tourism hazard management plan by the local government does not mean that the world heritage is in danger of being destroyed, but also that the traditional way of life of the local people is being destroyed by a large number of tourists.\nThe Acropolis has already implemented a daily visitor limit, which has been reduced from 23,000 to 20,000 per day, and the Parthenon Temple to 17,000.\nItaly (Venice)\nVenice has long been affected by subsidence, flooding, and the damage caused by the increasing number of tourists, adding to the stress of this ancient and fragile city, and adversely affecting the local environment and residents.\nAlthough the local government has taken several specific measures to try to reduce tourists, including charging a tourist tax of 5 euros (about NT $171) for all visitors over 14 years old who come to the city for a \u201cday trip \u201d between the end of April and mid-July next year, it is still considered unlikely to improve the problem.\nSan Gabriel Mountains National Monument, California\nThis \u201cnatural oasis \u201d in Los Angeles County, due to the number of tourists and lack of environmental awareness, not only is the monument graffiti by tourists, but even littering everywhere, causing the local environment to suffer a lot of damage.\nLake Superior (United States \u2013 Canada border)\nLake Superior, on the border between the United States and Canada, is the largest freshwater lake on the planet, and its ecology is now exposed to a variety of hazards due to human visits, including species invasion, rapid algal blooms, and fish consumption warnings.\nChile's Atacama Desert\nThe Atacama Desert, on the Pacific coast, is a spectacular natural beauty of deserts, geysers, lagoons, salt mines, cliffs and peaks, but the local environment is polluted by \"fast fashion\" and unfortunately becomes a landfill.\nNo need to smoke, no need to grab, now use the APP to watch the news, guarantee the daily winning point I download the APP\nRelated News\nInternational hot today.\n2024 Presidential Legislative Election\nSee more!\nPlease join the Free Times fan group.\nNetizens respond.\nThis page has been idle for more than 5 minutes. Please click on the transparent black bottom or the X button at the bottom right corner.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0035.json.gz:13336","uncompressed_offset":605618688,"url":"news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/4516465","warc_date":"2023-12-10T08:21:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:70db76f2-e430-46d3-8b33-bf6292e4cb3e>","warc_url":"https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/4516465"},"created":"2023-12-10T09:04:09.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
