for foreign borrowings, which has been distributed to senators as part of broader language preservation efforts."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"Historically, language regulation has been used as a political tool, as seen in Italy under Mussolini\u2019s regime, where foreign words and even dialects were banned in public use."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"Critics of language regulation argue that borrowing is a natural linguistic process and that artificial restrictions may be ineffective or even harmful, particularly in informal speech contexts."},{"citations":{"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":100.0},"text":"Despite the adoption of laws in Russia, enforcement challenges persist, as evidenced by the continued prevalence of English words in public spaces such as signs and clothing."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"In Arab countries, proposals have been made to protect the Arabic language through laws aimed at preventing the dominance of foreign languages, including English, in public spaces such as signs, menus, and school curricula."},{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"France provides a prominent example of language protection, where ministerial committees and governmental bodies actively regulate the use of French, viewing it as a matter of national identity and existential importance."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"Russia has implemented extensive measures to curb foreign borrowings, including a law prohibiting the use of foreign words in public contexts when Russian equivalents exist."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"The Russian law mandates compliance across various sectors, including government authorities, courts, media, advertising, cultural events, and signage, to ensure the preservation of the Russian language."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"Recent legislative efforts in Russia include amendments to the Federal Law 'On the State Language of the Russian Federation,' which aim to create normative dictionaries excluding foreign words unless no Russian analogues are available."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"Localized initiatives, such as in Krasnodar, require entrepreneurs to translate business names and signs into Russian, emphasizing accessibility for the local population."},{"citations":{"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010":100.0},"text":"Crimean officials have compiled a dictionary offering Russian substitutes for foreign borrowings, which has been distributed to senators as part of broader language preservation efforts."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"Historically, language regulation has been used as a political tool, as seen in Italy under Mussolini\u2019s regime, where foreign words and even dialects were banned in public use."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"Critics of language regulation argue that borrowing is a natural linguistic process and that artificial restrictions may be ineffective or even harmful, particularly in informal speech contexts."},{"citations":{"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":100.0},"text":"Despite the adoption of laws in Russia, enforcement challenges persist, as evidenced by the continued prevalence of English words in public spaces such as signs and clothing."}],"references":["99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858","1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622","fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617","95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010","430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380","b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582"],"documents":{"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010":{"id":"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010","text":"Matvienko read a poem about anglicisms in the Federation Council - RIA Novosti, 22.06.2022\nRegistration was successful!\nPlease follow the link from the letter sent to\nMatvienko read a poem about Anglicisms in the Federation Council\nMatvienko read a poem about Anglicisms at a meeting of the Federation Council\n\u00a9 Press Service of the Federation Council of the Russian Federation / Go to photobanPresident of the Federation Council of the Russian Federation Valentina Matvienko\nChairman of the Federation Council of the Russian Federation Valentina Matvienko.\nArchive photo\nRead ria.ru in\nMOSCOW, June 22 - RIA Novosti.\nSpeaker of the Federation Council Valentina Matvienko, during the discussion on Anglicisms and foreign borrowings in Russian, read poems on this topic and did it so artistically that she earned friendly applause from senators.\nOn Wednesday, all senators received a dictionary compiled by Crimean officials that transmits Russian-language substitutes for foreign borrowing.\nMatvienko praised its authors and read out the poems included in the handbook.\nKonstantinov told how in the Crimea are struggling with the dominance of foreign words\n\"And we have a workshop here, and you?\nAnd we got a babysitter hypanula the wrong word.\nA year of PR parent together with the child on a talk show.\nAnd we have a famous guru in the field of architecture made a selfie for PR, the bow he chose extreme.\nRealizing all our trables, in nostalgic sadness we remember how boyfriends were called grooms, instead of casting, our mothers held and not men, and men gave flowers to girls.\nThe party was a party, the upgrade was an improvement.\nMaybe after all we have enough Russians to offend people? \"- read Matvienko.\nThe senators greeted her reading with loud applause.\nThe speaker also suggested discussing the possibility of fixing at the legislative level a ban on clogging the Russian language with spilled borrowings.\n\u201cCashback \u201d as it was, and it is, and all this is pronounced at the government level.\nWell, there are analogues in the Russian language, why do we clog our beautiful wonderful unique language with such different words?\nWe need to look at it at the legislative level.\nOur responsibility is to preserve the language of Pushkin, the language of which we are proud and to stop these new trends that are absolutely inappropriate, \u201d Matvienko said.\nAccording to her, both France and other countries do not allow to clog their languages, and in Russia should avoid the use of foreign words that have analogues in Russian.\nThe task to study the issue was given to the profile committee on science, education and culture.\nFrom Proto-Slavic to Modern: Evolution and Features of the Russian Language\nNews feed\n0\nNew firstOld firstFirst\nloader\nOn-line\nTitle of the material to be opened\nTo participate in the discussion\nlog in or register\nloader\nChats\nTitle of the material to be opened","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0018.json.gz:139059","uncompressed_offset":213010010,"url":"ria.ru/20220622/anglitsizmy-1797269487.html","warc_date":"2022-06-23T06:16:39.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6>","warc_url":"https://ria.ru/20220622/anglitsizmy-1797269487.html"},"created":"2022-06-23T06:34:17.000Z","lang":"eng"},"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":{"id":"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858","text":"Spitting in the face of the Netherlands and the intimidation of the nuclear: what the propaganda of the Russian Federation said on February 21\n3 minutes\n552\nThe speech of Russian President Vladimir Putin before the Federal Assembly has already passed, nuclear threats to the world have traditionally been proclaimed, nothing unusual has happened.\nWell, except for the next \"Orvelovsky\" aggravation among the Russian politicum, which once again indicates the near-death convulsions of the empire.\nWhat the Russian propaganda has given out over the past 24 hours, the Center for Strategic Communications and Information Security analyzed\nVideo of the day\nPutin seeks to negotiate, but humiliates the West with his decisions\nThe basis of Putin \u2019 s much-publicized message to the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation was, of course, accusations of \u201csolving the war in Ukraine \u201d against the West and traditional threats to use weapons.\nThe only difference is that Putin has officially suspended Russia \u2019 s participation in the Treaty on Strategic Offensive Arms.\n\"The Russian Defense Ministry and Rosatom must ensure readiness to test nuclear weapons.\nOf course, we will not do this first.\nBut if the United States conducts a test, and we will, \u201d \u2014 said the head of the Kremlin.\nSuch a step is actually another attempt to achieve negotiations on a peaceful end to the war with Ukraine.\nThis time there was a lot of blackmail.\nHowever, Moscow for some reason does not take into account the fact that the West usually has a habit not to negotiate with terrorists, which, by the way, Russian politicians have actually recognized many leading countries in the world.\nAt the same time, with hints of a desire for dialogue, Putin continues to put sticks in the wheels of Russian diplomacy with his decisions.\nFor example, the assignment of the title of \"Guards\" 53rd anti-aircraft missile brigade - for \"mass heroism and courage, steadfastness and courage shown by the personnel of the brigade in combat operations to protect the Fatherland.\"\nAt the same time, the \"mass heroism and courage\" of this brigade was to take the lives of innocent people on board a passenger liner of Malaysian Airlines on July 17, 2014.\nThere were 298 people on board, all of whom died.\nBy the way, a court in the Netherlands ruled that the Buk, from which the Boeing was shot down, belonged to the 53rd brigade of the Russian Federation.\nBut Putin somehow decided that the Netherlands would get away with such a diplomatic slap.\nThe FSB debunks fakes from...\nMedvedeva\nHowever, the ability to lie is one of the key skills to get into the Russian government.\nOtherwise, it is impossible to explain the dominance of top propagandists in high positions.\nA striking example is former Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, who recently said that Joe Biden \u2019 s visit to Kiev was originally agreed by Moscow.\n\u201cBiden, after receiving security guarantees, finally went to Kiev, \u201d he said.\nBut the director of the FSB Alexander Bortnikov later said something different, in fact refuted Medvedev \u2019 s claim.\nAccording to the official, Washington did inform the Russians about Biden \u2019 s upcoming trip.\nHowever, the United States did not receive any guarantees from Moscow.\nWhether this is true is unknown, but the Kremlin \u2019 s general desire to increase its significance is too great.\nHe demonstrates this in relation to the Russian language, in defense of which a special law was recently adopted in the third reading.\nAccording to the document, the use of borrowed foreign words is prohibited in public use - such as \"trabl\", \"workshop\", \"fake\", etc.\nThis applies to those definitions that have analogues in Russian.\nThe implementation of the law will be mandatory for authorities at all levels, courts, media, advertising producers, film screenings in cinemas, theatrical and cultural events, inscriptions on signs.\nAnd this is a vivid repetition of history, because as early as 1929, a similar policy was pursued by the Italian dictator Benito Mussolini.\nThen, under the fascist regime, the use of not only foreign words, but also individual letters was prohibited in the country.\nAlso, even dialects and local dialects were recognized as \u201cstrangers \u201d, and it was impossible to use them publicly.\nIt is likely that a similar fate will soon await the Russian Federation, which will not surprise anyone at all.\nThe only nice thing is that everyone knows how the fascist government of Italy ended.\nTherefore, Putin \u2019 s government will expect the same...","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0005.json.gz:146618","uncompressed_offset":394095858,"url":"war.obozrevatel.com/plevok-v-litso-niderlandov-i-ustrashenie-yaderkoj-o-chem-govorila-propaganda-rf-21-fevralya.htm","warc_date":"2023-02-22T14:08:27.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2>","warc_url":"https://war.obozrevatel.com/plevok-v-litso-niderlandov-i-ustrashenie-yaderkoj-o-chem-govorila-propaganda-rf-21-fevralya.htm"},"created":"2023-02-22T14:24:30.000Z","lang":"eng"},"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":{"id":"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617","text":"There should be no excesses: a sociologist about the law on the protection of language - RIA Novosti Crimea, 29.10.2022\nRegistration was successful!\nPlease follow the link from the letter sent to\nRadio \"Sputnik in Crimea\"\nThere should be no excesses: a sociologist about the law on the protection of language\nPolitical scientist Kiselyova appreciated the bill on the protection of the Russian language\nRead in\nSIMFEROPOL, 29 oct - RIA Novosti Crimea.\nThe emergence of a law in the Russian Federation on the protection of the Russian language from excessive borrowing is appropriate, but there should be no excesses in this matter.\nThis opinion on the air of the radio \"Sputnik in Crimea\" expressed the head of the Crimean branch of the Foundation for the development of civil society, sociologist Natalia Kiseleva.\nCrimean teachers spoke out against the language repression of young people > >\nEarlier, a draft law on amendments to the Federal Law \"On the State Language of the Russian Federation\" appeared in the system of ensuring legislative activity.\nThe amendments provide for the protection of the Russian language from the excessive influence of borrowed words.\nIn particular, we propose the emergence of normative dictionaries that fix the norms of the modern Russian literary language, where foreign words cannot be entered, with the exception of those that have no analogues in the Russian language.\nLeave the \u201cbarn \u201d and\u201c dog \u201d alone: a linguist about the law on the protection of language\n\u201cI am a supporter of this bill.\nI think it should be adopted a long time ago, because we really see an unjustified dominance of foreign words.\nAt the same time, I, of course, do not propose to abandon all borrowed words - many of them have long and firmly entered the Russian language and became part of it, \"Kiseleva said.\nThe sociologist emphasizes that it is impossible to introduce language restrictions in colloquial speech, especially among young people, and this is not the case in the new bill.\nAt the same time, in her opinion, the official use of the language should be regulated:\nIn the Crimea proposed to introduce fines for foreign words in advertising > >\n\u201cIt \u2019 s about officials, the media.\nFor example, the latest fashionable foreign word \"hub\" - representatives of government agencies use it everywhere, although there is a great word in the Russian language \"node\": transport hub, interchange and so on, \"- gives an example of a guest ether.\nDictionary for the replacement of anglicisms needs improvement \u2013 opinion\nIn addition, according to Kiseleva, it is appropriate not only to regulate the use of the Russian language in the official sphere, but also to simplify the language of regulatory documents so that the ordinary citizen can understand legal norms, which now often require interpretation by lawyers.\nEarlier, Andrei Kibrik, a researcher at the Institute of Linguistics of the Russian Academy of Sciences, commented on the relevant bill, expressed the opinion that the artificial regulation of any language, including the Russian language, is a vain and even harmful idea, since borrowing is part of a natural process that cannot be stopped or reversed.\nNews feed\n0\nNew firstOld firstFirst\nloader\nOn-line\nTitle of the material to be opened","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0032.json.gz:76023","uncompressed_offset":444896617,"url":"crimea.ria.ru/20221029/ne-dolzhno-byt-peregibov-sotsiolog-o-zakone-po-zaschite-yazyka-1125141171.html","warc_date":"2022-10-29T01:35:19.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a>","warc_url":"https://crimea.ria.ru/20221029/ne-dolzhno-byt-peregibov-sotsiolog-o-zakone-po-zaschite-yazyka-1125141171.html"},"created":"2022-10-29T02:18:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":{"id":"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380","text":"To the New Frontiers: Spikai in Russian\nBeing in large cities, we all pay attention to the signs of shops, restaurants, cafes, firms and other institutions, the names of which are often written in English or the Latin alphabet.\nWhat does this so-called street language mean?\n.\nHere, for example, on the sign of the restaurant at the top you can see the inscription in Russian - restaurant.\nAnd below - the English letters BOLSHOI.\nFor what?\nYes, English is recognized as an official language, as a consequence of the colonialist policy of Great Britain, in almost 60 countries of the world.\nIt seems that Russia is falling into his linguistic bondage.\nA particularly powerful onslaught of Anglicisms has become in recent decades due to the mass impact of TV, the Internet: the sphere of the Russian language has become rapidly filled with Anglo-American words and terms.\nIn fact, it is dangerous not to notice this, because language is the foundation of the culture of any nation, on which generation after generation they create a home of their spirituality.\nFor thousands of years, our language has absorbed Greek and Latin, Turkic and Polish, Dutch and German, French and English words.\nSometimes the process of borrowing went very quickly, as, for example, in the time of Peter the Great.\nBut even then, the danger of excessive fascination with foreign words was not forgotten.\nThe same Peter strictly admonished his ambassador: \"... henceforth his relays to us to write everything in the Russian language...\".\nThe struggle for the preservation of the Russian language acquired a special scope in the 19th century.\n\u201cTo use a foreign word when there is a Russian word equivalent to it, \u201d wrote V.G. Belinsky,\u201c is to offend both common sense and common taste. \u201d\nHe was echoed by I.S. Turgenev: \u201cNever use foreign words.\nThe Russian language is so rich and flexible that we have nothing to take from those who are poorer than us. \u201d\nNow, the further, the wider the so-called runglish \u2013 an ugly mixture of Russian and English.\nIt is not surprising that a generation is growing up in Russia, for which the texts written by Pushkin, Chekhov, Bunin become incomprehensible.\nUnder these conditions, in 2005, the parliament adopted and President Putin signed the law \u201cOn the State Language of the Russian Federation \u201d.\nIt is aimed at ensuring the use of the state language and the protection and development of language culture.\nThe aggression of Anglicisms has since weakened, but not so much that one can calm down.\nThe law is not properly enforced.\nThat \u2019 s why we read on the signs: FAR\u0428 butcher shop, EXTRIMLAND adventure park, and on children \u2019 s T-shirts: \u201cSpeak in Russian \u201d.\nAuthor: T.\nRAISWICH.\nNewspaper \"To New Frontiers\"","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0025.json.gz:130446","uncompressed_offset":389433380,"url":"gornyak22.ru/gornyak/k-novym-rybejam-spikai-po-rysski/","warc_date":"2021-09-04T02:19:16.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746>","warc_url":"https://gornyak22.ru/gornyak/k-novym-rybejam-spikai-po-rysski/"},"created":"2021-09-04T03:10:35.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":{"id":"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622","text":"In Russia, they are determined to protect the language from excessive saturation with borrowings\nThe Russian language is one of the most popular in Eurasia, and attempts to abolish our culture have failed.\n\u00a9 Video: TRK \"Zvezda\" \u00a9 Photo: TRK \"Zvezda\"\nRead us on:\nStore, Department, Home and other foreign words in the names of shops, cafes and restaurants in Krasnodar soon will not be.\nThe Cuban capital decided to abandon all foreign names.\nThe Cuban authorities obliged entrepreneurs to translate business into Russian.\n\u201cA sign in a foreign language or using transliteration or a sign in Russian has a big difference.\nIn part of the fact that 100% of our population can read, understand the sign in Russian.\nAnd many, by ignorance and age, do not even understand what is written on these signs, \u201d said the chief architect of Krasnodar Artem Salamatin.\nSo far, the business has been given time until September 1.\nBut many entrepreneurs are ready to change now.\n\u201cEverything will be in Russian.\nWe will translate the site into Russian.\nWe'll change everything.\nWith pleasure, \u201d entrepreneur Hovhannes Hovhannisyan shared.\nWords borrowed from foreign languages became an integral part of Russian many centuries ago.\nMassive in our speech, they appeared in different iconic historical periods.\nFor example, the Mongol invasion.\nAnd after the Patriotic War of 1812 - there were a lot of gallicisms, that is, French words.\nNow in conversations predominate borrowing from English.\n\u201cWe began to use foreign words very actively in areas where such activity had not been observed before.\nFirst of all, it is the public sphere.\nSocial sphere.\nWhere actually came a lot of foreign words \u201d, \u2013 said the Chairman of the Association of teachers of literature and Russian language Lyudmila Dudova.\nRussia is now determined to protect the language from excessive saturation with borrowings.\nPresident Vladimir Putin recently signed a law \u201con mandatory observance of the norms of the modern Russian language when using it as a state language. \u201d\nWhat specific rules are we talking about?\nIt's not clear yet.\nThey are compiled by a special government commission.\n\u201cThe normative dictionary of the Russian language will be a single consistent comprehensive publication, which will be formed on the basis of dictionaries of the Russian language.\nInterpretive, spelling, \u201d explained Deputy Minister of Education of the Russian Federation Tatiana Vasilyeva.\nThus, foreign words should disappear as much as possible from all official documents.\nIn addition, officials should not use anglicisms and other borrowings during public speeches and generally avoid them in their speech.\n\u201cThere are so many wonderful and beautiful words in the Russian language.\nBut why then instead of the word mentor we say coach.\nWell, it doesn't sound.\nIt seems to me that we need to get rid of such words that are imposed, \u201d said Lyudmila Skakovskaya, Deputy Chairman of the Federation Council Committee on Science, Education and Culture.\nThis law, according to officials, should protect the Russian language from attacks from abroad, where they have long been trying to abolish all Russian.\nBut now these sentiments have intensified even more.\nThe Kiev regime has long declared war on our culture and heritage.\nThroughout the country, the monument to Alexander Sergeyevich Pushkin is being demolished, because it is he who is considered the creator of the modern literary Russian language.\nAnd it was the language issue that became one of the main reasons for the bloody confrontation in the East of Ukraine in 2014.\nResidents of Donbass then did not agree with the nationalists, they did not refuse the Russian language.\n\u201cThey use the term underdogs.\nAll these years, when the Maidan happened, they etched Russian in the Donbass, for them it is a symbol of communication.\nThe Russian world is hysterical.\nWhat connects the Russian world?\nThe Russian language, \u201d said political scientist Yuri Svetov.\nThe fact that our language and culture need protection is also said by the leaders of other neighboring states.\nDuring the autumn meeting of the heads of the CIS countries in Astana, the President of Kazakhstan Kassym-Jomart Tokayev called on his colleagues to create an organization for the protection of the Russian language.\n\u201cOur idea is to create an international organization in the image and likeness of the UN.\nUsing the positive experience of Francophonie.\nThe headquarters of which is located in Paris, \u201d said President of the Republic of Kazakhstan Kassym-Jomart Tokayev.\nRossotrudnichestvo recently conducted its own study abroad, which showed that openly Russophobic sentiments are present only among politicians.\nBut ordinary people continue to willingly learn our language and culture.\nAccording to the United Nations, Russian is spoken by 258 million people worldwide.\nIt is one of the most popular in Eurasia, and attempts to abolish our culture have failed.\nAbroad, Dostoevsky, Pushkin and other Russian classics are also read.\nExpert opinion and analytics\nRead more\nread below the following news","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0016.json.gz:204758","uncompressed_offset":362771622,"url":"tvzvezda.ru/news/2023662150-OSYkE.html","warc_date":"2023-06-06T19:33:11.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1>","warc_url":"https://tvzvezda.ru/news/2023662150-OSYkE.html"},"created":"2023-06-06T19:49:33.000Z","lang":"eng"},"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":{"id":"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582","text":"How can we restore the Arab world to its leading position?\nThere is no doubt that the achievement of Arabic leadership among the languages of the world, as it was in the past, requires concerted efforts at all levels, politically, socially and economically.\nThese are four steps that can be adopted by any Arab country, and I believe that they will bring the Arab world a tremendous leadership, in the medium and long term.\nGiving the Arab heritage and the sciences of the Arabic language, the highest priority in literary university studies.\nThere are university professors today who specialize in Arabic literature, yet they have never studied a house from Ibn Malik \u2019 s millennium, nor heard of Ibn Hisham \u2019 s testimonies.\nStep one.\nFill the courses with the ancient Arab heritage of stories, proverbs, books, and poetry, especially poetry.\nThe frequent exposure of the student to poetry, grows his sobriety and strengthens his linguistic faculty..\nBecause the ancient Arabic poet is necessarily a linguist, his poetry is a precise linguistic selection.\nThis is why the Mahathir people in Mauritania are keen to memorize the old poetry of children, and the result is clear for the graduates of the old Mahathir.\nThe more the child memorizes old Arabic poetry, the easier it is for him to learn Arabic, and it is not important to understand what he memorized at the time of memorization, but it is important to drink his subconscious mind of tens of thousands of linguistic examples scattered in his archives, so he has a straight language quality, without realizing it.\nStep two.\nGiving the Arab heritage and the sciences of the Arabic language, the highest priority in literary university studies.\nThere are university professors today specialized in Arabic literature, yet they have never studied a house from the millennium of Ibn Malik, nor have they heard the testimonies of Ibn Hisham, and the reason is that the modernist trend prevailed in the university halls, and the predominance of interest in Western literary models such as Dadaism, Surrealism and others. The Arabic language and its sciences must be a priority in the university environment.\nIf the opposite happens as it is today, you will find many specialists in language and graduates of the Department of Arabic Language, have nothing to do with language or literature, just as we saw an Arab university professor, specializing in rhetoric, can not read a paper she wrote, this is because the faculties of Arabic literature - except God 's mercy - neglect the science of language, and interested in modern curricula intrusive, resulting in \"language specialists\" They don \u2019 t know the language!\nWe have also seen from the results of this, that many graduates of the literary departments, know the leaders of literature in the West and boast about it, and are ignorant of the leaders of Arabic literature and are not ashamed of it.\nThese professors, except from the mercy of God, were raised in their universities to marginalize the science of the Arabic language and its heritage, and to provide modern literature translated from English, French and others, they are not specialists in the Arabic language, but specialists in the Arabic version of English literature.\nStep three.\nProtect the Arabic language by laws, and protect it from the invasion of foreign languages.\nIt is not right to see a shop in an Arab country that places a sign in a foreign language, a restaurant in an Arab country, a menu in a foreign language, a school in an Arab country that makes sure that its students are proficient in a foreign language at the expense of Arabic, or goods entering an Arab market with posters and information in a foreign language, or a doctor in an Arab country who writes a prescription in a foreign language.\nThis leniency leads to distorted Arab societies, alien to this world, in which every country protects its language with iron and fire.\nWe have seen some Arabic language synagogues, which are supposed to be the protector of Arabic, tolerate the introduction of all incoming and outgoing into Arabic, and people have taken note of them and warned them of their error.\nThe Arab state must also use all its institutions to serve and protect Arabic, just as the proud nations do in their own language.\nYou have, for example, the French model, where the state uses all its organs to protect the French.\nIn translation alone, the whole state stands against every foreign word, where ministerial committees work to monitor the new words and propose translations for them, then those translations are presented to another party, the French Language Enrichment Committee, for approval, then they are presented to another party, the French Academy, for approval, and then they are submitted to another party, the Prime Minister for approval. Sovereign, in which all France cooperates, because the state sees the protection of French as an existential matter, and does not leave it to a linguistic college, university or institution, as we have the Arabs.\nSTEP FOUR\nLinguistic censorship of art and media, especially art.\nThe Arabic series and films today are full of ridicule and neglect of Arabic, as well as many linguistic errors, and also full of many foreign words that these bullies have succumbed to: the writer, actor, director and producer, and they want to pass it to the poor Arab listener, to get used to listening to the intruder and his writing.\nThis is for works of art that are issued in Arabic dialects, and historical works that are issued in classical Arabic, you find a great chaos: you find an Abbasid or Umayyad series that speaks the language of the Mexican dubbed series: \"I'm sorry, dear,\" \"I'm a little upset,\" \"Let me disagree with your point of view.\"\nAlthough the proofreader of these works may be a university professor specialized in Arabic literature, but as I told you in a previous paragraph, these professors - except God 's mercy - were raised in their universities to marginalize the science of the Arabic language and its heritage, and provide modern literatures translated from English, French and others, they are not specialists in the Arabic language, but specialists in the Arabic version of English literature, it is not surprising that they write and authenticate Old historical baskets, you feel like you hear Google Translate!\nThese are the four steps: the first is related to elementary and intermediate education (filling courses with Arab heritage), the second is related to university education (giving the sciences of Arabic language and heritage, the highest priority, and not to modern translated literature), the third is at the legislative and executive level (protecting and fortifying the Arabic language by laws and the work of state agencies to implement those laws), and the art industry. from Arabic or ridicule them or work to spread foreign words at the expense of Arabic).\nThere may be other important steps, but these four steps, I believe, are one of the most important that can restore the Arabic language to its place in the world, as it was in previous centuries.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:13601","uncompressed_offset":694237582,"url":"www.aljazeera.net/blogs/2023/12/18/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D9%86%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7","warc_date":"2023-12-19T05:54:00.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f>","warc_url":"https://www.aljazeera.net/blogs/2023/12/18/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D9%86%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7"},"created":"2023-12-19T06:32:20.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1096","request_id":"1096","narrative_id":"1096"},"responses":[{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"The protection of the Arabic language has been proposed as a means to prevent the encroachment of foreign languages, including English, in Arab countries."},{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"Suggestions have been made that Arab countries should restrict the prioritization of foreign languages over Arabic in public domains such as shop signs, restaurant menus, and school curricula."},{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"France serves as a prominent example of a country actively protecting its language through state mechanisms, including ministerial committees, translation efforts, and approval processes involving multiple governmental bodies."},{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"The French government considers the protection of its language an existential matter, engaging all state institutions in this endeavor."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"In Russia, a special law was recently enacted to prohibit the use of borrowed foreign words in public contexts, such as 'trabl,' 'workshop,' and 'fake,' if Russian equivalents are available."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"The implementation of this Russian law is mandatory for various sectors, including authorities, courts, media, advertising, cultural events, and public signage."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":100.0},"text":"The Russian government has also submitted a bill to the State Duma aimed at protecting the Russian language from excessive foreign borrowings."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":100.0},"text":"This bill emphasizes the importance of adhering to the norms of the Russian literary language and prohibits the use of foreign words unless no Russian equivalents exist."},{"citations":{"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010":100.0},"text":"Valentina Matvienko, Speaker of the Federation Council of Russia, has proposed legislating a ban on the excessive use of foreign borrowings in the Russian language."},{"citations":{"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010":100.0},"text":"Matvienko has stressed the need to preserve the Russian language by avoiding foreign words when suitable Russian alternatives are available."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"A draft law in Russia proposes amendments to the Federal Law 'On the State Language of the Russian Federation' to safeguard the language from excessive borrowing."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"The proposed amendments include the development of normative dictionaries that exclude foreign words unless they lack Russian analogues."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"The bill aims to regulate the official use of language in government and media while refraining from imposing restrictions on informal speech."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"For instance, the bill suggests replacing foreign terms like 'hub' with Russian equivalents such as 'node' in official contexts."},{"citations":{"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":100.0},"text":"In 2005, the Russian parliament adopted, and President Putin signed, the law 'On the State Language of the Russian Federation' to ensure the use of the state language and promote language culture."},{"citations":{"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":100.0},"text":"This law was specifically designed to address the growing presence of Anglicisms in the Russian language."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"Russia has demonstrated a strong commitment to protecting its language from excessive borrowings, particularly from English."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"President Vladimir Putin recently signed a law mandating adherence to modern Russian language norms in official use."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"A special government commission in Russia is currently compiling rules to ensure the mandatory observance of Russian language norms."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"Under the new law, foreign words are expected to be largely eliminated from official documents in Russia."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"Russian officials are encouraged to avoid using Anglicisms and other borrowings in public speeches and general communication."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"In Krasnodar, entrepreneurs are required to translate business names and signs into Russian, with a compliance deadline set by local authorities."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"The chief architect of Krasnodar has emphasized that Russian-language signs are more accessible to the local population, as some residents may not understand foreign words."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"The Russian government is also working on a normative dictionary to standardize interpretive and spelling rules for the Russian language."},{"citations":{"1564c886-83d5-44ae-9bd7-34ce1edc95d1_362771622":100.0},"text":"The Deputy Chairman of the Federation Council Committee on Science, Education, and Culture has advocated for replacing borrowed words with native Russian terms."},{"citations":{"95e25f62-9f35-49d1-9222-a4f565e3a0b6_213010010":100.0},"text":"Crimean officials have compiled a dictionary offering Russian-language substitutes for foreign borrowings, which has been distributed to senators."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":100.0},"text":"Historically, Lenin advocated for a campaign against the unnecessary use of foreign words, a sentiment echoed during the 1940s in the fight against cosmopolitanism."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":100.0},"text":"Under Peter I, numerous Dutch and German words related to technology and mechanisms entered the Russian language, illustrating the long-standing role of borrowing in linguistic evolution."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":100.0},"text":"Critics of language regulation argue that language is a self-regulating system, and harmful or unnecessary borrowings will naturally fade over time."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"Some researchers contend that artificial regulation of language is ineffective and potentially harmful, as borrowing is an inherent aspect of linguistic development."},{"citations":{"fb815b07-fd05-49c4-ae6b-6e001a28849a_444896617":100.0},"text":"A sociologist has emphasized that language restrictions should not extend to informal speech, particularly among young people."},{"citations":{"430d0079-92a7-4660-8be7-b0077148a746_389433380":100.0},"text":"Despite the adoption of laws to regulate language, enforcement in Russia has been inconsistent, as evidenced by the continued prevalence of English words on signs and clothing."},{"citations":{"99bc6688-c6eb-4e99-a18a-99674efc63a2_394095858":100.0},"text":"In 1929, during Benito Mussolini's fascist regime in Italy, the use of foreign words, individual letters, and even dialects was prohibited in public contexts."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b36e7676-d687-4e7b-82f8-c4657494348f_694237582":100.0},"text":"The protection of the Arabic language has been proposed as a means to