280992062":100.0},"text":"In modern times, the struggles of the Luddites find parallels in the dynamics of Silicon Valley, where a small number of corporations wield significant control over emerging technologies."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The development of contemporary technologies often occurs in an undemocratic manner, with immense capital concentrated in the hands of innovators, frequently sidelining the interests and well-being of workers."},{"citations":{"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249":100.0},"text":"The fear of technology, known as 'technophobia,' has historical roots in the Industrial Revolution, when workers feared that automated systems would render their skills obsolete and deprive them of employment."},{"citations":{"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249":100.0},"text":"This technophobia persists in modern society, manifesting in concerns about advanced technologies such as artificial intelligence and their potential to disrupt jobs and societal norms."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The Luddites, a group of English workers in the early 19th century, were not inherently opposed to technology or progress but resisted specific technologies that they believed were being used to undermine their livelihoods and working conditions."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"Their revolt was fundamentally a labor movement aimed at addressing poverty and poor working conditions, rather than a blanket opposition to technological advancement."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The British government of the time portrayed the Luddites as being against progress, a narrative designed to mock and discredit their legitimate labor struggle."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The Luddites' destruction of machinery was both a symbolic and practical act, targeting technologies that they saw as transferring wealth and power from workers to employers."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"Ned Ludd, a legendary figure associated with the movement, served as a powerful organizational symbol for the Luddites' rebellion."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"Despite the significant impact of their organized rebellion, the legacy of the Luddites has often been treated less favorably than other historical figures like Robin Hood."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The myth of Ned Ludd was perceived as particularly threatening to elites because it directly encouraged rebellion against oppressive systems, unlike the more romanticized narrative of Robin Hood."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"In modern times, the struggles of the Luddites find parallels in the dynamics of Silicon Valley, where a small number of corporations wield significant control over emerging technologies."},{"citations":{"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":100.0},"text":"The development of contemporary technologies often occurs in an undemocratic manner, with immense capital concentrated in the hands of innovators, frequently sidelining the interests and well-being of workers."},{"citations":{"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249":100.0},"text":"The fear of technology, known as 'technophobia,' has historical roots in the Industrial Revolution, when workers feared that automated systems would render their skills obsolete and deprive them of employment."},{"citations":{"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249":100.0},"text":"This technophobia persists in modern society, manifesting in concerns about advanced technologies such as artificial intelligence and their potential to disrupt jobs and societal norms."}],"references":["1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062","0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249"],"documents":{"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249":{"id":"0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503_771453249","text":"10 curious near-technological facts to expand your horizons\nWhat do phones for the blind look like, where and when the first cell phone call was made, what font is considered the most hated in the world?\nRead the answers to these and other questions in our article.\nBlind people can use mobile phones\nThere is a special Braille technology and accessories for blind people to use mobile phones.\nIt uses special buttons that rise and fall, so that a person can touch and read information.\nGoogle \u2019 s first tweet was incomprehensible\nFor the average person, the very first post of Google on Twitter was something of a nonsense.\nIt read: \"I'm 01100110 01100101 01100101 01101100 01101001 01101110 01100111 00100000 01101100 01110101 01100011 01101011 01111001 00001010\".\nTranslated from the binary code, it means the phrase: \u201cI \u2019 m feeling lucky \u201d, which can be translated into Russian as\u201c I \u2019 m lucky! \u201d (this phrase you can see on the right button under the Google search query field).\nThe first cell phone call was made in New York.\nThe first ever mobile phone call was made in 1973 on a street in New York by Martin Cooper, an employee of Motorola.\n19 years later, British engineer Neil Papworth sent the first text message.\nMore than 6,000 new computer viruses are created and distributed every month\nThis number has increased dramatically since 1990, when there were only 50 known computer viruses.\nToday, 90% of emails contain malware that most people are unaware of.\nFacebook has more likes than photos\nMore than 300 million photos are shared on Facebook every day, with 800 million likes being placed over the same period.\nBy the way, the heart reactions are put only 175 million per day.\nThe iPhones were almost in the shape of an apple.\nThe original design for the iPhone was in the shape of an apple.\nInitially, the mobile phone was developed as a clamshell with a keypad.\nIn the closed state, it looked like the Apple logo.\nComic Sans is the most hated font in the world\nComic Sans was developed as a non-serious handwritten font for use in comics.\nAnd while everyone loves to hate this tasteless font, it \u2019 s actually very suitable for people with dyslexia.\nDue to its asymmetrical style, letters are easier to distinguish.\nInternet speed at NASA \u2014 91 GB per second\nThe average speed of the Internet connection for users is about 25 MB per second.\nThis is usually enough to watch Netflix without buffering delays.\nBut let \u2019 s face it: if there \u2019 s any technology company that could really benefit from the speed of the Internet, it \u2019 s NASA.\nNokia is the largest company in Finland\nSo much so that the Finns consider it a national pride.\nAnd although we often think that Nokia is just a manufacturer of mobile phones, under this famous brand in 1865 was originally made paper.\nThe company took up technology in the 1980s.\nSome people are afraid of technology.\nPeople experience a wide variety of fears, and technology is no exception.\nCalled \u201ctechnophobia, \u201d this fear arose during the Industrial Revolution, when workers began to fear that automated systems would deprive them of their jobs.\nSimilarly, this applies to modern society, as well as to people who are afraid of too advanced high technologies, such as artificial intelligence technology.\nSource: https: / / udivitelnoe.\ntemaretik.com / 2269583156035980278 /\nDear friends!\nBe sure to put likes, subscribe to the site and share your opinion in the comments!\nI also recommend reading:\nThe world is on the verge of war with Aliens? https: / / otari.mirtesen.ru / blog / 43009838561 /\nAncient artifacts: the mystery of the \u201cgenetic disk \u201d https: / / otari.mirtesen.ru / blog / 43649493804 /\nWhat does the shape of your eyebrows tell you about your character?\nhttps: / / otari.mirtesen.ru / blog / 43192033043 /\nPicture of the day\ntop\n,,","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0022.json.gz:45613","uncompressed_offset":771453249,"url":"otari.mirtesen.ru/blog/43381468533/10-prelyubopyitneyshih-okolotehnologicheskih-faktov-dlya-rasshir","warc_date":"2021-08-01T04:42:38.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:0d112bb3-0018-49c5-9587-6d22cb8ac503>","warc_url":"https://otari.mirtesen.ru/blog/43381468533/10-prelyubopyitneyshih-okolotehnologicheskih-faktov-dlya-rasshir"},"created":"2021-08-01T06:16:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062":{"id":"1dc26d01-915d-4b03-8245-1c4d93b27ee0_280992062","text":"Brian Merchant, author: \u201cLuddites are more dangerous to the rich than Robin Hood\u201d\n\nThe Luddites have been a great historical resource. Any showy enemy of anything that looked like technological progress has been called a Luddite. Today with generative artificial intelligence and its critics, the word has been revived. The author and journalist Brian Merchant (Iowa City, USA, 1983) saw it coming and has written a book that reviews the Luddite revolt in England at the beginning of the 19th century and its similarities with current technologies: Blood in the Machine (Blood in the Machine, currently without a planned edition in Spanish) thus explores the origins of the current revolt against big technology.\n\nAlthough the book has appeared in the midst of the AI \u200b\u200bhype, Merchant began his research a decade ago: \u201cUber was growing and it was beginning to be seen that it was having a hard impact on taxi drivers, I heard the term Luddite from the pro-Uber sector and wrote an article titled You don't understand anything about Luddites\u201d. Now in his book he remembers that the Luddite revolt was a labor struggle, not anti-technology, at a time when unions were prohibited. In a conversation with EL PA\u00cdS from his residence in Los Angeles, Merchant clarifies the historical impact of the Luddites and the possible similar struggles that are being played today in Silicon Valley.\n\n1. The Luddites were not against progress\n\nThe labor revolt over the loss of rights was more important than the destruction of textile machines: \u201cThe biggest mistake about the Luddites is to say that they were against technology and progress,\u201d says Merchant. \u201cThey were against certain technologies because they recognized the way in which they were going to be used in their context against them as workers. It was a labor movement, against poverty, not anti-technology. The British Government began to mold them in this way almost immediately, it was keen to mock the Luddites and present the argument that they were against progress. It is very similar to how today people in positions of power in technology companies accuse those who complain about poor working conditions. It's the same story for 200 years.\u201d\n\nThe book quotes a phrase from historian Eric Hobsbawm that explains this stage: \u201cIt was collective bargaining through riots.\u201d According to Merchant, this tactic in a workers' struggle was very powerful for two reasons: \u201cFirst, it was symbolic because everyone understood that what they were destroying was not just a machine. It was also the specific machine used to transfer wealth from the workers to the employer. Second, it was useful because they destroyed the equipment that businessmen needed.\u201d\n\n2. Why Robin Hood is better accepted than Ned Ludd\n\nNed Ludd was a legendary character. No one knows for sure if he existed. It was the legend of a teenager who would have broken the first machines at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution. In 1811, rebellious workers used his legendary name to sign letters and further scare: \u201cLudd probably never existed. But the incarnation of it would become a mascot, an organizational tool, a wink: a powerful 19th-century meme,\u201d Merchant writes.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The Commander of the Land Forces meets in Muscat a number of Omani military leaders\n\nLudd lived near Nottingham (United Kingdom), like another legendary figure who has been better treated by history. There must be a reason, says Merchant: \u201cThe Luddites organized a popular and powerful rebellion. People wrote popular songs about them. They were like Robin Hood. But it is interesting that Robin Hood has endured as a positive light, while the Luddites have not. He suggests that the myth of Ned Ludd is in some ways more dangerous to the elites and the wealthy than that of Robin Hood, which is a little more nebulous and open. The Luddites say: go ahead and break the machines of your oppression. Robin Hood says: steal from the rich and give to the poor. \u201cI think that\u2019s a little more tolerable.\u201d\n\n3. How are they similar to today's problems?\n\nThe background of the book is that the history of the Luddites is similar to what happens today in Silicon Valley, where a small group of corporations dominate new technologies. \u201cThe way technologies are developed has basically not changed. You have a handful of people with access to enough capital or political influence to be able to build a factory and use automation technologies. \u201cBack then, the most aggressive owners didn\u2019t ask anyone how to find a way to make this a win-win.\u201d\n\nMerchant has received criticism for equating the great businessmen of 19th century England with 21st century America. But there are details that he does not see that far away: \u201cThe technology development process is in some ways even more undemocratic today than then. There is this immense pool of capital available to Silicon Valley innovators through venture capital. Uber wasn't profitable for 10 years, but they had access to that capital. Did anyone really like that? Did it work for workers and delivery people? Nothing mattered, they just had more money and moved on.\u201d\n\nSee also\u00a0 Just the mystery","url":"https://pledgetimes.com/brian-merchant-author-luddites-are-more-dangerous-to-the-rich-than-robin-hood/"}}}
