{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1103","request_id":"1103","narrative_id":"1103"},"responses":[{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"In ancient Egyptian culture, animals were regarded as sacred and divine, with the belief that they played a significant role in shaping human destinies."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Cats held a particularly esteemed position, symbolizing spiritual and mythological concepts through their association with the goddess Bast, who was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat\u2019s head and represented well-being, joy, love, and fertility."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The Egyptians nicknamed cats 'sunny eye' due to their ability to see in the dark, which elevated their status as mystical and protective figures in Egyptian mythology."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Beyond their spiritual significance, cats were highly valued for their practical contributions, particularly their ability to exterminate rodents, which safeguarded grain stocks that were as precious as gold in ancient Egypt."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The deep reverence for cats extended to elaborate cultural practices, including mummification and burial rituals, as Egyptians believed their pets deserved eternal life alongside humans."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking mourning rituals involved shaving one\u2019s eyebrows upon the death of a family cat, a practice that underscored the profound emotional and spiritual connection Egyptians felt toward these animals."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"In ancient Egyptian culture, animals were regarded as sacred and divine, with the belief that they played a significant role in shaping human destinies."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Cats held a particularly esteemed position, symbolizing spiritual and mythological concepts through their association with the goddess Bast, who was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat\u2019s head and represented well-being, joy, love, and fertility."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The Egyptians nicknamed cats 'sunny eye' due to their ability to see in the dark, which elevated their status as mystical and protective figures in Egyptian mythology."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Beyond their spiritual significance, cats were highly valued for their practical contributions, particularly their ability to exterminate rodents, which safeguarded grain stocks that were as precious as gold in ancient Egypt."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The deep reverence for cats extended to elaborate cultural practices, including mummification and burial rituals, as Egyptians believed their pets deserved eternal life alongside humans."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking mourning rituals involved shaving one\u2019s eyebrows upon the death of a family cat, a practice that underscored the profound emotional and spiritual connection Egyptians felt toward these animals."}],"references":["f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389"],"documents":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":{"id":"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389","text":"The mummy of a pet: why and why did the ancient Egyptians do this?\n1: 43\nThe Egyptians showed special respect for their pets, their love was so great that they wanted these animals to have eternal life.\nAfter death, pets were mummified and went through a complex burial process.\nIn ancient Egyptian worldview, four-legged and feathered creatures were considered sacred, divine and influencing their destinies.\nThey occupied an honorable place in the pantheon, and the gods were often depicted with animal heads.\nMummification was an integral part of this religious practice, emphasizing the special status of these creatures in the eyes of the Egyptians.\nThe Egyptians mummified various animals, believing that their gods could take different forms.\nFor example, the goddess Bast, the daughter of Ra, was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat \u2019 s head.\nThis goddess symbolized well-being, joy, love and fertility.\nThe Egyptians especially revered cats for their ability to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, then considered valuable as gold.\nCats have also earned the nickname \u201csunny eye \u201d due to their ability to see in the dark.\nThis property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology.\nArchaeological studies conducted at the ancient Egyptian necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa have uncovered the burial of crocodiles, one of which has been preserved in the form of a practically whole mummy, providing a unique look at the ancient rites and veneration of animals in this culture.\nAuthor Petr Deryabin\nPetr Deryabin \u2013 journalist, correspondent of Pravda.Ru news service","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:108288","uncompressed_offset":297891389,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/","warc_date":"2023-12-21T15:51:28.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/"},"created":"2023-12-21T16:02:19.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1104","request_id":"1104","narrative_id":"1104"},"responses":[{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"In ancient Egyptian culture, animals were not merely companions or utilitarian beings; they were revered as sacred entities with divine qualities that could influence human destinies."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Among these animals, cats held a particularly exalted status, symbolizing a unique blend of spiritual and practical significance."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The goddess Bast, also known as Bastet, was a central figure in Egyptian mythology and was often depicted as a cat or a woman with the head of a cat, embodying attributes such as well-being, joy, love, and fertility."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This divine association elevated cats to a sacred status, making them integral to the spiritual and cultural fabric of ancient Egyptian society."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Cats were affectionately referred to as 'sunny eye' in ancient Egypt, a nickname that highlighted their ability to see in the dark and linked them to the sun and light in Egyptian mythology."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This unique ability to navigate darkness contributed to their symbolic representation of protection and vigilance, qualities that were deeply valued in Egyptian spiritual beliefs."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The ancient Egyptians demonstrated profound respect for their pets, particularly cats, to the extent that they believed these animals deserved eternal life through mummification and elaborate burial rituals."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This practice of mummifying cats underscores the depth of their spiritual and emotional connection to these animals, treating them as family members and sacred beings."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking cultural practices related to cats was the mourning ritual, where Egyptians would shave their eyebrows to signify the loss of a family cat."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This act of shaving eyebrows was a visible and deeply personal expression of grief, reflecting the profound bond between humans and cats in ancient Egyptian society."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Beyond their spiritual significance, cats were also highly valued for their practical contributions, particularly their role in controlling rodent populations."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"By exterminating rodents, cats played a critical role in preserving grain stocks, which were as valuable as gold and essential for the survival and prosperity of ancient Egyptian civilization."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This dual role of cats, as both protectors of vital resources and sacred beings, solidified their unparalleled importance in the daily lives and spiritual practices of the ancient Egyptians."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"In ancient Egyptian culture, animals were not merely companions or utilitarian beings; they were revered as sacred entities with divine qualities that could influence human destinies."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Among these animals, cats held a particularly exalted status, symbolizing a unique blend of spiritual and practical significance."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The goddess Bast, also known as Bastet, was a central figure in Egyptian mythology and was often depicted as a cat or a woman with the head of a cat, embodying attributes such as well-being, joy, love, and fertility."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This divine association elevated cats to a sacred status, making them integral to the spiritual and cultural fabric of ancient Egyptian society."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Cats were affectionately referred to as 'sunny eye' in ancient Egypt, a nickname that highlighted their ability to see in the dark and linked them to the sun and light in Egyptian mythology."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This unique ability to navigate darkness contributed to their symbolic representation of protection and vigilance, qualities that were deeply valued in Egyptian spiritual beliefs."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"The ancient Egyptians demonstrated profound respect for their pets, particularly cats, to the extent that they believed these animals deserved eternal life through mummification and elaborate burial rituals."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This practice of mummifying cats underscores the depth of their spiritual and emotional connection to these animals, treating them as family members and sacred beings."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"One of the most striking cultural practices related to cats was the mourning ritual, where Egyptians would shave their eyebrows to signify the loss of a family cat."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This act of shaving eyebrows was a visible and deeply personal expression of grief, reflecting the profound bond between humans and cats in ancient Egyptian society."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"Beyond their spiritual significance, cats were also highly valued for their practical contributions, particularly their role in controlling rodent populations."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"By exterminating rodents, cats played a critical role in preserving grain stocks, which were as valuable as gold and essential for the survival and prosperity of ancient Egyptian civilization."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":100.0},"text":"This dual role of cats, as both protectors of vital resources and sacred beings, solidified their unparalleled importance in the daily lives and spiritual practices of the ancient Egyptians."}],"references":["f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389"],"documents":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":{"id":"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389","text":"The mummy of a pet: why and why did the ancient Egyptians do this?\n1: 43\nThe Egyptians showed special respect for their pets, their love was so great that they wanted these animals to have eternal life.\nAfter death, pets were mummified and went through a complex burial process.\nIn ancient Egyptian worldview, four-legged and feathered creatures were considered sacred, divine and influencing their destinies.\nThey occupied an honorable place in the pantheon, and the gods were often depicted with animal heads.\nMummification was an integral part of this religious practice, emphasizing the special status of these creatures in the eyes of the Egyptians.\nThe Egyptians mummified various animals, believing that their gods could take different forms.\nFor example, the goddess Bast, the daughter of Ra, was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat \u2019 s head.\nThis goddess symbolized well-being, joy, love and fertility.\nThe Egyptians especially revered cats for their ability to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, then considered valuable as gold.\nCats have also earned the nickname \u201csunny eye \u201d due to their ability to see in the dark.\nThis property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology.\nArchaeological studies conducted at the ancient Egyptian necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa have uncovered the burial of crocodiles, one of which has been preserved in the form of a practically whole mummy, providing a unique look at the ancient rites and veneration of animals in this culture.\nAuthor Petr Deryabin\nPetr Deryabin \u2013 journalist, correspondent of Pravda.Ru news service","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:108288","uncompressed_offset":297891389,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/","warc_date":"2023-12-21T15:51:28.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/"},"created":"2023-12-21T16:02:19.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
