{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1107","request_id":"1107","narrative_id":"1107"},"responses":[{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles, a collection of 17 sculptures originally part of the Parthenon frieze in Athens, were removed by Lord Elgin in the early 19th century during his tenure as British ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, which ruled Greece at the time."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Lord Elgin claimed to have obtained permission from the Ottoman authorities to remove the sculptures, but no documentation has been found to substantiate this claim, fueling the controversy surrounding their removal."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Since their arrival in Britain, the Elgin Marbles have been housed in the British Museum, sparking a debate over their legitimacy and ownership that has persisted for over two centuries."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Greece has consistently sought the return of the marbles, with efforts intensifying after its independence in 1832 and gaining momentum in the 1980s under Minister of Culture Melina Mercury."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"In 2009, Greece opened the Acropolis Museum, specifically designed to house the Elgin Marbles should they be repatriated, underscoring their cultural and historical significance to the nation."},{"citations":{"d8527c83-5025-4344-ad1a-0d52b09332cf_835728356":100.0},"text":"However, the British Museum Act of 1963 prohibits the permanent return of items in its collection, creating a significant legal barrier to repatriation."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"In recent years, diplomatic efforts have explored alternative solutions, such as a 'Parthenon partnership' or long-term loan agreements, with Greece offering to exchange other artifacts in return."},{"citations":{"6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17_907513189":100.0},"text":"Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has described the separation of the marbles as akin to tearing apart a masterpiece, emphasizing their importance as symbols of national identity and sovereignty."},{"citations":{"9907d401-9c7d-4e43-83e5-bafa126e4120_340367488":100.0},"text":"The controversy has broader implications for international relations and cultural diplomacy, with UNESCO attempting to mediate talks and advocates like Stephen Fry proposing innovative solutions such as virtual replicas."},{"citations":{"c5684696-8997-4394-9642-4fab25660f72_976481682":100.0},"text":"While no resolution has been reached, ongoing discussions and recent repatriation agreements with other nations suggest potential pathways for resolving the dispute over the Elgin Marbles."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"The Elgin Marbles, a collection of 17 sculptures originally part of the Parthenon frieze in Athens, were removed by Lord Elgin in the early 19th century during his tenure as British ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, which ruled Greece at the time."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Lord Elgin claimed to have obtained permission from the Ottoman authorities to remove the sculptures, but no documentation has been found to substantiate this claim, fueling the controversy surrounding their removal."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Since their arrival in Britain, the Elgin Marbles have been housed in the British Museum, sparking a debate over their legitimacy and ownership that has persisted for over two centuries."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"Greece has consistently sought the return of the marbles, with efforts intensifying after its independence in 1832 and gaining momentum in the 1980s under Minister of Culture Melina Mercury."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"In 2009, Greece opened the Acropolis Museum, specifically designed to house the Elgin Marbles should they be repatriated, underscoring their cultural and historical significance to the nation."},{"citations":{"d8527c83-5025-4344-ad1a-0d52b09332cf_835728356":100.0},"text":"However, the British Museum Act of 1963 prohibits the permanent return of items in its collection, creating a significant legal barrier to repatriation."},{"citations":{"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":100.0},"text":"In recent years, diplomatic efforts have explored alternative solutions, such as a 'Parthenon partnership' or long-term loan agreements, with Greece offering to exchange other artifacts in return."},{"citations":{"6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17_907513189":100.0},"text":"Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has described the separation of the marbles as akin to tearing apart a masterpiece, emphasizing their importance as symbols of national identity and sovereignty."},{"citations":{"9907d401-9c7d-4e43-83e5-bafa126e4120_340367488":100.0},"text":"The controversy has broader implications for international relations and cultural diplomacy, with UNESCO attempting to mediate talks and advocates like Stephen Fry proposing innovative solutions such as virtual replicas."},{"citations":{"c5684696-8997-4394-9642-4fab25660f72_976481682":100.0},"text":"While no resolution has been reached, ongoing discussions and recent repatriation agreements with other nations suggest potential pathways for resolving the dispute over the Elgin Marbles."}],"references":["d8527c83-5025-4344-ad1a-0d52b09332cf_835728356","9907d401-9c7d-4e43-83e5-bafa126e4120_340367488","c5684696-8997-4394-9642-4fab25660f72_976481682","692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005","6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17_907513189"],"documents":{"c5684696-8997-4394-9642-4fab25660f72_976481682":{"id":"c5684696-8997-4394-9642-4fab25660f72_976481682","text":"UK museums strike loan deal to return Asante Gold to Ghana that was looted over 100 years ago\n\n25 January 2024, 07:25 | Updated: 25 January 2024, 07:27\n\nBy Jenny Medlicott\n\nThe UK is returning a selection of Asante Gold looted from Ghana over 100 years ago in a historic loan deal.\n\nListen to this article\n\nLoading audio...\n\nThe British Museum has struck a deal to return 15 pieces of the gold to Ghana and the Victoria & Albert Museum (V&A) 17 pieces, under a new three-year loan deal.\n\nLoan deals are used as a way to enable collections to return to their countries of origin.\n\nThe Ghanian loan deal, which can be extended by an additional three years, was agreed with Otumfo Osei Tutu II, the current Asante king known as the Asantehene.\n\nSome national museums in the UK, including the V&A and British Museum, are prohibited from permanently returning such items to their countries of origin.\n\nThe items will reportedly go on display at the Manhyia Palace Museum in Kumasi, the capital of the Asante region, to celebrate the Asantehene's silver jubilee.\n\nTristram Hunt, director of the V&A, said the gold items taken from the court of the Asante King are the equivalent of \"our Crown Jewels\".\n\nMr Hunt also said when museums \"hold objects with origins in war and looting in military campaigns, we have a responsibility to the countries of origin to think about how we can share those more fairly today.\n\nRead more: British military drawing up plans for 500,000-strong 'citizen army' as top general warns UK 'stumbling into war'\n\nRead more: Home Secretary defends Govt record on 'zombie knives' as Labour sets out \u00a3100m plan to tackle knife crime\n\n\"It doesn't seem to me that all of our museums will fall down if we build up these kind of partnerships and exchanges,\u201d he told the BBC.\n\nIt is hoped the historic deal will pave the way for handling other repatriation disputes - potentially including the long-running dispute over the Elgin Marbles.\n\nGhana\u2019s chief operation said he hoped the deal would bring a \u201ca new sense of cultural co-operation\u201d following years of anger.\n\nHowever, some have expressed concern that accepting the items on loan could be seen as acceptance of the UK\u2019s ownership of the contested items.\n\nMost of the items were taken during 19th-century wars between the British and the Asante.\n\nA sword of state and gold badges worn by officials charged with cleansing the soul of the king are among the items to be returned.\n\nThe artefacts are seen as a symbol of the Asante royal government and are believed to hold the spirits of former Asante kings.\n\nAs for other contested artefacts held by British museums, in the case of the Elgin Marbles, a senior British Museum has source said the museum was \u201cstill exploring if there is an arrangement that would allow some of the Parthenon sculptures to travel to Greece\u201d.\n\nIt is hoped deals such as these could help provide a solution to former colonial nations requesting the return of their cultural treasures.","url":"https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/ghana-uk-british-museums-return-loan-asante-gold-victoria-and-albert/"},"d8527c83-5025-4344-ad1a-0d52b09332cf_835728356":{"id":"d8527c83-5025-4344-ad1a-0d52b09332cf_835728356","text":"\nSend Them Home\n\nThe Elgin Marbles, actually the Parthenon Marbles, have been Greek for over two thousand years and still are in every way except location. They were taken, realistically stolen, by Lord Elgin in the early 1800s and most people believe should be returned but that is actually illegal under British Museum Act 1963 and offers to \u2018lend\u2019 them are insulting.\n\nOne of the most obvious concerns that many museums have is that they would be emptied of items that were acquired, a weasel word for stolen, during times when the attitudes were different. Different attitudes do not condone theft.\n\nLet\u2019s return the thefts of the past to their rightful owners and put the past attitudes in the rubbish bin of time.\n\nDennis Fitzgerald,\nMelbourne, Australia\n\nRelated Articles","url":"https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2023/01/07/send-them-home/"},"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005":{"id":"692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b_430177005","text":"LONDON (Reuters) - The historic Greek treasure of Elgin Marbles is nearing its return to its country of origin, 200 years after it was moved and ended up in the British Museum.\nThe Parthenon marble, seen as a symbol of freedom in Greece, was controversially moved out of the country by a British diplomat in a move that ignited a debate that lasted more than two centuries.\nGreece has made repeated requests for the sculptures to be returned after they were controversially removed from one of the world \u2019 s most historic landmarks.\nPrime Minister Rishi Sonak had been scheduled to meet his Greek counterpart Kyriakos Mitsotakis on Tuesday, but Downing Street canceled the arrangement and sent Deputy Prime Minister Oliver Duden instead.\nThe head of the British Museum, former Conservative Chancellor George Osborne, is pushing for a temporary loan to be returned to Greece, and is believed to have drawn up a deal.\nBut both Sonak and Labour leader Sir Keir Starmer say they will not support a change to the British Museum law that currently bars their return.\nThe museum said it was continuing \"constructive discussions\" about their possible return.\nGin Marble\nThe Algin marble is 17 sculptures that are 2,500 years old.\nHis pieces were part of a frieze that adorned the ancient Parthenon temple at the Acropolis in Athens, Greece.\nThe marbles make up about half of the 160-meter-long frieze of the Parthenon Temple, which is considered one of the greatest cultural monuments in the world.\nThese sculptures are seen as symbols of freedom in Greece, where they are known as Parthenon marble.\nBritish diplomat Lord Elgin removed the sculptures from the majestic Parthenon temple in the early 19th century.\nAt that time, he was ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, which ruled Greece.\nBeginning in 1801, Lord Elgin is said to have supervised the removal of the marble and shipped it to the UK in 170 boxes.\nHe is said to have claimed to have obtained permission from the Ottoman Empire to move the marble, but despite massive documentation from that period, nothing was found to support his actions.\nIn the United Kingdom, Lord Elgin received support and criticism, and sold it to the United Kingdom government in 1816 before the marble was transferred to the custody of the British Museum.\nThe beginning and evolution of the dispute\nThe controversy between Greece and Britain can be traced back to when the marble first arrived in Britain due to criticism of its removal.\nIn 1832, Greece gained independence from the Ottoman Empire before it began trying to recover sculptures and other works of art taken from the country.\nIn the early 1980s, the actress and then Greek Minister of Culture, Melina Mercury, reignited the campaign when she made it her mission to secure the return of marble sculptures.\nIn 1983, she met with the director of the British Museum, Dr. David Wilson, in London to demand the return of the sculptures.\nShe continued to press the museum and the British government until her death in 1994.\nDespite other requests and high-level media coverage, no agreement was reached in the years that followed.\nA new campaign\nIn 2009, Greece stepped up its marble recovery campaign after opening a new museum at the foot of the Acropolis Hill, hoping one day to house it.\nIn 2014, human rights lawyer Amal Clooney called on Britain to start talks with Greece over the return of the Elgin marble.\nThe lawyer, who is the wife of Hollywood star George Clooney, said: \"This is an injustice that has been going on for a long time, in a world full of intractable conflicts.\"\nIn 2015, Greece ruled out any legal action against the UK over Elgin Marbles.\nIn May 2022, the so-called Fagan fragment \u2014 a piece showing the foot of the ancient Greek goddess Artemis seated \u2014 was permanently returned to Athens from a museum in Italy.\nIt was originally part of the eastern frieze of the temple dating back to the 5th century BC.\nThe British reaction\nIn 2022, there were calls to make it easier for UK museums to consider returning cultural objects, but the government rejected them.\nFormer Conservative culture minister Lord Vaizi also headed a new body aimed at returning Elgin marble to Greece.\nThe refusal came after then-Prime Minister Boris Johnson told the Greek prime minister during talks at Downing Street in 2021 that the sculpture issue was \"a matter for the curators of the British Museum\".\nThen, at the beginning of December, George Osborne, the head of the British Museum, reportedly held secret talks with the Greek prime minister about the possibility of returning the marble sculptures.\nNegotiations between former Treasury Secretary Osborne and Kiriakos Mitsotakis have been taking place in London since November 2021, according to the Greek daily Ta Nea.\nThe Greek prime minister has on numerous occasions called for the relocation of the sculptures, and even offered to lend other treasures to the British Museum in return.\nA spokesman for Project Parthenon, a campaign advocating the return of marble sculptures, hailed the talks as a \u201cpositive sign \u201d that a\u201c win-win solution \u201d to the centuries-old debate could be reached.\nPossible deal?\nIn December last year, Downing Street said there were no plans to change the law that prohibits the museum from disposing of objects in its collection except in very limited circumstances.\nA spokesman for the prime minister said: \u201cThe Parthenon sculptures are legally owned by trustees and are practically independent of the government. \u201d\nLast month, the British Museum issued a statement saying it would not dismantle its collection \u201cbecause it tells a unique story of our common humanity, \u201d but added that it wanted to forge a new\u201c Parthenon partnership \u201d with Greece.\nThe talks in Westminster were used by former culture minister Lord Vaizi to press again for the return of the sculptures.\nHe said that the frieze in Athens \"resembles a film that was cut in half and half of it was moved against the will of its owners to another country.\"\nAfter cancelling the bilateral meeting between Sonak and Mitsotakis on Tuesday, the Greek leader said he was \"disappointed\".\nMr Sonak said the UK \u201chas no plans to change our approach \u201d but\u201c did not ask him [Mr Mitsotakis] what short-term or new ideas have been put forward \u201d.\nStarmer and Mitsotakis Meet\nOpposition Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer met Mitsotakis on Monday.\nA source close to Labour leader Sir Kiir Starmer told the Financial Times he was unlikely to change the law if he won the next election.\n\"We are committed to the current law, but if a mutually acceptable loan deal can be agreed between the British Museum and the Greek government, we will not stand in the way.\"\nIs the agreement possible?\nThe head of the National Museum, George Osborne, is understood to have drawn up a deal with Athens, according to the Daily Telegraph.\nCurrent legislation bars the museum from legally granting treasures, but Osborne is said to be seeking to repatriate the antiquities as part of a long-term \"cultural exchange.\"\nBut this loan deal is not expected to permanently end the long-running dispute.\nThe article was prepared from the site of (Sky News) British channel:\nhttps: / / news.sky.com / story / elgin-marbles-what-are-they-and-how-did-they-end-up-in-the-british-museum-12779617","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0034.json.gz:11001","uncompressed_offset":430177005,"url":"elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html","warc_date":"2023-11-28T18:49:10.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:692190b1-fd12-4a64-a3cb-9ef96377f96b>","warc_url":"https://elaph.com/Web/News/2023/11/1520797.html"},"created":"2023-11-28T19:10:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"9907d401-9c7d-4e43-83e5-bafa126e4120_340367488":{"id":"9907d401-9c7d-4e43-83e5-bafa126e4120_340367488","text":"Stephen Fry calls returning Elgin Marbles to Greece 'A classy thing at last'\n\nTHE ELGIN Marbles' return to Greece would be \"a classy act\" by the UK, says Stephen Fry.\n\nLink copied\n\nUK has 'no obligation' to return Elgin Marbles says Widdecombe\n\nGreece has called for the repatriation of the collection of Elgin Marbles for more than 200 years \u2013 ever since they were taken from the Parthenon in 1802 on the order of Lord Elgin, Britain's then-ambassador to the Ottoman Empire. Mr Fry, who said he is \"very keen\" to see the sculptures be returned to Athens, has been the latest to join the debate over the home of the monumental artwork.\n\nThe actor and broadcaster suggested the marbles be replaced with a virtual experience.\n\nHe stressed that with modern technology the carvings can be replicated using lasers.\n\nHe said: \"So the British Museum would have a Parthenon experience and you go in and see this fabulous technology using AR helmets or whatever you want to wear and you see how the originals were perfectly reproduced and out in place and you watch them being packed up and put on the train.\"\n\nThe sculptures, which sit at the London-based institution, have not been available to be publicly viewed for nearly a year due to ongoing maintenance work and the coronavirus pandemic.\n\nThe British Museum is to reopen its Greek galleries to the public on Monday, December 13.\n\nREAD MORE:\u00a0Boris in lockdown warning: 'Tidal wave' of Omicron to hit UK - PM unveils new jabs plan\n\nCritics argue the Elgin Marbles, which sit at the British Museum, should be repatriated to Greece (Image: Getty)\n\nMr Fry, 64, said: \"I know a lot of people say 'we've looked after them' and it's certainly true we've looked after them, but it would be such a classy act.\n\n\"I promise you one million Athenians would come on to the street to welcome them.\n\n\"They mean so much to the Greeks, they are part of the nature of what Athens is.\"\n\nThe British Museum houses 15 metopes, 17 pedimental figures and 75 metres of the original frieze.\n\n50 metres remain in Athens and other parts are in museums across Europe.\n\nComedian Stephen Fry called returning the artwork would be 'a classy act' from Britain's side (Image: Getty)\n\nThe sculptures have been a subject of debate ever since the were taken from Greece in 1802 (Image: Getty)\n\nMr Fry claimed a move such as returning the Elgin Marbles is what the country needs: \"There would be a hand-shake ceremony and suddenly people would for once look at Britain and say that was a classy act.\n\n\"It would be a classy thing and Britain hasn't done a classy thing for some time.\"\n\nGreek prime minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, speaking to the FT ahead of a foreign policy trip to the UK last month, said: \"If I were in the PM's shoes and I were thinking out of the box in terms of global Britannia, and the idea of Britain really playing a role in the post-Brexit world, [it] would be a fantastic coup for public diplomacy if they were to look at this from a different perspective.\"\n\nDON'T MISS\nBrexit Britain could avoid energy shortages with breakthrough renewable source [INSIGHT]\nDanny Miller crowned I\u2019m A Celebrity 2021 winner \u2018I\u2019m speechless for once!\u2019 [REPORT]\nEnraged Brit calls Macron 'jumped-up Napoleon' and urges Boris to 'get in ring' over fish [ANALYSIS]\n\nKyriakos Mitsotakis advocates for 'reunification' of Elgin Marbles\n\nGreek prime minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis has urged Boris Johnson to return the marbles to Athens (Image: Getty)\n\nThen, during his visit to London, he urged Prime Minister Boris Johnson to return the priceless ancient sculptures to Greece, again presenting it as a chance for the UK to strengthen its Global Britain standing.\n\nMr Johnson has so far not shown signs he intends to return the Elgin Marbles.\n\nSpeaking to the Greek paper Ta Nea earlier this year, he claimed: \"The UK government has a firm, longstanding position on the sculptures.\n\n\"They were legally acquired by Lord Elgin under the appropriate laws of the time and have been legally owned by the British Museum\u2019s trustees since their acquisition.\"\n\nThis aligns with the view outlined on the British Museum\u2019s website, which backs Lord Elgin's efforts to bring the marbles to the UK in the early 19th century: \"His actions were thoroughly investigated by a parliamentary select committee in 1816 and found to be entirely legal, prior to the sculptures entering the collection of the British Museum by act of parliament.\"","url":"https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1535206/elgin-marbles-news-stephen-fry-return-sculpture-greece-british-museum-boris-johnson"},"6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17_907513189":{"id":"6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17_907513189","text":"Countdown to the day of issuance\n0\n23\n11\n50.\nGo to Election Zone\nGreek PM reiterates demand for British Museum to return Parthenon statue, British PM cancels meeting, sparking diplomatic row\nGreek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, in an interview with the BBC on Sunday, reiterated that the authorities want the British Museum to return some of the statues that were \u201cstolen \u201d from the Parthenon Temple.\nWhat we want you to know is\nGreek Prime Minister Mitsotakis, in an interview with the BBC on Sunday (26), described the Parthenon shrine as part of the statue group in Greece, part in the United Kingdom, like the \"Mona Lisa smile\" torn in half and asked Britain to return it.\nBritish Prime Minister David Sunak then called the meeting a \"temporary cancellation\" hours before the meeting, prompting discontent from Mitsotakis, Greek officials and the public, calling it a \"diplomatic crisis.\"\nIn an interview with the BBC on Sunday, Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis reiterated that the British Museum wants to return some of the \u201cstolen \u201d statues from the Parthenon Temple. Subsequently, British Prime Minister Rishi Sunak, hours before the meeting with Mitsotakis, a temporary resolution to cancel, sparking a diplomatic dispute between the two countries.\nBBC, British authorities claim that Sunak cancelled the meeting because Mitsotakis broke his promise to \"not talk about the statue\".\nMitsotakis, however, said it was Greece \u2019 s consistent and public stance to demand the British Museum return of the statue, saying in a statement: \u201cI would like to express my dissatisfaction with the temporary cancellation by the United Kingdom just hours before the meeting. \u201d\nThe Greeks worked for hundreds of years to return the statue of the Parthenon.\nThe controversial statue is one of a group of marble statues used to decorate the Parthenon Temple in the ancient Greek city of Athens, also known as the Elgin Marbles.\nIn the 19th century, the British diplomat to the Ottoman Empire, the 7th Earl of Elgin, secretly removed the stone carvings and brought them back to Britain for collection in the British Museum.\nAt that time, Elgin claimed that he had taken the stone carvings with the permission of the Ottoman Empire and therefore had legitimacy.\nHowever, the Greek authorities do not think so.\nSince 1983, the Greek government has been trying to coordinate with the UK to ask them to return the stone carvings. In 2022, UNESCO also intervened to facilitate talks, but to no avail.\nTherefore, the issue of the return of the stone carvings has become the core issue and exchange condition of many negotiations between Greece and Britain, including of course the meeting originally planned by Sunak and Mitsotakis.\nStatues of the Parthenon Temple are mainly located in Athens and the British Museum.\nIn an interview with the BBC on the 26th, Mitsotakis described: \"The scattered statue is like tearing the famous painting\" Mona Lisa's Smile \"in two parts and giving it to two museums.\" He called on the British authorities and the British Museum to return the \"stolen\" stone carvings and work together so that people can enjoy the statue \"in its place\".\nBecause of these remarks, Sunak temporarily announced on Monday night that he would cancel his meeting with Mitsotakis on Tuesday.\nAccording to the Guardian, the British government said that the content of Mitsotakis \u2019 interview with the BBC violates the commitment of the two countries to \u201cnot talk about the return of stone carvings \u201d agreed in 2021.\nThe Greek authorities immediately denied the claim, and Mitsotakiston said that Greece \u2019 s position on asking Britain to return the statue was well known and reiterated during his tenure as prime minister.\nThe conversation should have been about the climate crisis, the Israeli-Kazakh conflict, the Russian-Ukrainian war, the British and Greek immigration plans, and the Parthenon statue.\nAfter Sunak cancelled the talks, the British offered to have Deputy Prime Minister Oliver Dowden attend, but Mitsotakis refused, and the two sides did not meet.\nUK has no plans to amend the British Museum Act\nThe New York Times reported that in the past two years, the Greek government and the British Museum have repeatedly held \"delicate negotiations\" over the return of the statue, but the two sides have yet to reach a consensus.\nAccording to the report, the Greek authorities want the British Museum to return all the Parthenon stone carvings, in exchange for which the Greek Museum will regularly select artefacts for display in the British Museum.\nFor its part, the British Museum agreed to \"borrow\" some of the Parthenon stone carvings and other exhibits from the Greek government for a short period of time. If Greece \"returns\" on schedule, the British Museum will \"lend\" more stone carvings.\nMitsotakis also mentioned in an interview with the BBC that the outcome of the negotiations at this stage is not as good as he expected, but he considers himself a man of perseverance and said: \"Greece has waited for hundreds of years, we can wait more.\"\n\u201cI \u2019 m going to stand firm and be willing to continue negotiations.\nA British government spokesman told The Guardian they were concerned that the return of stone carvings to Greece could create a \u201cslippery slope \u201d that could trigger a wave of returns of disputed artifacts from other collections.\nIn addition, the British Museum Act 1963 states that the British Museum may not return its collections to its homeland.\nAccording to the BBC, the British government has no plans to amend the decree, which means that the British authorities are unwilling to violate the decree and return the stone carvings to Greece.\nThe return of the stone sculpture is a matter of British election and diplomatic relations.\nEvangelos Kyriakidis, head of the Greek Agency for Monuments and Estates, told Euronews that the Greek government attaches importance to the statues of the Parthenon temple because they are not only important monuments, but also a symbol of Greek national strength.\nKiriadis uses the metaphor of \"the jewel of the crown of the king of England in Greece\" to argue that the issue of the statue group is a matter of sovereignty.\nThe New York Times pointed out that the news of the cancellation of the meeting in Sunak immediately triggered the dissatisfaction of politicians of the Greek political party and caused a wave of criticism on social media, with many accounts condemning it as a diplomatic incident and a mini-diplomatic crisis between Greece and the United Kingdom.\nThe Guardian also quoted a Greek government spokesman, accusing Sunak of using the issue of the return of stone carvings with Greece to divert attention from Britain's internal affairs.\nThe spokesman said more bluntly that Sunak \u2019 s decision has the potential to damage Britain \u2019 s reputation in Europe, which is divided after Brexit.\nA senior EU official also told The Guardian that cancelling the prime minister \u2019 s meeting and then sending the deputy prime minister to meet with the Greek prime minister would violate normal diplomatic procedures and damage Britain \u2019 s credibility.\nHe also said: \"The United Kingdom, which wants to go global, cannot stop talking to friends about a problem that has existed for 200 years.\"\nAnother observer also pointed out that the British government is ahead of the serious refugee problem, and Greece is a member of the European Union that links Europe and the Mediterranean, which has important geopolitical significance.\nNot only is there a diplomatic crisis, but the return of the stone carvings to the dispute may also bring about a domestic crisis for Sunak and the ruling party.\nThe New York Times reported that Britain will hold elections next year, and the ruling party is currently facing a long period of economic stagnation in the United Kingdom and divergent views on immigration policy. At this time, it has a conflict with Greece, which may make the question of the ownership of the statue an election point between the Labour Party and the Conservative Party.\nNews sources\nExtended reading\n(Join the critical review network member) Daily wonderful articles sent directly to your mailbox, each week exclusive editorial selection, current affairs selection, art weekly newspaper and other special electronic newspapers.\nYou can also leave comments with authors, journalists, and editors to discuss the content of the article.\nJoin now for free!\nEditor-in-chief: Yang Shifan","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0034.json.gz:7269","uncompressed_offset":907513189,"url":"www.thenewslens.com/article/195385","warc_date":"2023-11-29T09:42:38.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:6b21a93f-a723-47e7-aed4-7836bedbdd17>","warc_url":"https://www.thenewslens.com/article/195385"},"created":"2023-11-29T10:31:05.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
