-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":100.0},"text":"The construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":100.0},"text":"Experts like Claudia Kemfert suggest that the 5% share of German electricity from the last three reactors can be replaced without risking power outages."},{"citations":{"0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038":100.0},"text":"The German Technical Supervision Association stated that the three nuclear power plants were comprehensively inspected in March and could be restarted with limited further testing and monitoring."},{"citations":{"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":100.0},"text":"Nuclear energy advocates argue that Germany's decision could harm a technology seen as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels."}],"references":["fb5e4536-88df-4613-bc56-480ab5b00a3f_351849641","533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038","0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207","12f71d0d-8a71-46e5-9d7d-b45a8f75dbe2_1066539592"],"documents":{"fb5e4536-88df-4613-bc56-480ab5b00a3f_351849641":{"id":"fb5e4536-88df-4613-bc56-480ab5b00a3f_351849641","text":"Read the history of the moment: why is Germany so entangled in nuclear power? | German News | DW | 14.04.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nGerman News\nRead the history of the present: why is Germany so entangled in nuclear power?\nGermany was proud of its nuclear power generation technology, but at the same time the technology has been so controversial that it has finally decided that April 15, 2023 is the date of withdrawal from nuclear power.\nHowever, as the energy crisis caused by the Russian-Ukrainian war continues to intensify, the wisdom of the decision to say goodbye to nuclear energy has been widely discussed.\nGermany \u2019 s nuclear policy is in dispute again\nIt all started with an \"egg\" - Germany's first nuclear reactor in Garching, near Munich, went into operation in October 1957.\nBecause the nuclear reactor, which belongs to the University of Munich, resembles an egg, it is nicknamed the \"atomic egg\".\nIt was a milestone in Germany's nuclear energy research and a symbol of Germany's resurgence after World War II.\nThe nuclear reactor, which was used for scientific purposes, remained in operation until 2000.\nIn 1957, Germany built its first nuclear reactor.\nThree years later, in 1960, the first nuclear power plant for civilian use was built in the city of Kahl, on the banks of the Main River in Bavaria.\nAt that time, atomic energy was widely regarded as both safe and reliable. The 1973 oil crisis gave further impetus to the rapid development of nuclear energy in Germany.\nThe start of the anti-nuclear movement\nSince it has been impossible to find a foolproof way to store nuclear waste, opponents have begun to question whether nuclear energy is really a clean energy source.\nThousands of protesters clashed with police during the construction of the Brockdorf nuclear power plant in the state of Shihe.\nSince the 1970s, plans for the construction of the Brockdorf nuclear power plant have triggered numerous police and civil conflicts.\n\"Nuclear energy? No, thank you!\" has become a rallying cry for environmentalists.\nIn the 1980s, a new political party, the Green Party, emerged in West Germany. Its members are mainly leftists, pacifists, environmentalists and anti-nuclear forces. In 1983, the Green Party entered the Bundestag.\nIn 1983, Green Party politicians Gert Bastian and Petra Kelly were elected to the Bundestag.\nOn March 28, 1979, a serious accident occurred at the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant in Pennsylvania, United States. On April 26, 1986, a reactor at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in Ukraine, Soviet Union, exploded, causing the worst nuclear disaster in history.\nRadiation clouds spread throughout Europe.\nThe accident also marked a turning point in discussions about nuclear technology in Germany.\nAt the time, Germany was still divided.\nIn East Germany under the Communist Party, the public received almost no information about the nuclear accident and its effects.\nWest Germany, on the other hand, was in a state of confusion and politicians were helpless.\nPeople were unprepared for a nuclear leak, and the government was unable to provide guidelines and response strategies for the time being.\nA hastily formed crisis management team was also disbanded shortly afterwards.\nThe Chernobyl nuclear accident has caused widespread concern in Germany.\nPeople are buying iodine.\nA large quantity of fruit, vegetables and milk in the supermarket was ordered to be removed from the shelves because of concerns about nuclear radiation.\nChildren were banned from playing in the sand pools and citizens were warned not to go out in the rain.\nAlthough the health effects of radiation were not detected in Germany, the accident led to the introduction of nationwide radiation monitoring in Germany, which eventually led to the establishment of the Federal Ministry of the Environment.\nPlans to build a nuclear waste treatment plant in the Bavarian town of Wackersdorf have sparked serious riots.\nThe clashes left several protesters and civil servants dead and hundreds injured.\nThe project was finally halted in 1989, the first major victory of the German environmental movement.\nAnd...\nIn 2011, protesters handcuffed themselves to the tracks in an attempt to block trains carrying nuclear waste.\nMeanwhile, in northern Germany, Gorleben in Lower Saxony became a symbol of the struggle against nuclear waste, and the town was designated to temporarily store nuclear waste until a permanent storage site was identified.\nThe first shipment of nuclear waste arrived in the town on 24 April 1995.\nA long farewell to nuclear power - Germany's nuclear withdrawal process after many setbacks\nIn 2001, Schroeder's center-left coalition government of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Green Party reached an agreement with major energy companies to phase out nuclear power.\nAll 19 nuclear power plants in Germany have been given operating timelines and the last one is required to be shut down by 2021.\nIn 2001, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder announced that Germany would phase out nuclear power generation.\nIn 2010, the center-right government led by Chancellor Angela Merkel withdrew the nuclear withdrawal agreement.\nIt also decided to extend the operating time of nuclear power plants.\nHowever, the third major nuclear accident in the world has caused a change in Germany's nuclear energy policy. On March 11, 2011, the accident at the Fukushima nuclear power plant in Japan caused by the earthquake and tsunami.\nThe impact of the accident on Germany is even greater than that of Japan.\nAs a veteran physicist, German Chancellor Angela Merkel unexpectedly changed her usual stance on nuclear energy policy.\nMerkel suddenly announced that the era of nuclear power in Germany will end by the end of 2022. On July 30, 2011, the German Bundestag voted to approve the resolution.\nAfter years of fierce fighting, the Brockdorf nuclear power plant in the state of Ishih will finally become history in 2021 after 35 years of operation.\nIn 2017, Germany decided to start a nationwide search for a safe place to store highly radioactive nuclear waste, with the mission to be completed by 2031.\nAt the end of 2021, anti-nuclear activists celebrated the closure of a nuclear power plant in North Germany.\nRethinking the nuclear policy.\nThe war in Ukraine has made Germany anxious to get rid of its energy dependence on Russia, which has also reignited the already ironclad policy of denuclearization.\nThe coalition leader has spearheaded a proposal to extend the operating time of nuclear power plants to replace natural gas from Russia with nuclear power.\nIn August 2022, CDU Chairman Meltz and CSU Chairman Soder both put forward the idea of extending the time limit for nuclear power operations.\nChristian Lindner, finance minister of the business-oriented Liberal Democratic Party (FDP), immediately backed a return to nuclear power.\nHis party is junior partner in a centre-left coalition with the Social Democrats (SPD) and the Greens.\nThe latter will find it difficult to agree to an extension because opposition to nuclear power is one of their core issues.\nBut in the summer of 2022, no one in Germany completely ruled out that possibility.\nLDP finance minister Lindner, who is focused on business interests, was also quick to join the pro-nuclear camp.\nBut for the Green Party, which is also part of the ruling coalition, the possibility of agreeing to extend the operating time of nuclear power plants is slim, because opposition to nuclear power is their basic principle.\nAnything is possible in Germany in 2022.\nCan nuclear power be a climate savior?\nEditor: This article was originally published in August 2022\n\u00a9 2022 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.\nDW.COM","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:7327","uncompressed_offset":351849641,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E8%AF%BB%E5%8E%86%E5%8F%B2%E7%9C%8B%E5%BD%93%E4%B8%8B-%E5%BE%B7%E5%9B%BD%E5%9C%A8%E6%A0%B8%E7%94%B5%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98%E4%B8%8A%E4%B8%BA%E4%BD%95%E5%A6%82%E6%AD%A4%E7%BA%A0%E7%BB%93/a-62742413?zhongwen=simp","warc_date":"2023-04-14T10:26:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:fb5e4536-88df-4613-bc56-480ab5b00a3f>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E8%AF%BB%E5%8E%86%E5%8F%B2%E7%9C%8B%E5%BD%93%E4%B8%8B-%E5%BE%B7%E5%9B%BD%E5%9C%A8%E6%A0%B8%E7%94%B5%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98%E4%B8%8A%E4%B8%BA%E4%BD%95%E5%A6%82%E6%AD%A4%E7%BA%A0%E7%BB%93/a-62742413?zhongwen=simp"},"created":"2023-04-14T10:43:35.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038":{"id":"0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038","text":"World Vision: Restarting nuclear power, dragging the German government into crisis\nNovember 06, 2022 00: 03\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nWith Germany following the NATO sanctions against Russia, the German energy crisis is deepening and leading to serious political instability.\nThe gold-painted sign \u201cMade in Germany \u201d has been peeled off. First, the business community complained about the high price of electricity in Germany, averaging 0.37 euros per kilowatt-hour (kWh), compared with 0.18 euros in France, 0.24 euros in the United Kingdom and 0.10 euros in Hungary.\nEven if the German government proposed energy subsidies, but other European governments such as Britain and France will do so, German companies still can not compete. The result is that more and more industrial products that Germany was proud of in the past, either set up factories in foreign countries or import some foreign parts to complete in Germany.\nIn addition, some townships began to have problems with the opening up and strengthening of thermal power generation and transmission, and now there are rare power outages, which have caused great dissatisfaction among the public.\nThe Minister of Economy and Deputy Prime Minister Hajbek have become the target of attacks by the industrial sector, the German opposition, and the Liberal and Social Democrats in the government, focusing on Habek, who has no economic expertise but is responsible for the environmental ideology, and the government \u2019 s lack of understanding and compassion for industry, and has been deceiving the three nuclear power plants.\nHalbek has always stressed that the German people have long been the majority of anti-nuclear power, but the latest poll shows that 64% of the people support restarting nuclear power to increase supply and reduce electricity prices due to the energy crisis, with 40% of the Green Party voters.\nIn addition, the Green Party has spoken out in favor of improving climate change, but has been hiding experts \u2019 suggestions that turning on nuclear power could cut Germany \u2019 s carbon emissions by 25 million to 30 million tons a year.\nIn addition, Halbek stressed that the nuclear fuel rods needed for the nuclear power plant may not be available by early next year, but the expert opinion is that the old nuclear fuel rods can also be used and the nuclear power plant can be gradually opened.\nHalbek stressed that it would take a long time to open the safety inspection of nuclear power, but the world-famous German Technical Supervision Association immediately hit the face, claiming that they did a comprehensive inspection in March, all three nuclear power plants are normal, as long as limited further testing and monitoring, restart is not a problem at all.\nThe opposition party also criticized the three-party coalition government for delaying the setting of a gas price cap until March next year. At that time, the weather in Germany has begun to warm up. As a result, the opposition party and the public demand that Habaker resign, which can be regarded as the ruling coalition's biggest crisis to date.\nPh.D., Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0033.json.gz:3491","uncompressed_offset":847888038,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20221106/bkn-20221106000357564-1106_00832_001.html","warc_date":"2022-11-06T01:03:58.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20221106/bkn-20221106000357564-1106_00832_001.html"},"created":"2022-11-06T02:47:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":{"id":"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","text":"\u201cThere is no excuse for the rich West to be oblivious to the global debt crisis. \u201d \u2013 The Guardian\nWe start with an opinion piece by Larry Elliott, the Guardian \u2019 s economic editor, entitled \u201cThe wealthy West has little excuse for finally waking up to the global debt crisis. \u201d\n\u201cAfter a decade or more of their obsession with their own problems, countries in the wealthy West have begun to pay attention to the threat of a looming debt crisis in the poorer parts of the world, \u201d he says at a meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank in Washington this week.\nThe good news is that debt has risen to the highest level on the policy agenda and is seen as a problem that needs to be regulated, IMF Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said about the need for distressed countries to help: \u201cHelp them deal with the debt burden, which has made the shocks of past years more difficult; and help ensure that the IMF can continue to support them in the years to come. \u201d\nThe bad news, according to Elliott, is that Georgieva \u2019 s appeal has not yet been heeded, as rich countries are still primarily interested in their own problems.\nThe geopolitical rivalry between the United States and China is also not helping.\nCreditor countries may wake up to the idea that there is a debt problem but it is far from a solution.\nTalk is not like work. \u201d\nAchim Steiner, director of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), said: \u201cThere are more than 50 countries on his radar that can default very quickly. \u201d\nSteiner believes that the UN has no chance of meeting its ambitious 2030 development goals, unless there is urgent action.\nThe volume of lending by the private sector has made attempts to restructure or write off debt more complex than in the past.\nAt the time of the HIPC initiative, creditors tended to be either individual governments or multilateral organizations such as the World Bank.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cBut since the global financial crisis, many countries, especially middle-income countries, have borrowed heavily in financial markets, taking advantage of very low interest rates to finance domestic projects. \u201d\nAfter the setback of the COVID-19 epidemic, low- and middle-income countries have since been hit by two other undesirable shocks: the war in Ukraine, which led to higher food and fuel prices, and the sharp increase in central bank interest rates in large Western economies.\nThe result is that debt servicing has become much more expensive, with many countries now frozen out of financial markets altogether.\nSteiner said: \"The issue is not financial but political.\nThe United States has mobilized $400 billion to secure Silicon Valley Bank deposits.\nThis is more than the developing world has received in three years.\nIt took the Swiss government less than 48 hours to find 100 billion Swiss francs to secure the rescue of one of its banks.\n\u201cThe lesson of the recent banking crises is clear.\nRich countries can act fast enough when they want to, \u201d the writer concludes.\nFears of Macron \u2019 s politics\nWe turn to another Financial Times opinion piece by Alain Beatty, a trade writer, entitled \u201cThe Risks of Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s Strategic Insistence. \u201d\nMacron \u2019 s focus on keeping a distance from both Washington and Beijing in pursuit of the EU \u2019 s vague \u201cstrategic autonomy \u201d is not an innovation among European policymakers, but geopolitical Europe enthusiasts need to recognize that the lack of unity and trust within the EU, rather than the sinister manipulation by Washington and Beijing, is the main obstacle.\n\u201cWe \u2019 ve already seen this happen in trade policy, which is one area where the EU has long had the ability to act collectively.\nIn the same way that there is nothing stopping European governments from increasing military spending and playing a greater geopolitical role, the bloc can certainly increase its ability to use trade to project its strategic influence.\nBut while France has been keen to create new tools for intervening in trade and investment, other member states recognize that the views and interests of Paris are not necessarily those of the bloc as a whole.\n\u201cIn recent years, the European Commission has carefully designed a range of trade instruments to confirm the bloc \u2019 s geo-economic weight.\nThe most politically salient is the anti-coercion tool ECI, which will allow the EU to use a wide range of trade and investment measures to retaliate against the bullying of trading partners.\nFrance has strongly supported all this activity, and has also called for the creation of new EU central funds to pursue industrial policy.\n\u201cBut the Commission will struggle to use this set of tools if there is opposition from other member states that are mindful of their export interests or distrust in using trade tools to manage a centralized strategic policy.\nA few days before Macron \u2019 s trip, the Commission succumbed to pressure from some EU governments, including Germany, and gave member states a major role in determining the use of ECI.\nBerlin instinctively avoids confrontation that could damage German exports and investments abroad.\nThere have also been more principled objections from liberal member states including Sweden and the Czech Republic, sceptical of attempts to politicize trade policy and the likelihood that it will be overly influenced by certain governments.\nMacron inadvertently contributed to these concerns, especially as he unnerved some other EU governments two years ago with a clear orientation toward a major investment deal with China, \u201cleaving a legacy of caution. \u201d\n\u201cAttempting to push a union with divergent views to adopt a single approach to a specific global issue is unlikely to produce long-term results. \u201d\nGerman split on energy policy\nWe remain with an article by Laura Bettel, the Financial Times correspondent in Berlin, entitled \u201cGermany is being torn apart by energy policy with the closure of nuclear plants. \u201d\nBethel said Germany \u2019 s last remaining nuclear power plants were shut down on Saturday, \u201cmarking a watershed moment in a country that has long had deep doubts about atomic energy. \u201d\nAnti-nuclear activists hailed the shutdown of three reactors as a victory after a temporary delay following the start of the Russian-Ukrainian war that forced Berlin to look for alternatives to Russian gas.\nCritics see the shutdown as an act of madness at a time when Europe \u2019 s energy supply remains precarious and the world is struggling to stop using fossil fuels.\nAfter decades of anti-nuclear protests, the decisive moment came in 2011 when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants until 2036, bringing the phase-out date to 2022.\nThe anti-nuclear movement in former West Germany dates back to the 1970s, when a popular campaign succeeded in stopping the construction of a nuclear power plant in the southwestern village of Weil.\nThe nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 fuelled that movement.\nBut German public opinion shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War: an August 2022 poll from Der Spiegel found that 67 percent of Germans supported a five-year extension of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants.\n41% supported the construction of new plants.\nIn a similar poll three decades ago, only 3% said yes.\nBut the German Green Party, now part of the three-way coalition government led by Olaf Schulz, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis.\n\u201cThe way in which Germany has chosen to phase out nuclear power, and step back from fossil fuels as a bridging gap even as renewables increase dramatically, has been highly controversial. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:8737","uncompressed_offset":317213251,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036","warc_date":"2023-04-14T03:30:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036"},"created":"2023-04-14T03:57:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207":{"id":"0c07d66e-9f96-43b6-bf6e-ca7d4b09078e_764705207","text":"Three nuclear-fired power plants will be taken off the grid in Germany on Friday as part of the country's plan to end atomic power.\n\n\"The nuclear phaseout makes our country safer and helps to avoid radioactive waste,\" said Federal Environment and Nuclear Safety Minister Steffi Lemke.\n\n\"It is now essential to ... advance the search for a final repository for high-level radioactive waste as well as permanent solutions for low- and medium-level radioactive waste,\" the environment ministry said.\n\nFormer German Chancellor Angela Merkel speeded up the phaseout following the 2011 Fukushima accident in Japan.\n\nFriday's shutdown affects power plants in Brokdorf in Schleswig-Holstein, Grohnde in Lower Saxony and Gundremmingen C in Bavaria.\n\nGermany's remaining three nuclear plants \u2014 Emsland in Lower Saxony, Isar 2 in Bavaria and Neckarwestheim 2 in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg \u2014 will be closed by the end of 2022 \"at the latest,\" the environment ministry said.\n\n\"Since 2011, Germany has been drawing a line under a highly problematic technology in an orderly, reliable process,\" Lemke said.\n\nNuclear accounts for about 10 percent of Germany's electricity production. The shutdown has sparked criticism as Germany will have to dramatically ramp up renewable energy and has also increased its reliance on highly polluting coal-fired power.\n\n\"Security of supply in Germany continues to be guaranteed,\" said Robert Habeck, federal climate and economy minister. He added that reliable and \"sustainably generated electricity\" is a \"central requirement for aligning our economy and industry toward climate neutrality.\"\n\nThat stance puts Berlin at loggerheads with France, where nuclear is the largest element of its energy mix (and also helps supply Germany).\n\nEU Internal Market Commissioner Thierry Breton said in September that existing nuclear plants, which provide low-carbon electricity essential to the green transition, can be kept running \"for two, five, 10 years,\" adding: \"Why deprive ourselves of this production capacity?\"\n\nFrance is planning to scale down the share of nuclear in its electricity mix from 75 percent to 50 percent by 2035, but President Emmanuel Macron said in November that France \"will restart the construction of nuclear reactors\" while \"continuing to develop renewable energies.\"\n\nMacron also said France will invest \u20ac1 billion into research and development, notably into small modular reactors.\n\nBelgium recently decided to shut down all its nuclear power plants by 2025, but plans to invest \u20ac100 million in new generation nuclear reactors and research.\n\nMore from ... Louise Guillot","url":"https://www.politico.eu/article/germany-powers-down-3-nuclear-plants/?aid=app_feed"},"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519":{"id":"4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad_493378519","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEXPRESS: Germany \u2019 s exit from atomic energy sector affects Europe \u2019 s largest economy\nGermany \u2019 s closure of the country \u2019 s last three nuclear reactors and its eventual exit from the atomic energy sector raises concerns about the impact of the decision on the European Union \u2019 s largest economy.\nGermany \u2019 s action could deal a blow to the technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nBerlin is implementing its plan to limit electricity generation to renewable sources by 2035.\nEarlier this week, Germany shut down its last three nuclear power plants as part of Berlin's plan to limit power generation to renewables by 2035, ending a six-decade programme that has sparked one of Europe's most powerful protest movements.\nOther industrialized countries, such as the United States, Japan, China, France and Britain, rely on nuclear power to replace the fossil fuels that are warming the planet, and Germany \u2019 s decision to stop using both has been met with some skepticism, as well as unsuccessful last-minute calls to halt the shutdown, the report said.\nNuclear energy advocates around the world have criticized the German shutdown, realizing that the action taken by Europe \u2019 s largest economy could deal a blow to technology they see as a clean and reliable alternative to fossil fuels.\nThe German government has acknowledged that in the short term, the country will have to rely more on polluting coal and natural gas to meet its energy needs, even as steps are taken to dramatically increase electricity production from solar and wind power, and Germany aims to be carbon neutral by 2045.\nBut officials like German Environment Minister Stevie Lemke say the idea of a nuclear renaissance is a myth, citing data showing that the share of atomic energy in global electricity production is shrinking.\nThe construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns.\nLimki noted that the construction of new nuclear plants in Europe has faced significant delays and cost overruns, and said the money spent on maintaining old reactors or building new ones would be better spent on installing cheap renewables.\nExperts such as Claudia Kemfert of the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin say the 5% share of German electricity currently coming from its three remaining reactors can be easily replaced without risking power outages.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:26416","uncompressed_offset":493378519,"url":"www.dostor.org/4369517","warc_date":"2023-04-17T07:53:03.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4f1c1d64-2656-465e-a7f4-ca81c7711dad>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/4369517"},"created":"2023-04-17T08:28:34.000Z","lang":"eng"},"12f71d0d-8a71-46e5-9d7d-b45a8f75dbe2_1066539592":{"id":"12f71d0d-8a71-46e5-9d7d-b45a8f75dbe2_1066539592","text":"Home / News / World /\u00a0 Germany quits nuclear power; shuts final 3 plants\nBack\n\nGermany has shut its final three nuclear plants, marking the end of the country's end of nuclear era that has spanned more than 60 years.\n\nNuclear power has long been contentious in Germany.\n\nThe move has come as Germany's eyes achieve its green goal. Steffi Lemke, Germany\u2019s Federal Minister for the Environment and Consumer Protection and a Green Party member, \"The position of the German government is clear: nuclear power is not green. Nor is it sustainable\".\n\nClosure of three nuclear plant's history:\n\nGermany shut three plants-- Emsland, Isar 2, and Neckarwestheim, representing the culmination of a plan set in motion more than 20 years ago.\n\nDuring the 1970s, a strong anti-nuclear movement emerged in Germany. The movement gave birth to the green party, which is now part of governing coalition.\n\nHowever, it was in the 2000s the German government pledged to phase out nuclear power and start shutting down plants.\n\nBut in 2009, a new government came to power and it seemed brief as if nuclear would get a reprieve as a bridging technology to help the country move to renewable energy.\n\nThen Fukushima happened. In 2011, an earthquake and tsunami caused three reactors of the Fukushima Daiichi power plant to melt down.\n\nThree days later then-Chancellor Angela Merkel who was previously pro-nuclear, announced Germany would accelerate a nuclear phase-out, with older plants shuttered immediately.\n\nRussia's invasion of Ukraine provided another plot twist.\n\nGermany isn\u2019t the only country committed to walking away from nuclear \u2014 Italy gave up the technology in 1990, and Lithuania recently struck a deal to dismantle its Soviet-era reactors, which have sat idle for over a decade. But in many advanced economies, nuclear is experiencing a resurgence.\n\nOn Sunday, Finland will start regular power production at Europe\u2019s newest and biggest reactor. The 1,600-megawatt Olkiluoto-3 unit that faced years of delays had been planned to enter commercial production on Monday. France is planning to build at least six new reactors by 2050 as well as experiment with smaller, modular ones. The UK has similar ambitions. And even in Japan, after a decade of paralysis following the nuclear accident in Fukushima, the public is warming up to the use of nuclear power. The Japanese government wants to restart reactors that have sat idle since the disaster and to extend the lifespan of existing units.\n\nCatch all the Business News, Market News, Breaking News Events and Latest News Updates on Live Mint. Download The Mint News App to get Daily Market Updates.\nMore Less\nRecommended For You\n\u00d7\nGet alerts on WhatsApp\nSet Preferences My Reads Watchlist Feedback Redeem a Gift Card Logout","url":"https://www.livemint.com/news/world/germany-quits-nuclear-power-shuts-final-3-plants-11681628200941.html"}}}
