dule with a drill and sealant in March 2021."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"Despite the air leakage, which caused a pressure drop of 0.4 mm Hg, the situation posed no risk to the crew or the station, as oxygen and nitrogen were pumped in to compensate for the loss."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"A special committee formed by the Russian space agency investigated the incident, ruling out industrial defects as the cause of the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft's damage."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"The hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft was located in a non-critical area, ensuring it did not threaten the crew's return to Earth."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"The International Space Station (ISS) experienced an air leak that was first detected on the night of August 30, 2018, when the crew noticed a pressure drop caused by a hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft's household compartment."},{"citations":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":100.0},"text":"Subsequent leaks were identified in August 2020 and October 2020, with cracks discovered in the middle chamber of the Russian Zvezda module, where the crew had temporarily settled."},{"citations":{"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":100.0},"text":"Initially, the cracks were thought to have been caused by a miniature meteorite impact, but investigations later revealed they were the result of a manufacturing defect on Earth, with glue used to seal the cracks drying out during orbital flight."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"The aging infrastructure of the ISS, built in 1998, has been cited as a contributing factor to recurring technical issues, including the discovery of new cracks as recently as 2021."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"To locate the source of the leak, Russian cosmonaut Anatoly Ivanishin used a tea bag, observing the movement of tea leaves toward a metal wall in the Zvezda module."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"Temporary measures included isolating the crew in the Zvezda module and closing the hatch in the affected area to ensure the rest of the station remained unaffected."},{"citations":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":100.0},"text":"Repair efforts involved using a special sealant to fill the hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft and later sealing cracks in the Zvezda module with a drill and sealant in March 2021."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"Despite the air leakage, which caused a pressure drop of 0.4 mm Hg, the situation posed no risk to the crew or the station, as oxygen and nitrogen were pumped in to compensate for the loss."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"A special committee formed by the Russian space agency investigated the incident, ruling out industrial defects as the cause of the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft's damage."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"The hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft was located in a non-critical area, ensuring it did not threaten the crew's return to Earth."}],"references":["99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678","9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807","4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788","0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068","d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397"],"documents":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":{"id":"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397","text":"Astronauts discover cracks in another module of the International Space Station\nSpace\nInternational Space Station\nCopy Link https: / / en.rt.com / r64g\nVladimir Solovyov, chief designer at Energia, announced that astronauts have discovered new blind cracks in the Zaria module, the first and oldest module of the International Space Station.\nSolovyov, in an interview with the Russian news agency Novosti, pointed out that the astronauts, during their examination of the units of the Russian sector on the International Space Station, discovered the presence of blind cracks in the old unit \"Zaria\".\nAccording to him, this does not appeal to him, because the discovery of holes in the former Zvezda unit, indicates that the cracks discovered in the Zaria unit over time will inevitably expand.\nIn September 2019, astronauts detected a slight air leak from the International Space Station, in October 2020 they discovered cracks in the middle chamber of the Russian Zvezda unit, and in March 2021 they were able to repair them.\nIn January 2021, Solovyov announced that due to air leakage, the pressure inside the ISS drops by 0.4 mm Hg, which is compensated by pumping oxygen and nitrogen as well as transporting them from Earth.\nSource: Novosti\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0025.json.gz:7145","uncompressed_offset":672225397,"url":"arabic.rt.com/space/1267648-%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D9%8A%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%81%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%B4%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D8%B7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9/","warc_date":"2021-08-30T08:18:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/space/1267648-%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D9%8A%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%B4%D9%81%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%B4%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82%D8%A7-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%B1%D9%89-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D8%B7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D8%B6%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9/"},"created":"2021-08-30T09:10:49.000Z","lang":"eng"},"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":{"id":"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788","text":"29 Feb, 2024 11:18\n\nRussia comments on space station leak\n\nA NASA official had previously reported that air loss from the Zvezda module had doubled\n\nAir leaking from a segment of the International Space Station (ISS) poses no risk to its crew or the orbital outpost, the Russian space agency Roscosmos has said.\n\nA NASA official had previously reported that the rate at which air was escaping from the satellite's Russian Zvezda module under certain circumstances had doubled. The situation is under control and being constantly monitored, the\u00a0Roscosmos told Interfax on Wednesday, when asked about remarks by NASA\u2019s ISS program manager,\u00a0Joel Montalbano,.\n\n\u201dThe aging of the station\u2019s structure and the growing need for repair and maintenance work on board require a significant portion of the crew\u2019s time,\u201d Roscosmos said.\n\nMontalbano mentioned the issue during this week\u2019s briefing on the upcoming SpaceX Crew-8 mission, which is scheduled for launch on Friday.\n\n\u201dThere is an area in the aft end of the International Space Station. [There is] a small leak. We\u2019ve seen this leak increase about a week before the recent Progress launch and docking,\u201d he said, referring to a Russian automatic supply freighter.\n\nThe volume of lost air has increased to about two pounds a day, compared to a pound a day previously, Montalbano said.\n\n\u201dThe hatch is closed in that area. It\u2019s not an impact on Crew-8, but I didn\u2019t want anyone to be surprised, if they hear about that later,\u201d he explained.\n\nThe use of the module for retrieving the Progress shipment didn\u2019t pose any issues in terms of the leak, he said. The next opening of the hatch is expected in April. While it\u2019s closed, the rest of the station is \u201csolid.\u201d\n\nTechnical issues at the ISS are being reported on a regular basis. Roscosmos has said the age of the station is a key reason why it is developing plans for a new purely Russian-manned orbital structure as an alternative to participating in the international project.\n\nPodcasts\n0:00\n27:58\n0:00\n26:56","url":"https://www.rt.com/news/593386-nasa-roscosmos-iss-leak/"},"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":{"id":"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807","text":"NASA has excluded the involvement of its astronauts in the hole in the \u201cUnion \u201d\nAmerican astronauts are not involved in the appearance of a hole in the household compartment docked to the ISS \u201cSoyuz MS-09 \u201d in 2018.\nThis was stated by the assistant head of NASA for manned flights Katie Leeds, commenting on the publication of TASS, in which, with reference to the source, it is reported about the likely drilling of a hole in the ship by astronaut Serina Augnon-Chancellor.\n\"NASA crew members carry out their missions professionally and honestly.\nI support Serina and her professional behavior, and I don't find this accusation credible, \"Leaders said.\nOn the eve of TASS published an anonymous interview with an unnamed top manager of \u201cRoscosmos \u201d, in which the Agency interlocutor said that Aunyon-Chancellor, being the only woman in the crew, experienced\u201c acute psychological crisis \u201d.\nThe source of the publication explained that, wanting to speed up its return to Earth in connection with the emergency situation, the American drilled a hole that threatened to depressurize the station.\nAs one of the confirmations of his version, the Agency interlocutor indicated that NASA astronauts refused to pass the test on the \u201clie detector \u201d.\nAccording to the source, the hole was drilled in zero gravity.\nThe crew discovered an air leak on the International Space Station (ISS) on the night of August 30, 2018, which was caused by a hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft.\nIt was located in the household compartment, not in the lander, so it did not threaten the return of the crew to Earth.\nGeneral Director of Roscosmos Dmitry Rogozin reported that the commission of the rocket and space Corporation (RSC) Energia ruled out the version of damage to the skin of the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft as a result of industrial defects.\nNewsletters \"Vedomosti\" - get the main business news by mail\nI want to subscribe","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0023.json.gz:116440","uncompressed_offset":42775807,"url":"www.vedomosti.ru/technology/news/2021/08/13/882106-v-nasa-isklyuchili-prichastnost-svoih-astronavtov-k-otverstiyu-v-soyuze","warc_date":"2021-08-13T20:39:52.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949>","warc_url":"https://www.vedomosti.ru/technology/news/2021/08/13/882106-v-nasa-isklyuchili-prichastnost-svoih-astronavtov-k-otverstiyu-v-soyuze"},"created":"2021-08-13T20:42:00.000Z","lang":"eng"},"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":{"id":"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678","text":"How did a bag of tea help astronauts save $150 billion?\nHow did a bag of tea help astronauts save $150 billion?\nA few years ago, a torn bag helped save the ISS\nThe International Space Station was built in 1998 for $150 billion.\nEvery year, another 3-4 billion dollars are spent to maintain its operability, but the design is already very old and needs repair more and more often.\nFor example, in August 2020, a pressure drop was recorded aboard the space station, which is a sign of an air leak.\nAll astronauts and cosmonauts on board were isolated in the Russian Zvezda module.\nAfter some time, it was found out that the air-permeable crack was in the module in which the entire crew temporarily settled.\nOne of the Russian cosmonauts was able to quickly find the place of leakage with the help of a usual tea bag.\nOxygen on the ISS\nAccording to the India Times, the space station loses about 250 grams of oxygen every day and this is normal - it is difficult to achieve complete tightness.\nIn the event of an acute shortage of oxygen, it is delivered by cargo ships, but is most often produced directly at the station.\nIn the second case, members of the ISS use electrolysis - an electric current is passed through the water, as a result of which oxygen appears.\nTo do this, on board there is a life support system ECLSS, which not only monitors the operation of the station, but also provides people with access to water, protects against fires and so on.\nECLSS technical director Robyn Carrasquillo once praised Russia for using a way to extract moisture from the air, even in the old Salyut and Mir spacecraft.\nECLSS system\nOxygen leakage to the ISS\nIn August 2020, the space station began to lose about a kilogram of air per day.\nThe situation was serious, but the lives of the ISS crew were not threatened.\nAstronauts from different countries temporarily began to live in the Russian module \u201cZvezda \u201d and for four days searched for a leak in other parts of the station.\nThe search did not give any results, so it became clear that the gap is in the Zvezda module launched more than 20 years ago.\nThe leak could have occurred for various reasons, for example, due to the collision of the ISS with space debris, which is a lot in near-Earth space.\nAlso, it was not excluded that seals simply peeled off from the walls of the station, which just do not allow oxygen to leak.\nISS module \"Zvezda\"\nSearch for the place of oxygen leakage\nAn unusual way to find the leak was found by cosmonaut Anatoly Ivanishin.\nHe installed several cameras in the module and opened the tea bag.\nAfter some time, the ISS members noticed that the tea leaves began to move slowly towards one of the metal walls of the module.\nAfter studying the trajectory of the leaves, the space crew quickly found the crack formed on the ISS.\nFirst, they taped this place with tape, and then got permission to use a drill and sealant.\nIt is known that thanks to the trick with a package of tea, the astronauts managed to save about 150 billion dollars.\nRussian cosmonaut Anatoly Ivanishin\nThe International Space Station is aging and will one day become completely unusable \u2013 that \u2019 s a fact.\nNew cracks were discovered even in 2021.\nEspecially there are many of them in the Russian module \u201cZarya \u201d, which was launched into space in 1998 and today is the oldest part of the station.\nMore recently, Vladimir Solovyov, General Designer of the Energia Rocket and Space Corporation, announced his concerns about the safety of the station.\nIt is especially frightening that the station is planned to be used even after 2025.\nIn theory, the use of the old station could cause a terrible disaster.\nISS module \"Zarya\"\nFinally, I note that to replace the old module \"Dawn\" it was planned to send the module \"Science\".\nBut it became an independent module and docked to the ISS in July 2021.\nThe docking was far from perfect - the module deployed the station at 45 degrees.\n19 october 2021 /\n\u2022 0\nSimilar news\nWhy not bring alcohol to the ISS?\nAlcohol is officially banned on the ISS, but space researchers have found many ways to carry it with them.\nCognac is very popular with them, but it makes no sense to take beer with you.\nAnd all\nChina has launched an apparatus to collect lunar soil.\nWhen will he return to Earth?\nChina has successfully launched to the moon the apparatus \u201cChang \u2019 e-5 \u201d to collect soil samples.\nThis is the first such mission in 44 years, and if all goes well, China will become the third country to do so.\nRussia is developing its own space station.\nWhat will it look like?\nThe International Space Station was launched into orbit around our planet in 1998.\nInitially, it was planned that it will work for 20 years, but subsequently the period of its use was extended.\nAccording to the opinion\nOn the ISS found a place of air leakage.\nWhat's next?\nInside the International Space Station live astronauts from different countries and they all need oxygen.\nThe air necessary for the life of the crew is produced by special equipment, but\nSpace debris nearly damaged the ISS.\nHow did it all work out?\nHumanity began to actively explore space with the help of complex technology around the middle of the 20th century.\nFirst, hundreds were launched into Earth orbit every year, and then thousands began to be launched.\nHow does space affect human vision and movement?\nthe brain, like the heart, is one of the main organs of the human body.\nIt consists of many areas, each of which has certain tasks.\nTake the brain for example, this\nComments\nPopular news\nImmersive exhibition of Claude Monet - a complete immersion in the world of the great impressionist In 2023, NASA will launch a new lunar rover VIPER into space.\nWhat's he gonna do?\nThe Vasimr nuclear rocket will take humans to Mars in one month.\nFrank Woolworth, creator of price tags and supermarkets Developed the smallest aircraft.\nWhat is it for? A Japanese cafe became famous all over the world with a toilet in the aquarium \"Rain Drops\" by Samuel Salcedo in the park of the city of EtretaThis picture of Renoir made a lot of noise... and three times!","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:134935","uncompressed_offset":674574678,"url":"secrets-world.com/space/30417-kak-paketik-chaya-pomog-astronavtam-sekonomit-150-milliardov-dollarov.html","warc_date":"2021-10-22T03:14:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f>","warc_url":"http://secrets-world.com/space/30417-kak-paketik-chaya-pomog-astronavtam-sekonomit-150-milliardov-dollarov.html"},"created":"2021-10-22T04:04:46.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":{"id":"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068","text":"Soyuz manufacturing defect causes air leak at International Space Station\nKazakhstan News Agency / Astana / September 3 - According to the Russian satellite network reported on the 3rd, Russian rocket space sources said that the manufacturing defect is the cause of the \"Soyuz MS-09\" spacecraft leak.\nThere was an air leak on the International Space Station on August 30.\nThe astronauts examined all the compartments and found tiny cracks in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft.\nIt is located in the living module, not in the return module, so it will not affect the return of the spacecraft to Earth.\nIt was previously thought that the fissure was the result of a miniature meteorite hitting the spacecraft.\nThe next night, Russian cosmonauts used special sealant to fill the hole.\nThe source said: \"The cause of the crack in the inner shell of the living module has been identified and it has appeared on Earth.\nThe person responsible for the fault was identified. \"\nAccording to another source, the crew likely sealed the leak with special glue after realizing the mistake, so it was not detected during the pre-launch check and the spacecraft \u2019 s first two months of orbital flight.\n\"However, the glue later dried out and was squeezed out, revealing cracks,\" he said.\nThe Russian space agency said a special committee would investigate and determine the cause of the accident.\n\u0421\u0435\u0439\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0442","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:41646","uncompressed_offset":113364068,"url":"cn.inform.kz/amp/article_a3377843/","warc_date":"2023-12-27T21:22:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75>","warc_url":"https://cn.inform.kz/amp/article_a3377843/"},"created":"2023-12-27T21:28:18.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T215","run_id":"gar","topic_id":"1118","request_id":"1118","narrative_id":"1118"},"responses":[{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"On the night of August 30, 2018, astronauts aboard the International Space Station (ISS) detected an air leak, which was later traced to a hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"The air leak was initially identified when a pressure drop was recorded aboard the station, prompting the crew to investigate the source of the issue."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"Subsequent investigations revealed that the hole was located in the household compartment of the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft, a section that did not threaten the crew's return to Earth."},{"citations":{"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":100.0},"text":"The cracks in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft were initially thought to have been caused by a miniature meteorite impact."},{"citations":{"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":100.0},"text":"However, further analysis determined that the cracks were the result of a manufacturing defect on Earth, where the area had been sealed with glue that later dried out and failed during the spacecraft's orbital flight."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"In a separate incident in August 2020, another air leak was detected on the ISS, this time in the Russian Zvezda module, which serves as the station's living quarters."},{"citations":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":100.0},"text":"The Zvezda module's air leak was traced to tiny cracks in its middle chamber, which were discovered in October 2020."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"The cracks in the Zvezda module were found in the area where the crew had temporarily settled during the investigation of the leak."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"The aging infrastructure of the ISS, which was built in 1998, has been cited as a contributing factor to the technical issues, including the appearance of new cracks as recently as 2021."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"The Russian space agency Roscosmos has acknowledged that the station's age necessitates significant repair and maintenance work, which occupies a substantial portion of the crew's time."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"To address the air leak in the Zvezda module, astronauts initially used temporary measures, such as isolating the crew in the module and closing the hatch in the affected area to ensure the rest of the station remained unaffected."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"Russian cosmonaut Anatoly Ivanishin employed an innovative method to locate the air leak by using a tea bag and observing the movement of tea leaves toward the source of the leak."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"Once the location of the leak was identified, the crew initially taped the crack and later sealed it using a drill and sealant after receiving permission from ground control."},{"citations":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":100.0},"text":"In March 2021, astronauts successfully repaired the cracks in the Zvezda module, ensuring the station's continued functionality."},{"citations":{"d84c416d-63f5-4e7a-9b4c-beb2f3c6bc7f_672225397":100.0},"text":"The pressure inside the ISS drops by approximately 0.4 mm Hg due to air leakage, a loss that is compensated by pumping oxygen and nitrogen and transporting these gases from Earth."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"Despite the air leakage, Roscosmos has stated that the situation posed no risk to the crew or the orbital outpost."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"The rate of air escaping from the Zvezda module was observed to double under certain circumstances, increasing from about one pound of air lost per day to two pounds."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"NASA reported that the air leak in the Zvezda module began to increase about a week before the launch and docking of a Progress spacecraft."},{"citations":{"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":100.0},"text":"A special committee was formed by the Russian space agency to investigate the cause of the air leak incidents on the ISS."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"NASA explicitly excluded the involvement of its astronauts in the appearance of the hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft in 2018."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"The General Director of Roscosmos, Dmitry Rogozin, reported that the commission of the rocket and space corporation Energia ruled out the possibility of industrial defects causing the damage to the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft."},{"citations":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":100.0},"text":"The ISS's aging structure has led to recurring technical issues, highlighting the need for ongoing maintenance and repair efforts to sustain its operations."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12-b19d-bc0320619949_42775807":100.0},"text":"On the night of August 30, 2018, astronauts aboard the International Space Station (ISS) detected an air leak, which was later traced to a hole in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft."},{"citations":{"99ddc9ed-c0a5-48b7-a41b-e778f7e5043f_674574678":100.0},"text":"The air leak was initially identified when a pressure drop was recorded aboard the station, prompting the crew to investigate the source of the issue."},{"citations":{"9c77bd0c-c040-4f12